<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8296 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-KNIGHT-ABUSE-HNS &LR;      03-26 1559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-KNIGHT-ABUSE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
Ricky Calloway figured it was time to speak up.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Calloway had read and heard former Indiana University basketball
player Neil Reed's accusations of abuse at the hands of Hoosiers
coach Bob Knight, and he knew what was going to happen next.
</P>
<P>
   The wall of silence would go up, and people would bend over
backward to defend Knight and discredit Reed, who in 1997
transferred from Indiana to Southern Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with CNN/Sports Illustrated, Reed claimed Knight
had choked him during a practice session, prompting a hail of
denials from former Hoosiers players and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Other than saying he didn't remember choking Reed, Knight has
refused comment on the incident. Knight is currently away on a
hunting trip.
</P>
<P>
   Calloway, who started as a sophomore on Indiana's 1987 national
championship team, claims tales like Reed's are true. And seeing
Reed vilified for his comments prompted Calloway, who transferred
to Kansas for his senior year, to break a 12-year silence on the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah, I've seen things (physical abuse) like that
myself,'' said Calloway, who now runs a swimming-pool construction
company, Red Sea Pool Services, in Houston. ``He (Reed) didn't
deserve to have all that stuff heaped on him. Everybody says he's
lying about all the abuse at Indiana, but he's not. It took a lot
of courage for him to come forward like he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see Neil Reed get choked, but I can be 95 percent
sure it happened because I've seen it happen (to other players). I
saw a lot of things happen. And with him (Knight), if you're going
to keep getting away with things like that, why would you change?''
</P>
<P>
   For years there have been whispers of a dark side to Knight, but
as the only active coach with three NCAA titles to his credit, he
holds tremendous sway in college and professional circles. His
Indiana program produced University of Iowa coach Steve Alford and
Bowling Green coach Dan Dakich, and NBA coaches Butch Carter
(Toronto) and Randy Wittman (Cleveland). Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski
played for Knight at Army.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last five years, nine players _ including several
highly regarded recruits _ have transferred from Indiana, including
Reed.
</P>
<P>
   Calloway did, too, leaving the program in 1988, saying he could
``no longer take all the stuff he was giving me and the other
players.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm not some bitter ex-player with shattered dreams,''
Calloway said. ``I made it to the NBA (playing one season with
Sacramento in 1991). I didn't play as long as I wanted, but I got
there. And I had a good career playing overseas (Turkey, France,
Greece and Poland) and in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   ``But some things just have to be said.''
</P>
<P>
   Calloway said he recalled two specific incidents of physical
abuse: Knight punching Alford, his star guard, and once slapping
forward Darryl Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah, I've seen him hit players,'' Calloway said. ``I saw
him punch Steve Alford. I saw him slap Darryl Thomas. I've seen him
threaten players. He got nose to nose with me one time saying that
he wanted to fight me, and I knew right then that it was time to go
because it had reached a point where I wanted him to hit me so I
could have a reason to hit him back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach knew the guys he could hit or really get into, and those
he couldn't. Darryl was a big guy (6-7, 240 pounds), but coach knew
what type of personality Darryl had. He (Knight) was mad at him,
and Darryl was sitting in his chair, and he (Knight) just came up
and slapped him, and it was hard. Then he realized what he did and
said, `Go ahead and hit me back.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, he realized what he did was all wrong, so he knew he had
to try and correct it by telling Darryl to hit him back. But Darryl
hit him real soft, and I remember when we got back to the dorm room
we were like, `Man, you should have hit him hard. You've been here
for four years, and he's been kicking your butt the whole time, and
you just tap him?' But (Knight) knew Darryl wasn't going to hit him
back.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Calloway said, neither was Alford.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all felt sorry for Steve,'' Calloway said. ``After practice
one day he (Knight) was mad. And Alford used to take a lot for
other people because he (Knight) would tell Alford that everything
that went wrong was his fault because he didn't get on us enough.
He would say, `(former Hoosier) Quinn Buckner would have slapped
one of these guys.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always going off on Steve like that, trying to get him
to be like Buckner, but Steve just wasn't like that. We were all
standing in a circle one day, and he (Knight) just turned around
and punched Steve right in the stomach, and for a minute and a half
Steve couldn't breathe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked. I wasn't really surprised he hit someone, but I
never expected him to hit Steve, his golden child. But Steve put up
with a lot. He really had to put up with a lot. Steve won't admit
that it happened, but he won't lie about it, either. He just
doesn't answer the question. He gets evasive when you ask him about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Calloway wants to make it clear he has no vendetta against
Knight. He would have remained silent on the subject had Reed not
spoken out. Calloway, a highly recruited 6-6 forward out of Withrow
High in Cincinnati back in 1985 _ more highly regarded than a 6-7
forward out of Michigan named Glen Rice _ in fact says his initial
impressions of Indiana were good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went there (to Indiana) because I wanted to go to a
top-notch program and I wanted to play for a good coach,'' Calloway
said. ``And one of the biggest things was that all of the other
schools that recruited tried to do that with a suitcase full of
money. And promises. I knew all that was b.s. I didn't want to be a
piece of meat for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Knight) was the only coach who came to my house and said,
`Look, whatever you get you'll earn. I guarantee you'll be a better
basketball player when you're through here. And we'll be on TV
every week.' I could respect that. I just didn't know it was going
to turn into three years of hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Calloway is certain Knight felt he was simply testing his
players, but feels it often went too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he didn't want to do it himself, he would try to get a
player to hit another player,'' Calloway said of Knight. ``If you
were the captain and you were going to the locker room after
practice or after a game, he would pull you out and tell you,
`Look, you need to go in there and slap Ricky upside his head and
tell him he's playing like .'
</P>
<P>
   ``And he actually wanted you to hit that player. I wouldn't do
it, which was a big problem between him and me.''
</P>
<P>
   And Calloway dismissed the notion that he could not play for a
strict coach, citing Kansas coach Roy Williams as one of the
toughest he has ever had to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's OK to be tough on players, but without physical abuse,''
said Calloway, who graduated from Kansas in 1990. ``And it wasn't
like I couldn't handle a tough coach. I went to Kansas after that,
and coach Williams' practices were actually harder than at Indiana.
Man, at Kansas we worked hard. Coach Williams was on us _ he was
tough. But he also built us up instead of putting you down.
</P>
<P>
   ``And at that age, when someone is constantly telling you that
you're no good and you'll never be anything, then you start to
believe it. There is no positive at all at Indiana, and I don't
think the ends justify the means. Look at (the program) now.
They're going to make the (NCAA) Tournament, but when was the last
time anyone thought they had a legitimate chance to win it all?
Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the players are no longer responding to all that stuff
he (Knight) does. They're just not responding. It got to the point
on our team where we just wanted the season to be over. It was
like, if we win, we win. If we don't, then we don't. We could
finish out the school year and go on about our business.''
</P>
<P>
   Indiana president Myles Brand on Thursday initiated an
investigation of Reed's charge, with the findings to be reported to
him in 90 days. Calloway said a professor at the same university
wouldn't get the same consideration from the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is that if a professor at Indiana did the things he
(Knight) does, he'd get fired,'' Calloway said. ``In a minute. If a
parent did the abusive things he does, they'd take the kid away. Or
if a spouse did stuff like that, hitting his wife, then he has to
go. No questions asked. But with him (Knight), everybody's telling
a lie. Everybody just has to be lying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to let other kids know that if you're not happy
and things aren't going the way you want them to go, you can always
leave. You don't have to be there. You don't have to take abuse. If
something was happening to my daughter, I wouldn't want her to just
sit there and be abused, either physically or verbally. But he
(Knight) thinks that's OK, but it's not.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to go too far one day, and he's going to hurt a
kid. Or a kid is going to hurt him. It'll be like (former Ohio
State football coach) Woody Hayes, where he loses control and
smacks a kid in public, right on national TV. Then everyone will
know what's been going on all these years.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it'll be too late by then.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
