<HEADLINE>
SUTTON'S TPC LEAD GETS WATER-DOWNED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ Hal Sutton was throwing the
third-round challenge back in the face of Tiger Woods Saturday
until he came to the question that demanded the shortest answer.
</P>
<P>
   Then he blinked, delivering a three-quarter 9-iron that flew
past the pin, hopped just once, and came to rest with the fishes,
the ducks, and all the heartache that resides in the water
surrounding the island green at TPC Sawgrass's 17th hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it was too long,'' said Sutton, after the
triple-bogey 6 on the 145-yard hole turned what should have been a
spectacular round into his third straight 3-under-par 69. That he
is at 9-under 207 and in possession of the lead in The Players
Championship is something to take heart in. That he allowed Woods
(66_208) to get within one shot is something to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   The question burned Sutton more than the shot he fired into the
water at 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no winning in this conversation, is there?'' he said,
knowing that the world probably thinks he may as well be eight
shots behind Woods entering Sunday's final round. He had made the
point earlier in the week that Woods was great but not unbeatable,
and now he goes head-to-head with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is No. 1 in the world, so I don't want to start anything,
but he is one shot down right now,'' said Sutton.
</P>
<P>
   True enough, but a short time before speaking those words,
Sutton had led by four shots, having countered Woods's best shots
with even better ones.
</P>
<P>
   A birdie on the opening hole by Woods set the agenda. Sutton
made one, too, so take that.
</P>
<P>
   Four birdies and a 32 on the front by Woods. No problem,
shrugged Sutton, who casually ripped off five and shot 31.
</P>
<P>
   How about an eagle for Woods at the par-5 11th, set up by an
eye-opening 4-iron out of a fairway bunker from 211 yards? Big
deal, yawned Sutton, who made his sixth birdie of the day at the
par-4 12th and built his lead back to four.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to answer everything that he did,'' said Sutton,
who was two groups behind Woods. ``I am not going to roll over and
play dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in the field did not share that approach. On a day when
Sawgrass was open for attack (the field average was 72.436, nearly
four shots easier than Thursday) only Tom Lehman and Jeff Sluman,
besides Sutton and Woods, shifted into forward.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman is alone in third, though his 72_211 left a bittersweet
taste thanks to a double-bogey at 18. He had one of the field's 11
birdies at 17 to get to 7 under, but drove it into the hay down the
right on 18 and had to lay up. An indifferent wedge fell short of
the green, and Lehman needed a chip and two putts to stumble in.
</P>
<P>
   Sluman, proving that Sawgrass can be played by those who don't
hit it into the next area code, shared the day's best round (66)
and leapfrogged 19 players into sole possession of fourth at
4-under 212.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Azinger had the shot of the day: a hole-in-one on No. 17
that helped him finish at 2 under for the day and the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But other than that, it was a leaderboard that refused to take
advantage of ideal scoring conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Omar Uresti, one behind Sutton at the start, made a triple bogey
at the par-4 10th and wasn't noticed again until he hit two into
the water at 17. His 80 dropped him to 28th.
</P>
<P>
   Woods's playing partner, Len Mattiace, was four shots behind to
start the day and made the turn in 33. But he hit his second shot
into the water at the 535-yard 11th, made bogey, then hit in the
water on the par-3 13th. He shot 73 and fell to 12th.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest fall belonged to Fulton Allem, who showed why
you haven't heard of him since that World Series of Golf win in
1993. Allem doubled the par-4 fourth, made the turn in 40, then
made three more doubles in an incoming nine to complete an 82 that
pushed him to 60th.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton and Woods were able to avoid letting such miserable play
sidetrack them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the course was going to be playing a little bit more
benign,'' said Woods, ``and I could be a little more aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Right out of the gate, too, as he bombed a drive on the 392-yard
opening hole and had a 60-degree wedge left. He made birdie there,
then two-putted for birdie on the par-5 second to give Sutton
something to look at.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry, said Sutton: ``I am very confident. I feel real
good about what I am doing.''
</P>
<P>
   It showed, too. Starting at the fifth, Sutton made five birdies
in eight holes to get to 12 under. By the time he walked off the
16th green, Sutton had played a stretch of 25 holes without a bogey
and owned a four-shot lead despite Woods throwing six birdies and
an eagle at him.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the diabolical 17th. ``I didn't think I overplayed the
shot,'' said Sutton, who had made par and bogey the first two days.
``I was aimed 6 feet left . . .'' Which is about the line it was
on. Only it carried farther than Sutton had expected.
</P>
<P>
   He took the drop, but his third shot hit a slope in the green,
spun back against the collar and required Sutton to negotiate a
difficult chip, which he could not pull off.
</P>
<P>
   That challenge passed, the question was directed to his next
one. Sutton glared, took a deep breath, and answered slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, this is what you dream about being in,'' he said.
``I am glad I am in the last group playing with Tiger Woods.''
</P>
<P>
   If only the one-shot lead was four.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
