<SLUG> BC-GLF-PLAYERSCHAMPIONSHIP-KEYSHOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUTTON HAUNTED BY TRIP TO TERROR ISLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, FLA. _ On a day when they combined for 135
swings in the third round of The Players Championship, Hal Sutton
and Tiger Woods were asked specifically about just two of them.
What resulted from these shots explained the contrast in their
moods.
</P>
<P>
   Hal Sutton's 9-iron to the 145-yard 17th island green Saturday
was a shot that melted a four-shot cushion down to one. It was a
good shot with a miserable result, said a somber Sutton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put a good swing on it and the ball just stayed in the air a
long time,'' he said, of the shot that hit behind the pin and
splashed into the lagoon. It led to a triple-bogey, but no second
thoughts. ``I don't know that I would have done it any differently.
Pitching wedge wasn't the right club.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Woods's second shot out of a fairway bunker into the
535-yard 11th hole? He was 200 yards from the front of the green,
211 to the pin _ the perfect distance for his 5-iron. ``But there
was too much sand,'' said Woods, who switched to a 4-iron.
</P>
<P>
   No problem. ``It came out absolutely perfect, just a nice, high
fade, about 4 or 5 yards. It hit nice and soft and I made the
putt.''
</P>
<P>
   Could anyone else have hit that shot, Woods was asked, and
before he could respond, the answer came from a reporter standing
nearby: ``God.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Woods laughed, but he said that the shot ``ranks up there''
with his greatest, a list that is already lengthy at the age of 24.
``I had to throw it up there pretty high and I wouldn't figure a
lot of guys could hit that, just because of the fact you have to
have clubhead speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Forget clubhead speed, Sutton wishes he had blinders for the
17th tee. He watched Omar Uresti hit into the water, the third
straight day he had seen a playing partner do that. ``That doesn't
give you positive vibes,'' said Sutton.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad he hadn't hit behind Paul Azinger, who aced the hole
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Uresti made things even more uncomfortable by taking his drop
and depositing that in the water. (He would make seven on the
hole.) Sutton then took his drop. He punched a sand wedge in the
direction he wanted, right in the middle of the green where there's
a crest, but ``it was just a foot or 2 short.'' Instead of
funneling toward the hole, the ball rolled back and came to rest
against thick, wiry rough that was taller than the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton stood there, bidding farewell to his four-shot lead and
wondering what to do next. He asked for an official when he spotted
a small television microphone buried in the rough, but there was a
deeper motive involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was biding for some time, trying to figure out the shot to
play,'' said Sutton, who won this event in 1983, back when he
wasn't nearly the player he is now. ``I mean, I was hollering
`uncle' the whole time and couldn't get away from the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   His options were to putt the ball or to try and chip it with
anything from a 3-wood to a sand wedge. He chose a putter. ``I had
to hit down on the ball (to pop it through the fringe), and I could
easily, if I had been too aggressive, have putted that ball across
the green in the water.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it came up well short, leaving Sutton 20- to 25-feet
for his fifth shot. He missed that putt, ``but the beauty of that
was I was able to tap in and finally finish the hole,'' he said,
trying his best to keep his sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Then he gathered himself and put on the Sutton stare. If not for
Woods, it perhaps would be the most intimidating in golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was obviously deflating,'' he said, ``and I'd like to have
the four-shot lead back. It was a triple-bogey, but it wasn't the
end of the world because I had (shots) to give back. That is why I
had to accept it and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Is the challenge Sunday to prove the point he had made earlier
in the week, that when he plays his game he can beat Woods? Again,
the stern, focused look.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only point I really want to make is driving it in the
fairway on the first hole (Sunday),'' said Sutton. ``I will start
trying to make my points after that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
