<SLUG> BC-BKC-MICHIGANSTATE-IOWASTATE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHIGAN STATE REACHES FINAL FOUR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ Iowa State's dream season ended Saturday
in a torrent of intensity and thrills, and so did the tournament
field's best chance.
</P>
<P>
   For if the tough, talented and superbly coached Cyclones could
not repel Michigan State with a six-point lead and five minutes to
play, what chance does anyone else have?
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't anything we did wrong, it was the opponent,'' said
Iowa State coach Larry Eustachy. ``I think they're the best team in
the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State qualified for its second consecutive Final Four
with a 75-64 victory Saturday before 21,214 partisan fans at The
Palace,which stands just 80 miles from MSU's campus in Lansing. The
Spartans will face Big Ten foe Wisconsin, champion of the West -
and a team they defeated three times this season - in one semifinal
in the RCA Dome in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   But before focusing on the surprising Badgers, Michigan State
(30-7) will spend a few hours relishing Saturday's awesome
performance. In perhaps the best game of the tournament - and
certainly the most intense - the Spartans outscored Iowa State 20-3
in the final five minutes, turning a 61-55 deficit into the
11-point victory that was far closer than the score indicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the most incredible game I've been involved in since
I've been at Michigan State,'' said Spartans coach Tom Izzo, who
has been there (in various capacities) for 17 years. ``Those guys
reached down and found something.''
</P>
<P>
   The second half featured several surges by each team. The
Cyclones built an eight-point lead with 12 minutes remaining,
watched the Spartans slice it to one, then darted to a seven-point
advantage when Izzo was assessed a technical foul for excessive
demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some coaches know when to get (technicals) and some don't,''
Spartans guard Mateen Cleaves said. ``Since we won, I think it was
a good time to get the tech.''
</P>
<P>
   Izzo's emotion energized his players, who scored 23 of the
next28 points and held Iowa State star Marcus Fizer scoreless for
the final five minutes. The signature play was an alley-oop from
Cleaves, the All-American point guard, to Morris Peterson, the
All-American small forward, following a timeout with 2:17
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson's dunk gave Michigan State a 64-61 lead, initiated Iowa
State's demise and showed why the Spartans are indeed the team to
beat in Indianapolis. They are tough, well-drilled, big, deep,
experienced and talented, and they execute their offense in
pressure situations better than any team in the country. Saturday,
they scored on nine of their last 10 possessions against the same
Cyclones defense that snuffed UCLA's fun-and-gun attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a great example of how they execute,'' Eustachy said.
``We went over that play and went over that play and broke down.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played better quality basketball in the last five
minutes, and that's why they're going to the Final Four. I don't
want to put pressure on their coach, but they're the best team in
the country. Butthat doesn't mean they'll win the national
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   There were several questionable calls against the Cyclones, and
with nine seconds remaining and the game out of reach, Eustachy -
who's wound Titleist tight on a good day received two technical
fouls, bumped an official and was ejected.
</P>
<P>
   It was a fitting end to an intense, dramatic game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might say it's unfair for these two great teams to meet in
the regional finals,'' Cyclones guard Michael Nurse said. ``But
that's the pick of the draw.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
