A8300 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-MUTINY     03-26 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-MUTINY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION IMPRESSIVE IN LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA _ The Revolution delivered one of the most impressive
offensive performances in their five-year history Saturday &UR;  &LR; night,
but they wasted several excellent chances and fell, 1-0, to the
Tampa Bay Mutiny.
</P>
<P>
   After a chaotic and sloppy start, the Revolution dictated the
tempo, and dominated the midfield by keeping Carlos Valderrama
under control. But the game was decided when the Mutiny's Raul Diaz
Arce headed in a Steve Ralston cross in the 51st minute, Tampa
Bay's only good opportunity of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution pressured Tampa Bay's goal with strikers Wolde
Harris and Eduardo Hurtado, but they failed to convert _ because of
their own inaccuracy and Scott Garlick's goaltending.
</P>
<P>
   ``They dominated the second half,'' Diaz Arce said. ``They are
going to be a strong team this year. But it was a game that was
very close. It was the kind of game where one goal was going to
make the difference, and they paid the price of giving up that one
goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution were far from perfect. But they were alternately
adventurous and patient offensively, maintaining their composure
and concluding the match on the offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time we lose, I am going to be mad,'' Revolution coach
Fernando Clavijo said. ``But I cannot be mad after that. We did
everything we needed to do to win. We just didn't put the ball in
the back of the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are becoming better as a team. Everyone gave everything
they had and we were the better team, but they won the game. We won
every ball in midfield and didn't give them any room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody should be discouraged after a game like that. It was
just one of those times that no matter what you do, the ball is not
going to go in. We can build on this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution, which have earned one point in two games,
continue their road trip to Los Angeles Saturday and Dallas April
8. But this was indeed a moral victory, since Tampa Bay had
expected to dominate this contest after taking a 5-1 victory over
Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution have seldom maintained possession and pressured
the opposing goal in such a clinical manner. Mauricio Ramos
improved his midfield choreography as the game continued, spraying
accurate and efficient passes to the wings. Leonel Alvarez and John
Harkes blocked Valderrama and ignited the offense in transition.
And Imad Baba was stopped twice by excellent reaction saves by
Garlick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the players to dictate the way we are going to play,''
Clavijo said. ``But we have eight new players and they still have
to get to know each other better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution forced the tempo and kept the Mutiny on the
defensive for much of the match, seldom allowing Valderrama to get
into the flow. Hurtado had the best opportunity of the first half,
efficiently trapping a cross from Baba in the penalty area, but
then skying a left-footed drive from 15 yards in the 34th minute.
They had several excellent shots in the second half, concluding
with Ramos's hooking attempt from just outside the penalty area
that was tipped over the bar by Garlick in the 89th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz Arce made the difference as he headed over Mike Burns, a
second-half replacement for Ted Chronopoulos, who suffered a
strained back in a collision with Chad McCarty.
</P>
<P>
   William Sunsing gave the Revolution another weapon in the final
minutes, entering as a substitute for defender Ivan McKinley as the
Revolution switched to a 3-5-2 alignment for the final 20 minutes.
But Sunsing, who returned early in the morning after playing for
Costa Rica in Morocco, lost possession on his first two touches and
needed time to get into the rhythm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
