<SLUG> BC-HKW-MINNESOTA-BROWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDEN GOPHERS TURN BACK BROWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For the first time in the history of the sport, the
best women's college ice hockey team in America is not from the
East.
</P>
<P>
   Striking for two rapid-fire goals in the third period, the
University of Minnesota upset No. 1-ranked Brown, 4-2,
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night in front of 2,249 at Matthews Arena to win the
American Women's College Hockey Alliance national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It still hasn't sunk in,'' said a stunned Laura Halldorson as
her team celebrated around her. ``Three weeks ago, we weren't sure
we were going to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   But Minnesota made good use of the at-large bid it got after
losing the Western Collegiate Hockey Association tournament to
upstart Minnesota-Duluth. Leading, 2-1, going into the third
period, the Golden Gophers put the game out of reach when Nadine
Muzerall, trying to ignore the neck injury suffered in a scary fall
during practice Thursday, scored her nation-leading 49th goal of
the season at 3:43, followed 58 seconds later by a high blast
through the legs of the country's top goaltender, Ali Brewer. The
1-2 punch gave Minnesota a 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great lead to get and we just relied on Killer to get
it done,'' said Halldorson. Her goaltender, junior Erica Killewald,
was named the tournament's most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   Although a flying rebounder by Kristy Zamora at 13:05 cut the
gap, Brown couldn't fight all the way back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the well ran dry,'' said Brown coach Digit
Murphy, whose Bears won the Ivy League, ECAC regular-season, and
ECAC tournament crowns. ``You look at the bright spots. How can you
be disappointed when you lose four games all year?'' Brown finishes
at 25-4-3.
</P>
<P>
   Not since their first game of the season Nov. 5, in a 4-0 loss
to this same Minnesota team, had Brown and Brewer been tapped for
four goals.
</P>
<P>
   There was some doubt that Brown could match Minnesota's physical
style, especially with Olympic defenseman Tara Mounsey out after
ACL surgery. But the Bears started strong, and drew first blood at
17:18 when sophomore defenseman Emily Sigman, out of Milton
Academy, rocketed a pass from the far edge of the faceoff circle to
freshman center Kim Insalaco, who one-timed it up the middle to put
Brown up, 1-0, for the period.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bears seemed to hit a lull in the second period, and a
Woburn-to-Minnesota family act took advantage when Courtney
Kennedy, a junior defenseman, got the puck from her sister Shannon,
a senior left wing, and sneaked it past Brewer head-on to tie the
game, 1-1, at 4:47.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't get any better than this,'' said Shannon Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Courtney Kennedy figured in the next goal, as well, earning
credit for an assist after Laura Slominski bounced the puck off of
Brewer's chest and into the net during a flurry with 1:11 left in
the second, putting the Gophers up, 2-1, at the second break.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Bears missed Mounsey, Murphy shrugged. ``If I had
her it may have been the difference, but we really felt we could
beat them without her.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Brown lost the Feb. 19 game against Harvard in which
Mounsey tore her ACL, it had gone 9-0 since.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota and Brown are the only teams that have been invited to
the tournament all three years of its existence, and the coaches
are such close friends that Halldorson is the godmother of Murphy's
six-month-old son, Sean. Brown has never won, while the Gophers
finished fourth, third, and now first. Asked how she would some day
explain to Sean why she beat his mother for the national
championship, she smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm competitive,'' she said softly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the consolation game, Carly Haggard scored on breakaways
twice in less than a minute near the end of the game to lead
Dartmouth to a 5-4 come-from-behind win over the University of
Minnesota-Duluth for the right to call itself the No. 3 team in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know she's a go-to player,'' said coach Judy Oberting of
Haggard, a freshman left wing from British Columbia whose
third-period hat trick included her sixth game-winning goal of the
season. ``She doesn't mind the pressure. She'll just keep getting
better and better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
