<SLUG> BC-HKC-BOSTONUNIVERSITY-STCLOUDST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. CLOUD CAN'T KEEP UP WITH TERRIERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Having grown up on Third Street in South Boston
and having skated since he was 14 months old at the MDC rink on Day
Boulevard, it's a given that Jack Baker is a tough hockey player.
But it's also a given that Baker is _ by his own account _ ``maybe
5-7 and maybe 163 pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   So when the Boston University hockey team became vulnerable
Saturday in the second period after racing to a 3-0 first-period
lead against St. Cloud State in an NCAA East Regional game, Baker
made the play that kept the Terriers in control.
</P>
<P>
   With the score 3-1 midway through the middle period, the
Fabulous Baker Boy threw his body at a one-timer from the blue line
by a St. Cloud defenseman (``I got it with my stick . . .
luckily''), then got to his feet as linemate Carl Corazzini
collected the puck and blew around the St. Cloud defense. Baker
caught up to the action and drove home the rebound of Corazzini's
shot for the key goal in BU's 5-3 win over the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   If the Terriers can beat St. Lawrence Sunday, they'll be more
than CYO champs. They'll be headed to the NCAA's Frozen Four next
weekend in Providence.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had just scored a goal and we always try to come back as
fast as we can to get another goal,'' said Baker. ``We try to get
another one as quick as we can to kill any momentum they have.''
</P>
<P>
   In that second period, said BU coach Jack Parker, ``all of a
sudden we were back on our heels a little bit and they got a goal
and, all of a sudden, we were a little jumpy.'' But Baker's huge
defensive play, followed by his goal, Parker continued, ``were huge
for us. They were great answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker and Corazzini are known for their speed, a trait of most
BU teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for me to imagine somebody faster than Carl
Corazzini,'' said Parker, ``but then it's hard for me to imagine
somebody faster than (former Terrier) Shawn McEachern and somebody
faster than Tony Amonte (another ex-BU star).''
</P>
<P>
   And that speed whiplashed St. Cloud early as Corazzini opened
the scoring with an unassisted goal at 2:35 of the first. Next,
Baker banged home his first goal of the game from a difficult angle
as his shot went in off the helmet of St. Cloud defenseman Derek
Eastman at 9:19. Then, at 15:39, Mike Pandolfo gave BU a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not the biggest line and a lot of teams try to
intimidate us by laying the body on us,'' said Baker. ``But a
majority of time we're able to get free and use the speed to our
advantage. We're usually able to break free against the line
playing against us, and if we're not scoring goals, we're at least
creating a lot of chances or putting some fear in the defense.''
</P>
<P>
   But BU fizzled early in the second period and St. Cloud
responded as defenseman Mike Pudlick banged home a one-timer from
the right faceoff circle at 12:22. BU seemed shaky, until Baker's
huge play just over a minute later.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got the draw back and they were trying to set up for a
one-timer,'' said Baker. ``I just got out there and laid down to
block the shot and it hit my stick and just sort of died. Carl was
able to pick it up and break down the wing and beat them wide and I
just tried to get back in the play. Carl just hit it off the goalie
and the puck was just sitting there and I was able to slam it in.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was BU's after that, as the Terriers smothered a St.
Cloud power play that covered the final 13 seconds of the second
period and the opening 1:47 of the third, the Huskies failing to
register a shot on goalie Rick DiPietro. St. Cloud was only 1 for 9
on power plays, compared with BU's 1 for 3. ``Our special teams
play was very good,'' said Parker.
</P>
<P>
   The Terriers had come out with their A game in the first period
``because we were terrible against Maine in the Hockey East
semifinals,'' said Corazzini. ``That's why we came out with a lot
of pride.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, BU, after a rare absence from the NCAA tournament last
year, is back in familiar territory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
