<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WISCONSIN-PURDUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BADGERS CRASH PAST PURDUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE _ You say there is no recorded instance of a town
ever actually being drunk dry? There's a first time for everything,
and that time might be next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Load up on the brewskis. Board up the windows. Wisconsin is
coming to Indianapolis. That's Wisconsin, as in state of.
Wisconsin, as in state of mind. That's Wisconsin, as in the
partyingest people north of Bourbon Street. And Wisconsin, as in
University of, a school whose rampaging basketball team has rolled
into the Final Four _ 13 losses, No. 8 seed and all _ by virtue of
a 64-60 victory over Big Ten rival Purdue in Saturday's West
Regional final.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these kids can play this game and study it. ``Us being
an 8 seed,'' said forward Mark Vershaw, ``I hope we repeat '85 and
do what Villanova did.''
</P>
<P>
   Rare is a kid who knows his hoop history, but if you were ever
going to find one, Madison, Wis., is probably a good place to
start. Vershaw really did come to Madison for an education. Like
his teammates, he knows that when his four seasons of collegiate
eligibility are up, his basketball will be over. But he now has a
Final Four on his resume, while several future NBA millionaires
will be watching him and his buddies play next Saturday evening in
the RCA Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin got there the usual Wisconsin way, by playing kung fu
defense and by each man remembering who he is and why he's here
when the ball is in his hands. Wisconsin had to survive a very
un-Badgerlike first half in which it had an unacceptable 2-1 ratio
of shots attempted (21) to turnovers. But the Badgers' defense
enabled them to squeeze out a 31-28 lead.
</P>
<P>
   As everyone had expected, the teams were evenly matched, and so
it was that with 5:23 remaining the teams were tied at 52. Purdue's
Brian Cardinal, scoreless in the first half, had just scored 11 of
his team's last 13 points to rescue the Boilermakers from a 45-39
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   That's when second-half hero Roy Boone (12 off the bench)
penetrated and dropped one down to forward Andy Kowske for a layup
that broke the final tie. The Badgers really needed only one more
big hoop, and that was provided by Boone, whose 12-footer in the
lane made it 56-53 with 2:49 left. Purdue never got closer again,
although Wisconsin made it dicier than it should have been with
some shaky foul shooting (13 for 24).
</P>
<P>
   Wily Wisconsin coach Dick Bennett can usually count on his team
taking care of business at the defensive end. But even pesky
Badgers need to score every once in a while.
</P>
<P>
   There were two critical offensive spurts. The first came at the
beginning of the game, when regional MVP Jon Bryant came off three
classic Kowske screens to drill 3-pointers for Wisconsin's first 9
points.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin, which isn't built to come from behind, must have a
good start.
</P>
<P>
   The second key offensive phase came early in the second half.
Purdue had scored the first 4 points to regain the lead at 33-32,
even as the Badgers missed two easy shots in their first two
possessions. But Wisconsin then scored on nine of its next 11
possessions over the next eight minutes, leaving itself with a
49-46 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was worried they might come out on fire,'' confessed
Bennett. ``I was worried; there's no question about that. Then we
started getting into the lane and getting good looks. It coincided
with us going to three guards by bringing Boone into the game. We
ran our offense better there than in any part of the game, and that
almost carried us to the wire.''
</P>
<P>
   It was no Monet, but Wisconsin games _ and Wisconsin-Purdue
games in particular _ never are. Wisconsin turned it over on six of
its first 15 and 10 of its first 24 possessions, and not all of the
turnovers were forced.
</P>
<P>
   But the good news for Wisconsin was that it was limiting Purdue,
which had scored 23 second-chance points against Gonzaga, to one
shot while scoring some bonus points itself.
</P>
<P>
   It is, truly, a fairy tale story. Wisconsin finished sixth in
the Big Ten. Vershaw (12 ppg) is the only double-figure scorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I think some people who really understand basketball
appreciate us,'' said point guard Mike Kelley, ``the majority of
people don't understand how we play or why we do it. Now they can
see it's all about winning.''
</P>
<P>
   With all the tips about to come their way, Wisconsin bartenders
will soon be retiring to the Bahamas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
