<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8305 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKW-CONNECTICUT-OKLAH     03-26 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-CONNECTICUT-OKLAHOMA_BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROMP KEEPS UCONN ON SCHEDULE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND _ The question no longer is will the University of
Connecticut beat its opponent, but by how many points. It's not
whether the Huskies will win, but how much damage they will do.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, it was the University of Oklahoma's turn to feel the
pain.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 1-ranked and top-seeded Huskies rolled over the Sooners,
102-80, in an NCAA East Regional semifinal before 5,702 at Virginia
Commonwealth's Siegel Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies (33-1) have won 14 straight games and move on to
face Louisiana State in the East final Monday night. LSU, which is
making only its second trip to the Elite Eight, defeated Duke,
79-66, Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   UConn will be playing in its sixth regional final in seven years
after cracking the 100-point barrier for the ninth time this
season.
</P>
<P>
   So coach Geno Auriemma should be ecstatic, right?
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly.
</P>
<P>
   He's not satisfied, and he won't let his players be satisfied,
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, they haven't done anything yet,'' Auriemma said,
shrugging off yet another blowout. ``All they've done is win a
bunch of regular-season games. But they can't be satisfied, because
if you're a competitor you want to win the national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma (25-8), the No. 5 seed, had a brief lead when a
3-pointer by Phylesha Whaley, followed by a layup by guard Stacy
Dales, put the Sooners up, 9-6, with 16:53 to go in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   That was enough for the Huskies, who went into attack mode with
an 18-0 run. They slammed the door shut, taking a 57-42 lead at
halftime that grew to 25 points before the game was over.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomores Tamika Williams and Asjha Jones came off the bench to
lead the Huskies with 16 points each as three of their teammates
also scored in double figures.
</P>
<P>
   Whaley, who played her final college game, led all scorers with
24 points.
</P>
<P>
   But with its trademark pressure UConn turned up the heat, making
21 steals and forcing 33 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a whole lot I can say that wasn't evident by how
we played,'' said Auriemma. ``We knew this would be a difficult
game to win, so I'm happy that we took control early.''
</P>
<P>
   UConn forward Svetlana Abrosimova, who finished with 15 points
and four assists, is obviously a top student in the Auriemma school
of winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that's how we play all the time, we don't look up at the
scoreboard and see we're up by 20 and stop playing,'' she said.
Anyway, she kept in mind that LSU was down by 17 to Purdue last
week but came back to win.
</P>
<P>
   Huskies guard Shea Ralph (10 points, eight assists) also isn't
satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always room for improvement, we didn't play perfect
tonight,'' she said, as her coach, seated next to her, said,
``rebounds,'' in a whisper. Oklahoma pulled down 40 boards to
Connecticut's 29. ``We have to concentrate to play our A game.''
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma coach Sherri Coale said the disappointment of loss was
tempered by the opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it goes without saying that we got beat by the best
team in the country,'' she said, comparing the Huskies' assault to
a tidal wave. ``They have this continuous wave attacking you, and
we don't have that kind of depth, so it's hard to survive those
waves.''
</P>
<P>
   But now, Coale said, she's ready to watch UConn move on and
victimize someone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Geno doesn't win it all, I'll be really mad at him now,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the other East Regional semifinal, Duke, which lost three
starters off last year's national championship runner-up team to
graduation, came up short.
</P>
<P>
   The teams seesawed the entire first half as Louisiana State
(25-6) clogged the lane and made Duke take outside shots. Forward
Lauren Rice was held to 10 points on 4-for-9 shooting as the Blue
Devils (28-6) shot 35 percent in the half.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the cold shooting, Duke had a 1-point lead, 31-30,
at the break and went up, 43-36, with 14:43 remaining. But LSU took
over from there. Junior guard Marie Ferdinand, who finished with a
game-high 22 points, made a steal and took it in for a layup as her
team went on an 18-4 run.
</P>
<P>
   ``All season I would just take on the defense and go by them,'
said Ferdinand, who had three steals.
</P>
<P>
   DeTrina White finished with 19 points and 11 rebounds for LSU,
while forward April Brown had 16 points and six assists and Katrina
Hibbert had 14 points. Rice paced Duke with 14 points, including
two 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt we had to keep it close,'' said LSU coach Sue
Gunter. ``I never felt that panic.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut is 30-1 this season when leading at the half, and
its 57.1 percent shooting Saturday marked the 10th straight game
the Huskies have shot 50 percent or better from the field . . . Of
the 12 Huskies who played, only Marci Czel didn't score. Center
Christine Rigby, who entered the game with a minute to go,
converted a 3-point play off a layup with 36 seconds to go . . .
Senior Stacy Hansmeyer, who played for Coale in high school at
Norman, Okla., scored 3 points and pulled down three rebounds in
eight minutes . . . Coale said she now has a clear understanding of
the Husky machine. ``This was like a regular-season game for
them,'' she said. ``The bottom line is we have never been here
before, and they live here.'' . . . LSU's Gunter spent Saturday
afternoon watching the Huskies annihilate Oklahoma. She said she
took solace in her team's win over Duke because ``people thought
Duke and UConn were the only teams playing here this weekend. I
think now maybe people will appreciate Louisiana State and spell
our name right.'' . . . It was only the third time this season the
Blue Devils have squandered a halftime lead. They were 28-3 when
leading at the intermission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
