<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8306 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-WISCONSIN-PURDUE-     03-26 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WISCONSIN-PURDUE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. _ Purdue knew it was coming.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The questions were, When would it come, how long would it last
and how painful would it be?
</P>
<P>
   It's called a Wisconsin-induced drought.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue fought through one in the first half but couldn't survive
one in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin held Purdue without a field goal for a crucial
six-minute stretch late in the game and toppled the Boilermakers
64-60 in the West Regional final Saturday before a sellout crowd of
16,004 at The Pit.
</P>
<P>
   The Badgers improved to 22-13 and became the first No. 8 seed to
advance to the Final Four since Villanova did it in 1985.
Wisconsin, which was unsure it would get an invitation to the NCAA
Tournament a week before it began, is the lowest seed to make the
Final Four since 11th-seeded LSU in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it'll be a repeat of the '85 Tournament and we can do
what Villanova did,'' Wisconsin forward Mark Vershaw said,
referring to the Wildcats' stunning upset of Georgetown for the
NCAA title.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin must feel like it's capable of accomplishing anything,
thanks to its current run of 12 wins in 14 games, with both losses
coming to Michigan State, its opponent in the national semifinals
in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue, which lost to its Big Ten rival for the third time in
four tries this season, took a 50-49 lead on a Brian Cardinal
jumper with 6:56 remaining. It was the second time the Boilermakers
went up by one in the second half, and it would be the last time.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue would not score another field goal until Greg McQuay put
back an offensive rebound with less than a minute to play. By then
Wisconsin had regained control, matching its biggest lead at 60-53.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last (seven) minutes they stepped it up a notch on
defense and we couldn't execute on offense,'' Purdue guard Jaraan
Cornell said. ``Somehow we couldn't get over the hump.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Bryant, who led all scorers with 18 points, drained a
3-pointer from the right corner, his fifth of the game, to put
Wisconsin on top for good 52-50 at the 5:48 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal, who had all 13 of his points in the second half, tied
the game for the Boilermakers with a pair of free throws, but Andy
Kowske answered with a layup off a feed from Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   Cornell missed two free throws, but Wisconsin failed to take
advantage as Roy Boone missed a shot, then picked up a steal and
blew an uncontested breakaway layup.
</P>
<P>
   Boone also had thrown up an airball and missed back-to-back free
throws after the Boilermakers grabbed the lead. But his fortunes
were about to change.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-3 junior reserve hit a huge running jumper in the lane and
went 4-for-4 from the foul line in the last 1:08 to help seal the
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't let the misses bother me, because I knew I was
going to have another chance to help the team win,'' Boone said.
``I was getting a little shaky, but it's a matter of how bad you
want it.''
</P>
<P>
   After Boone hit two free throws to give Wisconsin a 60-53 lead,
the biggest of the game, with just over a minute to play, Purdue
finally got a field goal and made one final push.
</P>
<P>
   McQuay's score got it going, and he added another tip-in
following missed free throws by Mike Kelley and Vershaw, to pull
the Boilermakers within 61-57.
</P>
<P>
   Boone was perfect at the line to up the lead to 63-57 before
Carson Cunningham, who had missed five consecutive 3-pointers,
finally put one home _ a leaning trey from the right side _ to cut
the lead to 63-60.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley hit one free throw with only 10.6 seconds on the clock
for a four-point lead, leaving Purdue with the slim hopes of a pair
of wild 3-point attempts before the Badgers' celebration could
begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a game (that was) about how I thought it would be,''
Purdue coach Gene Keady said. ``Unfortunately, they got the lead
and we didn't, so they dictated the tempo most of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we were a little impatient. When they got the lead, we
got a little too impatient and shot the ball too quick, and that's
the worst thing you can do against them. We had it (written) on the
board twice: `got to be patient, don't panic and take quick
shots.'''
</P>
<P>
   Purdue's offensive struggles in the second half (11-for-32 from
the field) can be traced to its poor outside shooting. The
Boilermakers went 4-for-17 from beyond the arc in the half, after
going 3-of-6 in the first 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I feel so bad about is that I didn't step up and hit
the shots down the stretch,'' said Cunningham, who matched Cardinal
with a team-high 13 points but was only 4-of-12 from the field. ``I
thought I had good looks, but I have to give Wisconsin credit. They
played good defense on me.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
