<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8307 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     03-26 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ For the second straight game, there was a
Palace revolt in progress, and it appeared the royal family was in
danger of losing a few heads.
</P>
<P>
   Mateen Cleaves was again struggling to find the range on his
shots, while the fouls were piling up on Andre Hutson, A.J. Granger
and Charlie Bell.
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight time in this upset-filled NCAA
Tournament, the Michigan State Spartans _ the only No. 1 seed left
_ were getting a bottoms-up view of the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Fizer, a daunting bull to ride in any rodeo, had just
ripped another rebound and signaled for a timeout while soaring
high above the out-of-bounds line. That set off an eruption from
Spartans coach Tom Izzo that drew a technical foul and gave Iowa
State a real reason to believe.
</P>
<P>
   For the second evening of what was supposed to be a home-court
coronation of sorts, the green-and-white celebration in the stands
had turned as nervous and fidgety as a wedding where the organ
music is playing and the bride is nowhere in sight.
</P>
<P>
   When Kantrail Horton made the pair of free throws off Izzo's
technical, resulting in a seven-point margin, Iowa State was most
definitely the Cyclones, and Michigan State was the trailer park.
</P>
<P>
   But if you listened hard through the funereal silence, maybe it
was possible to hear the Supremes singing You Keep Me Hangin' On.
Surely, if you cocked an ear, you could make out the Four Tops
crooning It's The Same Old Song. And wasn't that Martha Reeves and
the Vandellas echoing out of the rafters about a Heat Wave?
</P>
<P>
   That's right. Just up the road from Detroit, Morris Peterson was
turning up the volume on his collection of golden oldies. Welcome
back to Mo Town.
</P>
<P>
   Just as he did Thursday night against Syracuse, Mo Pete made his
presence felt like a guy with a handful of quarters standing at the
jukebox.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Orangemen in the regional semifinal, he ignited
Michigan State's comeback by slinging in three consecutive
3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Against Iowa State in Saturday's Midwest final, Mo Pete went
inside for layups, over the top for his sweet jumpers and way, way
upstairs for a mind-bending, Cyclone-shattering slam dunk off an
alley-oop pass from Cleaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't nervous when we were down,'' said Cleaves, who runs
the show on the floor and runs the rants in the Spartans' locker
room. ``I know that Morris is always there to make the big plays.
You always know what you'll get from him.''
</P>
<P>
   That is, mo', mo' and mo' from Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Pete scored 13 of his team-leading 18 points in the last 7{
minutes of the game and poured in a half dozen in the last 2:54,
when the Spartans got up off the floor and seized control.
</P>
<P>
   This is the attribute that makes Michigan State so special, the
team that was the preseason national championship pick of so many
and has been able to survive five months of playing with a
bull's-eye on its back. While so many of the giants have fallen in
this Tournament, the Spartans keep moving forward because they know
how to survive.
</P>
<P>
   The story so often told about them is of Cleaves' passing up a
chance to jump to the NBA last year _ after MSU lost in the
semifinal game at the Final Four _ and returning to lead his team.
</P>
<P>
   The story too often overlooked is that Mo Pete is also a senior
eyed just as hungrily by the pro scouts. Wouldn't he look nice in
those Rockets pajamas?
</P>
<P>
   Which one will have the better NBA career? You might be
surprised. Mo Pete is 6-6 and can do so many things. He cuts, and
he moves. He shoots those lefty jumpers faster than a hummingbird's
heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   And ooooh, yeah, he can fly.
</P>
<P>
   The brawling game had become a jumble of confusion thanks to
three referees named Moe, Larry and Curly. There was Izzo's
technical and the ejection of ISU coach Larry Eustachy with 9.9
seconds left in the game. There was a horribly gutless double-foul
call with 3:43 left and the Cyclones ahead 61-60.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Bell gave the Spartans a slim lead with a 15-foot
jumper. Then, after a timeout, Peterson took off and took over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll blow my cover,'' said Izzo. ``It was Morris' call in the
huddle. He asked what did I think about the lob. I said I thought
it was a great idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves, the quarterback, threw the high TD pass. Mo Pete, the
eagle, soared and slammed it home for a 64-61 lead that was as big
as a mile. Now Iowa State could hear the Temptations singing I
Can't Get Next To You.
</P>
<P>
   Mo-mentum. The Spartans closed with a 20-3 rush.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves made the all-tournament team. But Peterson was named the
Most Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a team with a purpose and still games to play,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Two Mo, in all likelihood.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
