<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8308 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-26 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
AUSTIN _ The lure of the NBA was supposed to temper the allure of
the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   So many kids began bolting out of school early, beginning in
earnest shortly after the unforgettable Magic Johnson-Larry Bird
showdown for the national championship in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Two words in the college game's vernacular were supposed to
become virtually extinct as the trend for early entry into the NBA
draft grew: Senior year.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomores began bolting. Freshmen. Then, high schoolers began
skipping their chance at university life altogether, chasing the
lure of NBA dollars and causing the college game's purists to wring
their hands and worry that maybe the greatest single-sport
spectacle in America would lose some of its attraction.
</P>
<P>
   But look now at the captivating 2000 Tournament, which has won
ratings wars with NBA games across the board this month. And look
here, at the South Regional in Austin, where no team has epitomized
the seemingly endless magic of the Tournament more than Tulsa,
which faces North Carolina at 1:40 p.m. for the right to advance to
the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always believed that we could get the job done,'' Tulsa
senior guard Tony Heard said. ``We trust each other. We play team
ball. We won a lot of games early, and the more we've won, the more
we've believed.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a team that has proved itself a national championship
contender for one reason alone. It has no superstars.
</P>
<P>
   Witness Duke's marvelous team of 1999. It was an overwhelming
team that fell just short of winning it all. Had even just two of
the four players that bolted to the NBA after last season's run
stayed in Durham, N.C., this 2000 season might still be going for
the Dookies.
</P>
<P>
   But instead, coach Mike Krzyzweski was forced to rely on youth
and more high school all-Americans. The Blue Devils again marched
to the nation's No. 1 ranking, but Friday night in a Sweet 16 loss
to the Florida Gators, the lack of Tournament-proven experience
contributed mightily to the Blue Devils' not having what it took to
finish off a feisty Gators team.
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa, on the other hand, features three seniors, a junior and a
third-year sophomore in its starting five. When the Golden
Hurricane fell behind Miami with less than seven minutes remaining
Friday night, it calmly and deliberately made every play, made
every perfect rotation defensively, sank critical free throws down
the stretch and walked away with an 80-71 win.
</P>
<P>
   Only one Tulsa starter stands taller than 6-5. Not one was a
high school All-American. The only Hurricane player widely
recruited was 6-10 center Brandon Kurtz, and the only reason he
wound up at Tulsa out of Bakersfield (Calif.) College was because
his coach was a friend of Tulsa head coach Bill Self.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, we were loaded with big guys, and I told
(Bakersfield coach Mark Arce) that we didn't need a big guy,'' Self
said. ``He told me, `You'll need this one.' (Kurtz) is a low-post
presence, and there just aren't that many in the college game right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   There's lots of them in the NBA, of course. But what will you
watch on TV today?
</P>
<P>
   While the overall talent level in the college game might not be
as high as it once was, parity has made the NCAA Tournament's
allure better, not worse.
</P>
<P>
   Two words: Single elimination.
</P>
<P>
   It is why teams such as Tulsa and Gonzaga can pull out huge wins
on any given Tournament day and captivate the nation. No superstars
equals balance. Given the right coach, which Self certainly is,
anything can happen.
</P>
<P>
   In the Tournament's second-round match, Cincinnati was without
stud big man Kenyon Martin, who broke his leg in the Conference USA
tournament. The Bearcats struggled to find a fluid game against the
Hurricane and were scrambling to find a leader in the final
minutes. Meanwhile, Tulsa calmly breezed from behind to take out
Cincy with yet another cool late-game run.
</P>
<P>
   Experience equals a legitimate chance to knock off squads that
feature high school all-Americans. Squads like Duke, Cincinnati, or
Tulsa's opponent today, North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I like about our team is you have to defend all five, not
two or three,'' Self said. ``If one guy isn't on, maybe three
others are, and that's a big plus.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Kurtz was huge in the win over Miami, as much with
his clever passing and tough rebounding in the first half as with
his 17 second-half points. Leading scorer David Shelton struggled
for Tulsa, but Eric Coley and guard Greg Harrington filled the
void.
</P>
<P>
   The best player on Tulsa's team is likely the high-hopping 6-5
forward, Coley, but he, too, was not a big-time recruit. Oklahoma
State showed the most interest of the big basketball schools, but
Cowboys coach Eddie Sutton backed away in the final days of
recruiting, and Coley signed with the Hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team plays well together, and that's half the battle right
there,'' Coley said. ``We know our niche, and when we find it, we
run with it. What we've done (in the Tournament) is no different
than what we've done in the first 30-something games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricane can play great basketball even without a great
player. No Tulsa player in the regular rotation averages more than
14 points, but five average in double figures. One, maybe two,
should earn a chance in an NBA camp when their eligibility expires.
</P>
<P>
   Superstars? Not at Tulsa. But that's what makes them so good.
That's what can make any experienced, balanced, gritty team slay
the high school All-Americans. And that's why the NCAA Tournament's
feared demise was greatly exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-00 0108EST &QL; 
