<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8309 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-MICHST-IOWAST-HNS     03-26 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MICHST-IOWAST-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY WIZIG  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ For the third straight time in the most
precarious of situations, Michigan State looked at a glaring sign
that read ``Exit'' from the NCAA Tournament.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And once again, the Spartans survived, thanks to Morris
Peterson's late awakening and Andre Hutson's heroic defense that
carried Michigan State to a stirring 75-64 triumph over Iowa State
on Saturday night in the Midwest Regional final at the Palace of
Auburn Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, for the second straight year, the Spartans join another
Big Ten school in the Final Four next week. This time, it will be
West Regional champ Wisconsin, making its first Final Four
appearance since winning the 1941 title. A year ago, it was Ohio
State.
</P>
<P>
   It is also the fifth time since 1980 that the Big Ten has
provided half of the Final Four, with Michigan in 1989 the only
national champion out of that group.
</P>
<P>
   After a rib-rattling battle that at times called to mind the
32-5 Cyclones' nationally renowned wrestling program, the Spartans
(30-7) will arrive at the Final Four as the lone No. 1 seed to
survive. They will be matched against a Wisconsin team they beat
twice in the Big Ten regular season and again in the conference
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, voted the regional's Most Valuable Player, provided 13
of his 18 points in the second half, including seven of MSU's 11
points in a critical stretch in the last 4:37. Hutson, a 6-7
junior, got help from 6-9 A.J. Granger and others in jousting with
Marcus Fizer, ISU's 6-8, 265-pound center.
</P>
<P>
   Hutson also paired 17 points with 11 rebounds, and Granger added
18 points. Mateen Cleaves had 10 points with only two assists and
five turnovers, but he played stern defense on Cyclones point guard
Jamaal Tinsley.
</P>
<P>
   After a near-brawl of a game that brought one technical to
Michigan State coach Tom Izzo and two technicals and an ejection in
the final seconds to Iowa State's Larry Eustachy, Izzo perceived
the evening in the only way that was logical.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' he said, ``was the most incredible game I've been a
part of in my five years at Michigan State.''
</P>
<P>
   And no wonder. After trailing Utah by six in the second half in
the Midwest's second round, then Syracuse by 14 in the second half
of the Midwest semifinals Thursday night, the Spartans were behind
59-52 with 5:49 left when ISU's Kantrail Horton hit two free throws
following Izzo's technical.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had lost the game, there would have been a trail through
the whole state,'' said Izzo, referring to the unhappy MSU fans who
might have been after him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some coaches know when to pick their spots to get a T, and
since we won the game, I have to say that coach picked the right
time,'' said Cleaves as Izzo smiled at him.
</P>
<P>
   Granger then hit a 3-pointer for the Spartans that again aroused
their huge gathering among the crowd of 21,214. Fizer, the
Cyclones' main man, then muscled up an inside jumper between two
defenders, but it would be his final points of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, 3-of-11 shooting at the time, lobbed in a trey from
the corner, and Charlie Bell sank two free throws when Fizer was
called for his fourth foul on an illegal screen, one of several
calls that enraged Eustachy.
</P>
<P>
   With the Cyclones ahead 61-60, ISU's Paul Shirley drove inside
and collided with Bell, with Bell apparently called for a foul
before the officials decided a double foul was proper. The
possession arrow favored ISU, and at that point his assistants had
to restrain Izzo. But Horton missed, and Hutson rebounded.
</P>
<P>
   Bell's jumper connected from the right wing, and the Spartans
regained the lead 62-61 with 2:54 remaining, a margin that grew to
67-61 with 53 seconds to play, increasing MSU's run to 15-2. In
their previous game, the Spartans had held Syracuse scoreless for
the final 5:54 during a closing 17-0 burst, so it was as close to a
reprise as possible.
</P>
<P>
   After Fizer missed from underneath, Izzo called a timeout, and
the Spartans then set up Cleaves' lob to Peterson over the 6-3
Tinsley for a slam that kept the MSU spree alive. Peterson then
added two free throws and Cleaves one of two, but Michael Nurse's
3-pointer with 44 seconds left reduced the MSU lead to 67-64.
Peterson's two free throws made the margin safer, and then Eustachy
briefly lost control with 9.9 seconds to go when Nurse was called
for a foul on Hutson. The ensuing two technicals on Eustachy and
Nurse's personal resulted in six closing free throws.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, the Cyclones failed to take advantage of a
monstrous 12-1 early rebound edge, offset by 10 Iowa State
turnovers in the first 10 minutes. The Spartans went 9{ minutes
before taking down their second rebound of the night, yet they led
14-12 at that juncture on a Bell jump shot.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves' 15-footer from out front gave the Spartans a 23-19
lead, but the Cyclones rallied with a 10-4 run with Fizer on the
bench for the final 4:30 before halftime with his second personal.
In Fizer's absence from the paint area, Hutson laid in a basket off
a Granger assist, then Granger took Cleaves' only assist of the
first half for another MSU layup and a 31-29 lead. After Shirley's
two free throws tied it at 31 for ISU, Cleaves hit again for the
Spartans' 34-31 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, the Cyclones held a 38-27 rebounding edge over the
nation's No. 1 rebounding team but shot only 35.5 percent in the
second half as they ended the best season in school history.
</P>
<P>
   Neither team was especially accurate, with ISU 9-of-26 on 3s,
five of them by Nurse, and Michigan State 5-of-19. But in the match
of pit bulls that filled the night, it was to be expected.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
