<DOCNO> NYT20000326.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8310 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-TPC-HNS &LR;      03-26 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TPC-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ Hal Sutton wants it known that he will
not ``roll over and play dead.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Never mind that it looked Saturday as if he already had suffered
a lethal injection into the lake surrounding the 17th green at the
Tournament Players Course at Sawgrass. Sutton is downright defiant
about going head-up against Tiger Woods today in the final round of
The Players Championship.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, this one comes straight out of the
be-careful-what-you-wish-for file. As early as Wednesday before the
tournament began, Sutton made a point of saying that Woods doesn't
intimidate him. Now, Sutton has a chance to put the money _ $1.08
million for the winner _ where his mouth is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to start anything, but he's one shot down going
into tomorrow,'' Sutton said after limping to the end Saturday with
a triple-bogey 6 on golf's most famous par-3. ``Obviously, it's
deflating. I'd like to have the four-shot lead back. But I can't
take it back. So I'll just take what I have and go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton's situation going into the final round today is sort of
like sitting down to enjoy a gourmet dinner and then realizing
you'll have to pick bones out of every bite of the fish. It could
have been as easy as picking through a fillet if not for the 17th.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've both got some work to do,'' Sutton said. ``Probably,
we'll have to get down in the dirt and fight a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton threw away the chance to start the battle with a serious
advantage. Before the 17th, he still was four strokes ahead of
Woods. As it turned out, Sutton had to settle for his third
consecutive 69 and a 9-under-par 207 total. Woods, who never had
broken 70 at the TPC as a pro, shattered that stat with a 6-under
66 and will start today at 8-under 208. Tom Lehman is a distant
third at 5-under 211 after double-bogeying 18 for a third-round 72.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I play for _ to be paired on Sunday in The Players
Championship with the greatest player in the world,'' Sutton said.
``That's what you dream about as a little boy _ a long time ago for
me. I'm glad I'm in the last group playing with Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very confident. I mean, to stand up there on 18 after
making triple bogey and letting Tiger back into the tournament like
that, I played good (on the finishing hole). So I felt like I had
control of my golf swing.''
</P>
<P>
   He had control of the tournament for the longest time Saturday
as it became increasingly clear through the day that Woods was
going to be the only pursuer with a realistic chance of running
down Sutton.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Woods birdied four of his first six holes, he couldn't
bite into Sutton's lead, which was only a shot over Lehman and Omar
Uresti starting the day but _ with those players backpedaling _
quickly grew.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton was sizzling yet kept dodging the heat-seeking missile
that is Woods, who had tracked Sutton the way the Pentagon keeps
tabs on satellites. But every time he lined up Sutton for a direct
hit of birdies or an eagle, Sutton hit his own thrusters and bolted
further out of Woods' view.
</P>
<P>
   There was a three-hole birdie binge starting on No. 5, with the
longest putt coming from 15 feet. When Woods bogeyed the 10th after
he knocked his approach over the green, he was losing touch with
Sutton. The lead, first three, then four shots, had become a
massive six-stroke advantage as Sutton was 11 under par. He was
heading into another galaxy, far, far away from a mere all-world
player like Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying,'' Sutton said, ``to answer everything he did.''
</P>
<P>
   And then Sutton burned up on re-entry at the notorious 17th hole
at the TPC at Sawgrass. Rarely has a splashdown been more
injurious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to recall that shot on 17, but I'm not sure I'd play
it any differently,'' he said. ``I put a good swing on it. We had
145 yards, and I hit a three-quarter 9-iron. I don't normally hit
it that far.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, the ball one-hopped over the island green and into
the water. Sutton dropped but watched Uresti hit a ball into the
water again from the drop area. Overly cautious, Sutton left his
70-yard pitch about 50 feet short, and his first putt came up 15
feet shy. He narrowly missed the double-bogey putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hollering `uncle' the whole time and couldn't get away
from that hole,'' Sutton said. ``It was a triple bogey. But it
wasn't the end of the world, because I had it to give back. That's
why I said I had to accept it and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   For Woods, this was like giving him a hand up off the mat. A
four-shot deficit against one of the world's top players would have
been a tall order today. Now, he is one down and basically
toe-to-toe with Sutton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ultimate goal is to win,'' Woods said. ``In order to (do
that) you've got to beat the rest of the field. I'm going to go out
there and play my own game and see what happens. Obviously, Hal
might think a little different (with only a one-shot lead).''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton even seemed to get a little defensive about his
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is you've got the greatest championship in the game
and you've got the best player in the world, according to the world
rankings, right there on my tail,'' Sutton said. ``Now that doesn't
mean he is going to win, even though everybody else in the world is
trying to figure out a way for him to go ahead and do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to make any other points. The only point I really
want to make is driving it in the fairway on the first tee. I will
start trying to make my points after that.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Saturday's developments proved to Sutton that
he should be prepared for anything and everything today.
</P>
<P>
   That is part of what makes the Tournament Players Course at
Sawgrass so intriguing, he said. Sutton said you have to expect the
unexpected. Then, he amended his thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be willing to accept the unexpected,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
