<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8312 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-LAPD-RAMPART-LADN &LR;      03-26 1378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAPD-RAMPART-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Eds. note: this is a copyrighted story 
By BETH BARRETT AND GREG GITTRICH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES, Calif. -- Confronted with confidential internal
memos, the District Attorney's Office admits that a highly regarded
prosecutor urged his bosses to file conspiracy charges against
several Rampart Division cops -- days before he was pulled off the
LAPD corruption task force.
</P>
<P>
   The office's backpedaling Saturday came one day after District
Attorney Gil Garcetti, responding to a Los Angeles Daily News
report on the thwarted prosecution effort, denied on a local radio
talk show that Deputy District Attorney George Rosenstock had
aggressively sought approval to indict cops involved in a brutal
station-house beating.
</P>
<P>
   Garcetti, who has refused repeated requests for interviews,
insisted on KCRW's ``Which Way L.A.'' that the controversy was
manufactured by the Los Angeles Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   When faced Saturday with a series of confidential memos obtained
by the Daily News, Garcetti's spokeswoman Sandi Gibbons
acknowledged that Rosenstock wanted to file the first criminal
charges against cops other than Rafael Perez, the central figure in
the worst police corruption case in city history.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbons said other top D.A. officials were aware of the memos,
but insisted Garcetti was never informed by the senior prosecutors
he hand- picked to lead the task force.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no reason for them to notify him (Garcetti). It was
just a memo, basically a prosecutor's assessment of what needed to
be done,'' Gibbons said. ``He (Garcetti) probably would have been
notified when they were ready to file.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcetti was wrong when he said Rosenstock was pulled off the
Rampart prosecution team at his own request. According to Gibbons,
Garcetti meant to say Rosenstock asked to be assigned to Long
Beach, almost 24 miles southwest of Los Angeles, after he was
removed.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenstock, who now handles routine, low-profile cases, first
explained his prosecutorial plan in memos last December, including
one sent to Head Deputy District Attorney Clifford Klein, who was
then in charge of the corruption probe. Rosenstock specifically
noted that he believed enough evidence existed to prosecute
disgraced officer Brian Hewitt for a vicious 1998 station-house
beating. Rosenstock added that he needed more information from the
LAPD.
</P>
<P>
   In the ensuing two months, the deputy district attorney
repeatedly updated Klein, members of the LAPD, de facto lead
prosecutor Richard Rosenthal, and eventually Dan Murphy, the man
chosen by Garcetti in January to lead the police corruption task
force.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenstock's efforts culminated in a Feb. 4 memo to Murphy and
five other prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the six pages of correspondence, Rosenstock explained
in detail that he had a solid conspiracy case against Hewitt and at
least three other officers involved in the Feb. 26, 1998,
station-house beating of Ismael Jimenez.
</P>
<P>
   While Rosenstock could not be reached for comment, there is no
mistaking his intent. He led off the memo with this
straight-forward declaration:
</P>
<P>
   ``Each of the prosecution theories outlined herein are viewed by
the writer as viable and are recommended for filing.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on to underscore the importance of filing a conspiracy
case against the elite anti-gang officers in Rampart's now
disbanded Community Resources Against Street Hoodlums unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rampart CRASH conspiracy includes a heightened danger to
the public welfare even beyond that which may be expected from
conspiracies among law enforcement officers because the conspiracy
was so extensive as to include intimidating witnesses to official
wrongdoing from registering complaints with appropriate authorities
further insulating the conspiracy from discovery,'' Rosenstock
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after he sent the memo, Rosenstock was yanked from
the task force by Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the incident said the decision to exile
Rosenstock, who was highly regarded by LAPD investigators, was a
significant flashpoint in the acrimonious relationship between
Garcetti and Police Chief Bernard C. Parks.
</P>
<P>
   After learning about Rosenstock's fate, sources said, LAPD
detectives felt all of their work gathering evidence to prosecute
Hewitt was being mishandled and swept under the rug.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequently, Parks increased his calls for Garcetti to
immediately indict dirty cops. The chief repeatedly mentioned
Hewitt and two other cops by name. In response, Garcetti said he
was being thorough to ensure the investigation was complete and
charged that police investigators were refusing to cooperate with
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   In sworn statements last September,
corrupt-cop-turned-key-informant Perez said he and other cops shot
at least one unarmed man, routinely framed suspected gang members
for crimes, and lied in court to send innocent people to jail. To
date, 46 convictions have been overturned, and at least 20 officers
have been removed from duty, if not fired.
</P>
<P>
   No cops have been indicted.
</P>
<P>
   Garcetti has consistently argued that his office shares none of
the blame for the scandal even though his prosecutors put scores of
innocent people behind bars without a clue of wrongdoing. He has
come to refer to the corruption as the LAPD's ``mess'' and has
rejected any calls for an outside review of his office's handling
of perhaps hundreds of cases involving falsified evidence and
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   In Rosenstock's final memo before being removed, he concluded:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rampart/CRASH conspiracy appears to be an especially
insidious form of (an) illegal agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibbons said Saturday that senior prosecutors had received at
least two pieces of the Rosenstock correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   The first memo was written in early December to Klein. The
second was a ``personal and confidential'' memo to Assistant
District Attorney Michael Tranbarger, written after after
Rosenstock was reassigned. Gibbons said she was unable to reach
other senior prosecutors to track down additional confidential
memos obtained by the Los Angeles Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   The two memos Gibbons referenced went all the way up the chain
of command but never were submitted to Garcetti himself, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Together, all of the Rosenstock memos paint a picture of a
conscientious prosecutor seeking a broad body of evidence from the
police as he was building a legal foundation to indict cops on
conspiracy charges. All along, he kept his bosses informed.
</P>
<P>
   In some instances, he described a tense relationship with the
police and expressed difficulty getting some information from the
Internal Affairs unit. But sources said Rosenstock was well
respected by police for his ability and thoroughness.
</P>
<P>
   Citing his experience as a federal prosecutor in New York,
Rosenstock was convinced by early February that he had enough
evidence to corroborate Perez's sworn statements about officers
being in a conspiratorial ``loop'' to commit crimes or cover up
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The ``loop'' is ``in essence, the description of an express
and/or tacit agreement to commit the unlawful acts of obstruction
of justice, perjury, witness intimidation, and filing of false
reports,'' Rosenstock wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In the Hewitt case, Rosenstock noted that cops badgered a
witness to withhold information.
</P>
<P>
   They warned: ``Don't say (expletive) to them (Internal
Affairs).'' Hewitt, who was fired for the beating, has denied any
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   In sworn statements to investigators, Perez has said Hewitt
enjoyed beating up people and was in ``the loop.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Rosenstock's work, sources said, Murphy was reluctant to
file the indictments because he wanted more corroboration of
Perez's statements from other cops.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy also rebuffed Rosenstock's efforts to bring in federal
agents to help LAPD investigators, sources said. Eventually, six
federal agents joined the task force at Parks' request on Feb. 23
-- nearly three weeks after Rosenstock's reassignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Rosenstock) had a new office, a new fax, a new team,'' said
attorney Dennis Chang, who represents the man beaten by Hewitt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then there was nothing,'' Chang said. ``It went completely
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   --30--
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
