<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS STILL HAVE MAJOR QUESTIONS TO ANSWER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since we've all now witnessed it, there is no debate _ the road
to the Stanley Cup is the ultimate in grueling journeys. For sheer
physical and mental torture, the NHL proudly gives us the mother of
all playoff systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom'' was good to the Stars a year ago. ``Mom'' is about to
come calling again.
</P>
<P>
   It's two weeks and counting. The regular season is in deep
stretch. The Stars' world championship defense begins the second
week in April.
</P>
<P>
   Is this team Cup-ready? Compared to a year ago, it's not even
close. Too many injuries have caused too much turmoil, and this has
been going on since the first puck dropped in October. Plus, clubs
with only one scoring line tend to take an early playoff hike. At
the moment, if it's not Modano and Co., the goals don't come
consistently enough.
</P>
<P>
   But at this late stage, opinions from within the locker room are
more important than shooting from the hip in a newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, here's a sampling:
</P>
<P>
   Best team the Stars have faced this season?
</P>
<P>
   ``St. Louis,'' coach Ken Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   ``St. Louis, positionally and defensively, is right there,''
center Joe Nieuwendyk said. ``Detroit is a different club, but very
explosive on offense. And from what I'm seeing of Colorado lately,
that team is suddenly looking great.''
</P>
<P>
   ``St. Louis reminds me of us a year ago, and that's very
dangerous,'' winger Jamie Langenbrunner said. ``Colorado changed
some faces, and you have to watch out for them. Detroit is still
very tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the locker room, there was eager anticipation about
Colorado's visit to Reunion Arena this afternoon. ``That's been a
different team since we last saw them,'' Nieuwendyk said.
</P>
<P>
   But for wire-to-wire consistency in this regular season, there
has been nothing in the NHL to compare to St. Louis. The kicker
here, of course, is that the Blues have the best record in the
league behind the goaltending of a certain ex-Star.
</P>
<P>
   In the form of Roman Turek, the Stars traded the Presidents'
Trophy to St. Louis. Did they also trade the Stanley Cup?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I told you I'd never had a second thought about that deal,
then I'd have to spend several hours in the confessional,'' Stars
general manager Bob Gainey said. ``I guess we'll cross that bridge
when we come to it, if we come to it. There are plenty of
challenges, however, between now and then.''
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner, pausing and smiling at the mention of last
summer's trade, added, ``that was unfortunate the way that whole
thing happened. Turek is doing great. But if we face him in the
playoffs, we'll have to hope we can score some goals on him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Time will tell on how that trade impacts us,'' Nieuwendyk
said, smiling. ``Let's hope it doesn't come back to haunt us.''
</P>
<P>
   On the question of concern about the Turek trade also resulting
in a Stanley Cup trade, Hitchcock had a quick reply. ``There's none
at all. We know how long and difficult the process is. At the end
of the day, it's going to be all about us, not about anyone on the
opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Without a doubt, however, the Turek situation adds to the
upcoming playoff intrigue for the Stars. As if defending a world
championship wasn't enough ...
</P>
<P>
   What if there is a future meeting with the Blues? What if Turek
wins the duel with Eddie Belfour? Would the second-guessing ever
end?
</P>
<P>
   How do you compare the Stars right now with where the team was a
year ago?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's hard to judge,''Nieuwendyk said. ``Due to injuries,
we've still got players coming and going. I don't know yet if this
team is ready for the playoffs. A year ago, without question, we
were. And we were also the favorite to win it all. This time that
won't be the case.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting close to ready, but unlike this time a year ago,
we aren't there yet,'' Langenbrunner said. ``Maybe all the
adversity, and what we've had to overcome, helps us in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What I see right now is a lot of energy and a lot of
enthusiasm,'' Hitchcock said. ``Last year, we were a methodical,
workmanlike club. By comparison, this team is almost giddy in
nature. The pressure isn't there like a year ago. We know what to
expect, know what it takes, but overall, we have the same
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   The time is near. ``Mother'' is calling. Only the baddest of the
bad should bother to answer. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
