<HEADER>
A8314 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-CAR-LEBRETON-NASCAR-T     03-26 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-LEBRETON-NASCAR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR'S PROBLEMS NOT SO BAD, BUT KEEP IT TO YOURSELF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the annual pilgrimage of NASCAR nation prepares to descend
upon us, we learn that not all is well.
</P>
<P>
   The races have been ``less interesting,'' or so some say. The
media won't cooperate. The drivers won't drive fender-to-fender.
And when driver Dale Jarrett tried to say something about it all,
he was taken to task so swiftly that he apologized the very next
week and said, ``I promise to race hard and keep my opinions to
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than that _ and, oh, yes, the empty seats _ it's been a
grand Winston Cup season.
</P>
<P>
   Is NASCAR's 15 minutes of fame over?
</P>
<P>
   Some may think so. Some may even write it. But NASCAR recently
celebrated its 50th year of racing, which suggests a lot more
staying power than just exhaust fumes.
</P>
<P>
   The question was posed to Eddie Gossage, who has a uniquely
vested interest in NASCAR's ongoing vitality. As general manager of
Texas Motor Speedway, Gossage next Sunday has to fill 170,000
seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal take is that the season has not been as bad as
some have said, but on the other hand it's not as good as it's been
in the past, either,'' Gossage said.
</P>
<P>
   Fair enough. Gossage likened the Winston Cup series to an NFL
season, with its cycles of nail-biters and blowouts.
</P>
<P>
   The Cracker Barrel 500 in Atlanta earlier this month ended in a
mesmerizing photo finish. On the other hand, the Daytona 500, the
sport's showpiece, was barely more exciting than the postrace
traffic jam.
</P>
<P>
   Even people inside the sport, however, are admitting that the
racing has been different this season. They blame prominently the
circuit's switch to steel-belted radial tires. The old ones, the
bias-ply models, may have been prone to cuts and punctures, but the
drivers say that at least they knew what they were getting in the
corners.
</P>
<P>
   The tires were changed for safety reasons. But therein lies the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR, some would suggest, has become too safe for its own
good. Even when Jarrett talked himself into the verbal wall a few
weeks ago, he was patched up and fitted with press conference
``restrictor plates,'' and NASCAR sent him on his way.
</P>
<P>
   The sport needs characters. Its grassroots fans grew up watching
Cale Yarborough battle the Allisons. It needs tracks with
personality, like Bristol, where the drivers are racing this
weekend. And rather than single-file, follow-the-leader racing, it
needs more paint-swapping, side-by-side contests, even if it means
slowing the cars down another 15-20 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   But there we media people go, trying to influence the paying
public again. And the folks at NASCAR seem not to know exactly how
to handle that.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Winston Cup season began, writers noted that the new
credential application contained language by which the organization
claimed rights to every picture, quotation and printed word seen or
heard at a NASCAR event.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has been muzzled. Someone must have gotten hold of the
Bill of Rights.
</P>
<P>
   But cloaked in Jarrett's original charges was the implication
that the media, as a way of sniping back at NASCAR's feeble try at
censorship, was going out of its way to criticize the racing.
</P>
<P>
   No, I would argue, we wouldn't do that. But the old guard is
changing. There is a different breed of reporter covering the
NASCAR circuit these days _ and more of them, as the number of
tracks expands.
</P>
<P>
   And discontent, whether it comes from a frustrated driver or
from a fan who bought a $50 ticket and sat in a four-hour traffic
jam, makes good copy.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR does have a problem with rising prices. (In fairness, it
should be noted that Bruton Smith, whose Speedway Motorsports Inc.,
owns TMS, lowered prices for some tickets at Charlotte).
</P>
<P>
   But this is an organization, remember, that just signed a
six-year, $2.6-billion TV deal. There were empty seats spotted at
Darlington, Rockingham and Atlanta, but the early-season Winston
Cup circuit is vulnerable to foul weather. Some of those empty
seats, too, were new seats, added mostly for that track's
more-popular second Winston Cup race.
</P>
<P>
   Gossage is confident that he will have a sellout _ all 170,000
worth. For the first time, the weekend's three main events will all
carry the names of big-time sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Has NASCAR peaked? There's a four-hour traffic jam next Sunday
that will prove absolutely not.
</P>
<P>
   But don't tell NASCAR I told you.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
