<SLUG> BC-HKC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-WISCONSIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO. 1 WISCONSIN TAKEN DOWN BY EAGLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Boston College, doing it the hard way once again,
is two victories away from its first ice hockey national
championship since 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday &UR;  &LR; night the Eagles took on the best in the West,
top-ranked Wisconsin, and whipped the Badgers, 4-1, at Mariucci
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   And now they'll be playing closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   The win set up a potential best-of-Boston battle in the Frozen
Four in Providence. BC will play the winner of Sunday's Boston
University-St. Lawrence East Regional game in one of the semifinals
April 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be interesting to see who we'll play,'' said standout
defenseman and captain Mike Mottau. ``It's exciting. We've been
there the last two years, and the experience could help get us over
the hump.''
</P>
<P>
   Said coach Jerry York: ``We want to win one of these Final
Fours. We're kind of geared up for Providence.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be the third straight Frozen Four appearance for the
Eagles. For the second year in a row, they played their way into
the championship round through the West Regional. Both years BC had
to win a pair of games, one of them against the top seed, to
advance.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Eagles (28-11-1) took out Northern Michigan and
North Dakota in Madison, Wis., before falling to eventual national
champion Maine, 2-1, in overtime in the semifinals. This year BC
victimized Michigan State _ with a last-minute goal to tie, then a
goal in overtime to win _ and Wisconsin (31-9-1), which had been
No. 1 in the country for much of the season.
</P>
<P>
   BC won this one on the strength of first-period goals by Blake
Bellefeuille and Brian Gionta for a 2-1 lead, an insurance goal by
Jeff Giuliano to open the third, and the 28-save goaltending of
junior Scott Clemmensen. Gionta added an empty-net goal with three
seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Clemmensen, shaky at times in Friday night's 6-5 overtime win
over Michigan State, was sharp all night. He had a dozen saves in
the second period _ including one on which he slid back into the
crease after going out after the puck, and one on Matt Doman with
his leg _ to preserve BC's lead.
</P>
<P>
   And before that, in the last minute of the first period,
Clemmensen stopped Andy Wheeler in close after Mottau had committed
a rare mistake. ``I think the player was just as surprised to get
the puck as everyone else was that he had it,'' Clemmensen said.
``He shot it right away, and fortunately I got my pad on it.''
</P>
<P>
   He got his pads on most of them throughout the game.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Michigan State game, ``I kind of got back on my heels
early,'' Clemmensen said. ``But I knew we still had a chance to
win, and that's my main goal _ to get the team in position to win,
no matter how badly I'm playing.''
</P>
<P>
   York said he gave no thought to replacing Clemmensen for
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night. Clemmensen had split time through much of the year
with Tim Kelleher, but York settled on Clemmensen and his stretch
run experience a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timmy's really good and if Scott pulls a groin or something,
he's ready to go,'' York said. ``But this is kind of Scott's team
to take us through.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemmensen, backed by Mottau and the defense, did just that
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, shutting down Wisconsin standout Steve Reinprecht
and his big line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they had that top scoring line,'' Mottau said. ``We
play five `D' and (Brooks Orpik's) hand was bothering him a little
in warmup and we didn't know if he'd be able to go. And he played
one of the best games of his career.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliano's goal gave the Eagles some breathing room as the third
period started. BC was just coming off a power play when Mike
Lephart burst around his man on the right wing. He shot and Graham
Melanson made the save, but the rebound bounced straight out to
Giuliano. With his back to the net and a defender all over him,
Giuliano got off a blind backhander that went under Melanson. It
was Giuliano's 10th goal of the year and first in his last eight
games.
</P>
<P>
   With a two-goal lead, the Eagles were flying. Toward Providence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
