<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLANDSWORTH WILL PROVE VALUABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ Devon White worked out at Dodgertown
rather than take the two-hour bus ride to play the Baltimore
Orioles on Saturday. Even so, F.P. Santangelo started in center
field while Todd Hollandsworth was in left.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody's mentioned to Hollandsworth where the battle with White
for the starting center-field position stands, but nobody needs to.
The facts, to Hollandsworth, are enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can read into it,'' Hollandsworth said. ``It's odd. You
can see what's going to happen. You can see Devon is playing there
all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``My impression is (manager) Davey (Johnson) is going to give
Devo a shot at it. That's Davey's decision, Davey's choice.''
</P>
<P>
   It leaves Hollandsworth with the role of backup outfielder. It's
a role he doesn't love, but his versatility makes it a natural. He
can play left, center or right field. And his left-handed bat is
just added incentive for the Los Angeles Dodgers to keep him,
though teams are constantly inquiring about him.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle general manager Pat Gillick has called numerous times
about Hollandsworth, but the Dodgers are unwilling to part with
him, particularly because of his versatility. Gary Sheffield missed
the last week with a hand injury, and Hollandsworth's been the
perfect replacement.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Dodgers had a big desire to trade Hollandsworth, it
probably would have happened prior to the 1999 season, when
Hollandsworth's agent, Jeff Moorad, said the one-time National
League Rookie of the Year wanted to be traded so he could start.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing the Dodgers' position, and a promise Hollandsworth would
be given a chance to beat out White, no such declaration was made
this past offseason. But the chance was given to Hollandsworth as a
way of motivating White, and it seemed to work.
</P>
<P>
   Though White is hitting just .216 this spring, he's played well
defensively. Hollandsworth, who has a team-high 57 at-bats and his
hitting .263, has been inconsistent at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   But Hollandsworth, 26, does have one thing in his favor. He's a
free agent after the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do whatever Davey wants me to do,'' Hollandsworth said.
``I'm confident Davey will use me a lot like he did last year.
Whether it's left, center or right, it doesn't matter. Whatever
helps us win. We all know what year it is. They know what year it
is. I know what year it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Orel outstanding: Right-hander Orel Hershiser continued his
sizzling spring by pitching five no-hit innings against the
Orioles. He issued one walk and hit a batter in lowering his spring
ERA to 1.80. Hershiser said he hasn't felt ``this good in the
regular season'' since `93 or `94.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm crisper and firmer, so I'm throwing the ball better,'' he
said. ``Now, it's more glimpses of the old guy (Hershiser).''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser would like to carry the spring success into the
season. He's 3-5 with a 5.60 ERA in his past three Aprils.
</P>
<P>
   Castro or Berroa?: The play of switch-hitting outfielder Tony
Mota this spring may change Johnson's plans to carry six
outfielders and, thus, six infielders. Originally, Geronimo Berroa
was going to be the sixth outfielder because Johnson thought the
organization lacked outfield depth and needed to keep him.
</P>
<P>
   Mota, sent to the minors Friday, changed that thinking and has
opened the way for infielder Juan Castro. A magician with the
glove, Castro lacks the offensive punch to be the regular
shortstop. However, because of his defense, he could be an ideal
late-inning defensive replacement for Kevin Elster, who is
consistent at shortstop but lacks range.
</P>
<P>
   Castro plays second, third and shortstop, and is out of
minor-league options. The Dodgers have talked about trading him,
but haven't found the right deal and they don't want to give him
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how to feel,'' said Castro, a career .188 hitter.
``Every chance (Johnson) gives me, I'm going to try to do my best.
I don't know what's going to happen. It's their decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Johnson said Sheffield, who's missed the last
eight games after injuring his left pinkie, would be in the lineup
today against the Marlins. Sheffield may need the at-bats. He said
he typically needs 35 to 40 at-bats in the spring to get his
timing, and he's had 23. He's batting .261.... Right-hander Eric
Gagne pitched six shutout innings in a Triple-A game against the
Mets, but it doesn't appear that will be enough to get him back in
contention with Carlos Perez for the final spot in the rotation.
Johnson said the reports on the outing were that Gagne was still
high in the zone. ``He showed signs of improvement. He looked more
comfortable,'' Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said....
Johnson dipped into minor-league camp and brought former Mets first
baseman Chris Donnells and infielder Mike Metcalfe on the two-hour
trip to Baltimore so he can get a look at them for later in the
season if injuries deplete the big-league club.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
