<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS CAN'T MISS -- CAN THEY?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A mismatched pair of 7-footers jump for a tipped
pass near the Los Angeles Lakers basket. Their extra-long limbs
become tangled, they lose their balance and they hit the floor,
Shaquille O'Neal tumbling backward over Luc Longley of the Phoenix
Suns and landing with a thump at the edge of the purple-painted
key.
</P>
<P>
   Longley scrambles to his feet and follows the action upcourt.
O'Neal briefly remains supine, perhaps to make sure his tailbone
and wrists and testy hamstrings are in one piece, and while he does
that, 19,000 pairs of eyes in the Staples Center Friday night are
locked on him.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal might be immobile for only a second, but it's a second
that seems to stretch to June.
</P>
<P>
   In such moments you sense the fragility of the Lakers'
championship potential, dreading what an injury to O'Neal or Kobe
Bryant would do to the season.
</P>
<P>
   Then Shaq leaps to his feet and the feeling passes.
</P>
<P>
   These days, with the Lakers 58-12 and all but assured of
finishing the regular season with the NBA's best record, it's hard
to imagine anything except an injury to one of their two star
players keeping the team from winning the title in June. Coach Phil
Jackson can keep saying, ``The regular season and the playoffs are
like two different seasons,'' but the words ring hollow, a dramatic
warning against complacency.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are on a pace to win 68 games, joining only 10 teams
in NBA history in the 65-and-up category, the mark of the great
regular season. Of those 10 teams, nine went on to win the NBA
title.
</P>
<P>
   They included the 69-win Lakers of 1972 and the 65-win Lakers of
1987. And three Jackson-coached Chicago teams, the 67-win Bulls of
1992, the record-setting 72-win Bulls of 1996 and the 69-win Bulls
of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was on the right side, also, in the only case of a
65-win team failing to win the title. That occurred in 1973, when
the Boston Celtics were beaten in the Eastern Conference final by
the New York Knicks, with whom the 27-year-old Jackson was a backup
front-court man. The Knicks had played part of the regular season
without injured Willis Reed, and the Celtics lost John Havlicek to
a bad shoulder for the series' seventh game, so this one could be
chalked up to medical circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The question for the Lakers, their coach and their fans is ...
What could go wrong now?
</P>
<P>
   I've come up with a short list.
</P>
<P>
   --O'Neal or Bryant could get hurt.
</P>
<P>
   --Another team could get hot and catch the Lakers in an
ill-timed cold spell.
</P>
<P>
   --John McCain could announce a third-conference candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Am I missing anything?
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers can't think of it, or if they can, they aren't
telling, since it's hard to talk and whistle in the dark at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell you the truth, I don't think anything can go wrong,''
Bryant said after the Lakers' sometimes-lazy, 109-101 victory over
the depleted Suns. ``My mind doesn't work like that, know what I
mean? As long as everybody stays healthy ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't want to focus on it,'' Rick Fox said of the
inevitability question. ``That's the kind of question that can only
give you a negative answer. Why would we want to focus on what can
go wrong?''
</P>
<P>
   The playoffs, when they get under way in less than a month, will
be different. More energetic, more physical. Opponents will have
more than 48 minutes to try to figure out how to beat L.A.
</P>
<P>
   To reach the finals, the Lakers might have to go through
Sacramento (the only team to beat them in one 24-game stretch),
Portland (which beat them at home and at the Staples Center) and
San Antonio (which handed them a 24-point defeat).
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Derek Fisher said, ``We don't feel there's any team
out there that can beat us in a series.'' And they shouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   After their 16-win streak in December and January, they lost six
of nine games and appeared shaken. But since having their 19-win
streak ended in March, they have won five games in a row. The
question about mental toughness seems to have been answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have said we've positioned ourselves as the best team
in the regular season. But,'' Fox said, ``they don't hand out a
trophy for that. Nothing's going to be given to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet it's fair to say that if the Lakers can play as well in
April, Mayand June as they have so far, a championship is
inevitable. As long as their MVP center and their all-around
slasher remain standing, and as long as complacency doesn't set in
(there's no reason to think it will).
</P>
<P>
   I asked Glen Rice about Jackson's warning about the difference
between the regular season and playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you expect to keep dominating teams the way you have?'' I
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not?'' Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   Knock on hardwood, it's a good question.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-00 0236EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000326.0023 </DOCNO>
