<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-PISTONS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS LOSE TO PISTONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Although pure coincidence is suspected, the Los
Angeles Clippers do seem to win about as often as they get paid ...
twice a month.
</P>
<P>
   With that quota satisfied for March, they failed to make a case
for a third paycheck during Saturday night's 126-107 loss to the
Detroit Pistons before 17,840 at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``They worked as hard as they could for 48 minutes,'' interim
coach Jim Todd said of a team that had just been waxed.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds fishy, but the Clippers did have a truly sweet alibi.
</P>
<P>
   For the third game in a row, a small-caliber ankle sprain KO'd
their most-willing shooter, Maurice Taylor. Gone was an opportunity
to audition for his hometown (Mo-town?) Pistons, who rate way up
there on Taylor's free-agent-to-be wish list.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Lamar ``Kingpin'' Odom, the Clippers' best player, was
reduced to civilian battle dress by a strained left calf. Odom
missed last Monday's loss to the Washington Wizards with a strained
right calf.
</P>
<P>
   Odom earned ``Kingpin'' status by rolling the ball the length of
the court to earn a spare technical following an unfavorable call
Thursday in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Tyrone Nesby (22 points), Michael Olowokandi (21), and
Eric Piatkowski (20) served as top guns. Olowokandi had a mere 3
personal fouls and just 3 rebounds, because Detroit (a toasty 63.3
percent from the field) rarely misfired.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play no defense,'' said Nesby for all who were
wondering. ``They had us on our toes all night.''
</P>
<P>
   Seems as if they were stepping on your toes, Tyrone.
</P>
<P>
   With 31 points from Jerry Stackhouse, 19 from celebrated
sidekick Grant Hill, 20 from Lindsay Hunter and impressive
button-pushing by interim head coach George Irvine, Detroit (36-33)
was able to triumph for the eighth time in its last 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to get a kick in the butt,'' said Stackhouse,
referring to Irvine's appointment as head coach and not Saturday's
foe.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers (14-57) chaperoned their losing streak to seven,
while maintaining the lead for the top seed in the NBA Draft
lottery. They jumped ahead of Chicago on Friday when the Bulls lost
their heads and defeated Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The Pistons, who lost Friday night at Sacramento, opened up in a
nasty defensive mood, shot 66.7 percent from the field and led,
35-25, after one quarter. They fired away at a 77.8 percent rate in
round two and held a relatively tolerable 68-52 lead at
intermission.
</P>
<P>
   After taking Detroit's best shot, the Clippers trimmed the
deficit to as little as 11 points midway through the third quarter
before fading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you're short-handed or not, you can't give up 126
points,'' Todd said.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Saturday's Clipper down-and-out list included Keith Closs,
who bowed out due to an asthma attack during pre-game warm-ups.
Closs was taken to the hospital, received medication and will be
evaluated Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-00 0237EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
