<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNEDY IMPRESSIVE IN DEBUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. _ Adam Kennedy began his Anaheim Angels career
with a bang Saturday afternoon, hitting a home run in his first
at-bat, and adding a two-run triple in the Angels' 10-0 victory
over the San Francisco Giants at Scottsdale Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Batting second in the lineup, Kennedy hit the second pitch he
saw over the right-field fence off Giants starter Russ Ortiz to
give the Angels a 2-0 lead. He finished the day 2 for 5 with four
RBI, one spectacular defensive play at second base, several good
plays and one throwing error to make an immediate impression on his
new team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great way for a guy to break in,'' Angels manager
Mike Scioscia said. ``He played the game hard. He was tested and
did a great job. It's exciting to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, acquired along with pitcher Kent Bottenfield Thursday
in a trade for Jim Edmonds, is excited about the opportunity to win
the starting second base job, but he said he wasn't nervous about
making a good first impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go through it all the time before a game,'' said Kennedy,
who grew up in Riverside and was a standout at Cal State
Northridge. ``You get the adrenaline going and the excitement of
playing. It wasn't too different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone here has made it easy for me. The adjustment has been
happening gradually.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia hasn't said for sure if Kennedy will bat second, but
Kennedy is comfortable there.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the spot I hit in the last couple of years,'' he said.
``It's a big responsibility right there, with Darin (Erstad)
getting on base in front of me and big Mo (Vaughn) behind me. It's
just a great spot to hit in.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting pitcher Kent Mercker was the beneficiary of Kennedy's
play on a sharply hit ball by Marvin Benard in the fifth inning.
Kennedy backhanded the ball on a short-hop and threw Benard out.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was what I saw last year,'' said Mercker, who played for
the Cardinals last season. ``He's a good player. You don't get
picked in the first round and win minor league player of the year
for nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong outing: Mercker took a big step toward winning a spot in
the starting rotation with five scoreless innings. He allowed two
hits and only one Giants baserunner got as far as third base, as
Mercker improved to 3-0 with a 3.78 ERA this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his ever-improving chances of starting the season in
the rotation, Mercker shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to worry about getting people out,'' he said. ``I
don't worry about making the team, if I'm going to start, play the
outfield or play catcher. I know what I can do. It's tough enough
to get hitters out at this level than to add pressure that if I
don't get guys out I'm going to be gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival watch: Closer Troy Percival pitched a scoreless inning,
allowing one hit. He was clocked at 93 mph, but said he thought he
was up to 97 warming up in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warming up in the 'pen was the best I've felt all spring,''
Percival said. ``When I got in the game I overthrew a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival, coming off shoulder surgery, has an ERA of 5.14 in
seven spring games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
