<SLUG> BC-BBN-BELTRE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY BELTRE IS WORTH IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ Adrian Beltre stands at third and rubs the
heal of his glove. As the pitcher begins his wind-up, the third
baseman takes a couple of quick, tiny steps to ready himself before
diving left to snare a grounder. He pops up and fires the ball to
first for an out.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre makes it look so wonderful and simple at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   It is why Los Angeles Dodgers managing partner, CEO and superfan
Bob Daly sat through 18 negotiating sessions, and held countless
phone conversations with Beltre's agent, Scott Boras.
</P>
<P>
   For as aggravating as the last five months could be for the
Dodgers - not to mention the fans - as Beltre sought free agency,
the real reason the Dodgers signed him wasn't because they felt bad
about the previous regime's illegal signing.
</P>
<P>
   Daly and the Dodgers singed Beltre because he's already one of
the premier third baseman in baseball. And with the ink dry on the
three-year, $5.05 million deal that will keep Beltre around for at
least the next five years, that can again be the focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has great talent, but he also has great instincts,'' said
utility infielder Jose Vizcaino, Beltre's closest confidant on the
Dodgers. ``That's going to help him a lot. It's like when (Rey)
Ordonez came up. He made all those plays because he had great
instinct.''
</P>
<P>
   It is talent and instinct and many other things that has Beltre
in his current on-field situation. With no help from Ponce De Leon,
Beltre enters his second consecutive season as a 20-year-old. He
just happens to be one of the most mature 20-year-olds around.
</P>
<P>
   In one year, Beltre's metamorphosis is incredible. An offseason
of workouts, playing in his native Dominican Republic and plain ol'
growing has changed his physical appearance. He's added muscle
mass, but only added a few pounds.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a transformation in Beltre's demeanor. He came to
spring training a year ago as a wide-eyed 19-year-old unsure of
what he should be doing, or what was expected of him.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, with confusion and turmoil surrounding him, he
maintained his calm. Through the chaos of an offseason filled with
interviews from the commissioner's office and the baseball world
focused on his case, Beltre remained composed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it comes from hanging around people that were older
than me when I was growing up,'' Beltre said. ``It's family and
friends. I saw the way they acted, and they were very mature. I
think it's the way it rubbed off on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Davey Johnson shielded Beltre in every possible way last
season. Johnson never criticized him despite his 29 errors, and
never showed concern about a one- or two-week slump at the plate.
When Beltre faltered in the second spot in the batting order,
Johnson quietly moved him back to seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre was handed the third base job, but didn't fully know what
to make of it. He thought he had to show he belonged during every
drill, every day. After hitting .275 with 15 homers, 67 RBI and 18
stolen bases, at, as it turns out, the age of 19, things are
different for Beltre.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to make a mistake last year because I didn't
want to go back to the minor leagues,'' Beltre said. ``This year
I'm more relaxed because I'm supposed to have my position so I'm
working on things I need to work on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked on a lot of things, like my throwing to first. I was
disappointed with it last year, and I'm working at hitting the ball
better to the opposite field, and being more relaxed and not try to
rush the play.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not just Beltre's talent, though the soft hands, strong arm
and tremendous instinct don't hurt. It's Beltre's attitude which
made Daly so willing to negotiate a deal.
</P>
<P>
   During the five-month saga, Beltre never complained publicly. He
never threatened not to play for the Dodgers. He never showed any
disdain toward the organization that signed him at 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the type of player we're trying to build the
organization around,'' Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said.
``We believe he has all the things we want. He's a hard worker,
he's a competitor, he wants to win, he carries himself in the right
way. He's the kind of player you can build an organization
around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
