<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND THE WINNER IS ... FINAL FOUR, CBS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ The Final Four was going to be glamorous,
all right. In the same way tonight's Academy Awards gala would be
if all the nominated actresses arrived in baggy sweats and scuffed
sneakers, with their hair uncombed and their faces unmade.
</P>
<P>
   With fewer than five minutes remaining in Saturday's Midwest
Regional final, Michigan State trailed Iowa State by six points in
front of what appeared to be the entire population of East Lansing.
</P>
<P>
   A tournament that had lost its razzle in a rash of upsets was
watching its dazzle evaporate like cheap perfume.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans were by far the most esteemed team of the surviving
eight. They were the last No. 1 seed standing, so it had to give
the executives at CBS, which is televising the Final Four, severe
heartburn to see them tottering against Iowa State's ensemble cast.
</P>
<P>
   The CBS suits weren't the only ones swallowing hard. All around
The Palace there were Spartans fans wearing green faces and a lot
of them weren't even painted.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just say you won't see any more stupefied expressions
tonight if a very pregnant Annette Bening's water breaks while
she's in her Shrine Auditorium seat than the collective look frozen
on the faces of the Michigan State fans when Cyclones standout
Marcus Fizer's basket gave Iowa State a 61-55 lead with 4:51 left.
</P>
<P>
   There are some people - mostly Iowa State fans - who will say
the fourth foul Fizer picked up, for setting an illegal screen on
Charlie Bell around midcourt less than a minute later, was an
abomination. No question it was the beginning of the end for the
Cyclones as they lost their momentum and soon thereafter, the game,
75-64.
</P>
<P>
   We say the greater crime would have been if the Final Four had
proceeded without Mateen Cleaves, who is breathtaking to watch even
when he's firing up shots so fast it's obvious the meter is running
out on his collegiate career.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-3 senior missed eight of his 12 shots (and had five
turnovers against two assists), but when he's in the backcourt
that's beside the point. His leadership loomed large in the final
five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the years he has assisted fellow Flint products
Morris Peterson and Bell and in that decisive stretch they
justified his boundless confidence in them.
</P>
<P>
   It was a 3-pointer by Peterson that helped the Spartans get
their groove back. It pulled Michigan State to within 61-58 and
stopped the Cyclones' path of destruction. Iowa State proceeded to
cough up the ball twice and miss its next seven shots, including
two gimme layups by its starriest players, Jamaal Tinsley and
Fizer.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson and Bell can't even claim the highest popularity rating
in their hometown - Cleaves is easily the largest luminary. But
every time they touched the ball down the stretch it was gold:
Between them, Peterson and Bell accounted for all the Spartans'
points in an 11-0 run.
</P>
<P>
   When Peterson scored the fourth and fifth points of his
seven-point burst with a dunk off an alley-oop pass by Cleaves to
put MSU ahead 64-61, it got so loud inside The Palace you couldn't
hear yourself gasp.
</P>
<P>
   In a scintillating stretch of three minutes, 44 seconds, the
Cyclones were snuffed out and the Final Four was saved. No offense
against either Iowa State or Wisconsin, a winner earlier in the day
over Purdue, but an NCAA semifinal game pitting them would have
been as riveting as the competition for the Oscar for Best Sound
Editing.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans, who advanced to the Final Four last year, have
been every bit the front-runner for college basketball's most
coveted prize as ``American Beauty'' has been for the movie
industry's. So it was Michigan State's win Saturday which kept
alive the illusion that the so-called experts know of what they
speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played a better quality game during the last five
minutes,'' Iowa State coach Larry Eustachy said, ``and that is the
story.''
</P>
<P>
   If anybody deserved the chance to add another chapter to his
fable of a career, it's Cleaves. He could have turned pro after his
junior year. Cleaves chose more memories over lots of money, only
to injure his right foot before the start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   He missed 13 games and much sleep wondering if he'd be able to
regain his fabulous form.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves came back for his senior season expressly because he
wanted to lead the Spartans to the Final Four and beyond. He can't
say he was confident throughout Saturday's dogfight that he'd get
it done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did get a tad bit nervous, to tell you the truth,'' Cleaves
said.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say a lot of people knew the feeling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
