<HEADLINE>
SPEED TRUCK DRIVER USING CHALLENGE TO FIND MISSING STUDENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIMOTHY HADDOCK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When UCLA freshman Michael Negrete disappeared
from his dorm room the weekend before finals in December, campus
police and the FBI began searching for the missing teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   In the four months since Negrete's disappearance, neither has
been able to locate him. Now Speed Truck series driver Chris Hines
is getting involved.
</P>
<P>
   The Mechanix Wear Speed Truck Challenge opened Saturday at the
Orange Show in San Bernardino. Coincidentally, it was the same day
as Negrete's birthday. He turned 19.
</P>
<P>
   Hines displayed Negrete's picture in the bed of his race truck
in the hopes someone would recognize the missing music student from
San Diego and end months of heartache and frustration for the
Negrete family.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the 37-year-old from Chandler, Ariz., knows the chances
of finding a missing person are slim.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality of finding children is very difficult,'' Hines
said. ``I want to try to raise awareness rather than find kids. But
you never know with an adult case like this. Maybe something else
happened. And maybe he'll say to himself, `Man, I need to get a
hold of my parents.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hines and his wife, Donna, who volunteers for the Nation's
Missing Children and Center for Missing Adults in Glendale, Ariz.,
select a different person, usually a child, to publicize in each
race. The Speed Truck Challenge makes stops throughout the
Southwest, including Phoenix International Raceway, Mesa Marin
Raceway in Bakersfield and Irwindale Speedway. The Hines pick a
missing person from the communities in which the series visits in
its weekly races.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to carrying a picture of Negrete on his truck, Hines
also invited the Negrete family to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little surprised,'' said Mary Negrete, Michael's
mother. ``We're not really into racing. But it was a nice thing to
do. We are just looking for that one person who knows something
about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Negrete, who did not have a car, was last heard from in
the early morning of Dec. 10, 1999. He was playing a computer game
with another student and logged off at 3:40 a.m. When Negrete's
roommate awoke the next morning at 9, Negrete was not in the room.
</P>
<P>
   The Negrete Web site is
www.four-schools.com/negrete/negrete.htm. Additionally, there is a
link to the Web site at UCLA.edu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
