<SLUG> BC-BBN-KERRY-WOOD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH OFF-SEASON REGIMEN HELPS FUEL KERRY WOOD'S RAPID COMEBACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, Ariz. _ Kerry Wood suffered through a long, lonely, boring
off-season.
</P>
<P>
   He'd get up in the morning and make the 25-minute drive from his
Scottsdale, Ariz., home to the Chicago Cubs' training complex for
an intense, grueling workout. By himself.
</P>
<P>
   He'd go back to his sparsely furnished, four-bedroom house to
spend time. By himself.
</P>
<P>
   He'd take his bass boat out to the lake to get in a little
fishing. By himself.
</P>
<P>
   He'd repeat the process, day after day, week after week. By
himself.
</P>
<P>
   He made it home to Texas just twice, for Thanksgiving and
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   His buddies from Irving, and the ones he went to high school
with in Grand Prairie, the guys he used to hang out with after the
baseball season, didn't understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my friends back home were saying, `Why are you moving out
to Arizona to live by yourself?' '' Wood said. ``I moved out here
because I didn't know a lot of people out here. I knew I could get
my work done and not have any distractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I moved out here because my career was on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood is threatened by a pitcher's nightmare: a catastrophic
elbow injury. He tore the ulnar collateral ligament in his elbow
during spring training last year. Now, he's back in spring training
almost a year after ligament replacement surgery attempting to
resurrect his once promising career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan on coming back with the same stuff,'' Wood said. ``I
plan on being the same pitcher as before.''
</P>
<P>
   The pitcher he used to be seemed headed for a Hall of Fame
career almost from the time he arrived in the majors two months
short of his 21st birthday in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5, 220-pound right-hander with the upper-90 mph
fastball, hard curve and biting slider went 13-6 with a 2.40
earned-run average. He struck out 233 batters in 166 2/3 innings,
including a record-tying 20 against the Houston Astros in just his
fifth major-league start in his rookie-of-the-year season.
</P>
<P>
   His heroes while growing up in Irving were Nolan Ryan and Roger
Clemens, two other big, hard-throwing Texans. There seemed no
reason why he wouldn't follow in their legendary bootsteps.
</P>
<P>
   Then his seemingly indestructible, magical right arm failed him.
He missed the final month of the season because of a sprained ulnar
collateral ligament. In spring training it tore, and Wood faced the
three words pitchers most dread: ``Tommy John'' surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure, named after the former pitcher who was the first
to undergo the surgery in 1974, involves removing the damaged
ligament and replacing it with a tendon from another part of the
body. In Wood's case, it was a tendon from his right forearm.
</P>
<P>
   Some pitchers thrive after the surgery. John won 164 of his 288
career victories after having the surgery. Others, though, such as
former Cincinnati All-Star Jose Rijo, never make it back.
</P>
<P>
   Wood knows the success stories. He knows the failures. He knows
if he wanted to be one of the former, he had to change, to work
harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely a slap in the face,'' he said. ``It was a
wakeup call. You go from thinking you're invincible, then
everything's taken away from you and you're starting over from
scratch.''  &LR; subheds:Making changes  &LR; body:Before the injury, Wood
thrived with natural talent. After dominating batters during the
season, he'd go home to Texas and hang out with his buddies.
Conditioning was not exactly a priority.
</P>
<P>
   After the surgery, he spent virtually the entire off-season at
his Arizona home and changed his workout routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' he said. ``I actually had one. I actually worked out.
I really went after it.''
</P>
<P>
   It shows. Wood lost 15-18 pounds. He replaced much of the baby
fat with muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great,'' Wood said. ``Usually you hate conditioning
when you come to spring training; that's the worst part of your
day. I haven't had any problems. I feel like I have good endurance
and my legs feel strong beneath me ... I feel like my arm strength
is pretty close.''
</P>
<P>
   The few batters he has faced this spring might say very close.
</P>
<P>
   Wood began throwing off a mound early in camp, hitting the low
90s on the radar gun. On March 13, the one-year anniversary of the
day he tore the ligament, he faced live batters for the first time.
He threw 10 modified curveballs to catcher Jose Molina, then threw
37 pitches to minor-leaguers Chris Petersen and Mike Amrhein. Eight
were put in play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every pitch was awesome,` Molina said. ``He was spotting it in
and out.''
</P>
<P>
   Five days later he started against the Chicago White Sox in an
exhibition and his fastball hit 97 mph on the radar gun.
</P>
<P>
   Friday he pitched two innings against Milwaukee's Triple-A team.
Although he allowed three runs and five hits, the more important
statistic was that he was throwing 94-96 mph, saying after the game
he felt good.
</P>
<P>
   Wood has yet to attempt throwing his slider or a hard breaking
curve, but by any measure he is well ahead of schedule. Not
everyone thinks that's such a great idea. Like Wood, St. Louis
Cardinals right-hander Matt Morris had Tommy John surgery in early
April last year. He hasn't been back on a mound yet, and is aiming
for a return in late June or early July.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't impressed by Wood's early outings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's stupid, to be honest,'' Morris said. ``Everyone you
talk to says a good 18 months is about what you need. I can pitch
in a game today, but it's not going to help me tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs, naturally, don't place a high value on Morris'
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will listen to the input from licensed physicians,'' general
manager Ed Lynch said.  &LR; subheds:Trying to be careful  &LR; body:Wood is
so eager, he wants to be back yesterday. Manager Don Baylor has
talked about Wood making it back by June, although he later amended
it to say he thinks it will be sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're taking every precaution they can, and honestly I feel
like at some points they've been too cautious,'' Wood said.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor knows he needs Wood pitching well if the Cubs are going
to contend. The Cubs made the playoffs with him pitching every
fifth day in '98. When they didn't have Wood last year, they fell
to 67-95.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor also knows Wood is the future. He doesn't want to rush
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking far ahead into his future,'' Baylor said. ``That
will be the determining factor, not just throwing him out there to
win games this year. The two guys who are his role models are Roger
Clemens and Nolan Ryan. I'd like for him to fulfill those kind of
dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood, for now, is having a hard time being patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to one thing: I'm the only one in the world who
knows how my arm feels,'' he said. ``If my arm's bothering me, I'm
not going to go out and pitch. But if it's not bothering me, I'm
going to push it and get my work done to get back on the mound.
That's my job, to get back on the mound as healthy as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what the long, lonely, boring off-season was all about.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
