<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONG OUTING PUTS CORDERO CLOSE TO ROSTER SPOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRADENTON, Fla. _ Francisco Cordero, continuing to impress
manager Johnny Oates, all but nailed down a spot on the Opening Day
roster with 1 2/3 scoreless innings in a 5-5 tie with the
Pittsburgh Pirates yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Cordero has now not allowed a run in six appearances covering
82/3 scoreless innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was up a little bit today, but he's got enough stuff to get
by,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Cordero's chances of making the team improved considerably when
Oates revealed he was strongly leaning toward going with a
seven-man bullpen and a 12-man pitching staff for Opening Day. That
leaves room for both Mike Venafro and Cordero in a bullpen that
already includes right-handers John Wetteland, Jeff Zimmerman and
Tim Crabtree, and left-handers Matt Perisho and Mike Munoz.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is I would probably use that 12th pitcher more
than I would that 14th regular,'' said Oates, who went with a
12-man staff for most of last season.
</P>
<P>
   If Oates does go with 12 pitchers, it leaves a crowded field
battling for the final remaining spot on the bench next to catcher
Bill Haselman, infielder Frank Catalanotto and outfielder Chad
Curtis.
</P>
<P>
   Oates indicated he has a preference for someone who can play
shortstop, which would give an edge to Scott Sheldon or Edwin Diaz
over outfielders Jason McDonald, Scarborough Green and Mike Simms.
</P>
<P>
   Much depends on Venafro being ready for Opening Day. Venafro,
sidelined for most of the spring with a finger injury, made his
first appearance in an exhibition game yesterday, allowing three
hits and a walk in one inning of work.
</P>
<P>
   Oates was encouraged but said Venafro was not as close to being
ready as closer John Wetteland, who has also been limited this
spring by a strained groin muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were opening the season today, Wetteland would pitch,
Venafro would not,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Oates said pitching coach Dick Bosman, ``thinks no
problem. He's seen enough stuff that with three or four more
outings, he'll be right on track.''
</P>
<P>
   Of his outing, Venafro said, ``It went well ... little fatigued
... the finger felt fine. Performance-wise, beggars can't be
choosers, but I've only got one way to go. I guess that tells you
what I think of my performance.'' International push The Rangers
are making a run at Cuban pitcher Adrian ``El Duquecito''
Hernandez, the latest and hottest defector/free agent from that
island. Rangers scouting director Chuck McMichael said there is
interest, although the early asking price is a little too high.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're asking for multi millions and a major-league
contract,'' McMichael said. ``I'd like to say they won't get it,
but I might be wrong. I've discussed the parameters of an offer
with them, but I haven't put an offer on the table. I'm due to talk
with them on Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez is known as ``El Duquecito'' because he is similar in
style to Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez (no relation) of the New
York Yankees. But McMichael said he's more likely to start at
Double A rather than the majors.
</P>
<P>
   McMichael has had a good spring, signing four Dominican Republic
pitchers, including Omar Beltre and Jose Dominguez. Both are 17,
6-foot-3 and can throw 90-94 mph. Briefly Justin Thompson, taking
another weary step on the road to recovering from shoulder surgery,
threw 30 pitches in a simulated game in Port Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Oliver, John Wetteland, Jeff Zimmerman and Matt Perisho
are scheduled to pitch against the Philadelphia Phillies today in
Port Charlotte. Tim Crabtree and Mike Munoz are scheduled to pitch
in a minor-league game because the Rangers are running out of
innings in their exhibition games.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
