<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HACKETT SAYS USC QUARTERBACK PALMER LOOKS `OK'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC ran a tightly controlled scrimmage Saturday
afternoon to work on its running game, but it also gave fans a
first chance to look at quarterback Carson Palmer in a game-like
environment since he suffered a broken collarbone last season.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer completed 6 of 7 passes for 81 yards in a solid effort
while backup Mike Van Raaphorst was 5 of 12 for 40 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he looked OK,'' Paul Hackett, the USC coach, said of
Palmer. ``He certainly didn't have a sensational day. I thought our
runners ran the ball well.''
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore tailback Sultan McCullough gained 59 yards on 14
carries, including a 40-yard run and Malaefou MacKenzie gained 40
yards on 9 carries.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans' first-string defense looked slightly ahead of the
offense, with Hackett singling out linebacker Zeke Moreno and
defensive tackle Ryan Nielsen. A surprising standout was linebacker
John Cousins, a transfer from West Los Angeles College.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought John Cousins showed up a couple times nice ... he's
got a suddenness to him,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on what we were trying to accomplish, working on the
running game and the basic fundamentals, I'm very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem area was penalties. The Trojans had 11 during the
scrimmage, which was reminiscent of last season, when they had 128
in 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm vowing we will improve in that area,'' Hackett said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
