<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR MONDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Monday, March 27:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ELECTION (Moscow) _ Acting President Vladimir Putin
appeared to hold a commanding lead over his 10 rivals in Russia's
second presidential election Sunday, according to early results
from exit polls conducted across the nation's 11 time zones. But it
was less clear whether he was attracting the 50 percent of voters
he needed to win the election outright and avoid a runoff. By
Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-VOICES (Moscow) _ Russian reaction to the presidential
vote. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ASSESS (Moscow) _ What the outcome of the Russian
election means, particularly on the foreign policy front. By
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ASSAD (Islamabad, Pakistan) _ President Clinton meets in
Geneva with the Syrian president, Hafez Assad, in hopes of
restarting peace talks between Syria and Israel. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   POPE (Jerusalem) _ With 86 shuffling steps, Pope John Paul
Sunday approached the Western Wall, reached out a trembling hand to
touch its cool stone and, as is the custom of Jewish visitors,
tucked into a crevice a note to God. Then he made the sign of the
cross at the most sacred site in Judaism, and a hush carpeted the
plaza as the moment sunk in. The pope's note bore the message of
reconciliation that has been the public theme of his six-day
personal pilgrimage. By Deborah Sontag and Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA-CULT-LEADER (Kabumba, Uganda) _ For a man so devoted to
God, the idea must have seemed so right, so real. Three women,
meeting Joseph Kibwetere for the first time, told him that the
Virgin Mary had led them to him and that he had been anointed to
help them spread the word of God. It was, he believed, his reward
for a lifetime of piety and prayer. It was, his family now says,
the beginning of his unrepentant turn away from the faith that had
made him a model man and toward an obsession that would make him a
murderer. By Henri E. Cauvin.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-SABOTAGE (London) _ Sabotage at a British nuclear plant
increases pressure for the government to close the site. By Alan
Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   TYRANTS-SWIMMING-POOLS (Istanbul, Turkey) _ When Ethem Erkoc
decided to go into the swimming pool business, he had no idea that
he would one day be known as poolmaker to tyrants. It just turned
out that way. Asked how he assembled his unusual client list, which
includes Saddam Hussein and Moammar Gadhafi, Erkoc said he assumes
that authoritarian leaders chat about things like swimming pools:
``Maybe it's not an official club, but they communicate,'' he said.
``When they get together, one might say to the other, `Nice pool,
who built it for you?''' By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-ARTIFACTS (Suitland, Md.) _ A treasure trove of American
Indian artifacts and objects is being quietly trucked from a Bronx
warehouse to the Smithsonian Institution's new Cultural Resources
Center under the respectful scrutiny of members of the surviving
tribes, their population having rebounded from the 250,000 total of
a century ago to near 2 million. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-YOUTH (Austin, Texas) _ How the Republicans hope to break
through to a younger generation with their first presidential
candidate in several decades who is under the age of 60. By Frank
Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-CONTROL (Washington) _ The contest for control of the
House of Representatives is as close as, well, the margin in the
House itself, where the 11-vote Republican majority is the smallest
in nearly half a century. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DALEY-PROFILE (Washington) _ Profile of Commerce Secretary
William Daley. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Undated) _ Commentary; subject TK. By William
Safire.
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (Undated) _ Commentary; subject TK. By Bob
Herbert.
</P>
