<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of Monday, March
27:
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Coded e)
</P>
<P>
   OSCARS-RDP (Hollywood) _ The Academy Awards. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   WRITERS-ON-WRITING (Undated) _ Barbara Kingsolver is the latest
author in the Writers-on-Writing series.
</P>
<P>
   SPRING-AUCTIONS (Undated) _ A preview look at the spring auction
season. By Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   ARGERICH-MUSIC-REVIEW (New York) _ Martha Argerich, pianist, at
Carnegie Hall. By James R. Oestreich.
</P>
<P>
   KIPLING-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Richard Bernstein reviews
``Rudyard Kipling,'' by Harry Ricketts.
</P>
<P>
   ARREST-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ Ben Brantley reviews ``House
Arrest'' at the Papp Public Theater.
</P>
<P>
   TV-HEPBURN-REVIEW (Undated) _ Anita Gates reviews ``The Audrey
Hepburn Story'' on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded f)
</P>
<P>
   USEDBOOK-BOOM (Undated) _ The used book market used to be a
musty corner of the book industry. Now, with the Internet, it is
becoming a big business. The dust mites are flying with the flashy
emergence of Alibris, a virtual used bookseller with $60 million in
Silicon Valley money and more people in its executive suite than
most used booksellers see wandering in their stores. Some dealers
refuse to supply books to Alibris. But others welcome the newcomer,
believing that Alibris could expand demand for used books into a
mass market. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   POLAROID-DIGITAL (Cambridge, Mass.) _ Compared with conventional
camera makers and other film companies, Polaroid Corp. has always
been in the instant picture business. Nowadays, because digital
photography is essentially an electronic form of instant pictures,
Polaroid is either in a unique position to move into this field _
or uniquely suited to be rendered obsolete by it.
</P>
<P>
   IP-TELEPHONY (Undated) _ A big corporate installation of
telephones that use the Internet to carry calls indicates that the
long-predicted era of so-called IP telephony may have arrived. By
Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   IBM-QWEST (Undated) _ IBM will build data centers for Qwest, and
the companies will jointly operate them as Web-hosting centers. By
Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   CINEPLEX-HITECH (New York) _ Opening in a Bronx cineplex:
technology that allows the deaf and the blind to enjoy movies. By
Tom Holcomb.
</P>
<P>
   DIGICOM-COLUMN (Undated) _ The Digital Commerce column: the
focus on money, money, money that we encounter daily in the
Internet economy is almost impossible to discuss rationally in most
quarters. Try telling someone hit by the money truck, that the
making of millions overnight does not justify the present means _
like poor business practices, rejection of even sensible government
oversight and early profit-taking. Say that out loud and you can
live the experience of clearing a room in 10 seconds flat. But it
appears that something is shifting. Venture investors, the fuel of
the Internet economy, have started to question the path that so
many Internet companies have taken _ despite the tremendous profit
they make from the present state of affairs. By Denise Caruso.
</P>
<P>
   ECOMMERCE-COLUMN (Undated) _ The E-Commerce column: e-commerce
companies have always seemed a lot like not-for-profit operations _
constantly on the lookout for new funding and constantly losing
money, all the while stressing that profits are not the immediate
priority. The similarities are getting greater still, as nonprofit
groups have begun to rely on e-commerce to generate revenues and
streamline their organizations. By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   FREE-INTERNET (Undated) _ LaGrange, Ga., a city of 30,000, is
paying for the installation of cable-modem Internet access and a
year's free service for any household that wants it. By Laurie J.
Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   INTERACTIVE-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The Advertising column: two
interactive ad agencies _ Nuforia and Red Sky _ are set to merge.
By Patricia Winters Lauro.
</P>
<P>
   PATENTS (Undated) _ The weekly patents column. By Teresa
Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Short news items about computers.
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Major financial stories at a glance.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-CALENDAR (Undated) _ Key government figures this week.
</P>
<P>
   BOND-CALENDAR (Undated) _ The week's planned offerings.
</P>
<P>
   EQUITIES (Undated) _ Equity issues coming to market this week.
</P>
<P>
   DIVIDEND-MEETINGS (Undated) _ Major meetings this week.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   (Coding varies.)
</P>
<P>
   FATMAGS-MEDIA (Undated) _ A new breed in the evolution of media:
the obese magazine. Not just large, but 400-1,100 (Modern Bride)
pages long. Mark Clements, the president of Mark Clements Research,
has a new idea for a product. ``It's a special piece of luggage
designed to carry the fashion magazines,'' Clements said.
``Considering how much these things weigh these days, it will be
indispensable. Who can carry this stuff home with them?'' By Alex
Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   BIZTV-WEB-MEDIA (Undated) _ Interviews with analysts have been
the stock in trade of financial television broadcasts for years.
Now the large brokerage companies like Merrill Lynch, PaineWebber
and others that have provided the analysts are putting them
directly before clients, via their own Web sites. By Anthony
DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   ABC-NEWS-MEDIA (Undated) _ ABC news shows have been using the
mascot for Pets.com _ for mock interviews on Nightline and Good
Morning America _ and not saying that ABC's owner, Disney, owns 5
percent of the Web site. The incidents demonstrate the difficulties
of news divisions in policing potential conflicts of interest these
days, when TV networks, or their owners, take stakes in Internet
companies by swapping equity in such start-ups for advertising
time. By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   FM-RADIO-MEDIA (Washington) _ Congress and the FCC, two of this
city's slowest bureaucracies, are moving with remarkable alacrity
in a fight over control of the airwaves and the future of FM radio.
By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   YAHOO-FESTIVAL-MEDIA (Hollywood) _ Ground zero at the Yahoo
Internet Life Online Film Festival this past week was in the coffee
shop at the ostentatiously retro Standard Hotel on the Sunset
Strip. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-TALK (Undated) _ Short news items about the media
business.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other stories
from our partners: The Arizona Republic, The Boston Globe, Cox News
Service, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Hearst Newspapers, The Houston
Chronicle, Kansas City Star, Los Angeles Daily News, San Francisco
Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
