   OSCAR-SONG _ For Monday office talk. Billy Crystal's back and
that means a funny song making fun of the movies. So here's some of
the lyrics from his Sunday night Oscar standup act. (Horne, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15 ETA: 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   OSCAR-WINNERBIOS _ The winners circle: bulleted bios on each of
the nominated actors and directors, moving in advance of the
announcement of the winners. (BLongino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   OSCAR-BESTFILM _ Eleanor Ringel Gillespie breaks down the finer
points of the movie that won best picture. (Ringel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 7.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT
</P>
<P>
   TV-HEPBURN _ Let's face it: Jennifer Love Hewitt's breasts are
as famous as she is. So it's no wonder some Hollywood insiders
snickered when Hewitt wanted to play the glamorous, stick-thin
Audrey Hepburn in a TV movie. After all, Hepburn was flat-chested.
Hewitt is, well... we all know what Hewitt is. (Thompson, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   WWII-MUSEUM _ TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ From the front lines in France
came a birthday present for 2-year-old Dan Buschhoff _ a letter
from his Uncle Fred, who was clearing a path toward Germany with
the 101st Airborne Division. In swirling blue ink on thin brown
paper, Fred Buschhoff made an eloquent argument for waging a brutal
war in the name of equality and opportunity, and he made a lasting
impression on his young nephew. ``It means an even chance for every
man to get a job, a home, a meal, or to raise a family free from
the fear of destitution,'' Fred Buschhoff wrote in the Jan. 5,
1945, letter. ``It applies to big things and little things and is
one more important reason that we are fighting today. Protect it,
cherish it, and nourish it always for it's your birthright and your
future.'' ( Kiehl, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ I really don't wish to pile on Ricky Williams.
He's down. He had a miserable rookie season. He's been hurt. He's
been homesick for Austin. He's also a multi-millionaire. He plays a
boys game for a living. He's rung up more magazine covers in the
last two years than Bill Clinton, and without a write-up from
Kenneth Starr. Sure, it it was a bad year for the Heisman Trophy
winner, and last week has probably the worst. Williams had to
apologize to New Orleans and his team for comments in Sports
Illustrated about the town and the Saints. Once again, I wish not
to pile on. But I read the same article that has the Bayou
steaming. And what bothered me about it was something entirely
different: Ricky leaves half-eaten food on his floor. (Young, Waco
Tribune-Herald.) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   EZZARD-COLUMN _ I am not married to a dot-com man, or even a
low-tech man. When it comes to our North Georgia vineyard, where my
husband John gets to know his eight acres of wine-grape vines
personally, I am married to a no-tech man.(Ezzard, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
