<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8431 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-POPE-0327-COX     03-26 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-POPE-0327-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RELIGION, NOT POLITICS, REIGN ON POPE'S LAST DAY IN HOLY LAND
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM Pope John Paul II Sunday ended his Holy Land
pilgrimage with images of piety and reconciliation whose quiet
eloquence could be plainly heard above the usual din of political
and religious acrimony.
</P>
<P>
   The 79-year-old, hunched and hobbled pontiff looked small,
praying at the base of the Western Wall, sacred to Jews. He laid a
trembling hand on the huge stones set in place in the time of
Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   On the hilltop above, he viewed the rock where the Muslim
Prophet Mohammed is said to have risen to heaven. Nearby, he slowly
bowed to kiss the stone of Jesus' tomb in the Church of the Holy
Sepulchre.
</P>
<P>
   The three sites are near each other in Jerusalem's walled Old
City, for centuries the focal point of religious fervor and
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``These have been days of intense emotion, a time when our soul
has been stirred not only by the memory of what God has done but by
his very presence, walking with us once again in the Land of
Christ's birth, death and resurrection,'' he said during a mass in
the cavernous, dim, Church of the Holy Sepulchre.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when this most media savvy pope was scheduled for a rest
before the flight home, he gave Israeli security officials an
unexpected task. He returned to the church, praying alone and
without any cameras at Catholicism's most sacred place.
</P>
<P>
   The six-day visit to Israel and the Palestinian National
Authority was the highlight of the pope's year 2000 ``Holy Year,''
dedicated to reconciliation between the church and other faiths.
</P>
<P>
   It was historic from the beginning. This is only the second time
in history that a Roman Catholic pope visited the land where Christ
was born and crucified. It is the first visit by a pope since the
Vatican established diplomatic ties with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The visit quickly became the object of the region's political
disputes. Israelis confronted the pope with frequent reminders of
their claim to Jerusalem. A Muslim cleric walked out of an
interfaith meeting with the pope Thursday after debating who should
control Jerusalem with a rabbi.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Minister Haim Ramon acknowledged that officials kept two
prominent Palestinian politicians from Sunday's mass because Israel
wanted to show that it controlled Jerusalem politics.
</P>
<P>
   A Muslim cleric asked the pope to support Palestinian claims to
Jerusalem Sunday during the pope's visit to the Dome of the Rock
Mosque. The pope listened quietly. A few Arab and Jewish hecklers
tried to disrupt events Sunday, but many more were supportive.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, he remained steadfast in his mission of
reconciliation and personal pilgrimage.
</P>
<P>
   During the trip, his words broke little new theological or
political ground, but he provided an album of indelible pictures
for everybody.
</P>
<P>
   He met weeping Holocaust survivors from his native Poland and
said the church was ``deeply saddened'' by Catholic persecution of
Jews.
</P>
<P>
   He told Palestinian refugees, who feel neglected and mistreated,
that the world must pay attention to their ``torment.'' He rode
through the tense, mostly-Muslim city of Nazareth and showed the
beleaguered Christian Arab minority that they had support from the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The politics did not cease. Sunday, Palestinians sent their
flag, suspended by party balloons, into the sky above the Old City.
</P>
<P>
   But, the pope's hosts seemed to subordinate their political
agendas if not set them aside to acknowledge that something great
had occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt it was an historical visit to the Holy Land. I
believe this visit brings to an end the era of conflict, the era of
dispute and the era of war between Christianity and Judaism . . .
after 2000 years,'' said Ramon, who coordinated the visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can say we stayed several days with a great man,'' said
Faisal Husseini, the PLO representative in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   At the Western Wall, the tight security for the papal visit
delayed prayer for many. Some had criticisms, but acknowledged a
reverence.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is that Israel is too eager to please the
gentiles,'' said Orna Cohen, 44, of Jerusalem. ``But we lack the
historical perspective. Maybe we can't understand the importance.
Time will tell.''
</P>
<P>
   The final day was not the top news in Israel. That went to the
summit talks between President Clinton and Syrian President Hafez
Assad. But, each stop on the pope's visit took on historic
proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Many visitors to the Wall leave small prayers folded between the
cracks in the stone. The pope, after praying to the wall, left a
large page asking God to forgive Catholics for misdeeds against
Jews. The paper was taken to Jerusalem's Holocaust memorial for
display.
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   The pope has talked about the year 2000 since he started his
pontificate in 1978. He intended to illustrate these goals through
a trip that would follow the development of monotheism and retrace
the steps of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month he asked God for forgiveness for Catholic
mistreatment of Jews and others.
</P>
<P>
   Moslems remember Catholicism for the brutality of the
church-ordered medieval crusades.
</P>
<P>
   Jews remember Catholicism for the murder and torture of the
Spanish Inquisition and the silence by many Catholic leaders during
the Nazi Holocaust..
</P>
<P>
   John Paul (cq, no II on second reference) has lived a life
emblematic of the twentieth century witnessing the Holocaust and
Communism in his native Poland, working as an actor, stone cutter
and poet.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he is an ailing pope who shakes with the symptoms of
Parkinson's disease, though Vatican officials do not confirm that
diagnosis. This trip his 91st as pope and by far more than any
other could be the lasting legacy of his papacy.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that legacy could vary according to who is viewing
it. For his Catholic followers, his visit to the Church of the Holy
Sepulchre Sunday may be the most important.
</P>
<P>
   ``This the highlight. It is the most spiritual. Of all the trips
of the pope, this takes us to the roots of our faith. Spiritually
for Christians, the Holy Sepulchre is where it all began because of
the resurrection,'' said Cardinal Adam Maida, of Detroit, who
attended the mass.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of the pope, he described him as a ``mystical and
spiritual man. The pilgrimage has brought that out like never
before.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is unsteady on his feet. He appears weak, but this has
probably been the strongest moment of his pontificate,'' Maida
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
