<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHOLIC-VOTE0327-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Much ado over Catholic vote
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It has been three weeks since Gov. George W. Bush
wrote to the nation's foremost Catholic leaders to express regret
for speaking at Bob Jones University. But Republicans are worried
over alienating a powerful voter constituency and Democrats are no
longer taking them for granted.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Republican National Committee Chairman Jim
Nicholson reignited the battle over the Catholic vote, calling on
Vice President Al Gore to repudiate two abortion-rights groups that
want the Vatican to lose its non-voting United Nations status. The
Democratic National Committee fired back with a reminder of Bush's
Feb. 2 visit to Bob Jones University, an evangelical school with an
anti-Catholic philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, House Speaker Dennis Hastert, stung by the
uproar over who should be the House chaplain, appointed a Roman
Catholic priest for the first time in that body's 211-year history.
</P>
<P>
   It's all much ado about politics. The last time Catholicism
figured so prominently in an American election was when John F.
Kennedy ran for the presidency in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason that the Catholic vote is so important in American
politics today is because of where it's found,'' said Steven
Wagner, a Republican pollster and author of, ``Catholics &AMP;
Evangelicals: Can They Be Allies? `` part of a series in Crisis
Magazine, a Catholic periodical. ``While Catholics are a greater
percentage of the population in New England, there are more of them
in the states of the upper Midwest and these are the states that
will determine who gets elected president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   About a third of voters in any given presidential election are
Catholics. They have traditionally voted for Democrats, but the
tide is shifting, especially among white Roman Catholics who
regularly attend mass, said Wagner, who is not working for any
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very salient moment,'' said Deal Hudson, editor of
Crisis. ``Either that slow migration is going to pick up and
continue or it might begin to reverse.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent poll by Pew Research Center for the People and the
Press found Bush and Gore evenly split among white Roman Catholic
voters. The two candidates are preparing for battle in
heavily-Catholic swing states such as Ohio and Pennsylvania.
Speculation over who Bush might choose as a running mate includes
Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge, who is Catholic and also pro-choice
and so might help Bush win over social moderates.
</P>
<P>
   Appealing to Catholics is going to take more than charges of
anti-Catholic bias, said Patrick Scully, spokesman for the Catholic
League for Religious and Civil Rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think that there will be a preponderance of issues
taken into consideration for a Catholic voter come November,'' he
said. ``I don't think a Catholic voter is going to go into the
voting booth and say, 'I won't vote for this candidate because of
the Bob Jones and the House chaplain situation.'''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats were quick to attack House leaders when they passed
over the Rev. Timothy O'Brien, a Catholic priest who had the
support of an 18-member bipartisan search committee. Republicans
complained that Democrats were exploiting religion for political
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope Speaker Hastert's actions and words will help put an
end to the divisive tactics of playing upon religious fears and
pitting people against one another for political gain,'' said Bush
spokesman Scott McClellan, echoing that theme Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Reed, former head of the Christian Coalition, now a
political consultant, said the furor over Catholics has been a wake
up call for Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican party has undergone a quiet metamorphosis over
the last decade,'' he said. ``We used to call these folks Reagan
Democrats, but they're not Democrats anymore, they're Republicans.
I think the Catholic vote is going to be very important for
Republicans in November.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
