<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8434 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-WWII-MUSEUM0327-COX     03-26 1325
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WWII-MUSEUM0327-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The human face of inhuman conflict
 &HT;    By Stephen Kiehl
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ From the front lines in France came a
birthday present for 2-year-old Dan Buschhoff _ a letter from his
Uncle Fred, who was clearing a path toward Germany with the 101st
Airborne Division.
</P>
<P>
   In swirling blue ink on thin brown paper, Fred Buschhoff made an
eloquent argument for waging a brutal war in the name of equality
and opportunity, and he made a lasting impression on his young
nephew.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means an even chance for every man to get a job, a home, a
meal, or to raise a family free from the fear of destitution,''
Fred Buschhoff wrote in the Jan. 5, 1945, letter. ``It applies to
big things and little things and is one more important reason that
we are fighting today. Protect it, cherish it, and nourish it
always for it's your birthright and your future.''
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks after writing those words, 19-year-old Fred
Buschhoff was dead _ shot during the Battle of the Bulge. Dan
Buschhoff kept the letter close to him as he moved from New York to
New Jersey and, in 1990, to Hobe Sound.
</P>
<P>
   Now it has a new home at Florida State University's Institute on
World War II and the Human Experience, a place where the letters,
photos and diaries of veterans and their families are being
preserved and indexed for the future use of historians, teachers
and students.
</P>
<P>
   Buschhoff's letter is just one of 2,000 donations in the
collection, which fills three cramped, windowless rooms in the FSU
history building. The boxes are stacked from floor to ceiling _ a
black-and-white record that tells the story of the war in the words
of those who lived it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to convince veterans that what they have is worth
saving,'' said William Oldson, the institute's director and an FSU
history professor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This generation is so modest. One guy said, 'Why do you want
this? I'm just the anonymous American soldier who helped win the
war.' Well, that's it. That's what we want.''
</P>
<P>
   The project has taken on a new urgency as even the youngest
World War II veterans are now in their 70s. The Pentagon estimates
that about 1,500 die every day, leaving Oldson with a five- to
10-year window to gather as much as he can.
</P>
<P>
   For many veterans, parting with the most permanent reminders of
their service is a difficult, wrenching decision, Oldson said. But
it's made easier by their desire to educate tomorrow's children and
their fear that all their letters and photos and medals will end up
in a landfill.
</P>
<P>
   MORE THAN JUST LETTERS
</P>
<P>
   So veterans have emptied their closets to the institute, giving
more than just letters and pictures. There's a huge, gold-colored
9mm anti-aircraft shell carried off a battlefield in Europe, a
sprocket chain from a bomber that crashed, a pinup-girl playing
cards and V-discs with messages to the soldiers from Frank Sinatra
and Bing Crosby.
</P>
<P>
   There are dozens of uniforms and medals, tiny saws and colorful
silk maps of Europe that pilots kept in their shoes in case they
were shot down. Oldson says women come in, see the silk maps and
say, ``So that's where all my stockings went.''
</P>
<P>
   While the World War II veterans are now in their 70s and 80s,
their letters are reminders that they were once vigorous
18-year-olds trying to make sense of a terrifying world.
</P>
<P>
   On April 30, 1945, Milton Telfeyam wrote home to Westchester,
N.Y.: ``As long as any war lasts, there is always a tension in mind
and body. You sort of go to sleep with one eye open, and wake up
with the feeling that another day is here and you'll have to fight
your way through it. ... This war scares the hell out of me, as it
no doubt does to most everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   The World War II institute started three years ago when
Tallahassee businessman George Langford was looking for a home for
all the letters he and his brothers and sister wrote to their
mother during their war. He wanted them to be saved, so he talked
to Oldson about donating them to FSU.
</P>
<P>
   All four Langford children joined the services, two in the Navy,
two in the Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all wrote to my dear, sweet momma, and she saved all those
letters,'' Langford said. His older brother, Bill, was killed by a
grenade on the beach at Luzon the night before he was to return
home. He had spent 30 months in the South Pacific without a
scratch.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is important for the memory of my brother,'' said
Langford, 76. ``History is written from the generals' reports. They
don't tell you what our boys and girls were really doing.''
</P>
<P>
   A big part of the institute's mission is education. Oldson gives
his history students copies of the World War II letters to make the
war more personal for them, to put human faces on a conflict that
many students find as ancient as the Civil War. He is also
establishing links with Florida high schools so history teachers
can use materials on the institute's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Oldson wants the institute to be a resource for students and
researchers. So he has about a dozen graduate students cataloging
the letters and photos to create a searchable database on the Web.
People will be able to enter a relative's name, and then they'll
get pictures of that person and other related information.
</P>
<P>
   ``These students are not going to listen to me if I teach
straight military history,'' Oldson said. ``This makes it all a
little more real.''
</P>
<P>
   REVEALING THE HOLOCAUST
</P>
<P>
   During the war, much of the Western world knew very little of
the Holocaust. But as the Allied forces swept across Germany in the
spring of 1945, some soldiers wrote home with graphic details of
the horrors they uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   On April 12, 1945, Lt. Col. Ralph Willey wrote a letter headed
``Dear Friends'' and told of the 5,000 dead he found at a
concentration camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their bodies were lying in the buildings, stacked under the
staircases like wood and lying over the ground in a 40-acre
field,'' Willey wrote. ``The bodies were nothing but skin and
bones, with a large number of bones broken. The greater part of the
remaining 1,000 to 2,000 (people) were living skeletons with
hundreds of them expecting to be dead in a few days.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``Five dead men lying beside a dead horse and the
ribs of the horse gone and the bones laying beside them. They had
been trying to get something to eat. I saw a boy dead from
starvation and beating lying in the green field. ... I do think
that you back home should know and want to know firsthand that such
conditions did exist here. It is not propaganda, I assure you.''
</P>
<P>
   `NOT GOING TO SIT IN A BOX'
</P>
<P>
   Every letter and every photo holds some clue to how people lived
_ and died _ during the war, Oldson said. And he wants all of it.
He is frequently on the road, sharing his mission with veterans and
their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``One big selling point I've had with veterans is that this is
not going to sit in a box,'' he said. ``This will be put to some
use. And they just don't want what they did forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Buschhoff was posthumously awarded the Purple Heart. And
though he never made it back home for his nephew's birthday, as he
had hoped in his letter, his brother _ Dan Buschhoff's father _ did
survive the war and lived to celebrate many more birthdays with the
son who was born while he was in the South Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Buschhoff died in 1996. His wife, Marge, donated the letter
to the institute in September because she wanted people to remember
those who had been lost _ and why they were fighting at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept that letter in our fire box. We treasured it,'' said
Marge Buschhoff, who keeps the family's letters, photos and records
from the war in her Hobe Sound home.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think of the things you have as not important, but then
you realize: that letter is more important than most anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just says it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
