<DOCNO> NYT20000326.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8435 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EZZARD-COLUMN0327-COX     03-26 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN0327-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Toil in vineyard leaves no room for high-tech
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I am not married to a dot-com man, or even a low-tech
man.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to our North Georgia vineyard, where my husband
John gets to know his eight acres of wine-grape vines personally, I
am married to a no-tech man.
</P>
<P>
   Little did I know when I blithely volunteered to help with the
spring planting of another half acre that the vines themselves
hadn't yet arrived. I was set for the easy task of sticking the
gnarled bare roots in holes, covering them with a little soil and
dousing them with water, all to a reliable choir of birds on our
farm. But that wasn't what John had in mind when he hollered that I
should bring some heavy gloves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are the plants?'' I asked, holding my sloshing coffee
mug out the pickup truck window as we jostled over the creek and up
the hill to the new vineyard. It was laid out in perfect
12-foot-wide rows against a backdrop of majestic white pines, once
part of the Christmas trees John's dad planted. That was part of
the late W.T. Ezzard's winter work, when he wasn't busy plowing
corn and beans, pruning apple trees or cultivating blueberries.
</P>
<P>
   The vines haven't been shipped yet, John said with a sly grin,
the kind he normally saves for telling me he'd rather grab a quick
hot dog than go for pasta and a glass of wine at my favorite
restaurant. Suddenly, we heard the rattatat cry of a pileated
woodpecker. We could see him perched high on a pine tree, red head
bobbing in the morning sunlight. From John's standpoint, it was
perfect timing. I couldn't even feign a scowl as he handed me a
post-hole digger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't we use a gismo on the tractor for this last year,'' I
asked lamely. Not worth the trouble, John replied, except for
setting the posts. I winced, recalling my first and only previous
encounter with the diggers _ last summer, on hard red clay. Pulling
the wooden handles apart to make the metal shovels scoop up some
dirt was like taking on cement with ice tongs.
</P>
<P>
   ``About two-and-a-half feet deep,'' John yelled from the other
end of the row , pointing to a marker on the wooden handles.
</P>
<P>
   Prepared for a miserable challenge, I peeled off my jacket and
began to dig away. The earth was surprisingly soft and moist,
although a little rocky. A good workout for shoulders and arms, I
told myself, getting into a steady rhythm of forcing the diggers
down, pulling the handles apart and piling the dirt out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, we're not planting grapes in China,'' John teased when he
came to inspect my first hole. It was way too deep. I'd forgotten
to measure, concentrating instead on my perfect round hole. Half a
dozen holes later, with my shoulders aching and a jammed finger
throbbing, I saw three doe scamper out of the woods. They stopped
to graze in the pasture just below the vineyard. A yearling played
in the grass, showing its white tail. They grazed for a good half
hour, ignoring John and me but looking up periodically at a
neighbor's dogs. The pain in my shoulders suddenly didn't seem so
bad.
</P>
<P>
   We examined the vines in the old vineyard on our way back to the
house for lunch. The buds are just beginning to swell, and we feel
lucky they aren't further along. A late freeze after they pop out
is our chief worry every spring.
</P>
<P>
   John checked the special thermometers _ placed at strategic
spots in the vineyard _ that give us the high and low temperatures.
I suggested we look into software for my new computer to record the
temperatures, the rainfall, and the spraying regimen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh-huh,'' John nodded with disinterest, pulling out his
tattered notebook to jot down the readings, as he does daily.
</P>
<P>
   I might as well give up, I told our daughter later. Maybe, she
suggested, we should capitalize on her father's computer
illiteracy. Advertise elite wine from hand-tended vines that
produce the perfect old-world grape _ on the Web, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-00 1636EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000326.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8436 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0327     03-26 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0327 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trophies and trash
 &HT;    John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ I really don't wish to pile on Ricky Williams.
He's down. He had a miserable rookie season. He's been hurt. He's
been homesick for Austin.
</P>
<P>
   He's also a multi-millionaire. He plays a boys game for a
living. He's rung up more magazine covers in the last two years
than Bill Clinton, and without a write-up from Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it it was a bad year for the Heisman Trophy winner, and
last week has probably the worst. Williams had to apologize to New
Orleans and his team for comments in Sports Illustrated about the
town and the Saints.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, I wish not to pile on. But I read the same article
that has the Bayou steaming. And what bothered me about it was
something entirely different: Ricky leaves half-eaten food on his
floor.
</P>
<P>
   SI portrays Williams as a sort of Howard Hughes recluse in New
Orleans, with this key difference: Hughes took every pain to avoid
contaminating himself (needing a new tissue to touch so much as a
door knob). Williams' pad sounds just this side of a landfill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Couldn't see the floor for a month,'' said a training-camp
roomie of Williams' habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll eat like part of a banana and like throw it on the
floor,'' said his sister, disgusted with how he keeps a new and
spacious New Orleans home.
</P>
<P>
   Far be it from me to read too much into someone else's ditched
tea leaves. I hope this is nothing more than Ricky Williams',
freshman year, the rest-of-his-life-wise. Anyone who's been to
college remembers going, um, too long without using the dorm linen
service, or losing contact with the floor for all the loose
laundry.
</P>
<P>
   But throwing food on the floor? Pardon me, Ricky, but that's
obscene. It's not just the waste. It's not just the filth. It's the
statement.
</P>
<P>
   You bet, if I'm Ricky Williams and I'm reading this, I'm saying,
``Bug off. It's my life, my house.''
</P>
<P>
   Yours and the bugs'.
</P>
<P>
   HOLD THE PHONE, PEOPLE
</P>
<P>
   Really, this is not to comment on anyone's lifestyle, more to
comment on many lifestyles _ or those of too many people who have a
lot and take it for granted.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most grating commercials of all time has something to
do with wine. Granted, wine commercials are grating in and of
themselves. But this one pops my cork.
</P>
<P>
   In it, a group of leisure has its fashionable afternoon on the
pier interrupted by a cell phone. Once the group decides whose
phone has rung, the woman holding it decides not to answer. She
flings it in the pond with a fashionable laugh. And then so do the
others.
</P>
<P>
   La la la. That's five cell phones in the pond, cumulative
retail, oh, $600.
</P>
<P>
   We have people begging for food on street corners, people
appealing to relief agencies for assistance to pay their utilities,
and we've got models throwing cell phones into the pond and
millionaire athletes discarding food on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   I wish I could say this throw-away mind-set was confined to the
fashionable. A few years ago the PTA at our boys' elementary school
introduced a pencil machine to raise money. Some of the kids, most
from blue-collar homes or backgrounds even more humbling, were
thrilled to put a quarter into the machine. A few were so thrilled
that they would buy a pencil, and then deliberately break the
pencil, so they could put another quarter in the machine.
</P>
<P>
   Obscene.
</P>
<P>
   For one who's not very materialistic, I should not worry about
the fate of pencils, half-eaten bananas and soggy cell phones. The
Depression-era seed that created me, however, causes umbrage to
flare every time I see people frivolously treat things others
scrape and struggle to have.
</P>
<P>
   Stop your whining and pouting, Ricky. Life is very good. New
Orleans is a kickin' town. You're a blessed man. So am I. The next
banana I eat _ all of it _ is in your honor.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
