<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000326.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8440 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CLINTON-SYRIA-0327-CO     03-26 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SYRIA-0327-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton Can't Budge Syrians, Israelis
 &HT;    By Bob Deans
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA President Clinton was unable to pull the leaders of
Israel and Syria back to the negotiating table, despite a day of
face-to-face and telephone diplomacy among the three men on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton sent a special envoy to the region to try to press the
issue further, but White House spokesman Joe Lockhart told
reporters it was ``impossible to predict,'' when formal peace talks
might resume between Israel and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met here for three hours with Syrian President Hafez
Assad and spoke twice during the day over a secure telephone line
with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak in Jerusalem. Also
participating was Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and her
Syrian counterpart, Farouk Sharaa, and a host of senior aides.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aim was to reinvigorate Israeli-Syrian peace talks
held under his auspices last January in the West Virginia hamlet of
Sheperdstown.
</P>
<P>
   Those talks collapsed after the two sides couldn't agree on a
formula for Israel's return to Syria of the strategic Golan Heights
in exchange for peace and normal diplomatic relations with its long
time Arab foe.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his diplomatic corps have been trying to narrow the
differences between the two sides for the past two months. The
president tacked his meeting with Assad onto the end of a week-long
swing through India, Bangladesh and Pakistan, hopeful that he could
get the Syrian and Israeli leaders to agree to a new round of
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   During Sunday's conversations with both leaders, though, Clinton
became convinced that these longtime foes remained too far apart
for talks to be productive, said Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   ``The differences are significant and important, and obviously
more work needs to be done in order to bridge them,'' said
Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impossible to predict when these talks might resume,''
Lockhart told reporters traveling with the president. ``It is not
worthwhile to have meetings just to have meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also dispatched his special Mideast envoy, Dennis Ross,
who was part of Sunday's meetings here, to Jerusalem. Ross is
expected to give Barak a comprehensive briefing on Monday, and
Lockhart said Clinton remained hopeful that he would be able to
bring the two sides together.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president committed to both sides to remain engaged and
working hard at this process,'' said Lockhart, ``and I think he
received in return from these two parties a commitment to do the
same.''
</P>
<P>
   The immediate outcome of Sunday's effort, though, appeared to
lengthen the odds against one of the highest foreign policy
priorities of Clinton's career securing an end to half a century of
war and enmity in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   While White House aides tried to downplay down expectations
going into the meeting, it was Clinton's first substantive meeting
with Assad in five and a half years. Clinton had hoped to use
personal diplomacy to get the two leaders to at least agree to
talk.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's talks wound up a flurry of weekend diplomacy for
Clinton, who met Saturday in Islamabad with the head of Pakistan's
military government, chief army general Pervez Musharraf.
</P>
<P>
   That meeting, too, was slow going for Clinton, who was unable to
secure assurances from Musharraf that he would rein in Islamic
militants in the disputed territory of Kashmir, return Pakistan to
civilian rule or roll back the impoverished country's nuclear
weapons program.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton left Geneva immediately after the meeting with Assad. He
was expected to return to the White House early Monday.
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   Brokering a comprehensive Middle East peace accord has been a
primary foreign policy aim of Clinton's since his earliest days in
office.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes for such an outcome have been raised and dashed repeatedly
since September, 1993, when Clinton hosted a signing on the White
House lawn of the historic peace accord reached between Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Yitzak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   That accord set a five-year timetable for those two parties to
resolve all matters outstanding between them, including the
difficult so-called ``final status'' issues such as the future of
Jerusalem, the fate of thousands of Palestinian refugees and the
question of Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and Arafat missed a Feb. 13 deadline for establishing a
framework those talks. But the men are trying to complete that
phase with an eye toward resolving final status issues by autumn.
</P>
<P>
   The broad outlines of an Israeli-Syrian peace accord have long
been known. Any agreement would require Israel to return to Syria
the strategic Golan Heights, which Israeli troops captured in the
1967 Arab-Israeli war.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, Syria would agree to normalize its relations with
Israel, open its borders to Israeli transit and trade and embrace
the Jewish state as a regional partner.
</P>
<P>
   At issue, however, are questions about precisely where to draw
the border dividing Israeli territory from Syrian land. In an area
of particular contention, debate has raged over a patch of land 30
feet wide because it holds the key to fresh water supplies critical
in the desert region.
</P>
<P>
   Syria has demanded that Israeli troops pull back to the borders
in existence before the 1967 war. Barak has hinted that he would go
along with that, but Assad wants a commitment to that effect before
Syria will proceed with further talks.
</P>
<P>
   Israel, for its part, wants to be assured that it will receive a
genuine peace if it gives up the Golan. Israel also wants security
agreements to compensate for the loss of the Golan.
</P>
<P>
   The Golan Heights has provided Israel with a valuable listening
post, from which it can eavesdrop on the activities of military and
militant activity inside Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has conducted extensive talks with Pentagon officials
over how best to compensate for the loss of those assets.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has shown interest in acquiring a wide array of advanced
weaponry, attack helicopters, cruise missiles and other high-tech
gear. The deployment of an international peacekeeping and
monitoring force - perhaps including U.S. troops or advisers - is
also under review to enable Israel to maintain at least some of the
surveillance functions.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
