<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8441 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-POPE-ART-1200(2TAKES)     03-26 0353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-ART-1200(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE GOES TO WESTERN WALL ON LAST DAY OF HOLY LAND TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG and ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ With 86 shuffling steps, Pope John Paul on Sunday
approached the Western Wall, reached out a trembling hand to touch
its cool stone, and as is the custom of Jewish visitors, tucked
into a crevice a heartfelt note to God. Then he made a fluid sign
of the cross at the most sacred site in Judaism, and a hush
carpeted the plaza as the moment sank in.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's note bore the message of reconciliation that has been
the public theme of his six-day personal pilgrimage, which
concluded peacefully Sunday as he moved from the Al-Aqsa Mosque to
the wall and then to the Church of the Holy Sepulcher. Traveling in
an armored jeeplike vehicle with heavy security, he linked with his
presence the nerve centers of the three Abrahamic faiths that
consider Jerusalem holy and reluctantly share the walled Old City
in its heart.
</P>
<P>
   But the interfaith link was a tenuous one. And it wavered even
before the pope flew off Sunday evening, visibly moved by his
journey along Jesus' footsteps, though the path traversed a Holy
Land mined with religious and political sensitivities. Having made
a mark on a place that does not impress easily, the pope left
behind the tensions _ and an open white sheet of paper that stood
out among the hundreds of folded slips wedged into the Western
Wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``God of our fathers, you chose Abraham and his descendants to
bring your name to the nations,'' said the note, in English, which
was later moved to the Holocaust museum to be preserved. ``We are
deeply saddened by the behavior of those who in the course of
history have caused these children of yours to suffer. And asking
your forgiveness, we wish to commit ourselves to genuine
brotherhood with the people of the covenant. Jerusalem, 26.3.2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joann
</P>
<P>
   One after the other, Melchior, in Hebrew, and thenthe pope, in
Latin, read Psalm 122, an ode to peace in Jerusalem. Melchior said
the Jewish-Catholic reconciliation had been difficult for both
sides, ``which is why it took 52 years for this to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult for them theologically, and it's difficult for
us psychologically,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As the ceremony progressed, most of the Jewish visitors to the
wall stopped praying and watched, hemmed in by security officers.
One young man, who shouted out in Hebrew, ``Jews, Jews, my family
was killed in Europe,'' was quickly hauled away by the police. The
police detained seven Jews and three Palestinians for disrupting or
planning disruptions of the visit, Israeli radio said.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's message created a document for Israel from a prayer
of forgiveness that the pope originally offered at St. Peter's
Basilica earlier this month. ``A 2,000-year-old account is now
closed!'' said Binyamin Ben- Eliezer, the communications minister.
</P>
<P>
   Like everything else here, the Church of the Holy Sepulcher is
riven. Three major Christian rites and several other denominations
share it. But the strife was quieted for the day as the sects
postponed their individual services to allow the pope to celebrate
Mass in what he called ``the mother of all churches.'' It stands on
what are venerated as the sites of Jesus' crucifixion, burial and
resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   Greeted by Syrian Orthodox clergymen wearing red Fez hats,
gold-embroidered tunics and ceremonial swords, John Paul was led to
the pink slab where tradition says that Jesus was prepared for
burial. Assisted, the pope sank to his knees and kissed it, lifting
from its marble surface a face lost in reverie.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he delayed his departure from the Holy Land so that he
could return to the Holy Sepulcher to pray once more before
leaving. ``The message of the Gospel takes on flesh and blood when
you come to these places,'' Maida said. The pope is ``a mystic and
very spiritual man _ the pilgrimage has brought this out like never
before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
