<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, March 27, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Showers and isolated thunderstorms will accompany a cold front
crossing the East on Monday. Rain will move east from the Ohio and
Tennessee valleys on Monday morning, reaching the Appalachians by
afternoon. Ahead of the front, breezes from the south will direct
mild air into the Northeast as morning sun yields to increasing
clouds. Onshore breezes will temper the warmth on the northeast
coast.
</P>
<P>
   Blustery winds from the northwest will import colder air into
the Middle West on Monday. As the sun heats the ground and
overlying atmosphere, vigorous currents of rising air will generate
clouds and spotty showers, some of which will produce small hail.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, a pair of disturbances will bring clouds and
scattered showers to portions of the Pacific coast.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Winds of March
</P>
<P>
   This past weekend, winds exceeded 30 mph in much of the
Northeast as a weak low-pressure system swept through the region.
Even in the absence of a big storm, the March atmosphere is primed
for strong winds. In early spring, winds several thousand feet
above the ground often blow at fast, winterlike speeds. Meanwhile,
a strengthening March sun warms the earth, generating updrafts and
downdrafts of air. These vertical motions mix the lower atmosphere,
directing fast winds aloft toward the earth's surface, setting the
stage for the gusty winds of March.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
