<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8456 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BIZTV-WEB-MEDIA-ART-8     03-26 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZTV-WEB-MEDIA-ART-855(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL STREET USING WEBCASTS TO REACH INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The word ASTERISK in parentheses has been used instead of the
symbol, which is nontransmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Interviews with analysts have been the stock in trade of
financial television broadcasts for years. Now the large brokerage
companies like Merrill Lynch, PaineWebber and others that have
provided the analysts are putting them directly before clients, via
their own Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Using streaming video technology, which is essentially
broadcasting over the Internet, the financial service companies are
experimenting with daily programs that resemble half-hour newscasts
but feature the companies' own analysts, reporting on market trends
and recommending hot stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street Webcasting stands to further blur the line between
financial service companies and the traditional media _ a process
that began years ago when some of the big brokerage firms started
sending television stations recorded interviews with analysts and
video news packages featuring the firms' big clients.
</P>
<P>
   The self-generated Webcasts also raise questions about
maintaining objectivity, when the primary purpose of the
information being given is to attract clients and sell services.
</P>
<P>
   The new Wall Street Webcasts are an example of how ``the walls
that have separated e-commerce from the media are coming down,''
said Mark A. Thalhimer, director of the Future of News project at
the Radio and Television News Directors Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening now is that the news provider, to a much
greater degree than before, has a financial stake in the
transaction that is being presented to the public,'' Thalhimer
said. ``I wonder how consumers will view that, and how they will
make the distinction between the news and someone so closely
associated with selling something.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the financial service companies see no conflict.
They consider what they are providing to be information that helps
both their large investor clients and the typical individual
investor.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're providing is not just content, but context,'' said
Frank Zammataro, first vice president of the Digital Business
Development Group at Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is no question that the brokerage firms are
competing with Internet stock trading services like
E(ASTERISK)Trade for investors' attention. ``If you understand how
consumers are making decisions, then using the Internet this way
presents an opportunity to shape those decisions,'' Zammataro said.
</P>
<P>
   What Merrill Lynch provides is not really news, company
officials say, but information and opinion to help investors.
``What we feature can be newsworthy, but we are not a news
organization,'' said Fred Yager, director of Merrill Lynch Global
Broadcast Service.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch is far ahead of the other financial service
companies in Webcasting. Since last March the firm has put out two
daily menus, one on its general Internet site
(www.merrilllynch.com) for casual browsers and another just for
clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were getting calls from clients asking, `How come I've
always got to see your analysts on CNBC _ why can't you get them to
us first?''' Yager said.
</P>
<P>
   The Webcast on the company's general Internet site, which is
available starting at 11 a.m. each day the stock market is open,
includes streaming video reports about industry trends. Securities
regulations force Merrill Lynch to stop short of discussing
particular stocks, because the audience is too broad.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the reports, however, viewers are told that if
they want to know what Merrill analysts think about individual
stocks in the featured industry, they should follow a link to the
client site, askmerrill.com, which includes what is called the
Global Investor Network. Once there, they have access to the
complete Webcast. They can try a 30-day subscription, and get free
permanent access by opening an account.
</P>
<P>
   While the company has spent only an estimated $2 million on the
Global Investor Network, it can put out a half-hour report using
Merrill Lynch analysts on trading floors in New York, London, Hong
Kong and Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of this Webcast is the summary of Merrill Lynch's
morning call, the 7 a.m. meeting at which analysts discuss the most
widely held and active stocks of the day. There also are segments
on mutual funds, international investing and personal finances, all
with Merrill Lynch analysts who talk about stocks they recommend.
</P>
<P>
   With high-speed Internet connections, the Webcasts resemble
television broadcasts, and once put on the site they can be
downloaded by clients at any time. The connections tend to get
clogged, which affects the video quality. At slower speeds, the
images are hazy and movements are quite jerky.
</P>
<P>
   Yager, a former reporter and television producer, said that
since the project began last March, viewership had increased from a
few thousand per day to more than 100,000 daily hits.
</P>
<P>
   In a few weeks, the site will be overhauled. Yager said that
under the new format, clients would be able to switch from Webcast
reports on one company to archived reports on other companies in
the same field. They also will be able to download the text of
complete research reports done by Merrill Lynch analysts on related
stocks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch has long been involved in television production.
Through its television network, it provides video interviews with
Merrill Lynch analysts to hundreds of local television stations
around the world that subscribe to the service.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the production is handled by Bob Plunkett, a former Fox
network television reporter who runs his own production company.
Plunkett said the main difference between preparing a news segment
for Merrill's Internet site and one for network television had to
do with packaging.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're putting something out on the Web, you're basically
giving it a lot more raw, straight objective data because we know
who the audience is,'' Plunkett said. ``If I was back at Fox, my
audience would have been so broad that I'd have to present the
material so that it could be understood by a big investment banker
and the guy who shines his shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Other financial service companies that do not have small clients
do not have to put on separate Webcasts the way Merrill Lynch does.
Goldman, Sachs, for example, plans to start a Webcast soon, but it
will be directed toward its institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   PaineWebber expects to begin a trial of a daily Webcast this
summer, according to Dennis M. McCann, the firm's director of
marketing communications. Clients will also be able to pay bills
and transfer funds while viewing the analysts' report.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest Wall Street firms, Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, took a tentative step into streaming video earlier this
month when it put on a widely publicized special Webcast about,
appropriately, Internet stocks. The firm says it will follow up
with other special Webcasts as warranted, but it is not ready to
put out a daily report that includes video on demand.
</P>
<P>
   Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co. is already using streaming video to take the
place of the investor road shows it puts on in cities across the
United States to drum up support for new stock offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Peter D. Cherasia, head of e-commerce for Bear, Stearns, said he
was discussing a deal with CNBC to use the firm's Web site to
rebroadcast interviews done with its analysts after they appear on
television. Once the company generates enough content, he said, it
will revamp its Web site to include its own daily Webcast and other
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make our site as sticky as possible,'' Cherasia
said, using a term that refers to visitor retention, ``so clients
will have a reason to stay on or come back throughout the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as financial service companies seem intent on moving onto
the terrain of the traditional media, broadcasters and news
agencies are finding their way into financial services.
</P>
<P>
   In September, CNBC bought a 12.4 percent equity stake in
Archipelago, a large electronic communications network that has
applied to be registered as an Internet stock exchange. Other
investors in Archipelago include Goldman, Sachs and Instinet,
another electronic trading system that is part of Reuters Group,
the parent of one of the oldest news services in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The president of CNBC, William L. Bolster, said there was
currently no plan to take CNBC in that same direction. He noted
that General Electric, CNBC's parent company, already has a
financial arm _ GE Capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``The CNBC business model doesn't envision that,'' he said in a
telephone interview. ``I'm saying no, but I can't categorically say
that it will be no forever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-00 1723EST &QL; 
