<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FM-RADIO-MEDIA-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FCC HEADS FOR SHOWDOWN WITH CONGRESS OVER RADIO PLAN
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress and the Federal Communications Commission,
two of this district's slowest bureaucracies, are moving with
remarkable alacrity in a fight over control of the airwaves and the
future of FM radio.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers and the regulators are quickly heading for a
collision over the government's plan to transform the nation's FM
radio band by giving away hundreds of new licenses for
noncommercial, low-power stations for schools, churches, community
groups and others.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, in response to thousands of requests to open such FM
stations, the FCC intends to begin the licensing process by
conducting a lottery to determine which states will be eligible
first. The licenses would enable so-called microradio broadcasters
to use inexpensive equipment and relatively small antennas for
100-watt stations that could beam programs over geographic areas as
large as seven miles in diameter.
</P>
<P>
   But Capitol Hill, responding to a wave of lobbying from the
nation's largest broadcasters, is moving swiftly to kill the plan.
Last Thursday, legislation blocking the plan sailed through a House
subcommittee, after the National Association of Broadcasters,
National Public Radio and many lawmakers raised concerns that the
signals from the new low-power stations would interfere with the
signals of existing stations.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which has 153 co-sponsors in the House and 21
in the Senate, is expected to be considered by the House Commerce
Committee soon. And because it has the endorsement of House Speaker
Dennis Hastert of Illinois, it could reach the floor shortly after
that.
</P>
<P>
   The debate has been bitter over the low-power radio program,
which has been in the works for more than a year and is among the
highest priorities of the FCC's chairman, William Kennard. The
controversy has involved unusual political alliances and dueling
technical studies about the effects of the new stations on existing
broadcasters. It has also made political enemies of some
traditional allies.
</P>
<P>
   National Public Radio, for instance, a bulwark of alternative
radio programming, has urged the FCC to delay the start of the
low-power program until July so that field tests can be conducted
to determine whether there will be significant signal interference.
Kevin Klose, the president of NPR, said the organization had not
endorsed the legislation, as proposed by the National Association
of Broadcasters, which would kill the FCC program.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, NPR now finds itself in the awkward position of
being opposed by some of the same religious, educational and
community organizations that were crucial allies in years past,
when NPR came under attack from Newt Gingrich and the Reagan
administration.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition supporting the FCC's plan includes the United
Church of Christ; the U.S. Catholic Conference; the National League
of Cities; the Communications Workers of America; musical artists
like Bonnie Raitt and the Indigo Girls; and a number of colleges
and universities with NPR-affiliated stations.
</P>
<P>
   The community groups supporting the plan, in turn, find
themselves at odds with broadcast services for the blind _ whose
advocates fear that the new low-power stations would disrupt the
frequencies set aside for special programs on which volunteers read
newspapers, magazines and provide other essential information to
more than one million visually impaired listeners.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, a divided FCC approved the plan after government
engineers scaled back the program and said their tests had found
that the low-power stations would not create any significant new
signal interference.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's decision prompted both legislative and
courtroom challenges from the industry. The National Association of
Broadcasters filed a lawsuit in U.S. Appeals Court here to overturn
the FCC's vote, while NPR asked the FCC to reconsider its decision.
</P>
<P>
   Under assault from such quarters and confident that its
technical analysis was superior to that of the industry's, the
agency decided to meet the industry's challenges by moving quickly
to implement the program. The lottery on Monday will determine
which states will be considered first to receive the new stations.
</P>
<P>
   The low-power program comes as the radio broadcasting industry
itself is at a crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   Kennard has tried to increase the number of voices on the
airwaves in response to the rapid consolidation of the commercial
broadcasting industry. According to a report this month by the
Congressional Research Service, the number of radio station owners
decreased by nearly one-fifth between 1995 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But that consolidation has had little discernable impact on the
volume of traffic across the spectrum, which has only grown more
congested in recent years as a result of new wireless technology,
and which broadcasters say would be overwhelmed by the introduction
of hundreds of new low-power stations.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to accusations that the agency has been reckless with
its management of the radio spectrum, Kennard and his aides say
that the broadcast industry has waged a scare-and-smear campaign.
They accuse the industry of using fraudulent technical arguments
about signal interference from the new low-power stations out of
fear that the new stations will lure listeners away from existing
broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the National Association of Broadcasters has
blanketed Capitol Hill with compact disks that purport to
demonstrate the kinds of interference that would be caused by
Kennard's plan. The disk simulates such interference as a cacophony
of radio programs colliding on one frequency. Although government
engineers say the simulation is downright fraudulent and cannot be
replicated at the FCC's radio lab, the compact disk has had a
substantial impact on the debate in Congress and has repeatedly
been cited by lawmakers as evidence of the need to block the
low-power radio program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The broadcasters have engaged in a systematic campaign of
misinformation and scare tactics to shut off new voices from coming
onto the airwaves,'' Kennard said in an interview last week. ``This
is not rocket science. We have studied the way FM signals propagate
around the country. The interference argument is being used as a
smoke screen to mask a historic battle by incumbents who want to
protect their markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seems to be this undercurrent that low-power licensees _
community groups, schools, churches _ are somehow riffraff and
that's just not fair,'' he said. ``My plea to people is they should
allow this to go forward, and once they see that it will not create
havoc they will calm down.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the FCC had carefully crafted the rules, after
study by its engineers, to preclude any significant new radio
interference. The rules require, for instance, that there be at
least two frequency intervals on the radio dial between a low-power
station and any other station.
</P>
<P>
   The industry has replied that the rules are insufficient to
protect the spectrum and that the FCC, in its zeal to score
political points by helping the small community groups, have
abandoned its responsibility to protect the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``The FCC has turned its back on its principle mission of
maintaining spectrum integrity,'' said Edward O. Fritts, president
of the National Association of Broadcasters. ``The technical
arguments are not a smoke screen. They stand on their own merit. If
this could be done, it would have been 20 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Fritts said that the compact disks given to congressmen and
senators were not misleading.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clearly identified as a simulation of interference
effects, not a demonstration of actual interference,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While the legislation opposing the plan has been sponsored and
supported largely by Republicans, a growing number of Democrats
have begun to endorse it. Kennard, however, continues to enjoy
support for his proposal from other more powerful quarters of the
administration.
</P>
<P>
   A White House official said on Friday that presidential aides
were supportive of the proposal and did not see any need for
legislation to limit the FCC's ability to oversee the spectrum.
During the presidential campaign, Vice President Al Gore spoke out
in favor of Kennard's plan and said he thought it was a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush has not addressed the issue or taken a
position on it, according to Mindy Tucker, the press secretary to
Bush's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But whether support from the White House will be sufficient
remains to be seen. In recent days, the National Association of
Broadcasters has mounted a vigorous campaign, getting broadcasters
in every state to urge their congressional representatives to kill
the plan. Fritts said he had not discussed the matter with his old
college roommate _ Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of
Mississippi. But apparently, Fritts sees no such need.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't spoken with him about this subject,'' Fritts said.
``I'm sure he'll be talking to the Mississippi broadcasters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
