<HEADER>
A8472 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-HEPBURN-REVIEW-NYT     03-26 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HEPBURN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE AUDREY HEPBURN STORY': A BIG-SCREEN LEGEND, ONLY SMALLER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(ms) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   We see her first in front of Tiffany's, where a bright yellow
Checker cab deposits her. She has on big black sunglasses and that
sleek black evening dress; her hair is swept up in a huge early-60s
French twist; she carries her coffee and pastry in a white paper
bag. And a man who looks like Truman Capote is sitting a few feet
away in a director's chair, grumbling about how much better Marilyn
Monroe would have been in the role.
</P>
<P>
   The first scene of ABC's movie ``The Audrey Hepburn Story''
takes us to the New York filming of ``Breakfast at Tiffany's''
(1961), in which Hepburn played the sort-of call girl Holly
Golightly from Capote's novella. It evokes Hepburn's star power and
tests the mettle of Jennifer Love Hewitt, the 21-year-old
television actress who has dared to play a sacred screen star whom
many movie fans consider inimitable.
</P>
<P>
   But Hewitt, as she probably knows by now, can relax. Her
portrayal of Hepburn, who died in 1993, is not the disaster many
people expected. In fact, with the help of a voice coach (getting
Hepburn's voice right makes up for a lot) and an intelligent script
by the playwright Marsha Norman, Hewitt, the star of her own Fox
series, ``Time of Your Life,'' does an admirable, obviously
respectful impersonation.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that ``The Audrey Hepburn Story'' rises above
its genre. All three hours of the film argue against the
advisability of making biographical films like this at all. When
the subject is a contemporary _ someone viewers vividly remember
and can still see, in her radiant originality, in dozens of films _
even Meryl Streep might have trouble capturing the magic.
</P>
<P>
   The film's flashback narrative begins in Brussels in 1935, with
the 6-year-old Audrey hiding under the dining room table eating
sugar buns. Her parents argue, and after little Audrey (Sarah
Hyland) dances once with her father (Keir Dullea) in the park, he
leaves for a new job in London and is scarcely seen again.
</P>
<P>
   Next we see the lonely adolescent Audrey (Emmy Rossum), whose
father has not telephoned in five years, being shipped off to
boarding school in England, where it is hoped she will make
friends. At Rigden's School in Kent, Audrey discovers ballet,
which, as her roommate explains, ``makes you forget how sad you
are.'' But once she has happily settled in, her mother (Frances
Fisher, in a reprise of her ``Titanic'' role as an aristocrat
holding her head high through hard times) insists on moving to the
Netherlands, which looks like a safer bet than England as World War
II expands.
</P>
<P>
   Bad idea. Arnhem, where Audrey and her mother stay with an
uncle, is soon invaded by the Germans. The uncle, working for the
Resistance, is killed. Audrey, who helps the Resistance by
delivering messages on her bicycle, sees people she knows shot dead
by German soldiers or taken away by them. There are terrible food
shortages, and when Audrey becomes ill (anemia, asthma and colitis)
the town is out of medical supplies.
</P>
<P>
   After the war Hepburn (now played by Hewitt) continues her
ballet studies in London, but her teacher levels with her. ``I
regret to tell you,'' she says, ``that you have neither the stature
nor the talent to achieve success as a prima ballerina.'' A dance
classmate (and future star), Kay Kendall (Seana Kofoed), suggests
dancing in musical theater, and Jerome Robbins casts them both in
``High Button Shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   For Hepburn, this leads to bit parts in movies, mostly playing
cigarette girls. Meanwhile she meets the perfect man, James Hanson
(Peter Giles), who is handsome, kind, fabulously rich and supports
her career wholeheartedly. But when Colette (Lenie Scoffie) spots
her near a movie set in Monte Carlo and immediately knows that she
should play her heroine Gigi onstage, Hepburn breaks off her
engagement and heads for Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   From there it's one career success after another. After ``Gigi''
comes her first film, ``Roman Holiday,'' and a best-actress Oscar;
the play ``Ondine''; the film ``Sabrina,'' during which she has an
affair with William Holden; and ``The Nun's Story,'' during which
she first becomes concerned with the plight of hungry children
around the world. This inspires her work later in life with Unicef.
</P>
<P>
   She marries Mel Ferrer, and they have a son. She finds her
father again and learns that he has not changed. The film ends with
``Breakfast at Tiffany's'' and summarizes the rest of Hepburn's
life _ a second marriage, to Dr. Andrea Dotti; a second son; her
final years with Robert Wolder in Switzerland, where she died of
colon cancer at 63 _ in a few sentences.
</P>
<P>
   In this version of Hepburn's rise to fame, directed by Steven
Robman, virtually everyone who meets her is instantly charmed. In
some cases, normally sophisticated people seem a little too easily
impressed. It is possible that Colette, upon seeing Hepburn for the
first time, said, ``Look at her, she's charming,'' but surely not
in such an astonished voice. And Capote (Michael J. Burg) may have
really been surprised that Hepburn understood the symbolism of
tossing the nameless cat out of the taxi in ``Breakfast at
Tiffany's,'' but he probably didn't stare at her dumbfounded as a
result.
</P>
<P>
   In the end the lesson of Hepburn's life seems to be that
privilege followed by privation and a mother who imparts lessons
like ``Women of our class do not whine or sulk'' are great
character builders. Not even Hollywood could take that away.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE AUDREY HEPBURN STORY' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. ET Monday on ABC
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 7 in New York)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly Rubin and Robert Greenwald, executive producers;
Jennifer Love Hewitt, co-executive producer; Steven Robman and Kay
Hoffman, producers. Teleplay by Marsha Norman. Directed by Robman.
A production of Robert Greenwald Productions in association with
Endemol Entertainment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Jennifer Love Hewitt (Audrey Hepburn), Frances Fisher
(Ella), Eric McCormack (Mel Ferrer), Keir Dullea (Joseph), Gabriel
Macht (William Holden), Peter Giles (James Hanson), Emmy Rossum
(Audrey, age 14), Sarah Hyland (Audrey, age 6), Seana Kofoed (Kay
Kendall), Michael J. Burg (Truman Capote), Lenie Scoffie (Colette),
Stephane Archambault (Marcel Le Bon) and Joan Copeland (Cathleen
Nesbitt).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
