<HEADER>
A8474 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     03-26 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 2000 Chronicle Publishing Company 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LEARNING HOW TO CRACK A JOKE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In ``Survival Skills for the Modern Man,'' Men's Journal tells
how to make your friends slap their knees. According to
 &UR; Rodney Rothman &LR; , who writes for the ``Late Show With  &UR; David &LR; 
 &UR; Letterman &LR; ,'' ``Everyone knows about the rule of threes. You know,
people tend to find things funny in groups of three. What people
don't know is the rule of 17s. Four through 16 is not funny.
Seventeen is funny again.''
</P>
<P>
   The old saw about the letter ``K'' being funny is passe, says
Rothman. ``In my opinion, that's no longer true. Today, H is funny.
And A if there's an umlaut over it.'' (Sharp-eyed readers will note
that today is Umlaut Day in Personals, and where else can you find
a diacritical jamboree?)
</P>
<P>
   One more thing: ``If a joke doesn't fly, say, `Then I got hit in
the face by a goose.' Or `Then I got hit in the face by
 &UR; Charles Durning &LR; 's pendulous breasts.' Now it's funny.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GAMESMANSHIP &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Responding to last week's item about the Six Degrees of
 &UR; Kevin Bacon &LR;  game,  &UR; Phil Lapsley &LR;  notes that mathematicians bestow
Erdos Numbers. If a scholar has co-written a paper with the
``incredibly prolific'' Hungarian mathematician  &UR; Paul Erdos &LR;  (note
to editors; there should be an umlaut over the o in Erdos), the
scholar has a rating of 1. If a paper has been co-written with
someone who has written with Erdos, the rating is 2.
</P>
<P>
   Lapsley points to the Erdos Numbers Project, as described in a
Web site maintained by  &UR; Jerry Grossman  &LR; of Oakland University.
Erdos is actually linked to Bacon in four steps, starting with the
mathematician's appearance in the 1993 movie ``N Is a Number.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. In response to a recent New York Times story about
mah-jongg, a letter to the editor recalled that his aunt used to
play with friends on the front porch of an executive of the
Institute for Advanced Studies in Princeton.
</P>
<P>
   One day,  &UR; Albert Einstein &LR;  ``wandered by, puffing on his pipe.
</P>
<P>
   He watched for a while and then asked Aunt Margery what was
going on.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Mah-jongg,' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   `` `I can't follow it,' Einstein responded. `It's too
complicated.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE PERFECT INTERVIEW &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At a rock-critic panel at the recent Austin music conclave South
by Southwest,  &UR; Jaan Uhelszki &LR;  of Rolling Stone Online recalled an
interview with Led Zeppelin's  &UR; Jimmy Page &LR; , in the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   After Page ignored Uhelszki's questions, the critic realized
that she was supposed to direct each question to Page's publicist,
who would then pose it to Page.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think of the new album?'' Uhelszki asked the
publicist.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wants to know what you think of the new album,'' the
publicist asked Page.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have strangled him,'' said Uhelszki to the panel's
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually,'' said myplay.com editorial director  &UR; Ben &LR; 
 &UR; Fong-Torres &LR; , another Bay Area member of the panel, ``you should
have strangled the publicist, and then she would have strangled
Jimmy Page.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Robin Williams &LR;  _ who was hilarious lampooning  &UR; Al Gore &LR;  at
last week's Bread &AMP; Roses benefit in San Francisco _ is master of
ceremonies Tuesday night, when  &UR; Hillary Clinton  &LR; receives a ``Woman
of Courage'' award at a Los Angeles gala raising money for breast
cancer research. She was chosen for her ``lasting commitment to
family, women and children,' organizers said, before she declared
for the Senate in New York.
</P>
<P>
   - Rep.  &UR; Jim Traficant &LR; , D-Ohio, the target of an FBI
investigation of organized crime, has discussed his case informally
with colleagues. ``I'm scared to death,'' he said, in comments
quoted in the Hill. ``I'm not a macho. ... I have a lot of pressure
on me. I'm in a hell of a situation.''
</P>
<P>
   His official position, as quoted in a speech cited in Roll Call,
is different: ``I plan to fight like a junkyard dog,'' he said.
``And if I die in that courtroom, bring it on!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss America when it was boring, when you came home at 5
p.m. to a dinner of mashed potatoes, a little roast beef and
creamed corn out of a can. There was no self-esteem movement in the
old America. Nobody really thought they deserved a Hermes scarf.''
</P>
<P>
   - &UR; Peggy Noonan &LR; , conservative columnist and author of ``The Case
Against Hillary Clinton,'' in W.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
