r a BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     03-26 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 2000 Chronicle Publishing Company 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LEARNING HOW TO CRACK A JOKE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In ``Survival Skills for the Modern Man,'' Men's Journal tells
how to make your friends slap their knees. According to
 &UR; Rodney Rothman &LR; , who writes for the ``Late Show With  &UR; David &LR; 
 &UR; Letterman &LR; ,'' ``Everyone knows about the rule of threes. You know,
people tend to find things funny in groups of three. What people
don't know is the rule of 17s. Four through 16 is not funny.
Seventeen is funny again.''
</P>
<P>
   The old saw about the letter ``K'' being funny is passe, says
Rothman. ``In my opinion, that's no longer true. Today, H is funny.
And A if there's an umlaut over it.'' (Sharp-eyed readers will note
that today is Umlaut Day in Personals, and where else can you find
a diacritical jamboree?)
</P>
<P>
   One more thing: ``If a joke doesn't fly, say, `Then I got hit in
the face by a goose.' Or `Then I got hit in the face by
 &UR; Charles Durning &LR; 's pendulous breasts.' Now it's funny.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GAMESMANSHIP &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Responding to last week's item about the Six Degrees of
 &UR; Kevin Bacon &LR;  game,  &UR; Phil Lapsley &LR;  notes that mathematicians bestow
