<DOCNO> NYT20000326.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8479 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INTERACTIVE-AD-COLUMN     03-26 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERACTIVE-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SKY AND NUFORIA PLAN TO MERGE HOT, INTERNET-DRIVEN ENTITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By PATRICIA WINTERS LAURO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the nation's hot creative boutiques specializing in
Internet marketing and advertising plans to merge with a larger
interactive shop, reflecting a trend of marriages between
Internet-driven firms and agencies that produce creative material
for the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The companies plan to announce the merger Monday, according to
executives for both agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sky Interactive, the San Francisco-based shop known for its
work on the Web for clients like Nike, Absolut vodka and Altoids
mints, will merge with Nuforia Inc., a larger shop based in New
York and Houston that was formed through a merger just nine months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The newly combined company will have 315 employees in seven
offices. The two merging companies had combined revenues of about
$30 million in 1999, roughly $7 million of which came from Red Sky.
The new firm will be called Red Sky Interactive, with its top
executives located in various offices around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The merger came out of Red Sky's need for both critical mass and
greater technical ability, which the company said would be needed
with the advent of broadband, or high-speed, Internet technology.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sky and other interactive shops contend that broadband
capacity will have profound effects on advertising. It will combine
broadcast and interactive technology to give consumers extensive
choices for programming and information, said Tim Smith, Red Sky's
40-year-old founder and chief executive officer, who will become
the new firm's chief strategic officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The projects we are going to do are going to get enormous, and
we knew we weren't going to make it as a boutique,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The marriage was blessed by Omnicom Group Inc., the world's
largest advertising agency organization, known for huge global
agencies like BBDO Worldwide and TBWA Worldwide. Omnicom has
minority stakes in both Nuforia and Red Sky, as well as 19 other
interactive and digital firms, largely through a unit called
Communicade. In fact, according to Smith, the two firms were
introduced to each other by Omnicom's president and chief
executive, John D. Wren. Smith said that Wren was a personal friend
who sat on Red Sky's board.
</P>
<P>
   ``He introduced us and left the room,'' said Smith. ``It wasn't
a shotgun wedding.''
</P>
<P>
   In Nuforia, Smith said Red Sky found the technical structure,
engineering base and personal chemistry that it had been seeking in
a partner for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   The merger is part of a big trend among interactive agencies. In
the last year, interactive shops involved in mergers include
Agency.com, Razorfish and USWeb/CKS, now called MarchFirst after
its acquisition in December by Whittman-Hart. Meanwhile, several
big shops have started their own interactive agencies, like BBDO's
(at)tmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Nuforia itself is the result of a merger last June between Belk
Mignogna Associates, a New York Web-design and brand-creation firm,
and Net Explorer Inc., an e-business company with a staff of some
100 developers and engineers. BMA merged for similar reasons as Red
Sky, said BMA's founder, Howard Belk, who becomes president of the
new Red Sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a branding and interactive shop that was front-end
focused,'' Belk said. ``We had a thin rank of developers and
engineers, and we were frustrated by partnering with companies.''
</P>
<P>
   And there are more mergers to come, predicted Bill Bingham, 48,
formerly chief executive officer of Nuforia and now chief executive
of the new Red Sky. He said agencies needed to merge the technical
and creative sides to offer ``end-to-end'' services for clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be more,'' predicted Marissa Gluck, analyst with
Jupiter Communications in New York, the Internet research and
consulting company. ``Merging tech and creative is a no-brainer.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the activity is simple: the market for
interactive services is booming, from Web site design to
promotional CD-ROMS to direct interactive advertising on the Web,
like banner ads. Online ad spending alone is expected to grow to
$4.7 billion this year, from $3.2 billion last year, according to
Jupiter Communications. Firms in the business have seen their
revenue double, triple and quadruple since their meager starts just
a few short years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually every company in this area is turning work away,''
said Ted Kempf, a senior analyst with the GartnerGroup's Dataquest
research unit, in Mountain View, Calif. ``The companies that merge
what we call the back end with front-end new media capabilities are
well positioned to help traditional brick-and-mortar business enter
the e-connected age, the new business era.''
</P>
<P>
   Gluck said the mergers also had allowed some firms to reach
sufficient size to go public, including Razorfish, Organic and
Agency.com, which are all Communicade agencies. Red Sky said that
it, too, would consider a public stock offering, but that no plans
for one were currently under way.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Omnicom has high hopes for the new Red Sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our view is that both companies combined have all the
potential to become the next market leader,'' said Bruce Redditt,
an Omnicom Group executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The current market leader is Sapient, in Cambridge, Mass., with
1999 revenues of $277 million, according to AdweekOnline, published
by the trade magazine Adweek.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sky will continue to seek mergers and acquisitions over the
next 24 to 48 months and has plans to expand internationally as
well, Bingham said.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1993, Red Sky has done work that included a Web site
for Altoids mints; among its features is the Peppermint Lounge,
where users can download and mix their own funky music. Another is
millerlite.com, a site that allows users to create a beer pager
that alerts friends when it is ``Miller time.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Sky and others predict that broadband technology will create
a revolution in the ad business. Stephen O. Frankfurt, a longtime
ad executive and senior vice president at Nuforia and the new Red
Sky, said he expected broadband to remake advertising the way TV
remade the ad world in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sky calls the new advertising ``strategic entertainment,''
which essentially means merging product news or advertising with
entertainment. Red Sky has been using entertainment, like the beer
pager, to pull people into the site, but Smith said that was just
the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, because of broadband, the television screen may
offer broadcast programming that is also interactive. Rather than
watch a program and then go to a Web site for more information, a
consumer might be able to click on a link right on the screen, with
no interruption of the entertainment programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``The enormous challenge here is realizing the nature of
advertising is fundamentally about to evolve,'' Smith said. ``And
we are right on the cusp of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-00 1846EST &QL; 
