<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IP-TELEPHONY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CISCO TAKES INTERNET PHONES TO NEXT STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a year ago that John T. Chambers, chief executive of
Cisco Systems, said he wanted the traditional telephone on his desk
to be gone in 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   That has not happened; the old phone is still there. But Monday,
Cisco intends to announce an office telephone system based on
Internet technology.
</P>
<P>
   The system, which transmits voice calls in the electronic
language of the Internet, could push the company to the top of the
budding Internet-telephone market. Proponents say such systems
bring new convenience, efficiency and cost-savings to corporate
communications.
</P>
<P>
   While North America's traditional office telephone powerhouses,
Lucent Technologies and Nortel Networks of Canada, are also
developing Internet phone systems for offices, Cisco may have the
early edge.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch intends to make Cisco's the main phone system at a
new campus in Hopewell, N.J., with 5,000 of the new phones to be
installed over 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Texas Instruments is experimenting with about 500
of the new phones in an international test. Executives from both
companies are giving the new Cisco system positive reviews.
</P>
<P>
   For all of the ways in which technology has changed how people
live and how companies do business, the final frontier of the first
Internet revolution will probably be the humble telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Many communications companies are promoting so-called Internet
telephony as a low-cost long-distance alternative for consumers.
But the sound quality of phone calls over the public Internet is
generally inferior to that of calls over traditional telephone
systems. The technologies and systems are not yet in place to allow
the Internet to reliably transmit high-quality phone calls for
millions of people.
</P>
<P>
   Office networks, however, are in some ways much more stable than
the public Internet, perhaps making them more amenable to early
Internet telephone efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Most offices now have two communications networks, one for
computers and another for telephones. Many companies maintain
separate staffs for each. Cisco's vision is to allow companies to
use a common Internet-based network for both computers and
telephones internally, reducing cost and complexity and adding new
functions to the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The networks that can't do data, voice and video are
dinosaurs,'' Chambers said in an interview last Friday. ``We're
going to see open standards for any new telecommunications or
computer product to connect to one network. This is the first
gauntlet thrown down in that direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisco's new Internet phones connect to an office's Ethernet data
network using a jack like those on the back of a standard office
computer. One of the most attractive features of the system is that
the phone can identify itself to a corporate network regardless of
its location. A worker from New York, for instance, could take his
or her phone to a corporate office in San Francisco and be reached
as easily as in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can plug the phone into any connection, and it will keep
the same number you had,'' Brian J. Bonner, chief information
officer and a vice president at Texas Instruments, said. ``You can
take your phone and plug it in at a TI office in Germany, for
instance, and I can dial your number, which looks like Dallas, and
it rings in Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   When a worker changes offices at a company that uses a
traditional phone system, a technician must generally reconfigure
the phone system so that the worker's old phone operates correctly
at the new location. An Internet phone system can eliminate that
effort and cost, leading some of Cisco's customers to believe that
the Internet system would be much cheaper to operate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some very compelling economics associated with IP
phones relative to traditional phones,'' said John A. McKinley,
chief technology officer and an executive vice president at Merrill
Lynch, referring to Internet protocol, the language of cyberspace.
``Ultimately, I think this represents the next stage in growth for
Cisco.''
</P>
<P>
   Chambers must think so, too. The traditional phone by his desk
shares space with one of his company's new creations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
