<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MEDIA MACHINE GETS TOO CLOSE TO HOME  
 ON THE OUTS AT FOX AND CONDE NAST  
 SHORT LIFE FOR SHORT'S SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The e-mail message that hundreds of journalists received from
the P.R. Newswire started out routinely enough. Executives of the
distribution service and Web site for public relations offices
wrote that it sought ``to strengthen the link between companies
posting press releases to the site and journalists like yourself
who will use it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many readers might well have hit the delete key right then. But
some who did not were dismayed at what came next: ``Beginning in
early April, public relations professionals will be able to know
which journalists opened their releases on the Press Room site.
Reports will be available that will say who, what media
organization and when a particular news release was read.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It did strike me as creepy,'' said Michael Armstrong, an
assistant business editor at The Philadelphia Inquirer. ``I
objected primarily to their characterization that this would
actually benefit journalists. The only benefit I saw was to p.r.
firms.''
</P>
<P>
   P.R. Newswire, which is owned by United News and Media Group of
London, says that some 1,700 reporters use its Web site. As the
e-mail message arrived, a small but fervent band of outraged
journalists protested. By week's end, P.R. Newswire was in need of
some good p.r.
</P>
<P>
   Renu Aldrich, its spokeswoman, stepped into the breach. ``The
reason this evolved is that we are getting into the measuring and
monitoring business,'' Aldrich said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``We just purchased eWatch, an Internet monitoring
service. Measuring and monitoring are key for public relations and
investor relations professionals. They need to know where they are
being mentioned, what people are saying about them, so they can
track crises, rumors, things being said on message boards'' and
elsewhere in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   But in response to the protests, she said, no report will
include a journalist's name or news organization unless they have
explicitly allowed themselves to be tracked.
</P>
<P>
   Asked for the names of some of the 25 or so reporters who had
complained, Aldrich said: ``I wouldn't feel comfortable telling you
without their permission.''
</P>
<P>
   _ FELICITY BARRINGER
</P>
<P>
   Two media execs leave
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, vulgarity and cutting edge were on the ascendant. Some
mainstream media companies felt, well, out of step.
</P>
<P>
   So two of them, Fox Entertainment and Conde Nast Publications,
plucked media executives from the edge and brought them in to liven
things up.
</P>
<P>
   Fox hired Doug Herzog, the former Comedy Central executive
responsible for the scatological humor of ``South Park.''
</P>
<P>
   In a similar vein, S.I. Newhouse Jr., chairman of Conde Nast and
its parent, Advance Publications, recruited Mark Golin, editor of
Maxim magazine, to resuscitate Details magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Events last week showed how fickle the corporate world can be.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Herzog resigned after a little more than a year as
president of Fox Entertainment, a unit of News Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since his first prime-time lineup in September had no hit
shows, there had been reports that he would be replaced. Then last
fall, Fox sent him a veiled vote of no confidence: They hired
another executive, Sandy Grushow, to help run his division.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Mark Golin, the editor in chief of Details, was
dismissed after an eight-month tenure, during which he tried to
resuscitate the Conde Nast men's magazine by featuring on the cover
a succession of nearly nude actresses.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out that Golin did not mesh with the more rarefied
tastes of the Conde Nast culture. That would have been fine if the
newsstand numbers had turned around, but they never did. Details
lost the race to Maxim, the publication Golin built, which surged
past all other men's titles in circulation last year.
</P>
<P>
   Steven T. Florio, the president of Conde Nast, told the Details
staff that the May issue would be the final one under Conde Nast's
ownership; after that, the magazine will be remade by Fairchild
Publications, a corporate cousin of Conde Nast.
</P>
<P>
   The day he was dismissed last week, Golin said, ``Well, I sure
could have used more time.''
</P>
<P>
   At least, the Fox Network still exists. Details turned out to
have had as much staying power as a deposed Soviet apparatchik
airbrushed from a Stalin-era government portrait.
</P>
<P>
   Staff members cleaned out their offices on Friday. All
references to Details magazine in media material relating to a
party that the magazine was to have co-sponsored in Los Angeles
last Friday night were quickly expunged, replaced with Conde Nast
Publications.
</P>
<P>
   And in ``Contact,'' a play by John Weidman that will reopen at
Lincoln Center Theater on Thursday night, a character makes a
reference to the ``What's Hot, What's Not list in Details
magazine,'' a line that elicits a knowing laugh from the audience.
Last Friday, Philip Rinaldi, a spokesman for the play, said that
Weidman would change the reference to another magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to stay hip and contemporary,'' Rinaldi said.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
<P>
   Martin Short Show Not Quite Canceled
</P>
<P>
   The producers of ``The Martin Short Show,'' an ambitious,
syndicated, nighttime-style talk show that made its debut in
September, will tape what is expected to be its final episode this
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The producers are not happy.
</P>
<P>
   King World Productions, the show's owner, will not formally
pronounce the show dead.
</P>
<P>
   But is it alive? Bernie Brillstein, one of its executive
producers, said on Friday: ``I am telling you as a betting man, on
my five children, my wife, my home and my business, that it's not.
The staff is dispersing as of next Friday. We're just going to
finish out its season and it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Short's Los Angeles-based show garnered considerable attention
when it was first broadcast last fall, in part because it was
devised with a nighttime sensibility, even though it was to be
shown in the morning or afternoon in many parts of the country.
Aside from interviews, it also featured sketch comedy, character
portrayals by Short _ a ``Saturday Night Live'' alumnus _ and it
generally won favorable reviews. In his first episode, Short played
Martina Navratilova as a secret agent in a failed television pilot
called ``La Femme Martina'' and, in a spoof of news magazine shows
called ``Prime Time Edition Tonight,'' impersonated Janeane
Garofalo campaigning to save a serial killer.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Brillstein said, its late-night appeal may very well
have been its undoing. The show is watched in about a million homes
nationwide, compared with more than 11 million for ``Wheel of
Fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think `good' should be able to play anywhere, but maybe our
sensibility was nighttime more than nine o'clock in the morning,''
Brillstein said. ``I think it is very strange to wake up to some of
those sketches at nine o'clock in the morning.'' He said the show
needed more time to catch on and more night slots.
</P>
<P>
   Short was on vacation in Mexico last week and unavailable for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   _ JIM RUTENBERG
</P>
</TEXT>
