<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8484 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-KIPLING-BOOK-REVIEW-N     03-26 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIPLING-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RUDYARD KIPLING': BEHIND IMPERIALIST RHAPSODY, A CHILD ABANDONED 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(lb) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rudyard Kipling is one of the few writers to have their own
adjectives, but while that would normally be a mark of distinction,
in his case it is an ambiguous honor.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the orotund elegance of ``Jamesian,'' for example, or the
insinuative darkness of ``Kafkaesque,'' the word ``Kiplingesque''
has something comic and preposterous about it now. It summons up a
blimpish, condescending, epic-heroic, white-man's-burden
patriotism: not only jingoism but jingleism too.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all we have and are,'' Kipling wrote at the outbreak of
World War I, ``For all our children's fate/Stand up and take the
war./The Hun is at the gate!''
</P>
<P>
   The Kipling of lines like those, who was, as Robert Graves put
it, ``the literary aspect of the British Empire,'' is very much
part of the larger Kipling in this sure-handed new biography by
Harry Ricketts, an English editor of several editions of Kipling's
prose and poetry. But Ricketts' ``Rudyard Kipling: A Life'' shows a
more elusively full figure than the image of the writer that has
emerged over the last half-century or so.
</P>
<P>
   Kipling was, to be sure, a man who admired above all others
Cecil Rhodes, the imperial and imperious administrator of British
South Africa. In his later years Kipling seems to have been annoyed
at almost everybody _ Bolsheviks and Jews and suffragists as well
as British aristocrats and Liberals _ though he seems to have had a
particularly strong venom for the Jews.
</P>
<P>
   But Ricketts' Kipling was a man of contradictions who belonged
to the imperial club and judged it unfavorably at the same time.
Ricketts subjects Kipling's oeuvre, the many dozens of stories
especially, to an illuminating scrutiny and finds evidence that
this literary expression of the British Empire went more deeply
into the human realities of the experience of empire than just
about any other writer of his time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immediately outside of our own English life, is the dark and
crooked and fantastic, and wicked, and awe inspiring life of the
`native,''' Kipling, then a young journalist in India, wrote to a
friend, expressing at the same time a sense of superiority and a
frustrated desire to belong.
</P>
<P>
   One of the pleasures of reading Ricketts' book is its evocation
of the gingerly interaction between colonizer and colonized, with
its powerful sexual and social ambiguity, which Kipling's early
stories _ like ``In the House of Suddhoo'' or even ``The Man Who
Would Be King'' _ captured so well.
</P>
<P>
   Kipling was born in 1865 in Bombay, India, and at age 5 was
taken by his mother to England (``home,'' as it was called by the
Anglo-Indians) for schooling.
</P>
<P>
   Ricketts makes much of the fact that the young ``Rud'' spent
several unhappy years living with an elderly foster mother for whom
he developed an early and lasting antipathy. The theme of childhood
abandonment, of being cast out of the family, repeats itself,
Ricketts persuasively argues, in Kipling's stories. It is not a
coincidence, he contends, that Kipling's two most famous child
heroes, Kim and Mowgli of ``The Jungle Book,'' are orphans.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 17 Kipling returned to India to take a job as a
newspaper reporter in Lahore, and before he was 25 had achieved
considerable fame with what are still regarded as some of his best
short stories. Ricketts' accounts of those years reflect the
excitement but also the anxiety experienced by the young English
writer on the make in a land of intense exoticism.
</P>
<P>
   Kipling longed for female companionship and shied away from it
at the same time; he yearned to delve into India, and he was also
horrified by it in a way that prefigures the famous scene of Mrs.
Moore in E.M. Forster's ``Passage to India'' visiting the Malabar
caves.
</P>
<P>
   Kipling left India for good in 1889 and, in his years living in
the United States and England, he quickly became Kiplingesque, the
most visible exponent of muscular, nationalistic literary rhapsody,
tempered by a kind of patronizing large-mindedness: ``You're a
better man than I am Gunga Din.''
</P>
<P>
   But while that Kiplingesque tone seems grandly archaic now, in
Ricketts' view it makes Kipling much more of an outsider to
standard imperial pride than is often thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kim,'' perhaps Kipling's best novel, about an abandoned
English boy who lives as a native and is absorbed into the world of
spying and intrigue, is, as Ricketts calls it, ``a delighted
celebration of cultural and racial difference _ in the strongest
contrast to his White Man bluster.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately the bluster intensified as Kipling got older, and
he paid the terrible price of becoming a figure of satire and
parody. ``We are in a dreary plight when Mob-orator puts on the
Muse to move the country, and shows her as a slattern with a
furious jingle, to suit the country's taste,'' the novelist George
Meredith wrote to a friend at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Kipling never stopped enjoying ``an enviable popularity,'' as
Henry James ruefully called it, but he was more and more ``a
sitting target and a figure of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricketts gives us the private Kipling as well as the public one,
and contrasts the man who seemed to parody himself with the man
whose grief over the deaths of two of his children was boundless.
</P>
<P>
   Kipling's first child, a daughter born in the United States,
died early, and a son was killed in a German attack in World War I,
his body not found until long after Kipling's own death. The
personal tragedies, in Ricketts' view, made Kipling ``a sadder and
a harder man'' and are causes of the dark bluster that came in his
later years.
</P>
<P>
   On his last page Ricketts reminds us that when Kipling died in
1936, a ``national institution,'' The Times of London wrote, but no
longer a literary one, not a single writer served as a pallbearer.
That literary no-show represented an unfair judgment on Kipling as
a writer, which Ricketts' fine biography does much to set right.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `RUDYARD KIPLING'
</P>
<P>
   A Life
</P>
<P>
   By Harry Ricketts
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 434 pages. Carroll &AMP; Graf. $28.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-00 1913EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
