<HEADLINE>
A PLAN TO WIRE AN ENTIRE GEORGIA TOWN WITH THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By LAURIE J. FLYNN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leave it to La Grange. The small Georgia city 60 miles southwest
of Atlanta, already the regional home of several Fortune 500
corporations, now intends to become the largest entirely wired town
so far in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   According to a plan announced last week, every household,
school, government office and retail store in town will be
connected to one giant high-speed network. The system is being
created by combining the town's existing fiber-optic network with
coaxial cable from Charter Communications, the local cable
provider. The system, to be paid for by the municipal government,
is to be fully in place by fall.
</P>
<P>
   Households and businesses will receive free installation, which
includes a cable modem for Internet access. And for at least the
first year, Internet service is to be provided free to each user.
</P>
<P>
   Any home without a personal computer will receive an access
device and keyboard to attach to the television set, said the
mayor, Jeff Lukken. The city, which has a population of 27,000,
will provide Internet access through WorldGate Communications,
which specializes in interactive television.
</P>
<P>
   What prompted the project, called the La Grange Internet TV
Initiative?
</P>
<P>
   Lukken said one big motivation was La Grange's role as home to
the regional operations of Fortune 500 companies, including
Caterpillar, Kimberly-Clark and Georgia-Pacific. The network,
Lukken said, should help the town attract and keep big employers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to have a work force with the right skills, the
ones that meet the standards that information technology companies
command,'' Lukken said.
</P>
<P>
   The network will also let teachers communicate more easily with
parents, and enable more students to use the Internet at home, he
said. Retailers in town will be able to open online stores to help
them compete on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The network and equipment will cost the city roughly $300,000,
mostly to wire those households that do not already receive basic
cable television service _ about 2,200 of La Grange's 11,000 homes
_ and to supply the necessary set-top hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Besides providing set-top Internet-access devices for those
households without PCs, the city plans to send technicians into
homes to train people unfamiliar with the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``La Grange is a very progressive city,'' said Jerry Kent, chief
executive of Charter. ``But like all communities, they are afraid
of falling behind. This helps them attract businesses and people to
the town.''
</P>
</TEXT>
