<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-CONTROL-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVINING THE LOOK OF THE NEXT HOUSE IN A CLOSE CONTEST
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The contest for control of the House of
Representatives is as close as the margin in the House itself,
where the 11-vote Republican majority is the smallest in nearly
half a century.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, whose campaign committee reported $19 million cash on
hand compared with half as much for the Republicans at the end of
1999, seem poised to erase, or at least blur, the GOP's traditional
money advantage.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans, with control of the House, can set the late
summer-early fall agenda of roll call votes. If they think they
need to, they can give ground on some key measure the way they did
on health care and welfare in 1996. Then their incumbents could
boast of having delivered, for example, on prescription drugs for
the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have an advantage in that 23 Republicans, some of them
abiding by term-limits pledges they made in 1994, are retiring.
Party shifts occur most frequently in these open seats, and
Democrats have only seven retirees whose seats they must defend.
</P>
<P>
   But the numbers give mixed messages. With 222 Republicans and
one independent who votes with them to 211 Democrats and their one
independent, it would take a net loss of six Republican seats to
oust Dennis Hastert of Illinois from the speaker's chair and
replace him with Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the minority leader.
</P>
<P>
   Out of 435 House seats, a net shift of six amounts to a change
of only 1.4 percent, or less than the margin of error in any
election poll taken this year. But because incumbents win
re-election at rates that would have made the old Supreme Soviet
proud (98.3 percent won in 1998), and more than half of those open
seats are safe, the real battleground is much smaller. If there are
40 real races by fall, a net change of six amounts to a 15 percent
shift. If there are just 25, a six-seat shift equals 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
   National polls are not much help. The latest public polls really
show no more than the absence of any national trend. In 1994, when
they gained 52 seats, Republicans got 53.6 percent of the two-party
House vote and 52.9 percent of the seats (excluding the one
independent), or 230 in all. When they lost eight seats but held a
majority in 1996, they got 50.2 percent of the votes. Their vote
improved a bit in 1998, to 50.5 percent, but they lost five more
seats.
</P>
<P>
   Even a poll that showed a 53-47 edge for either party would
prove very little, considering the plus or minus three percentage
point margin of sampling error that is customary. But the public
polls show no such advantage anyhow. A CBS News poll of 909
registered voters conducted by telephone from March 19 through 21
found 40 percent of registered voters saying they would vote for a
Republican candidate for the House, and 40 percent saying they
would vote for a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   So anticipating House elections usually requires figuring them
out, seat by seat, a difficult task when races seem slow to take
shape and candidates are, in the words of Ed Goeas, a Republican
pollster, ``kind of plodding along and doing the things they need
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But in Washington this kind of seat-by-seat guesswork has become
a cottage industry, engaging not only the political parties but
highly specialized elements of the press. The best-known of these
is probably Charles Cook, who wrote in last week's National Journal
that ``an analysis of each of the 435 districts suggests that the
outcome in November will probably range between a Republican gain
of three seats to a Democratic gain of five, one seat short of a
majority.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook counts 16 seats as tossups that ``either party has a good
chance of winning.'' Five of them are now held by Democrats and 11
by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   He says 13 seats now held by Democrats lean Democratic, while
two lean Republican, and 17 Republican seats lean Republican. His
definition of lean is a competitive race with one side still the
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Cook's third tier consists of 26 Democratic seats he
thinks Democrats are ``likely'' to hold, and 20 Republican seats
the GOP is ``likely'' to retain. Such seats, he wrote ``are not
considered competitive at this point but have the potential to
become engaged.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Each party recognizes that the easy targets are gone. Vulnerable
Democrats either lost or quit in 1992 and 1994. The 1994 Republican
landslide, a truly national election, engineered by Newt Gingrich,
swept into office newcomers of all levels of merit. They included a
few Republicans whom Gingrich never expected to make it to
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   So 12 of the 1994 Republican freshmen were defeated in 1996 and
two more were beaten in 1998. A few others who would have been
beaten, like Enid Greene of Utah and Wes Cooley of Oregon, retired
when scandals caught up with them. By now no one left in the House
is as obviously vulnerable as Greene was after her husband played
fast and loose with campaign money or Cooley was after he was
caught lying about having served in Korea during the war.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   This year, in fact, there are just two members whose political
acts have invited defeat and they both come from that same
Republican class of 1994. But the first, Rep. Michael Forbes of New
York, is now a Democrat. Forbes switched in 1999, accusing
Republican leaders of being ``tone deaf'' to ordinary Americans'
concerns. His party is his problem, in a Suffolk County district he
carried with 64 percent of the vote as a Republican in 1998. Not
only are Republicans fighting to reclaim the seat, but some local
Democrats are unhappy with his conservative views on guns and
abortion. Forbes cannot expect the easy ride that several Southern
Democrats who switched to the GOP got when they ran as Republicans
in the 90s.
</P>
<P>
   The other is Rep. George Nethercutt of Washington, who kept his
Republican identity, but abandoned the term-limits pledge, to serve
no longer than six years, that got him elected. Nethercutt defeated
Tom Foley, the speaker of the House and an intense critic of term
limits, but now seems convinced that Foley was right about the
value of experience. The term-limits movement has lost strength
since 1994, but with all the fury it can still muster it will make
independent expenditures to join Democrats in trying to defeat
Nethercutt.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Aside from those cases, the 25 to 40 real contests for House
seats will hinge mainly on local personalities and local issues or
occasionally on national issues crafted in local terms. Democrats,
for example, have high hopes that gun control will help them in a
few tossup seats, especially in the suburbs. Alan Secrest, a
Democratic pollster who works House races, said: ``Everybody favors
trigger locks. Most people favor background checks.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither party is counting on the presidential campaign to win it
seats. Back before Gov. George W. Bush of Texas had a primary fight
on his hands, Republicans seemed to count on him to sweep to a
victory big enough to solidify their shaky House majority. They do
not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, they may have been dreaming. Presidential coattails
have not been a major factor in House elections since Ronald Reagan
won in 1980 and Republicans gained 33 seats.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the two parties should put the presidential election out
of their minds entirely. The last two presidents actually saw their
party lose House seats when they won the White House. Republicans
lost three when President Bush was elected in 1988. Democrats lost
11 with President Clinton in 1992.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
