<SLUG> BC-ECOMMERCE-COLUMN-(1300)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARITABLE GROUPS FIND REVENUE IN RETAILING GOODS ON THEIR WEB
SITES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BOB TEDESCHI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Companies involved in e-commerce have always seemed a lot like
not-for-profit operations _ constantly on the lookout for new
funding and constantly losing money, all the while stressing that
profits are not the immediate priority.
</P>
<P>
   The similarities are becoming greater still, as nonprofit groups
have begun to rely on e-commerce to generate revenues and
streamline their organizations. Nonprofits with disparate missions,
like the American Civil Liberties Union, the National Rifle
Association and Save the Children, now sell goods online, while
institutions like the Pew Charitable Trusts use the Internet to
skim inefficiency from the paper-intensive grant process.
</P>
<P>
   In so doing, these groups are not only finding new sources of
money, they are also making better use of the money they already
have.
</P>
<P>
   Save the Children, an international children's relief charity,
is a case in point. According to Aggie Stern, who runs the
charity's retail division, the organization cannot afford to mail
more than one catalog annually to its 100,000 patrons. Yet the
group suspected that there was year-round demand for the ties,
jewelry and other goods that it sells at its headquarters in
Westport, Conn., and in limited amounts through other retailers.
</P>
<P>
   So in mid-November it began selling the same goods on its Web
site (www.savethechildren.org), regularly updating the merchandise.
The results have been amazing, Stern said. The organization expects
to sell $300,000 of merchandise over the Web this year, she said,
while maintaining a similar level of sales in the store and catalog
operations combined.
</P>
<P>
   Such success stories are spreading quickly in the nonprofit
sector, said H. Robert Wientzen, chief executive of the Direct
Marketing Association, many of whose members are nonprofit
organizations. Wientzen said that a recent association report
showed that of the $102 billion that nonprofits raised from all
sources last year, $18 billion came from selling products mail
order and on the Internet _ $2 billion more than in 1998, and $5
billion more than in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The report did not break out mail order and Internet sales, but
Wientzen said e-commerce was responsible for a significant amount
of that growth. ``Nonprofits are finding that the Internet makes
niche marketing even more palatable and profitable than direct
mail,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he said, a nonprofit company that sells goods
through a catalog could sell the same amount of goods on the
Internet while spending 80 percent less, ``presuming you have a
site that's attracting people.''
</P>
<P>
   His caveat underscores a complicating factor for other
nonprofits looking to copy the success of Save the Children and
others. To begin with, as the for-profit e-commerce companies have
shown, building a site's traffic can be costly and arduous. But
even if organizations can somehow clear that hurdle _ by promoting
the Web site on every piece of fund-raising literature mailed, for
instance _ other sizable obstacles remain.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are finding staff with the time, expertise and
interest to maintain the Web site; convincing donors that a retail
operation will somehow advance a charity's mission; and, of course,
dealing with the customer service and fulfillment issues that have
brought even retail giants like Toys ``R'' Us to their knees in the
online realm.
</P>
<P>
   Stern, of Save the Children, said the organization's experience
with catalog marketing helped smooth the transition to Web sales
because the fulfillment and customer service systems had already
been established through the group's catalog. Even so, in the
middle of last year's holiday rush, the Web site generated so many
orders for Save the Children's goods that one company Stern hired
to help pack and ship items failed to keep up, forcing the
organization to take back those duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was madness,'' said Stern, who relies on part-time help to
handle the holiday rush. ``I can tell war stories from now until
tomorrow, but we're still very happy with the site.''
</P>
<P>
   The complexities of building a full-scale e-commerce operation
have been enough to prevent some other nonprofits from looking at
their Web stores as anything but marginal revenue builders. The
American Civil Liberties Union, for one, is taking a gradual
approach to building its Web store, which opened last year
(www.aclu.org).
</P>
<P>
   According to Loren Siegel, the organization's director of public
education, the ACLU devotes ``a tiny percentage'' of one staff
person's time to the Web store, which sells pamphlets, videos and
apparel, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the scant effort devoted to the Web store, Siegel said
it generated $50,000 in revenues last year, to go along with
$50,000 the organization raised through a one-page list of items it
included in newsletters. But that revenue has not yet been enough
to outpace the fulfillment, Web development and merchandising costs
associated with the store.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mission is not to make money,'' Siegel said. Instead, by
selling literature, the store helps disseminate information central
to the organization's programs, she said, while the apparel sales
build public awareness of the ACLU ``But we are still hopeful that
by using this medium for distribution, we will eventually make a
profit.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While e-commerce has provided a promising new tool for some
nonprofits, it has actually spawned other charities. Hugging Hands
International (www.hugginghands.org), a Web-based organization that
was founded last April to give money to children's charities,
``would not have been possible without the Net,'' said Jim Meyers,
a co-founder of Hugging Hands.
</P>
<P>
   The site features a gallery of children's artworks, but it does
not yet sell them. Instead, it uses the art to attract more than
100,000 monthly visitors to the site. Based on that traffic, the
organizers secure advertising sponsorships from corporate partners,
a portion of which goes to charities. Anderson Consulting is the
current sponsor, but Meyers said other ``million dollar''
sponsorships were pending.
</P>
<P>
   In the back offices of other nonprofit organizations, the
Internet is bringing changes that are less quantifiable, but no
less profound, said Ken Weber, director of nonprofit client
services for AppNet, an Internet consulting firm. ``More often than
not, the product that nonprofits deal with is information,'' Weber
said, ``and the Internet is helping them move that information much
more efficiently than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   One example of that is found at the Philadelphia-based Pew
Charitable Trusts, which gave nearly $250 million to nonprofit
groups last year. Because the trust, by definition, needs no annual
income from outside sources, the organization does not need to sell
goods on its Web site (www.pewtrusts.com). But according to David
Morse, a Pew spokesman, it has been able to cut ``substantial
costs'' from its operation simply by allowing prospective grant
recipients to submit some parts of their grant applications online.
</P>
<P>
   Morse said the organization might also build an extranet, or
password-protected Web site, so its grant recipients can
communicate more effectively with each other and with the Pew
trusts. A reason not to do so, however, may be that Pew's
beneficiaries do not always have the time or technical expertise to
make effective use of such a system.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we're hopeful about all of this, we also have to bear in
mind that we're trying to make our grantees more effective _ not
foist the latest tool or gadget on them just because we find it
interesting,'' he said. ``We want it to be a case where if we build
it, they will come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
