<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TICKETS-USAIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US AIRWAYS STRIKE THREAT SHOWS DRAWBACKS OF E-TICKETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOE SHARKEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Greenwald couldn't resist a little gloating as he and other
travel agents prepared to deal over the weekend with the
possibility of a shutdown of US Airways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a travel agent, you're on your own,'' he said. ``It's
a minefield out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenwald, a co-owner of Personalized Travel, a small travel
agency in Washington, was referring to a fault line in the current
air-travel landscape that was exposed as US Airways customers
worried about finding alternative flights last week. Increasingly,
whether purchased over the phone, at a travel agency, or online,
the standard air ticket is now a paperless electronic ticket, or
e-ticket, that exists only on an airline's computers.
</P>
<P>
   But until US Airways and its flight attendants reached a
tentative accord early Saturday morning, passengers holding
e-tickets for US Airways flights faced a real dilemma. While other
airlines and even Amtrak said they would try to accommodate US
Airways passengers with paper tickets, travelers with e-tickets
could not expect such service. Computers at different airlines do
not yet communicate well enough to share information on tickets
that have been issued electronically.
</P>
<P>
   Travel agents said they were ready to issue paper tickets to
customers who had booked e-tickets through them, but noted that
they could not help travelers who had bypassed travel agents to buy
tickets online from an Internet travel site or by telephone.
``There's nothing a travel agent can do for them in this kind of
situation because we're not involved in the transaction,''
Greenwald said.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic tickets represent 61 percent of the $75 billion in
tickets booked annually on the Sabre Holdings Corp., the company
that operates the main computer reservations system used by travel
agencies and others, according to Nancy Raynor, Sabre's senior vice
president for emerging businesses.
</P>
<P>
   As the strike deadline neared, US Airways said holders of
e-tickets could make arrangements at a US Airways ticket counter to
get paper tickets. But staffing at those counters could have been
affected by a strike.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwald's agency, however, offered to print out US Airways
tickets for its customers with e-tickets and deliver them by
messenger last week. ``That way, you have a document in your hand,
an actual US Airways ticket that is a negotiable instrument,'' he
said. The service, which would not be necessary under normal
circumstances, is included in the $20 fee the agency charges to
write an air ticket, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbluth Interactive, the online subsidiary of a major
world-wide travel agency, Rosenbluth International, mailed paper
tickets to hundreds of customers with e-tickets on US Airways
flights, said Neal Bibeau, the president of Rosenbluth Interactive.
</P>
<P>
   The US Airways strike threat ``was the first event of this
magnitude to create this kind of focus on e-tickets,'' said Bibeau,
who added that his company's online booking site, Biztravel.com,
sent out the paper duplicates over a week ago when it became clear
that the strike threat was real.
</P>
<P>
   Under normal circumstances, Bibeau said, customers like
e-tickets, which can not be misplaced or lost like paper tickets.
Ninety percent of the airline tickets booked on Biztravel.com are
electronic. ``People have the option to request paper tickets, but
we don't see it often,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the strike loomed, though, we thought it would be
appropriate for our travelers to notify them proactively that there
would be a benefit in this specific situation to have a paper
ticket,'' he added. ``In a situation like that, you're just better
off having a paper ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for traditional travel agents, who have suffered
in recent years as airlines have cut commissions, their competitive
edge in this kind of service may not last much longer. Sabre last
month announced that it had joined an alliance with EncrypTix Inc.,
a new company formed by Stamps.com, which offers technology
allowing businesses and home-computer users to print out postal
stamps.
</P>
<P>
   Sabre intends to help develop this technology to allow customers
on its various Internet sites to book and print out paper tickets
for sports and entertainment events. Later this year, Raynor said,
Sabre also expects to be able to offer e-tickets that can be
printed out, with a special bar code that will make them as readily
acceptable as traditional paper tickets. Airline ticket counters
will be equipped with new scanners to read the tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The next phase of electronic ticket technology, however, will be
a link between all of the airlines computer systems, ``so that if
you have an electronic ticket on one airline, the other airlines
would be able find that information and honor the ticket,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even that will not mean the end of paper tickets. ``The
reality is, if you look at travelers, starting with the experienced
road warrior and going to the mom and dad and kids who take a
vacation once every couple of years, there will always be people
who require or prefer to have a piece of paper,'' she said. ``They
want that document.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
