<HEADER>
A8502 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      03-26 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIBERTY MEDIA PLANS TO TAKE $130 MILLION STAKE IN IDT
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining its drive into the telecommunications industry, John
C. Malone's Liberty Media Group has agreed to invest $130 million
for a stake of almost 10 percent in IDT, the communications carrier
based in Hackensack, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Until AT&AMP;T's acquisition of Tele-Communications last year,
Liberty was TCI's television programming unit. But over the last
year, the company has shown interest in telecommunications. IDT
regularly takes a leading role in creating communications niches.
</P>
<P>
   OPENTV PLANS TO BUY SPYGLASS
</P>
<P>
   OpenTV, which provides software that enables television viewers
to go directly from TV shows to related Web sites, said that it
would buy Spyglass, a pioneer in Internet browser software, in a
$2.5 billion stock deal.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE SYSTEMS FOR DEAF AND BLIND
</P>
<P>
   Translucent screens that can carry text and images, but can also
be seen through, are being introduced as a way to let deaf
filmgoers view subtitles that are not visible to other patrons. The
technology, along with a separate system that lets blind people use
headphones to hear a description of the on-screen action, has been
developed by the National Center for Accessible Media, which is
trying to adapt existing systems to enable the deaf and the blind
to go to conventional theaters.
</P>
<P>
   CISCO TO INTRODUCE INTERNET PHONES
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems intends Monday to announce an office telephone
system based on Internet technology. The system could push the
company to the top of the budding Internet-telephone market.
Proponents say such systems bring new convenience, efficiency and
cost savings to corporate communications.
</P>
<P>
   IBM-QWEST DEAL ON DATA CENTERS
</P>
<P>
   In a move to expand its ability to manage Web sites and software
applications for corporate customers, IBM intends to announce
Monday that it has struck a multibillion-dollar deal with Qwest
Communications International. The deal calls for IBM to build and
help operate Internet data centers for Qwest across North America,
executives said.
</P>
<P>
   A DRAWBACK TO AIRLINE E-TICKETS
</P>
<P>
   The potential strike by flight attendants at US Airways, which
was averted over the weekend, exposed one drawback of the
electronic ticket not bought through a travel agent. While other
airlines and even Amtrak said they would try to accommodate
passengers with paper tickets, travelers with e-tickets could not
expect such service. Computers at different airlines do not yet
communicate well enough to share information on e-tickets.
</P>
<P>
   A SHIFT, PERHAPS, IN ONLINE VISION
</P>
<P>
   The only vision required to make zillions of dollars in the
Internet economy is nearsightedness. The stock market remains so
irrationally exuberant that almost every dot-com company can pick
up $10 million or so in venture capital and make a bundle either on
a quick initial public offering or acquisition, with nary a glance
toward long-term viability _ or long-term investors. But the view
may be shifting, with more emphasis placed on the creation of
substantial businesses, common sense and ethics.
</P>
<P>
   NONPROFITS RELY ON E-COMMERCE
</P>
<P>
   Nonprofit groups have begun to rely on electronic commerce to
generate revenue and streamline their organizations. In so doing,
these groups are not only finding new sources of money, they are
also making better use of the money they already have.
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD JOINS DOT-COM FESTIVAL
</P>
<P>
   The Yahoo Internet Life Online Film Festival, dedicated to the
making and distribution of digital movies on the Internet, was a
kind of coming out party, a faltering first date, for the worlds of
mainstream Hollywood and online entrepreneurship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
