<DOCNO> NYT20000326.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8510 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-ALAMIN-CONFLICT0327-C     03-26 1489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALAMIN-CONFLICT0327-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    System's color doesn't erase suspicions of some blacks
 &HT;    By John Head
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin claims he's living the
nightmare portrait he painted with fiery words so many times when
he was the radical known as H. Rap Brown. He says he is a black man
in the clutches of a racist system that is out to destroy him.
</P>
<P>
   But there's something wrong with this picture. The predominant
colors are not the stark blacks and whites of H. Rap Brown's 1960s
tableau, with black for the innocent victims and white for the
oppressors. The case against Al-Amin is a legal landscape drawn
mostly in black.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the accused, Al-Amin is black. But so are his alleged
victims _ Fulton County sheriff's deputies Ricky Kinchen, who was
shot to death, and Aldranon English, who was wounded, allegedly as
they attempted to arrest Al-Amin on a Cobb County warrant accusing
him of receiving stolen property and impersonating a police
officer.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff's department is headed by a black woman. So is the
Atlanta police department that searched for Al-Amin after the
shooting. The prosecutor who will decide whether to seek the death
penalty against Al-Amin is black. If the case goes to trial in
Fulton County, odds are that a majority black jury will decide his
guilt or innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin's apparent defense _ uttered to a reporter _ is that the
case against him is ``a government conspiracy.'' J.L. Chestnut, the
attorney who is fighting Al-Amin's extradition from Alabama where
he was captured Monday night, expanded on that theme when he said
his client ``will not be the first or the last black man framed by
the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Having blacks in all those key roles in the legal system argues
against a racially motivated conspiracy. Yet the claim resonates
with some in the African-American community, a community where
those who worked for black political empowerment _ as H. Rap Brown
did with the Student Non-Violent Coordinating Committee in the
early 1960s _ believed they were creating an antidote to the
system's racism.
</P>
<P>
   In the days following the shootings, reporters found reactions
ranging from refusals to say anything against Al-Amin to strong
statements of support for him in Atlanta's West End neighborhood.
Al-Amin moved there in the 1970s following his release from an
armed robbery sentence in a New York prison, where he converted to
Islam and changed his name. He became the imam, or leader, of the
neighborhood mosque and was credited by some residents with ridding
the area of drug dealers and prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a midday crowd at the West End Barber Shop was asked
what was being said there about the shooting. The barbers were
young men in their 20s; so was their clientele _ some of them, no
doubt, students from the nearby Atlanta University Center campuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people thinks it's a setup,'' said one barber, who
refused to give his name.
</P>
<P>
   Others chimed in in agreement, but declined to be quoted. Then a
customer waiting his turn in the chair spoke up. ``I think it's
unfortunate,'' he said. ``A lot of it is not making sense, as far
as the charges against him.''
</P>
<P>
   He was asked his name. ``Serge,'' he said. And last name? ``I'll
refrain from giving that,'' he said, ``because (the police) might
stop me one day and want to get back at me.''
</P>
<P>
   Serge said he finds it hard to believe the deputies did nothing
to provoke the shooting, that they were simply the victims of an
``ambush'' as described by Sheriff Jackie Barrett. ``The level of
disrespect the cops show to the black community is appalling,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   What about the fact that the two officers themselves were black?
</P>
<P>
   ``I really am sorry for the family that has lost their loved
one,'' Serge said. ``But a part of me really is not mad at
(Al-Amin) because of the way the cops are, the way they act. I
don't mean to glorify a cop killer, or anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The police are simply out of control, Serge argued. He mentioned
the Diallo case, in which four New York police officers fired 41
shots at an unarmed man, killing him. And in West End, he claimed,
police recently mistakenly kicked in the door of a 90-year-old man
and didn't even offer an apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, as a black man,'' Serge concluded, ``I'm nervous
myself. The cops could stop me for no reason. When it's a black
person involved, we're guilty until proven innocent.''
</P>
<P>
   GAINS HAVEN'T CHANGED ATTITUDES
</P>
<P>
   Such attitudes have not been eliminated by civil rights advances
that put more African-Americans in positions of power, according to
Charles E. Jones, chairman of the Department of African-American
Studies at Georgia State University. ``One problem is that people
thought that just because you put black people in office you will
have have a more responsive system,'' he said. ``Clearly that has
not always been the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said there is sympathy in the black community for the
slain and wounded deputies. He noted that local black leaders in
the Muslim community offered public condolences to the officers'
families and that trust funds have been set up to help the
families. But the color of the officers' skin does not allay black
suspicion of the police, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   He emphasized that he has no knowledge of or opinion on the
validity of the allegation that Al-Amin is the victim of a
government conspiracy. But he understands why that claim might play
well in the black community. ``There is still a distrust of the
criminal justice system emanating from the black community,'' Jones
said.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, political advances have allowed
African-Americans to overcome a lot, but not all of their
deep-seated suspicions and once-well-founded fears of government
power.
</P>
<P>
   Jones also blames the media for creating doubt about the case
against Al-Amin. He accuses the press of ``sensationalizing'' the
story by harping on Al-Amin's connection to the Black Panther
Party. Jones, who has made the Black Panthers his academic
specialty and who edited the book ``The Black Panther Party
Reconsidered,'' says the former H. Rap Brown's connection to the
Panthers was tenuous at best, with only five months of membership.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen the media repeatedly attempt to tie him to the
party, while we have not seen an exploration of why this incident
might have happened,'' Jones said. ``And we have not heard much at
all about the discrepancies in the case, such as that there was a
trail of blood away from the scene but (Al-Amin) had no wound when
he was arrested, or why he would just start shooting when the
arrest warrant was for minor charges.''
</P>
<P>
   BOLSTERING COMMUNITY SUPPORT
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Jones argues, the portrayal of Al-Amin as a former
black radical is more likely to bolster his support in the black
community than to lessen it. ``Some former members of the Black
Panther Party are held in high regard,'' he said. ``They've been
elected to public office. They're still respected. Part of the
support for Al-Amin is the result of the credibility he accumulated
during the 1960s.'' For example, former Panther Bobby Rush is
seeking his fifth term in Congress from Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Attorney General Thurbert Baker knows what it's like to
be a black official prosecuting a criminal case weighted with the
history of a black icon. Last year, he brought fraud charges
against Ralph David Abernathy III, a former state senator and the
son of the late Rev. Ralph David Abernathy, the Rev. Martin Luther
King Jr.'s closest aide and his successor as head of the Southern
Christian Leadership Conference. Supporters of Abernathy accused
Baker of being part of a racist plot to get him. Baker was asked
this week if, as a black elected official, he was bothered by such
a charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, `` he said, ``because I know it isn't true. I don't think
we can allow ourselves to be distracted from carrying out our duty
under the law ... The cardinal rule is that in every case, whether
it's a high-profile case or it's somebody no one has ever heard of,
you have to treat it like every other case. I believe the vast
majority of people, including in the African-American community,
understand and support that.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite strong evidence that included tape recordings of
the defendant virtually admitting to the crimes, it took Baker two
trials to convict Abernathy.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Fulton County District Attorney Paul Howard, who is
black, will have a similarly tough time trying Al-Amin is yet to be
seen. But, if GSU's Jones and others are right, having a case
involving black victims, investigated by black police officers,
prosecuted by black DAs, presided over by a black judge and decided
by a majority black jury won't be enough to convince some
African-Americans that a black defendant won't be railroaded.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
