<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8517 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ALAMIN-PERSONAL-WOES0     03-26 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALAMIN-PERSONAL-WOES0327-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    2 wives, money woes for Al-Amin
 &HT;    By Dan Chapman and Andrea Jones
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The ramshackle house where Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin's
wife lives is within a stone's throw of the grocery store and coin
laundry he used to own in Atlanta's historic West End.
</P>
<P>
   It's a neighborhood quite different from the upscale,
suburbanlike Flamingo Drive, three miles to the west, where Al-Amin
also owns a home _ a 5,100-square-foot beauty on 3-plus acres.
</P>
<P>
   That's where his other wife lives, according to Milton D. Jones,
an attorney who represented Al-Amin in bankruptcy proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The multiple marriages are additional pieces in the mysterious
puzzle that is Al-Amin, who was arrested last week in the slaying
of a Fulton County sheriff's deputy and the wounding of another.
</P>
<P>
   Three times since 1998, Al-Amin has filed for protection from
creditors who are demanding tens of thousands of dollars from him.
</P>
<P>
   A Fulton County judge labeled Al-Amin's latest petition ``an
abusive filing'' not undertaken in ``good faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the financial and criminal troubles, the 56-year-old
Al-Amin still commands respect among his Muslim brethren.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wish to remind everyone of Imam Jamil Al-Amin's
longstanding role as a community leader who had a positive impact
on the lives of so many people,'' the Council on American-Islamic
Relations said in a statement issued last week. ``The charges
against Imam Jamil are especially troubling because they are
inconsistent with what is known of his moral character and past
behavior as a Muslim.''
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin, formerly known as H. Rap Brown, once advocated violence
as the means necessary for African-Americans to get their due in
American society. He moved to Atlanta in 1976 after serving time in
a New York state prison for a robbery and shootout with police.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin embraced Islam while in prison, and afterwards his
lifestyle mellowed in Atlanta. He become an imam, or spiritual
leader. He founded a mosque near Atlanta University Center and
helped clean up the crime-plagued neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, he bought a brick building in the West End and opened a
grocery store and laundromat. (The building changed hands in
October 1999 and is no longer owned by Al-Amin.)
</P>
<P>
   Also in 1985, he bought a clapboard house, a block from the
store. Ten years later, he bought the brick house on Flamingo
Drive, with its green-and-white trim and large magnolia in the
front yard.
</P>
<P>
   The doors were closed and the windows barred Saturday morning at
the laundromat and grocery store. Three children in Muslim garb
strolled past. A man sat on the picnic table across the street,
where Al-Amin would frequently hold court.
</P>
<P>
   The cream-colored house also was silent, its window blinds
pulled tight and piles of leaves in the front yard awaiting pickup.
Weeds and trash filled the vacant lot across the street. This
house, lawyer Jones said, is where one of Al-Amin's wives lives.
</P>
<P>
   The azaleas bloomed pink and white on Flamingo Drive, where
another wife lives, according to Jones. The blinds were pulled
there, too.
</P>
<P>
   Neither wife could be reached for comment. One of them, Karima,
visited Al-Amin in jail Friday in Alabama, where he is being held
pending extradition to Georgia. The other wife's name could not be
learned.
</P>
<P>
   The Koran, Islam's holy book, permits a man to marry up to four
wives, and teaches that a husband must treat all wives fairly and
equally.
</P>
<P>
   Polygamy was approved during the seventh century, when Islam's
prophet Mohammed and his followers endured religious wars that
killed many men, leaving women without husbands.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Muslim Almanac, however, ``polygamy always has
been relatively rare (less than 5 percent).'' It is even rarer in
the United States, where it is illegal.
</P>
<P>
   There are no marriage records on file for Al-Amin in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The nicer of his two homes _ the one on Flamingo Drive _ is at
the root of Al-Amin's financial troubles. Unable to pay the
mortgage on that home, valued at $250,000 _ or on the other
properties, valued at another $160,000 _ Al-Amin filed for
bankruptcy in January 1998. At the time, he was almost $10,000 in
arrears.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern, repeated three times so far, was set: Attorneys
start foreclosure proceedings against Al-Amin only to see him file
for bankruptcy protection, effectively stalling foreclosure.
</P>
<P>
   Court records show he also owed more than $4,200 in property
taxes. Credit card companies and others demanded $24,542.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin listed monthly income of $7,250. He owned no checking or
savings account, stocks, jewelry, antiques, art objects or
computers, according to the bankruptcy petition, although he
claimed a 1987 Toyota 4Runner, valued at $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   The petition was thrown out after the judge agreed with the
bankruptcy trustee that Al-Amin had failed to list the assets in
the grocery store and laundromat.
</P>
<P>
   ``All household income and expenses must be disclosed,'' wrote
trustee James H. Bone. ``This includes debtor and his two (2)
wives.''
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin refiled for bankruptcy in May 1998. This time, he pegged
the value of the laundromat's washers and dryers at $5,000. Jones
said it was his oversight that the machines _ and Al-Amin's wives _
were left out of the first petition.
</P>
<P>
   While much of the petition repeated earlier financial
disclosures, Al-Amin's monthly earnings had risen to $9,000. He
added $1,750 for money made from lectures.
</P>
<P>
   Creditors and Bone, the trustee, again objected to any deal, and
attorneys again began foreclosure proceedings against the Flamingo
Drive home. Al-Amin was $8,041 in arrears.
</P>
<P>
   ``The present case is another repetitive, bad faith filing,''
the attorneys wrote in seeking dismissal of the protection plan.
</P>
<P>
   The judge dismissed the case when Al-Amin came up with a plan to
pay $46,953.
</P>
<P>
   One of the largest creditors was paid $5,727, but then the
monthly payments stopped. The firm again tried to foreclose.
Al-Amin again filed for bankruptcy protection.
</P>
<P>
   Gady Zeewy, who represented the creditor, said Saturday that
Al-Amin would file for bankruptcy as ``a stall tactic'' and that
creditors were being ``strung along as long as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The third and, so far, final round of bankruptcy protection was
dismissed last March. The judge ruled that Al-Amin failed to file
necessary documents and skipped bankruptcy workout meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court concludes that this case was not filed in good
faith,'' the judge wrote, adding that it was an ``abusive filing.''
The judge dismissed the case with prejudice, an extreme measure
that prohibited Al-Amin from refiling for 180 days.
</P>
<P>
   Again, though, Al-Amin came up with money to pay off some debts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came up with a lot of money in a relatively short amount of
time,'' Zeewy said, adding that ``he worked the system for several
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
