<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READY-TO-WEAR ACCESS TO THE WEB; INTERNET STRATEGIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, the MIT Media Lab has experimented with various types
of wearable computing devices.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Charmed Technology, which licenses Media Lab technology,
has been demonstrating wireless Web-access computers that might be
inexpensive enough to be given away, with users paying a service
fee. ``We've been working on this 10 years, and I want to see it
happen,'' said Alex Pentland, head of the lab's academic program
and a technology adviser to the company.
</P>
<P>
   Katrina Barillova, left, a co-founder of Charmed Technology,
wears a mock-up of a Web-access device whose screen is a
translucent eyepiece.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tim Race
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET STRATEGIES
</P>
<P>
   Given all the e-talk the last two years, one might think big
businesses that have not yet fully implemented an Internet strategy
are at least on their way. A recent survey of 78 big companies
indicates otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   According to the survey by PricewaterhouseCoopers and the
Conference Board, a business-financed research group, nearly 80
percent of the companies said that Internet business accounted for
less than 5 percent of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Only about a quarter of the companies were able to process
transactions online, and fewer than half had methods in place to
assess e-commerce performance. Just 17 percent rated themselves as
e-commerce innovators.
</P>
<P>
   In the view of Ed Berryman, e-business director for
PricewaterhouseCoopers, the results ``were not entirely
surprising.'' Nearly all of the companies have annual revenue of
over $1 billion, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turning the corner, especially for such large firms, is easier
said than done,'' Berryman added.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the survey indicated that at least some change was under
way. Two-thirds of the companies reported that senior executives
were involved with e-commerce planning and nearly half had
full-time business units devoted to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, e-commerce is a state of mind. ``The strategic
process can't be the traditional annual affair,'' Berryman said.
``They need to have a much more flexible, quickly reactive way of
managing ideas and opportunities. So instead of thinking of
themselves as a battleship that needs to be turned, they may need
to change the shape of the organization into a fleet of cruisers.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies may also need to be willing to spend some money. Even
though most of the companies surveyed indicated that online
procurement was a top priority, only 25 percent said they planned
to invest in it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bob Tedeschi
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
