<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATENTS: AN ONLINE CLASSROOM THAT KEEPS STUDENTS AWAKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TERESA RIORDAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The idea of online learning got a lot of attention recently when
Michael J. Saylor, the head of MicroStrategy Inc., announced that
he was putting $100 million toward creating a free, online
university. Even so, much online learning thus far consists of
regular lecture-hall fare repackaged for the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But what if an online classroom could feature a computerized
professor who teaches by Socratic method, administers pop quizzes,
sounds an alarm when inattentive scholars snooze during lectures,
and kicks students out of the discussion when they start asking
stupid questions?
</P>
<P>
   Peter Tong and Chi Fai Ho say that they have invented such an
educational system, and that they are acquiring a patent portfolio
that broadly covers their approach to online learning. Last month
they received their 10th such patent, for a system that monitors
and responds to the learning of students in a virtual classroom,
both individually and as a group.
</P>
<P>
   Their learning system is powered in part by an automated
natural-language search engine created by Tong and Ho. They say
their search engine, which is the basis for their company,
ProfessorQ, bears some resemblance to the one powering the popular
AskJeeves reference site.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, two professors from the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology received a lot of press recently for suing AskJeeves
over a patent. But they are not the only ones. Tong and Ho last
summer filed a lawsuit in the Northern District of California
against AskJeeves, saying that the company infringed on three of
their search-engine patents.
</P>
<P>
   Tong and Ho contend that their patents cover the Socratic method
_ as long as it is a computer that is asking the questions. This
computer ``allows you to learn through questioning,'' Tong said.
``Based on your answers, the computer knows your level of
understanding _ whether you need to review material or move on.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of an online classroom, Tong said, the computerized
professor also learns from and responds to group dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, if someone is constantly asking irrelevant
questions and disrupting the discussion,'' Tong said, ``the
computer can send a message saying, `Wouldn't it be better if you
were more focused in the subject area?''' And if the irritating
student persists with the nongermane questions? ``The computer can
shut down his communications link,'' Tong said.
</P>
<P>
   Another of the Tong-Ho patents covers software that prevents
students from doing things for fun _ like playing music or games _
on their computers until they have finished a prescribed amount of
homework.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another patent covers the technology that monitors a
student's attentiveness with a video camera, which, while perched
on a computer, is constantly patrolling for drooping eyes and
nodding heads.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, however, Tong said, the computer observes passively _
by noting whether the student's response time to questions is
slower than usual, for example. ``The monitoring part is not
intrusive,'' he said. ``It's not like some systems that monitor
your brain waves, where you have to put gear on your head.''
</P>
<P>
   So what will the computerized professor do if it catches you
slacking?
</P>
<P>
   ``It can yell at you and say, `Wake up!''' Tong said. ``Or it
can suddenly play a piece of music or change the screen display.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Tong knows a thing or two about old-fashioned academia. Like Ho,
he has a Ph.D. in computer science from the California Institute of
Technology; he also has a law degree and an MBA. This month the
former product manager at Hewlett-Packard quit his day job as a
patent lawyer so he could devote his full attention to ProfessorQ.
</P>
<P>
   The Tong-Ho prototype of the digital professor is rather
primitive, Tong said, because thus far the two inventors have been
unable to attract much investment capital for the project. In part,
Tong says, this is because he and Ho are ``a couple of
technologists who don't know anything about marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, it's an idea ahead of its time, Tong said. ``One can
have great technology, but when one is ahead of the game, people
won't be buying it. We're waiting for the industry to be ready, and
then we'll develop it.'' In the meantime, Tong said, the two are
concentrating their efforts on their search engine.
</P>
<P>
   Tong and Ho were most recently awarded patent 6,029,043.
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov. They may be
ordered through the Web site or through the mail, by patent number,
for $3 from the Patent and Trademark Office, Washington, DC 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
