<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: IN BASEBALL, RICH ALWAYS GET RICHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKOROZOWA, Japan _ Halfway around the world, baseball looks
very much the same. The dude who whips his BMW into a narrow
parking space at the players' lot knows he is young and cool and
rich.
</P>
<P>
   Also, just as in North America, people worry about the growing
gap between the rich teams and the poor teams. Before the Mets and
Cubs meet Wednesday and Thursday in the official National League
opening series, they will play two Japanese teams with the deepest
corporate pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday the Mets will play the traditional champion with a
classic uniform and a historic reputation for getting the close
call. We are not talking here about the Yankees but rather the
Yomiuri Giants from Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get the benefit of the doubt against them,''
recalled Leon Lee, now the Cubs' Pacific Rim scout, who had a long
and honorable career in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' opponent Monday afternoon used to be a joke but is now
respected and maybe even resented a bit for the way it keeps buying
new talent. We are not talking here about the contemporary Atlanta
Braves but rather the Seibu Lions who are 25 miles _ that is to
say, nearly two hours _ from downtown Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are competitive, young and flashy,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   By some strange stroke, neither Yomiuri nor Seibu won the
pennant in their respective leagues last year, but they raise the
stakes for the other 10 teams. In this shrinking world of global
networks and fast jets, there is a danger in the emergence of
superteams. In European soccer, the best teams play in a midweek
Champions League that only diminishes the national leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is not there yet, what with the huge barrier of the
Pacific Ocean, but American baseball has come up with interleague
play, with the Yanks getting the Mets and Braves every summer, and
lesser teams are stuck with dog teams.
</P>
<P>
   Some people in Japan fear that Yomiuri and Seibu, by commanding
a top price of $200 a ticket for these exhibitions, are taking away
from the start of the regular season this weekend. Other teams are
ignoring this hoopla.
</P>
<P>
   Sadaharu Oh, who merely hit 868 home runs, more than Henry
Aaron, managed the Fukuoka Daiei Hawks to the Japan Series
championship last fall, but he will not be greeting Sammy Sosa this
week. He is said to be too busy making his charges field grounders
to attend the hoopla.
</P>
<P>
   With and without Oh, the Giants have won 28 pennants in the past
50 years. They are owned by the huge and respected Yomiuri Shimbun
newspaper chain, with its 10.2 million circulation, the largest in
the world, and the only newspaper in the world to sponsor its own
orchestra, the Yomiuri Nippon Symphony Orchestra. Monday's
opponents, the Cubs, are also owned by a newspaper firm, Tribune
Co., which has not helped the Cubs break their gloomy hex.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants are clearly the most popular team in Japan.
Sometimes, it used to seem, even with the umpires.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I didn't like was that the umpires seemed to want to
balance everything out,'' said Lee, who batted .308 in 10
fulfilling seasons here. ``I'd see the Giants celebrating, and I'd
think, `Why are they celebrating?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more parity now,'' added Lee, who is everybody's best
friend on this trip because of his familiarity with the language
and the electronics stores.
</P>
<P>
   Parity or not, the Giants have their dome near downtown Tokyo,
with an amusement park and restaurants all around it. Seibu
recently put a dome right over a relatively new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions have come a long way _ from Fukuoka, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were named the Crown Lighter Lions,'' Lee said.
``Everybody who hit a home run would get a free lighter, whether
you smoked or not.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lighters were extinguished when they were purchased by
Yoshiaki Tsutsumi, one of four brothers who run the far-flung Seibu
dynasty. Tsutsumi relocated the franchise to this distant suburb,
reachable mainly by Seibu Railways from the basement of _ oh, but
you guessed it _ the Seibu department store on the north side of
the city.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions led the Pacific League in attendance for nine straight
years, and have won 13 pennants in 13 years. Tsutsumi is distant
and discreet, but also a hard-driving owner who could match George
M. Steinbrenner III, for stark childhood lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father used to punch me a lot, whenever I did something he
didn't like,'' he once said. ``And I could let him do it. Even in
school when I was young. He used to hit me even after I got out of
college, the last time was when I was 27. I think that was a
valuable thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In his spare time, Tsutsumi ponied up the money that brought the
1998 Winter Olympics to Nagano. Monday, instead of bringing
snowboarders to Nagano, Tsutsumi brought the New York Mets to the
suburbs. The rich do like to hobnob with each other. Can a
Champions League be far behind? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-00 2021EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
