<SLUG> BC-FOOD-COLUMN-OWEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIBS, HAWAIIAN-STYLE, BUT WITHOUT THE SPAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Signs posted prominently at a beach entrance on Maui's southwest
coast list the dangers involved in swimming, snorkeling, surfing or
splashing in the Pacific. In large letters, the signs warn: ``Never
turn your back on the ocean!''
</P>
<P>
   Tourists who heed those instructions literally will either set a
record for endurance swimming when they step ashore in Japan. Or
else they won't.
</P>
<P>
   Either possibility would probably be acceptable to Maui's native
Hawaiians. One-way swims away from the island should eventually
clear the roads of rental cars and sweep the streets clean of
malahini.
</P>
<P>
   Pronounced Mah-le-HEE-nee, the word is Hawaiian for tourist or
newcomer. If the malahini is wearing a hula-girl T-shirt, the
accent is on the ``HEE.''
</P>
<P>
   Yr. Obdt. Correspondent has been learning the language so that I
won't holler for a cop (uwalo) when I'm actually trying to order
sweet potatoes (uwala) at Mama's Fish House in Paia.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all restaurants also carry English names on the menu.
But unless you learn that the cute little fish you had your eye on
is spelled humuhumunokunkuapua'a, you're not playing the game. And
don't overlook the apostrophe before the final ``a.'' It signifies
a glottal stop _ or a total break in sound.
</P>
<P>
   I thought I had a grasp on the glottal stop until I learned some
of them occur at the start of the word.
</P>
<P>
   It seems to me the Hawaiians have developed some off-putting
words. According to my pronunciation guide, an appetizer is
pronounced ``poopoo.'' Beer is pronounced ``pee-or'' and if you
want a cut of beef steak, you ask for ``pee pee.'' If your tongue
slips and you ask for poo-hee, what you get is octopus.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, octopus in wine sauce makes a terrific entree if you
cook it according to instructions in the 50th anniversary cookbook
published by the Maui Association for Family and Community
Education.
</P>
<P>
   ``To clean octopus, turn body inside out,'' the recipe begins.
The author might also have added, ``before the octopus turns you
inside out.''
</P>
<P>
   Other popular seafood selections include ahi (tuna), ono,
opakapaka (pink snapper), shutome (swordfish) and mahimahi
(dolphin.) But it seems the favorite fish in Hawaii kitchens is an
exotic creature known as a ``Spam.''
</P>
<P>
   The Maui cookbook contains recipes for Spam sushi, Spam won ton,
Spam salads, Spam and pineapple, Spam stir-fry, Spam tempura and
Spam deep-fried with eggplant, green tomato and Velveeta.
</P>
<P>
   I believe Velveeta was the polynesian god of edible lava.
</P>
<P>
   If you are unable to hook any Spam on your next fishing trip,
the Maui cookbook also has lots of terrific recipes for another
island favorite, kalbi ribs. Included is this one, which can be
prepared with either Maui or Walla Walla onions.
</P>
<P>
   Walla-Maui Ribs
</P>
<P>
   5 pounds short ribs
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters cup catsup
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters cup water
</P>
<P>
   2 large onions, sliced
</P>
<P>
   Cut the short ribs into serving pieces. Mix together all the
other ingredients except the onions, and pour over the ribs.
Refrigerate at least an hour, mooshing the ribs with the sauce once
or twice.
</P>
<P>
   Plunk everything into a large casserole and top with the onion
slices. Cover and bake in a 350-degree oven for 2 hours, checking
once or twice to ensure that the sauce isn't cooking away.
</P>
<P>
   When the meat is tender, serve the ribs with cooked rice or egg
noodles. This should be enough ribs for six or more guests.
</P>
<P>
   South Sea Squash
</P>
<P>
   2 acorn squash
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-third cups frozen peas, cooked
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons sour cream
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons dill weed
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Cut the squash in half and remove seeds and fibers. Melt the
butter and add the brown sugar. Divide among the four squash
halves. Place squash in a pan, cut-side up. Pour { cup water into
the pan. Bake 75 minutes at 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the peas with the sour cream, dill and lemon juice.
Divide among the squash halves, then return them to the oven for 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to make this an authentic Hawaiian dish, you should
grow, cut and squeeze the sugar cane yourself. The process
shouldn't be that difficult. Just remember to never, ever turn your
back on the ocean.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
