<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8526 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-CLINTON-ASSAD-ART-2TA     03-26 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ASSAD-ART-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S EFFORT FAILS TO GET SYRIA TO RESUME TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: map is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ President Clinton failed in three hours of talks here
on Sunday to persuade the Syrian leader, Hafez Assad, to moderate
his differences with Israel, and the White House said afterward
that it was ``impossible'' to predict when talks between Israel and
Syria would resume.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe it would be productive for them to resume
now,'' the White House spokesman, Joe Lockhart, said of the
Syrian-Israeli negotiations after Clinton headed home to Washington
on Sunday night. ``In our judgment it is not worthwhile to have
meetings for meetings' sake.''
</P>
<P>
   The president, who presented proposals from Prime Minister Ehud
Barak of Israel but none of his own, had decided to meet Assad on
his way home from a six-day tour of South Asia in the hope of
finding enough agreement between the Syrian and Israeli positions
that peace talks, which broke down in January, might resume.
</P>
<P>
   Though Lockhart would not address the substantive issues
discussed during the meeting on Sunday, the first face-to-face
encounter between Clinton and Assad in more than five years, it
appeared clear from the spokesman's terse comments that almost no
common ground was found on any issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are significant differences and a lot of hard work that
needs to be done,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   The quick ending here appeared to dash Clinton's hopes of
presiding over a comprehensive peace deal that would incorporate
Syria, the Palestinians and Israel before he left office. Instead,
there could well be a worsening situation between Israel and Syria,
some officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of the talks on Sunday was met with near despair by
diplomats involved in both the Syrian and Palestinian tracks of the
Middle East peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very bad news,'' one diplomat in the region said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke to Barak just before the talks began and again
after they ended, Lockhart said. In a written statement, Lockhart
said the administration ``will continue to try to help the parties
overcome these differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats speculated that Assad may have come to Geneva with
unrealistic expectations of what Barak was prepared to offer.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Assad, Joubran Kourieh, said the talks on Sunday
had dealt ``the obstacles which Israel put and is still putting to
the resumption of talks.''
</P>
<P>
   With the failure of the talks, it was now likely, the diplomat
in the region said, that Israel would move quickly to begin a
withdrawal from what it calls its security zone in southern
Lebanon. Once Israeli soldiers start leaving Lebanon, where Syria
is the dominant power, Syria will lose a bargaining chip with
Israel and the incentive to reach a deal will further evaporate,
diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility then of conflict between Syrian-backed groups,
such as the Hezbollah guerrillas, striking Israel across the
international border between Lebanon and Israel was ``quite high,''
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no news conference with Clinton and Assad on Sunday
and the president left Geneva soon after the talks ended. He had
been prepared to extend the meeting through Monday if needed, his
aides said on Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   If the talks had gone well here, it was anticipated that the
national security adviser, Sandy Berger, would brief reporters.
Instead, Lockhart spoke. And Secretary of State Madeleine Albright,
who was to go to Israel to explain the results if the talks went
well, returned to Washington, too. Dennis Ross, the
administration's special envoy for the Middle East, will fly to see
Barak on Monday, Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The talks opened in midafternoon with little fanfare in a green
and gold conference room in the Intercontinental Hotel here, the
same room where Clinton and the Syrian leader met in the spring of
1994.
</P>
<P>
   Assad, 69, who is in failing health, looked very thin in face
and body. At the urging of a Swiss photographer, the two leaders
shook hands during a quick photo session, as their delegations _
including Albright and the Syrian foreign minister, Farouk al-Shara
_ looked on.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Clinton and Assad met _ in Damascus in October
1994 _ the atmospherics were brittle. Then, at a joint news
conference, the Syrian leader denied that Syria backed terrorist
groups and took exception at the fact that Syria was on the State
Department's list of countries that support terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   While the White House had tried in the last few days to play
down expectations on results of Sunday's session, senior
administration officials had also said that they had a good enough
grasp of the Syrian and Israeli positions to lay out a road map for
proceeding with talks.
</P>
<P>
   Three days ago, Berger told reporters that the ``best case
result would be that we have a sense of enough common ground that
negotiations could be resumed and that we could envision them
ending in success.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the breakdown of talks between Syria and Israel in
Shephardstown, W. Va., Clinton had talked with Barak and Assad by
telephone. Through these ``extensive conversations,'' Clinton
gained a fuller understanding of the ``needs'' of both sides,
Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the major sticking points, according to administration
officials and diplomats, came down to what would constitute the
international border between Israel and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Assad has made clear, to his people at home and to the outside
world, that he wants an Israeli withdrawal to the border that
existed between the two countries on June 4, 1967, just before
Israel captured the Golan Heights from Syria. By this he means an
Israeli withdrawal right to the edge of the Sea of Galilee, which
provides much of Israel's water.
</P>
<P>
   But for Barak, having the Syrian border extend right to the
banks of the Sea of Galilee is unacceptable for security and
emotional reasons, administration officials and diplomats said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the last several weeks, the question became how to compromise
on the Sea of Galilee or as an administration official said ``how
to finesse it so that the border of Israel remains just beyond the
eastern shore of the Sea of Galilee.''
</P>
<P>
   Just before the talks began on Sunday morning, a Western
diplomat who is in touch with the Americans, the Israelis and the
Syrians predicted that there would be no progress in Geneva
``because Syria will not yield on the banks of the Sea of
Galilee.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's session was the first time that Assad _ through Clinton
_ had heard Barak's bottom-line on the issues that divided them.
</P>
<P>
   Each of those issues represented a ``double-edged sword, ''
Berger had said on the eve of the talks. ``If Israel decides that
it's going to withdraw from some portion of the Golan, it will give
up some modicum of security,'' he said. ``How are those security
needs going to be addressed? If Israel gives up some portion of the
Golan, is it for a paper peace or is it for a real peace? Those are
the questions that the Israelis are asking.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanging over the talks was the knowledge within both Clinton
administration and the Barak government that time was running out.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has said he would put any agreement to a referendum, but
opinion polls show that popular support in Israel for a deal with
Syria has steadily eroded over the last few months. One survey
released last week in Israel showed that 55 percent of the
respondents said they would not trust a peace agreement signed with
Assad.
</P>
<P>
   Another element pointing to the shortage of time is Barak's
pledge to pull the Israeli army out of what Israel calls its
security zone in southern Lebanon by early July. It will take the
Israeli army three months to complete its withdrawal, thus troops
will begin pulling out next month, an administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the all important border issue around the Sea of
Galilee, other questions that needed resolution included
arrangements for an early warning station on Mt. Hermon on the
Golan Heights; the amount of time that Israel would take to
withdraw from the Heights; and how quickly Syria would be willing
to normalize relations with Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
