<HEADER>
A8530 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-26 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: CONTRACTS FOR CRONIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the enduring paradoxes of government procurement is that
sweetheart deals tend to give off a terrible odor.
</P>
<P>
   The city's normally mild-mannered comptroller, Alan Hevesi, is
loudly objecting to a pair of particularly foul-smelling contracts
that improperly bypassed the competitive bidding process and, he
believes, were carefully and insidiously crafted to benefit cronies
of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   The contracts, to help manage the city's welfare-to-work
program, were awarded to Maximus Inc. of McLean, Va., and are worth
$104 million. And they are renewable for an additional $104
million. They should have been competitively bid, but were not,
said Hevesi. One of the major beneficiaries of the contracts _ a
partner that would rather not be known as a partner in this venture
_ is a company called Opportunity America, which just happens to be
run by Richard J. Schwartz, a former senior adviser to Giuliani who
designed the mayor's welfare-to-work program.
</P>
<P>
   Opportunity, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   When he left government for the private sector, Schwartz said he
would not enter into any consulting contracts with New York City. I
guess he misspoke.
</P>
<P>
   For a glimpse of blatant favoritism in the awarding of
government contracts, consider the following:
</P>
<P>
   According to Hevesi, Maximus, in its application, asked to be
paid $4,620 for each person it was able to place in a job. But the
city, through the Human Resources Administration, would have none
of that. Maximus was told it must be paid more than $4,620. So the
price for each client placed in a job was jacked up to $5,000, an
increase worth millions over the life of the contracts.
</P>
<P>
   It pays to have friends in high places.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over these contracts erupted a couple of months
ago when the mayor began submitting, for Hevesi's approval, what
turned out to be 17 welfare-to-work contracts that had been awarded
without competitive bidding.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the contracts were with agencies that do fine work.
Nevertheless, they should have been competitively bid.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out, said Hevesi, that those contracts were supposed
to ``camouflage'' the biggest contract in the batch _ the one with
Maximus.
</P>
<P>
   When Hevesi and his aides began perusing the Maximus paperwork,
they found that Maximus had gotten what the comptroller described
as ``huge preferred treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the contracts were not competitively bid, notices
went out to companies that might have wanted to do the work that
was slated for Maximus. Preliminary discussions between those
companies and HRA were to begin March 2, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Said Hevesi: ``We now have documents showing a series of
conferences, meetings and exchanges between Maximus and HRA
starting the prior December.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times' Nina Bernstein, in a story earlier this
month, wrote: ``The city did not hold its first informational
meeting for other companies seeking to bid on the contracts until
mid-May.''
</P>
<P>
   The result, said Hevesi, was that Maximus had its contract
proposal ``all ready to go'' before anybody else was aware that
proposals would be requested.
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``They had schematics for their offices in New York _
they had their salaries figured, you get the idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, Hevesi and his aides discovered the Richard Schwartz
connection.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz, who is also a former deputy campaign manager for
Giuliani, has repeatedly denied that he is a partner in this
venture with Maximus. He claims he is simply a subcontractor.
</P>
<P>
   But he's a subcontractor who walks, looks and smells very much
like a partner in this deal. The Maximus paperwork submitted to the
city says it is ``in partnership with'' Schwartz's company,
Opportunity America. And Opportunity America is, under the
contracts, supposed to get 30 percent of the $104 million.
</P>
<P>
   The comptroller has refused to approve the contracts, saying he
will not participate in ``favoritism and cronyism.'' He has
referred the matter to the Manhattan district attorney and federal
investigators for possible further action.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani angrily denied that there was anything wrong with the
contracts and said he will sue Hevesi to force their approval.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
