<HEADER>
A8531 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-AGING-0327-COX     03-26 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGING-0327-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Congressional Bill Could Unintentially Harm Patients
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO, Calif. - Congressional efforts to block
physician-assisted suicide could unintentionally harm patients
suffering great pain near death, an aging conference here was
warned Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Although the bill, the Pain-Relief Promotion Act, is intended to
alleviate pain among terminally-ill patients, its passage could
have ``a chilling effect'' on the use of aggressive pain-relief
medications, said Marshall B. Kapp, an attorney and director of the
office of Geriatric Medicine and Gerontology at Wright State
University School of Medicine in Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Kapp, who said he agreed with the intent of discouraging
physician-assisted suicide in states such as Oregon, told a
conference at the annual American Society on Aging meeting here
that the bill would cause physicians to worry that they might
violate the law by prescribing pain relief medication in
potentially lethal doses even if their intent was merely to relieve
pain.
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed the House in October by a vote of 271-156 and is
now pending in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Panel members at the conference, which focused on legal, moral
and practical concerns for caring for patients at the end of life,
said decisions regarding such care are often complicated by the
fact that patients may be suffering from numerous ailments as they
near death.
</P>
<P>
   Kapp and Monsignor Charles J. Fahey, senior associate at the
Third Age Center at Fordham University in the Bronx, N.Y., also
agreed that someone acting as the patient's proxy is prefererable
to so-called ``living wills.'' In a living will a patient puts in
writing whether he or she wants invasive and life-prolonging care
at the end of life. By contrast a patient can sign a durable power
of attorney in which someone is chosen to act at the patient's
representative in making end-of-life care decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Fahey said family members and friends who have participated in
caring for the dying patient should have priority in deciding how
much and what type care should be given at the end even if other
relatives might have a stronger legal claim but have not been close
to the patient.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians should not be bound by a living will in making
decisions about care, Kapp said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for a doctor to pick up a piece of paper and say 'is
this really what Mrs. Jones wants in this situation?' `` he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although some living wills may indicate that a patient does not
want surgery near the end of life, Kapp noted that some surgery
might be desirable to make the patient more comfortable even though
it might not make the patient live longer.
</P>
<P>
   Former Florida state Sen. Jack Gordon, D-Miami Beach, president
of the Hospice Foundation of America, said hospices have flourished
in part because they reject the medical model for treating dying
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Patients nearing death need a coordinated approach that
emphasizes relieving pain, helping the family and meeting the
person's emotional and spiritual needs, Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   The medical model for treating patients involves numerous
specialists each trying to cure a specific ailment, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Catherine Eng, medical director of On Lok (CQ) Senior
Health Services in San Francisco, said the current generation of
medical students is being taught to give a high priority to
relieving pain.
</P>
<P>
   Eng said doctors do not intentionally seek to cause their
patients' pain, but the fractured system of medicine sometimes does
not allow physicians to treat the whole patient.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
