u s BC-SKATE-DRUGS-NYT &LR;      03-26 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKATE-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RUSSIAN SKATER TESTS POSITIVE AND IS FORCED OUT OF WORLDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NICE, France _ The drama-filled career of the Russian pairs
skater Yelena Berezhnaya took another turn today when the
International Skating Union announced on the eve of the world
figure skating championships that she had tested positive for a
banned stimulant in a random drug test.
</P>
<P>
   Berezhnaya and her partner, Anton Sikharulidze, the two-time
world pairs champions, already had been withdrawn from the
championships by the Russian Figure Skating Federation because of
the positive test.
</P>
<P>
   In a communique, the skating union said that Berezhnaya, now
based in Hackensack, N.J., with Sikharulidze and their renowned
coach, Tamara Moskvina, indicated that she had ingested the banned
and unspecified stimulant inadvertently while trying to treat
bronchitis.
</P>
<P>
   The skating union also said that the Russian federation had
indicated that both it and Berezhnaya had accepted the positive
result and waived the right to have her B sample analyzed. The ISU
council, which rules on drug-testing offenses, will now determine
the penalty. Depending on the type of stimulant Berezhnaya
ingested, she faces a ban from competition of between three months
and two years.
</P>
<P>
   Positive drug tests are rare in figure skating. The most recent
involving a prominent skater came in 1991 when Marina Klimova,
another Russian skater, tested positive for a banned steroid. A
second test exonerated her a few weeks later, and Klimova later won
the Olympic ice dancing title in 1992 with her husband, Sergei
Ponomorenko.
</P>
<P>
   Berezhnaya and Sikharulidze won a silver medal in the 1998
Winter Olympics in Nagano, Japan, and then won their first world
title that spring. They were the dominant pair last season,
although their victory in the 1999 world championships in Helsinki,
Finland, was far from convincing. Berezhnaya fell during the free
program, but she and Sikharulidze still finished ahead of the
technically superior Chinese pair of Shen Xue and Zhao Hongbo.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the judges of the event, Alfred Korytek of Ukraine, and
Svyatoslav Babenko of Russia, were later suspended and then banned
from judging by the skating union for collusion after a Canadian
television network filmed them communicating during the
competition.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Berezhnaya and Sikharulidze were beaten by Shen and
Zhao at the ISU Grand Prix final for the second year in a row, but
the Russians won their national title and the European
championships, defeating their domestic rivals Marya Petrova and
Aleksei Tikhonov in both competitions.
</P>
<P>
   When the Soviet Union dissolved, Berezhnaya initially
represented the Baltic state of Latvia and competed with Oleg
Sliakov. Her career nearly ended in January 1996 when she was hit
in the head by Sliakov's skate blade while practicing a camel spin.
She was hospitalized and had to undergo extensive rehabilitation
and speech therapy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-00 2030EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
