u s BC-BKN-MIDWEST-MICHIGAN-     03-26 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MIDWEST-MICHIGAN-STATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHIGAN STATE IS LOOKING FOR MORE THAN NET 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ The Michigan State Spartans hardly hurried
to take scissors to the net after winning the Midwest Regional
Saturday night. Instead, they circled the floor at the Palace and
saluted the raucous crowd, which boomed the school's fight song in
one voice.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Mateen Cleaves, Morris Peterson, A.J. Granger, Andre
Hutson and Charlie Bell have strings of nylon from last year when
they advanced to the Final Four. No, the nets they want droop from
the orange rims at the RCA Dome in Indianapolis, where the national
champion will be crowned next Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me wrong, this is a great accomplishment and I'm
glad we did it here in front of our people,'' said Cleaves, his
ears still ringing from the Michigan State faithful who made the
80-minute drive from East Lansing. ``But we stayed together to win
this whole thing _ to be champions.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second time in the regional, the Spartans wiped out
their opponent's leads with the kind of blurring rallies usually
witnessed on the Motor City's speedways. Against Iowa State, the
Spartans needed just two minutes to turn a 61-55 deficit into a
64-61 lead before finishing off the Cyclones with a 11-3 run and a
75-64 victory. In the final six minutes against Syracuse on
Thursday, the Spartans squeezed off 19 straight points to barrel
past the Orangemen 75-58.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach always says tough players win,'' said Peterson, who
scored all but five of his 18 points against the Cyclones in the
second half, referring to Coach Tom Izzo. ``And I thought down the
stretch, we showed how tough we were. I think Mateen says it best _
we've got a refuse-to-lose attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   They are resilient and tough, too. They clawed out a 9-4 record
in their first 13 games without Cleaves, who was out with a
fractured foot. The Spartans' other guard, Bell, has hobbled
through the tournament and missed practices with tendinitis in his
left knee, but he found extra burners and rediscovered a smooth
gait on Saturday to power the Spartans' final rush.
</P>
<P>
   The tight-knit Spartans will travel to Indianapolis with a heavy
heart. Moments after Peterson soared along the baseline and stuffed
down a lob pass from his best friend, Cleaves, that demoralized the
Cyclones for good, the senior was told his grandmother, Clara Mae
Spencer, had died early Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   His family decided to tell him after the game in the Michigan
State locker room with Izzo and Cleaves. She had suffered a stroke
in February and had been in an out of a coma. ``My grandmother was
right there with me,'' he said, his eyes still red from tears. ``It
seemed like somebody was guiding those shots in. When I got the
news, it was very emotional. My grandmother was my best friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson insisted he would attend her wake and funeral in
Mississippi on Thursday and Friday before the Spartans take on
Wisconsin in the semifinals Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to go,'' he said. ``She's been there for me. She'd do
anything for her grandkids.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans _ the only top-seeded team remaining _ once more
cannot bank on accomplishing what they set out and failed to do
last season: win the national title. A year ago, a 36-1 Duke team
bounced them in the semifinals. This season, the first obstacle in
what has been a wacky tournament is a team as iron willed as
Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   The Badgers (24-10) have made the tournament field only six
times in the school's history, last advanced to the Final Four 59
years ago and won the title and have already been beaten three
times by the Spartans in Big Ten play _61-44, 59-44, 55-46.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Iowa State game, another Spartan senior, Granger,
said that despite the team's impressive record _ 30-7 _ this had
been one of the most trying years at Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We struggled without Mateen; we've been banged up and
frustrated at times because we couldn't put 40 minutes of good
basketball together,'' Granger explained. ``But at the same time
we've gotten to know each other real well and understand some
truths _ like not everybody can score all the time, that sometimes,
you know, you need a guy like Mateen to get on you. We've learned
to trust each other, though, and know what to do when it's each of
ours' turn.''
</P>
<P>
   In the locker room late Saturday, Cleaves made it clear that the
Spartans know there is one last thing that he and his teammates can
do together. ``We can play two perfect games _ a full 40 minutes
each playing as hard as we can,'' he said, then added
matter-of-factly, ``We do that and we go out on top.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, the Spartans will hurry to the ladder. And they will divvy
up the net. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
