<HEADER>
A8536 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-KINGDOME-THIEL-COLUMN     03-26 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KINGDOME-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUT INSTINCT SAYS IT WAS A BAD THING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ This time, the thump in the chest came from the
outside, not inside.
</P>
<P>
   Ever the provider of noisy heart-pounders, the Kingdome saved
its concussive best for last, sending a final astonishment aboard a
shock wave felt as much as heard.
</P>
<P>
   In a dynamite moment, the Northwest's first true major-league
sports stadium was no longer too ugly, too big, too small, too
cheap or too dark.
</P>
<P>
   All it was, barely two percent into its fanciful life expectancy
of a thousand years, was too bad.
</P>
<P>
   The perch was a couple of football fields from ground zero, in a
fifth-floor office above McRory's landmark restaurant at the edge
of the Kingdome's north parking lot. From there, the symbol of a
quarter-century of local sports and cultural history disappeared so
fast the old neighbor building shook.
</P>
<P>
   As the roiling dust cloud suddenly swallowed McRory's building
into several minutes of a surreal mocha twilight, the Kingdome
provided one more glimpse of the previously unseen -- the location,
taste, smell and feel of smithereens.
</P>
<P>
   Concrete dust, flakes, pigeon feathers and the detritus of a
once-great notion flushed through the open window, giving a new
meaning to the sports phrase ``chalk talk.''
</P>
<P>
   As eyes watered and noses filled with an acrid sniff of
gunpowder and ash, instinct said a bad thing just happened.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but the head knew better. This was a good thing. Right?
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand natives and McRory's visitors Stephen Connor and his
mother, Betty, vacationing in Seattle, had read up a bit about the
Kingdome's controversial history. A few minutes before the building
went away, they remained puzzled.
</P>
<P>
   ``You owe so much on the building, but you don't pay for it, you
just blow it up,'' Stephen said, smiling. ``I guess that's the
ultimate American way.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Betty: ``That's what's called progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it was never that simple. Then again, how does one explain
a facility that cost $68 million in public money when it opened,
then 24 years later had a $120 million mortgage despite many years
of profitable operation, and wouldn't be paid off until 2016?
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, a bad thing did happen, over time. Even if it could be
explained to visitors, they wouldn't believe it.
</P>
<P>
   The only reassurance offered was that in June, 1997, 51 percent
of the state's voters thought the plan to replace the Kingdome was
a good idea. It wasn't mentioned that some of these same people
thought the WTO meetings in Seattle were a good idea, too.
</P>
<P>
   As the particle storm spread out over downtown and the Sound,
depositing a grainy return to citizens of their tax dollars, the
roof door on McRory's building was cleared to open.
</P>
<P>
   Shuffling through the debris and dust of the now-sunlit
spectacle, a small scrap of paper was found. It was backing, still
attached to the fluffy ceiling material that was sprayed onto the
Kingdome's underside following the 1994 fallen-tile debacle.
</P>
<P>
   Visible on the scrap were words and a small diagram, apparently
a cross-section of the layers of the Kingdome roof. One arrow on
the diagram pointed to the fundamental virtue of the roof, and
therefore the building: ``Waterproofing membrane.''
</P>
<P>
   As has been much chronicled and debated lately, Seattle has been
undergoing massive change, thanks to a booming economy and enormous
individual and corporate wealth. Never has that change been
manifested more dramatically than Sunday's hole punched in the
skyline. By 2002, the change becomes more startling with
side-by-side sporting palaces built with more than $600 million in
tax dollars, exclusive of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, even the weather is changing. We no longer need a
waterproofing membrane.
</P>
<P>
   Who needs it, when we're already getting soaked?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
