u i BC-ISRAEL-POPE-SECURITY0     03-26 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POPE-SECURITY0327-C0X </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Story originally slugged POPE-RELIEF
 &HT;    Many felt anxious despite tight security for Pope's visit to
Israel
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Pope John Paul II's trip here is being hailed as a
moral and spiritual triumph, but it
</P>
<P>
   was not without its wrinkles.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Palestinians rioted in the Dehaisheh refugee camp
after the pontiff held Mass in nearby Manger Square. Some Jews
complained that John Paul fell short in addressing the Church's
responsibility during the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   And the Grand Mufti of Jerusalem suggested to the media the
night before the papal visit to the Old City that Palestinians
might
</P>
<P>
   disrupt his trip.
</P>
<P>
   But in the final analysis, John Paul's visit to this religious
and political cauldron was an unequivocal success in the eyes of
many: He lived to tell about it.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility that the pope could meet his end in the Jewish
state in the same city where Jesus was crucified was an underlying
and often unspoken source of anxiety throughout this nation for
months leading up to this trip.
</P>
<P>
   The implications were nothing short of biblical. Though the
Second Vatican Council repudiated the concept of Jewish guilt for
the death of Jesus in 1965, the consequences of theologically
motivated anti-Semitism are indelibly branded into the collective
Jewish consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   So the prospect that Christ's vicar on earth _ as the pope is
understood to be by the world's 1.1 billion Roman Catholics _ could
be assassinated here, perhaps even by a Jew, seemed potentially
cataclysmic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the anxious type but I said a little prayer a few
weeks ago that nothing would happen to him while he was in
Israel,'' said Devorah Young, a religious Jew living in Jerusalem.
``I think people would say they did it again, they killed Christ
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing inside the Old City on Sunday waiting to catch a
glimpse of the pope's motorcade, Rina Hakimian said the thought had
crossed her mind, especially since this is the 2,000th anniversary
of Jesus' birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something happened, the resurrection of the idea of Jews
killing Jesus would be impossible to avoid,'' said Hakimian, a
lawyer living in Jerusalem. ``The image of Jews as Christ-killers
is still very much alive in a lot of circles.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while officials touted the massive international press
coverage as an unrivalled public relations opportunity, the
coverage also meant that any attack on the pope would be broadcast
around the world instantaneously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Operation Old Friend,'' the single largest security effort for
any visitor in the history of the state, was launched to minimize
the danger.
</P>
<P>
   More than 18,000 police and 4,000 soldiers worked security
details during the six-day trip. Police were not allowed to take
vacation while the pope was here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was glad to see all the security,'' said Tony Elia, a 25
year-old graduate student living in Jerusalem. ``There was a lot of
talk around campus that every 2,000 years was a tradition and it
was kind of sick.''
</P>
<P>
   John Paul's visit through the Old City of Jerusalem on Sunday
was the most difficult for security forces to prepare for,
officials said. While about $3 million was pumped into Jerusalem to
ready the roads for the pope's arrival, only so much could be done
to modernize the square-mile maze of thousand-year-old alleys and
rooftops.
</P>
<P>
   Security forces, including Israel's equivalent of the CIA and
FBI, saturated the area. At the Jaffa Gate, where the pope's
procession exited the Old City, snipers took positions on top of
nearly every visible rooftop and balcony. Two helicopters circled
in the air and hundreds of soldiers with rifles lined the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Intelligence officers corralled dozens of men deemed to be
suspicious _ Jews and Arabs alike _ away from the pope's proposed
exit route.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world supplies the actors,'' said Ehud Naveh, who
coordinated preparations for the pope's visit. ``We supply the
stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Less conspicuously, 150 security cameras posted above the alleys
filmed virtually every person in the Old City. The government has
been installing the cameras since last year with the pope's visit
in mind, officials said. Images are piped into a nearby police
station and monitored on dozens of television screens in a single
room.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of some grumbling about traffic tie-ups,
Israelis took the virtual martial law in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm delighted that (the pope) came by, but if anything
happened we would get blamed again,'' said Gila Gottlieb, a Jew
living in Jerusalem. ``I'm going to be glad when he gets out of
here today.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
