<HEADLINE>
BOOK ON RED IS ONE GREAT READ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Book title: ``Red Smith on Baseball: The Game's
Greatest Writer on the Game's Greatest Years''
</P>
<P>
   Vital stats: Ivan R. Dee Publishing, 363 pages with index,
$24.95.
</P>
<P>
   The intent: Here are 167 columns that the fabled New York Herald
Tribune and New York Times sportswriter pounded out from 1941 to
1981 (a year before his death), arranged chronologically to capture
the essence of the game and how it evolved during that 40-year
period.
</P>
<P>
   The execution: Exposing the best of Smith to anyone under 40
years old is a must. And even better, this collection definitely
stands the test of time.
</P>
<P>
   An excerpt: A tongue-in-cheek column about why the spitball
should be reinstated, written June 8, 1961:
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans today who never saw a kosher spitter thrown will tell you
that the damp delivery was banned because it is difficult to
control and consequently a menace to life and limb, or because it
is unsportsmanlike, or because it might offend fastidious
customers, or because there is something intrinsically dishonest,
not to say immoral, about moistening the hide of a dead horse. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``It's high time the poor slob (pitcher) got a break. These days
he can't even depend on his catcher having a raised eyelet on his
mitt and carving up the ball for him now and then. Sure as
anything, some interfering tape of an umpire would ring in a new
ball on the very next pitch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
