<SLUG> BC-BKW-RUTGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NCAA WOMEN'S TOURNAMENT GAMES APPEAR WITH THE INFOMERCIALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ It is difficult to tell from the evidence
available this past weekend whether the National Collegiate
Athletic Association and its television partner are trying to
promote women's basketball or to kill it.
</P>
<P>
   First, the NCAA placed the semifinals and final of the national
tournament's West Regional in a discarded arena, Memorial Coliseum,
where the floor has several dead spots. The Rose Garden, home of
the Portland Trail Blazers, sits right next door, available,
ignored. As organizers of last summer's Women's World Cup pointed
out, a second-class arena signals a second-class event.
</P>
<P>
   Second, ESPN chose to start Rutgers' regional semifinal against
Alabama-Birmingham at 12:30 a.m. Sunday Eastern time, consigning
the game to infomercial wasteland. Rutgers won, 60-45, but the only
people who most likely saw it were channel-surfing for bamboo
steamers and pan-flute artists.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's regional final against top-seeded Georgia will start at
midnight in the East, guaranteeing another small audience of hoop
junkies and mistaken seekers of Victoria Principal's skin-care
products. Even worse, the winner will have to fly cross-country and
play on three days of rest Friday at the Final Four in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wonder what kind of mind-set goes into this,'' Rutgers
Coach C. Vivian Stringer said. ``We know the name of the game is
green, it's not about women. It's about how they can best get their
dollar. That's the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowered expectations have always been the bane of women's
sports. The problem has been particularly exacerbated for minority
women. When Tasha Pointer was being recruited to play point guard
at Rutgers, she said that the athletic director at Whitney Young
High School on Chicago's West Side tried to discourage her.
</P>
<P>
   Pointer said the athletic director told her, ``It's like an Ivy
League school,'' hinting that she might not measure up
academically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people, a lot of times, discourage minorities and make
them question their own abilities,'' Pointer said. ``My parents
always taught me to believe in myself, and that I can do anything I
want with hard work and determination.''
</P>
<P>
   A junior, the effusive Pointer is on the dean's list at Rutgers,
majoring in broadcasting. She said that she will have an internship
with CBS Sports this summer. While spending time in New York City,
she hopes to engage in two of her passions, basketball and chess.
She began playing chess in grade school, she said with a laugh, to
avoid having to go straight home from school to baby-sit for her
younger brother after basketball season was over. She played in
school, and she brought her chessboard along with her basketball to
St. Louis Park in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chess is a lot like playing point guard,'' Pointer said. ``You
have to learn to think two or three moves ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday night, while her team was playing somnolently, and
even Rutgers' pep band was yawning, the Scarlet Knights let an
early lead dissipate in the second half. Twice, Alabama-Birmingham
threatened to go ahead, but both times Pointer kept Rutgers in the
lead with an assist or a shot, a long pass or a knifing drive to
the basket. She played all 40 minutes and finished with an
impressive line: 11 points on 5-of-8 shooting, 6 rebounds, 9
assists and 1 turnover.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the 5-foot-6-inch Pointer became Stringer's
second pivotal recruit, joining guard Shawnetta Stewart, who had
scored more career points than Wilt Chamberlain had while in high
school in Philadelphia. It was a tough time at an anonymous
basketball school, when people were asking, ``Where is Rutgers?''
and ``What is Rutgers?'' Stringer played to Pointer's pioneering
spirit, convincing her not to follow another school's
well-established path, but to come to Rutgers and create her own
path. Stringer calls it the bumblebee theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't believe what the scientists say, `That your body is too
fat and your wings are too heavy and aerodynamically you are not
capable of flying,''' Stringer implored, referring to the
possibilities of building Rutgers into a national power. ``We
continue to function as bumblebees.''
</P>
<P>
   In Pointer's freshman season, Rutgers advanced to the Round of
16, possessing a kind of innocence that displaced fear and
self-doubt, until it met undefeated Tennessee and was humbled,
92-60, in the regional semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just innocent youth,'' Pointer said. ``Tennessee
showed us how much work you've got to put into winning.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive year, Rutgers (25-7) has trampolined
into a regional final, this time against Georgia (32-3), which
shredded North Carolina, 83-57, earlier Saturday. No one doubts
Rutgers' disruptive matchup zone, but many question whether Rutgers
has the scoring ability to match Georgia, which defeated Tennessee
by 27 points earlier this season. Then again, Pointer has never
bowed to lower expectations.
</P>
<P>
   It is unfortunate for her that the television ratings will come
nowhere near as high as her hopes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-00 2042EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
