<HEADLINE>
THIS MAC ATTACK IS OFF MARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When he orchestrated the team veto of the
all-expenses-paid (plus $25,000 apiece) trip to Tokyo for the 2000
big-league season opener, Mark McGwire was really flexing his
muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Good for him.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, none of the St. Louis Cardinals will be enriched by
Japanese culture unless they're lucky enough to someday be cut from
the team and have to go overseas groveling for work.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball asked the home-run king to go as a good-will gesture.
McGwire gave them another gesture. He said the international
competition did not ``turn my crank.''
</P>
<P>
   Did Mac Daddy fear that he'd miss MTV's ``Spring Break'' week?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese have their own brand of baseball over there,''
McGwire said. ``I know Major League Baseball wants to do more
internationally, but there's no purpose in it. I don't agree with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs and Mets thank you for your small-minded, self-centered
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Y'know, if baseball wants to keep calling it a !ital!World
Series, someday it's gonna have to recognize the sport exists
outside the North American TV market.
</P>
<P>
   --So why aren't the Dodgers involved in this overseas excursion
after all the team has done for international relations? If Peter
O'Malley were running the show, that wouldn't have slipped by.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, they'll open the season outside the country, too. In the
Siberian tropics known as Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   How are the players supposed to smuggle back authentic Pokemon
cards from Canada? ...
</P>
<P>
   --When Mike Morgan, Jesse Orosco and Rickey Henderson all make
the final major-league rosters this week, they'll become the 23rd,
24th and 25th big-leaguers to accomplish what obscure feat?
</P>
<P>
   Be an active player in four decades, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Although !ital!active is a rather subjective term....
</P>
<P>
   --As Iowa State proved, UCLA still needs a coach who can adjust
during a game. Right, slick?...
</P>
<P>
   --They were supposed to hold Congressional hearings this week on
that NCAA-backed piece-o-legislation that would make it illegal to
bet on all amateur sporting events. Now they've been pushed back to
probably May.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is fairly obvious, as we tried to point out a few
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect it would be rather embarrassing to my colleagues to
have these hearings during March Madness,'' Sen. Richard Bryan
(D-Nev.) admitted to the Associated Press. ``I would bet that
two-thirds, if not more, of the Senate offices have pools betting
on which teams advance in which brackets. Our office has had a pool
for years.''
</P>
<P>
   You betcha....
</P>
<P>
   --There exists a city called Bracketville, in Texas. And the
citizens love the commercials....
</P>
<P>
   --After watching the Kingdome blown to kingdom come, we'll
gladly pick up the tab to have the L.A. Sports Arena placed next
before the firing squad.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, let's shoot for April 15 when the next Xtreme Pro
Wrestling show takes place....
</P>
<P>
   --Like I was saying, Hollywood Henderson was a real money
player....
</P>
<P>
   --Mark it on the calendar: Fayetteville, N.C., the birthplace of
the Putt-Putt Golf Course of America, will host the prestigious
$100,000 Professional Putters Association National Putting
Championship from July 30 to Aug. 5.
</P>
<P>
   There'll be 215 pro and amateurs entered. What distinguishes the
two? Last year's champ, 36-year-old John Napoli of Clearwater
Beach, Fla., shot a perfect 18 over 18 holes to win.
</P>
<P>
   Now you go out and do !ital!that at the Family Fun Center, with
a bunch of red-and-blue balls and sawed-off clubs, and kids
screaming for cotton candy, and the group playing behind you with
that one knucklehead who continues to smack his ball up the fairway
while you're trying to line up a 2-inch putt, after the ball you
previously were using got stuck in that tube beneath the windmill
and won't come out, and your wife stuck her club up the tube to try
to knock it out and ended up falling into the murky waters of that
moat near the castle.
</P>
</TEXT>
