u a BC-INTERNET-POLITICS-SPI     03-26 1444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-POLITICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTION POLITICS INCREASINGLY WIRED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY and ROBERT GAVIN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet-intensive campaigns of presidential candidates John
McCain and Bill Bradley are gone, but the Web promises to have a
sweeping effect on the 2000 election and to change the way
campaigns are run in America.
</P>
<P>
   Already Arizona Democrats have conducted the nation's first
e-mail presidential primary. And Vice President Al Gore has boasted
of how e-mail is replacing the telephone as his means of
communicating with staff aides.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, will it change the ways elections are fought
(and) the way issues are debated? Will the power be shifted?''
asked Steven Clift, the board chairman of Minnesota e-democracy, a
non-profit, non-partisan group.
</P>
<P>
   That is perhaps the key question as politicians, political
parties, lobbyists, grass-roots organizations and citizens look
ahead to the increasingly wired world.
</P>
<P>
   The most optimistic see a device that can break the grip of
money and powerful special interests that seem to drive politics
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet was the tool that allowed me to stay competitive
on the money front,'' Bradley said in an interview. ``We knew there
were established sources of money in the party. We knew they were
likely to go overwhelmingly for the vice president (Gore). We had
to find new ways of giving and new givers. The Web was our means of
finding the sort of people who would be sympathetic to our
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley lost his bid for the Democratic presidential nomination,
but he argues that the Web is an affordable, accessible tool that
can level the playing field for newcomers and insurgents.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Sen. John McCain would agree.
</P>
<P>
   As his Straight Talk Express bus plowed through a fresh New
Hampshire snowfall in January, the Republican presidential hopeful
joked: ``The computer Web site is a modern device for living off
the land.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web helped McCain raise a record $10 million in February,
with $3.7 million arriving via cyberspace. An estimated $2 million
poured in during the four days after McCain's win in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura used the Internet in 1998, and won.
</P>
<P>
   A long-shot, third-party candidate who beat two long-established
politicians, Ventura made the Internet the central structure of his
campaign, said Andrew Blauh of the Markle Foundation, which is
studying the impact of technology on public affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet allowed them to operate as if they had a large
campaign infrastructure,'' Blauh said. ``It allows a different type
of campaign. It allows insurgents to operate at a level that they
couldn't before.''
</P>
<P>
   Using e-mail and regular Web-postings, the Ventura campaign
organized volunteers, coordinated their activities and got people
out to rallies. But this time, work that in the past might have
required volunteers to come into campaign headquarters was done at
home.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Karr, the treasurer of last year's I-695 campaign in
Washington and the campaign manager of Tim Eyman's new initiative
efforts, said e-mail proved an invaluable and cheap way of tying
together and coordinating the work of far-flung, loosely-organized
volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   When the campaign needed to get up lawn signs, it set up
self-serve pick-up sites and posted the locations on the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so much cheaper to direct people to pick them up,''
Karr said. ``When your campaign is a lot of guerrilla warfare, it
really does help because it's free. You have to utilize every free
resource.''
</P>
<P>
   Low-cost and speed are what make the Internet a favorite tool of
grass-roots and insurgent campaigns. Here are some reasons why:
</P>
<P>
   Politicians can raise money over the Internet at a fraction of
the cost of direct-mail fund-raising, which can suck up to 40
percent of the money for administrative costs, according to David
Chiu, co-founder and vice president of Grassroots.com, a political
Web site that offers fund-raising services.
</P>
<P>
   The low-overhead and convenience makes it more attractive to
seek small donors and multiplies the donors' impact.
</P>
<P>
   Money raised over the Internet becomes available almost
instantly. Hit-and-run campaigns like McCain's can quickly tap into
new money and then compete in new contests without missing a beat.
``It was the key to our survival,'' said Secretary of State Ralph
Munro, who chaired McCain's campaign in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail is almost instant. Within moments, grass-roots
organizations can alert their supporters of an important vote in
the Legislature and those supporters can e-mail their
representatives while they're voting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It levels the playing field for everybody,'' said Ed
Zuckerman, executive director of Washington Conservation Voters.
``It has a huge upside potential to open up the process for
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   But David Broder, the veteran Washington Post political writer,
raises the prospect of a downside in his new book ``Democracy
Derailed,'' which deals with the growing use of voter initiatives
and referendums in 24 states that permit them.
</P>
<P>
   Broder worries that a wired society, with information instantly
available to all, will seek to push aside representative
government. He wonders about whether checks, balances and
restraints established by America's founders can survive the
Information Age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think it will be long before the converging forces of
technology and public opinion coalesce in a political movement for
a national initiative _ to allow the public to substitute the
simplicity of majority rule by referendum for what must seem to
many frustrated Americans the arcane, ineffective, out-of-date
model of the Constitution,'' writes Broder.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Internet has proved easily adaptable to the worst
features of modern campaigning _ personal attacks, distortion of
foes' records, consultant-created issues and the spreading of nasty
rumors about an opponent.
</P>
<P>
   During the Democrats' recent nomination battle, Gore's site
pointed surfers to his ``Bradley Information Bureau,'' which
criticized Bradley's positions and contained nasty observations
from Gore surrogates. Bradley's ``More about Gore'' site was filled
with hostile information about Gore's abortion and health care
votes while he was a member of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Blauh, of the Markle Foundation, noted that the political system
has a tendency to push back when threatened or co-opt the
technology that causes it discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Blauh said, Congress at first gave great weight to
e-mails that lawmakers received. When lawmakers realized the
technology could easily mass-produce the communications, they
discounted e-mail and gave new weight to a hand-written note, Blauh
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't just assume that the Internet is a hammer that's
going to break every other institution,'' Blauh said.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts are skeptical that the Internet can produce the
e-democracy that will reverse voter alienation. More information
doesn't necessarily translate into more participation, as is
witnessed by downward voting trends of the last few decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're interested in politics, (the Internet) is there, but
it really doesn't work the other way,'' said John Bowes, a
University of Washington communications professor. ``It isn't a
magic solution. Magic solutions, that's the stuff of Italian
operas.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Bimber, director of the Center for Information Technology
at the University of California at Santa Barbara, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is changing how professional politics are organized, but
what it's not going to change is low citizen participation, low
turnout rates and lack of knowledge about politics,'' Bimber said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet will indeed provide more information for people
who are intensely interested in politics, but it's not going to
create interest in the rest of the population.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the Internet could just become another tool used by
politicians and handlers, like television, direct mail and other
media. Or it could encourage the types of candidates, issues and
messages that might reconnect alienated voters to politics.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, a politician who found himself in hot water last year for
suggesting that he created the Internet, waxes eloquent on the
Internet's possibilities. But he still seems a little unsure about
what changes it will bring to his profession.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet offers an unsurpassed opportunity for people to
access information and act on it,'' he mused during a recent
Seattle visit. ``Just how they use this opportunity, we will have
to see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
