<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPENTV-SPYGLASS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPENTV, A SOFTWARE PROVIDER, TO BUY SPYGLASS FOR $2.5 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OpenTV, the largest provider of interactive television software,
said Sunday that it would buy Spyglass Inc., which licenses
Internet-access software and offers consulting services on Internet
applications, in a stock deal valued at $2.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   OpenTV's software, which is used in 6.1 million set-top boxes _
primarily in Europe and Asia _ enables viewers watching, say, a
golf tournament to, with a click of the remote, call up more
information about the clubs the players are using or the clothing
they are wearing. But it does not provide the ability to browse the
Web, and it has been slow to catch on in the United States.
Spyglass, in contrast, has a large customer base in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely positive for both companies,'' said Coleen
Kaiser, an analyst who follows OpenTV for Merrill Lynch in London.
``OpenTV needed the Internet technology, and Spyglass needed the
name brand and relationship with network operators.''
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition gives OpenTV access to Spyglass' technology for
delivering Web information not only to set-top boxes but to mobile
phones and other wireless devices. Thus, it will enable OpenTV to
offer Web-browsing capability on set-top boxes and will give it a
toehold in the growing wireless communications market, both
domestically and overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can expand the services we offer and our customer base
without forgoing any of the services we offer now,'' said Jan W.
Steenkamp, OpenTV's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The whole concept of interactive television has excited
shareholders. Spyglass lost $1.9 million on $29.6 million in
revenue last year, yet its stock closed at $69.875 on Friday,
giving it a market value of $1.28 billion. Similarly, OpenTV lost
$9 million on revenue of about $26 million, yet its shares closed
at $169 on Friday, giving it a market value of about $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, OpenTV, which just went public in November, announced
an alliance with Health Hero Network Inc. a privately held company,
to create an interactive health channel on which doctors can
communicate with patients through their set-top boxes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-00 2045EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
