<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ASSESS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: WHITE HOUSE ANXIOUS AS RUSSIAN VOTES ARE COUNTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (With RUSSIA-ELECTION, RUSSIA-VOICES) 
(mk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ When Acting President Vladimir Putin met behind closed
doors last month with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, he
made an unusual appeal that Russia be considered a member of the
Western club.
</P>
<P>
   Putin said that he liked to eat Chinese food, knew how to use
chopsticks and regularly practiced judo.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's exotic stuff,'' Putin said, according to aides who
attended the session. ``That's not our mentality. Our mentality is
European.''
</P>
<P>
   But Putin's stated desire for Russia to be in the Western camp
could be at odds with the expectations he has fanned for Russia to
become a stronger state and his promises to restore his country's
dented national pride.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has a lot riding on a Putin victory,
whether it comes Monday, as the early-morning election results
appeared to indicate, or must wait until a runoff next month. And
it has been heartened by his remarks about the need to integrate
Russia with the West.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton officials are not only anxious to get American-Russian
relations back on track after a year and a half of drift following
the August 1998 collapse of the ruble; in an election year, they
also want to silence Republicans who have charged that Russia fell
off the path of economic reform on President Clinton's watch.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton officials would also like to seal the Clinton presidency
with a major arms control accord _ one that would slash long-range
nuclear arms and enable the United States to field a new network of
anti-missile defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's autocratic instincts, however, have cast a shadow over
Washington's hopes. Setbacks on human rights or fresh reports of
Russian atrocities in Chechnya would be major obstacle to closer
relations, especially in an American election year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton would like a strong leader he can work with but not
one that is unleashed,'' said Toby T. Gati, who served as a senior
State Department official during the Clinton administration. ``The
hope is that Putin will turn out to be a reformer. The president
and his advisers want to show Yeltsin left a legacy of reform that
Putin can build on. They want to rebut the critics who say their
Russia policy was a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   With a complex agenda of overlapping and competing interests,
there is no simple answer to what a Putin presidency could mean for
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect for closer ties is more favorable in the economic
sphere, where Putin's goals overlap with Western interests, than in
the area of security and human rights, issues where the two sides
often collide.
</P>
<P>
   On economics, Putin has signaled that he wants to establish the
foundations of a modern capitalist state, not because he has a
romantic infatuation with the free market but because he
understands that Russia must attract foreign investment and
overhaul its rust belt industries to become a world power.
</P>
<P>
   ``A country where weakness and poverty reign cannot be strong,''
Putin wrote in an open letter to the Russian people.
</P>
<P>
   To this end, Putin and his top aides have talked about
overhauling the tax code, protecting the rights of shareholders,
phasing-out subsidies to money-losing enterprises and tackling
politically dicey issues like establishing the right to own land.
</P>
<P>
   American officials have been impressed by Putin's talk of
economic change, including his insistence that he wants Russia to
be integrated in the world economy. They say that he appears
interested in achieving concrete results and understands that a
boom in oil prices that has helped the Russian economy is not a
substitute for reform.
</P>
<P>
   Much will depend, of course, on Putin's willingness to challenge
the tycoons that dominate much of the Russian economy to level the
playing field for business and investors.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials, however, are already
discussing steps the West might take to demonstrate its support if
Putin does undertake serious reform. They include expanding
assistance by the International Monetary Fund and World Bank,
rescheduling Russian debt, and stepped-up efforts by the U.S.
Export-Import Bank to encourage investment in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the `Who Lost Russia?' debate is behind us,'' Thomas
Pickering, the undersecretary of state and former U.S. ambassador
to Moscow, recently told a business group in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Economics, however, is just one part of the agenda. Arms control
and foreign policy are also important. And here Putin's
nationalism, his background as a KGB officer and his domestic
constituency may make him less cooperative than Washington would
like.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration was pleased that Putin dispensed with
diatribes against Washington's plans for a limited anti-missile
defense during his February meeting with Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Putin said his goal was to preserve the principles of
the 1972 Antiballistic Missile Treaty. Administration officials
hope that vague formulation reflected a new, if cautious, sense of
pragmatism, one that might open the door to a grand bargain on
offensive and defensive systems in which the treaty would be
modified to accommodate the American antimissile program.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Russians are willing to negotiate over the matter,
however, the discussions may prove difficult. The Russian military
is strongly opposed to the antimissile program. And though Putin
recently restored ties with NATO, the political climate in Russia
is not conducive to wrenching compromises with the West.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of Russians who believe that Washington's hidden
goal is to take advantage of their country's weakness is at a new
high, according to the Clinton administration's own survey of
Russian opinion. The recent survey reports that 81 percent of
Russians believe the United States wants to reduce Russia to a
second-rate power, up from 59 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The mistrust stems from NATO's decision to expand eastward, the
Western alliance's war with Yugoslavia and the generally harsh
indictment of Russia by Western politicians and the Western media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the West thinks it knows what Putin will do on the ABM
treaty, but it is wishful thinking,'' Georgi Arbatov, the veteran
specialist on American-Russian relations, said about the arms
control treaty. ``We really don't know what Putin has in mind. The
attitude in Russia is against building of antimissile defenses.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also Chechnya. The brutal war there has been
temporarily pushed out of the news by the Russian election, but it
is still raging.
</P>
<P>
   The West has denounced the indiscriminate attacks against
civilians there but has been careful not to link the issue with the
question of IMF assistance or other policy objectives. And while
Washington and Moscow both appear to be hoping that the war will
quiet down so that they can do business on other items on their
agenda, nobody can guarantee that it will.
</P>
<P>
   New reports of human rights abuses would dampen the
administration's enthusiasm for a headline-making summit or
high-level meetings with Putin, even if progress was made on
Washington's arms control agenda.
</P>
<P>
   And even with the best of intentions, a strategic alliance
between the United States and Russia remains a remote possibility.
The 47-year-old Putin is not only likely to re-energize relations
with the West; he is likely to intensify diplomacy on other fronts,
including former Soviet republics, Iran and China.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials are also well aware of Putin's
talent for telling his audience what it wants to hear. And some
take his talk of Russia's fondness for the West's mentality and
values with a large grain of salt. Just imagine, they say, what
Putin will say about the United States when he meets with the
Chinese.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
