<SLUG> BC-CAR-BRISTOL-LEDE0327-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wallace relieved to hit 50
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRISTOL, Tenn. _ OK, it's officially spring: Rusty Wallace has
won a race at Bristol Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   This one is a career milestone. Wallace earned career win No. 50
in the Food City 500 by outfighting the field in the No. 2 Ford
Taurus and avoiding calamities that brought out 11 cautions for 76
laps.
</P>
<P>
   He beat surprising Johnny Benson in the No. 10 Pontiac by a
comfortable 2.622 seconds for the $87,585 prize.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace becomes the 10th NASCAR driver in history with at least
50 victories.
</P>
<P>
   He had been stuck on 49 for 32 races. His last win was here,
last April. His first win was April 6, 1986 at Bristol. Eight of
his 50 wins have come at Bristol, six in the spring race.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, he admitted No. 50 had become an obsession. It's why he
tested here this year for the first time in four years. ``I felt
like an addict: I've got to have it, I've got to have it,'' Wallace
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put a really big bull's-eye (on the calendar) right on this
race track and I told my guys, `this is ridiculous now. I've won
all my races at Bristol and Richmond and Martinsville and road
courses. I've got four car dealerships right down the street.
That's the site of my very first win. There are 147,000 people in
the grandstand and it's the number one most exciting track on the
circuit.''
</P>
<P>
   He was even inspired to name the new car he had built for this
track ``Bristol.'' He leaned heavily on his crew Sunday. But first
he had to receive some major gifts while biding his time. First,
Dale Earnhardt's fast Chevrolet was eliminated when it clipped the
wrecked car of Kenny Irwin as it slid down from the wall at turn 4
nearly halfway into the 500 laps. Then Jeff Gordon, who led for 225
laps, had his car damaged when he ran into a loose tire from the
car of Steve Park.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace overtook teammate Jeremy Mayfield over the last 100 laps
and weathered a couple more weird adventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the radio and I said, `Don't let this one get screwed
up. I want it,' '' Wallace said. ``(Crew chief) Robin (Pemberton)
was really making sure everybody was doing their job. We had a
lugnut fall off one time and I got on them about that. Then the
next time we had a heck of a fast stop going and some photographer
(was standing) on Bill Wilburn's air hose and we had a bad stop. I
think that guy is still in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
