<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-CYBER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOES THIS MEAN OSCAR GAMBLE IS NOW AVAILABLE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Having convinced itself that fantasy leagues are
not a form of gambling, and seizing an opportunity to make a little
cash on the side, Major League Baseball's official Web site has
established a faux paus league of its own this season for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Official Fantasy Baseball'' game (mlb.commissioner.com) at
the MLB site (www.majorleaguebaseball.com) follows the usual
routine: Fans submit a draft list, set an opening-day roster, make
free-agent acquisitions and trade with other league owners.
</P>
<P>
   All for $19.95 a pop.
</P>
<P>
   Every league winner gets an official baseball, with other prizes
including a trip to the 2000 World Series, regular-season tickets
and shopping on the site's store.
</P>
<P>
   For baseball to come around after years of resistance to this
concept is somewhat amusing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been thinking about it for a number of years, and with
all the historical and cultural weight these carry, we have to be
careful about it,'' said Alex Kam, the site's VP/director of new
media.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concerns of gambling aren't something we have now because
it is so much a part of the game's fabric. They're everywhere and a
great way for fans to follow players.
</P>
<P>
   ``All in all, it's a step in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Sportsline.com is listed as the official ``powered by'' site for
this game. It's all a copyright of Major League Baseball
Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first major sports league to offer a fantasy
version on its site. The NBA's official cyberhome (nba.com) has a
game called ``Virtual GM'' that carries no entry fee and has grand
prize of $750 worth of NBA merchandise. The site also has a link to
ESPN.com's family of fantasy games for every major sport.
</P>
<P>
   --The Angels, with the help of ACSSports.com, have juiced up
their Web site (www.angelsbaseball.com) with more updated
statistical information, audio archives of Angels highlights in
history narrated by Dick Enberg, and a daily diary by pitcher Brian
Cooper, who is trying to avoid being shipped back to Triple-A
Vancouver.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
