<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-REFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE TO UNVEIL CAMPAIGN FINANCE PLAN
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore, acknowledging himself to be
an ``imperfect messenger'' on the subject of campaign finance,
plans to propose a major change in federal campaign financing on
Monday and will pledge to make the overhaul of the system his top
domestic legislative priority.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's proposal calls for establishing an endowment fund from
donations by individuals, corporations and labor unions, among
others, to raise $7.1 billion over seven years, according to
briefing papers provided by his campaign. The interest from the
fund would be used to pay for the general election campaigns,
starting in 2008, of candidates for the House and Senate, but only
if they did not accept money from any other source.
</P>
<P>
   Gore advisers say the amount of money would be based on a
combination of factors, including the average cost of previous
House and Senate elections, and for Senate races, population and
media accessibility in each state.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the endowment plan would not include presidential
campaigns; general elections are already financed partly by
taxpayers through the federal tax check-off system.
</P>
<P>
   Most immediately, Gore would push for passage of the
long-debated McCain-Feingold legislation that would ban the large,
unregulated contributions known as soft money.
</P>
<P>
   He would then appoint a board of trustees, which would have to
be confirmed by the Senate, and over the next seven years the
trustees would raise the money and manage the endowment fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you elect me as your president,'' Gore will say in remarks
prepared for delivery on Monday, ``the McCain-Feingold bill will be
the first domestic legislation I send to the Congress on my first
day in office.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the presumed Republican
presidential nominee, immediately denounced Gore's proposal. In a
statement on Sunday night, he called it ``a government takeover
that replaces individual spending decisions with decisions made by
an unelected government committee.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who opposes the public financing of elections, also took a
shot at Gore's credibility on this issue. ``Any promise to reform
our campaign finance system will ring hollow unless it's grounded
in credibility, credibility based on consistency, integrity and
disclosure,'' his statement said.
</P>
<P>
   While the concept of a trust or fund for federal campaigns has
been discussed for some time, Gore would add some incentives to
attract contributors to the fund.
</P>
<P>
   The incentive for corporations, labor unions and other campaign
contributors to give to the fund would be a 100 percent tax
deduction for their donations. The estimated cost to taxpayers of
these deductions would be $2.13 billion over seven years. The Gore
plan relies heavily on broadcasters' donating air time _ five
minutes a night for the 30 nights immediately preceding an election
_ to reduce the overall cost of a campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Even if contributors gave to the fund, they could still pay for
issue-related commercials for a candidate under the umbrella of
independent expenditures. But Gore's proposal would discourage
commercial broadcasters from accepting these advertisements. For
each second that a commercial runs for one candidate, the station
would have to give matching free air time to both candidates in the
race as a requirement of keeping its broadcast license.
</P>
<P>
   If the fund does not raise the necessary $7.1 billion, the onus
would fall on broadcasters to provide free television and radio
time, as measured in ratings points, to the candidates to make up
the shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   The reach of Gore's proposal reflects both the extent to which
he believes special-interest money has corrupted the system and the
extent to which he hopes to cast himself as a legitimate voice of
reform. Those who know him well say he is still smarting from the
smudge that his fund-raising practices in 1996 brought to his Boy
Scout image, and his campaign hopes that this proposal and his
acknowledgment of his flaws will help inoculate him in November.
</P>
<P>
   Gore plans to announce his proposal on a campaign trip to
Milwaukee. There, he is to be joined by Sen. Russell Feingold, the
Wisconsin Democrat who, along with Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., has
been in the vanguard of the movement to revamp the campaign finance
system to rid it of the corrupting influence of special-interest
donors. Feingold is to endorse Gore's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Neither McCain nor Feingold could be reached on Sunday for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his proposal, Gore plans to tell his audience, at
Marquette University, that his No. 1 legislative priority is to
pass the McCain-Feingold proposal to soft money.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks prepared for delivery, Gore also acknowledges that he
is perhaps an unlikely vessel for reform. ``I understand the doubts
about whether I personally am serious on campaign reform,'' the
prepared remarks say. He goes on to say that in 1996 both Democrats
and Republicans ``engaged in fund-raising that pushed the system to
the breaking point and fueled further cynicism.''
</P>
<P>
   He adds: ``I've got the scars to prove it. And I know I may be
an imperfect messenger for this cause. But the real wounds will be
to our democracy itself unless we address this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   An advocate for overhauling the system, Fred Wertheimer,
president of Democracy 21, a nonpartisan group devoted to public
campaign financing, praised Gore's proposal as ``very creative and
very promising.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These are sweeping, broad-based reform proposals and meet the
test of real, fundamental campaign finance reform,'' Wertheimer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wertheimer said, ``The single most important step that
Vice President Gore can take is laying out a detailed operational
plan on what he would immediately do if elected to make this
happen. Spelling out a detailed plan on how he would overcome
Washington's entrenched resistance to campaign finance reform is
the key to his building credibility on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said voters might be skeptical of Mr. Gore's proposal
not just because of his own history in ``pushing the limits,'' as
Gore has acknowledged, but because he and Bill Clinton ran in 1992
on a promise of fixing the campaign system and then ``walked away''
from it. Wertheimer said that Gore needed to start ``building a
national coalition, use the bully pulpit and involve the American
people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-00 2055EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
