<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBERTY-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IDT SAYS LIBERTY MEDIA WILL BUY STAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Exclusive)  
(lh) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maintaining its drive into the telecommunications industry, John
C. Malone's Liberty Media Group has agreed to invest about $130
million for a stake of almost 10 percent in the IDT Corp., the
communications carrier based in Hackensack, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The companies plan to announce their deal Monday, said Howard S.
Jonas, IDT's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, Liberty will buy almost 10 percent of IDT for
$34.50 a share. On Friday, shares of IDT closed at $31.9375, giving
the company a market value of almost $1.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty's initial investment will be in IDT common stock, but
Jonas said that IDT would have an option in the future to convert
Liberty's stake into shares with subordinate voting rights. Liberty
will be invited to take a seat on IDT's board, Jonas added.
</P>
<P>
   Until AT&AMP;T's acquisition of Tele-Communications Inc. last year,
Liberty was TCI's television programming unit. It still trades as
an AT&AMP;T tracking stock.
</P>
<P>
   But AT&AMP;T holds no financial interest in Liberty, and while
Liberty's far-flung investments are mostly in media and television
programming, over the last year the company has shown interest in
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   Malone, TCI's former chairman, who still controls Liberty, has
proved to be a prescient investor, and as digital technology speeds
the convergence of media and communications businesses, Malone is
positioning himself to profit yet again.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, Liberty agreed to acquire the Associated Group for
about $2.8 billion. Among its other interests, Associated was the
biggest shareholder in Teligent Inc., the fast-growing wireless
communications company run by Alex J. Mandl, a former president of
AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Now Liberty is investing in IDT, a scrappy communications
carrier that regularly takes a leading role in creating new
communications niches.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, Jonas and IDT essentially invented the so-called
callback market, which allowed people in many foreign countries to
reduce their rates for international calls by routing the calls
through the United States.
</P>
<P>
   As nations around the world reduced regulations and rates on
international calls, the American-based callback market stagnated.
So a few years ago, IDT became one of the first companies to begin
transmitting phone calls using Internet technology, which can be
cheaper and more efficient than traditional telephone systems.
IDT's Internet calling subsidiary, Net2Phone, now has a market
value of $2.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, IDT has started a Spanish-language Internet
service provider and has begun marketing wireless phones that allow
users to avoid charges for incoming calls.
</P>
<P>
   For IDT, an investment from Liberty brings not only cash but
also potential marketing, distribution and product development
relationships with some of the companies in Liberty's portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Jonas said Sunday that IDT's Spanish-language
Internet company could surely find profitable common cause with
Telemundo, the big Spanish-language television network in which
Liberty owns a 50 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malone is like my idol,'' Jonas said Sunday. ``He's probably
the most successful investor in the country, and he has the most
media assets probably of anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonas gave much of the credit for negotiating the deal to Morris
Smith, a former manager of Fidelity Investments' Magellan fund, who
is now IDT's primary financial adviser.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-00 2056EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
