<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8559 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-26 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR SPREWELL, A YEAR HAS MADE A DIFFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ Latrell Sprewell was laughing Sunday morning,
throwing up crazy shots from halfcourt with Allan Houston after a
light practice at the Rose Garden. The Knicks are always accused of
being so serious and corporate, yet here were their star players
caught up in a shooting game, enjoying their first full day of a
seminal Western Conference road trip.
</P>
<P>
   In more chaotic times, this franchise went West and waited for
calamity to unfold. As for the Knicks' coaches from the mid-1990s
until last season, either Don Nelson was on the firing line or Jeff
Van Gundy was trying to keep his team from imploding.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, it's about defining how we're going to play going
into the playoffs,'' Van Gundy said before the Knicks met the Trail
Blazers Sunday night. ``Last year, that was about surviving.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to recognize Sprewell and the Knicks from last March,
when they went 1-2 during an abbreviated Western swing because of
the lockout, and he was pouting over his sixth-man role and
wondering when Van Gundy would understand what he was about.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell's ability to put his team before himself is one of the
primary reasons the Knicks have a decent shot of returning to the
finals.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just his slashing, scoring and passing. Less than two
weeks ago, his nasty demeanor on the floor inspired the Knicks to
victory in Philadelphia. When Sprewell scowls and grows intense,
the Knicks scowl and grow intense. He is often automatic from the
free-throw line and has developed one of the best left hands in the
game for a right-handed player.
</P>
<P>
   Ambidextrous and sometimes awesome, he is also happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like this is the team I belong on and I feel
comfortable with it,'' he said Sunday. ``I think we've just grown
together. We are definitely more familiar with one another and more
familiar with what we're doing on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   With five mostly grueling games over the next eight days,
anything can happen. But there is a serene quality to these Knicks
now, a feeling that nothing will ruffle them for too long because
they have been through some very difficult times together.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell's '99 Road Trip Out West: he lost his dribble against
Sacramento in the final seconds and inexplicably fouled Jason
Williams, who made the game-clinching free throw; in Phoenix, he
said, ``It's just one of those stats'' when asked how he felt about
his teams being a combined 7-22 with him in the lineup over the
previous two seasons; in Los Angeles, Van Gundy confronted him
after practice, and Sprewell ducked out on reporters who wanted to
ask about that meeting. With the Knicks in disarray, Sprewell
seemed not to care or fit in.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy remembered that meeting, and now understands that he,
too, misread Sprewell's mannerisms and words. ``I think what he
wanted to basically convey was, it wasn't all his fault they lost
out there,'' he said. ``Now, all he talks about is winning. I don't
think he's a stat guy at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy added: ``The other thing I'm impressed with Latrell
about: he never resents other guys' shooting, other guys' playing.
Some of the guys on our team, even though they knew Patrick was
going to be good for our team coming back, they were resentful of
what he might take away from them. Latrell was just the opposite.
He always talked about how good it would be for him and everybody
to have Patrick back.''
</P>
<P>
   How a guy perceived to be a chucker ended up as the Knicks' most
unselfish player is pretty amazing.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell recalls little from that trip, except, ``We were
fighting just to get in, I remember that.'' He also did not see any
grand significance behind returning to Portland for the first time
since February 1998. For more than a week, Sprewell rose before 8
a.m., dressed nattily and attended his arbitration hearing after
assaulting his coach at Golden State, P.J. Carlesimo, which
resulted in a one-year suspension. In some ways, Portland is where
Sprewell's transformation began.
</P>
<P>
   After all the testimony, the arbitrator, John D. Feerick, the
dean of Fordham Law School, sharply reduced Sprewell's suspension
and reinstated his contract. Sprewell began the journey, going from
Most Vilified Sports Figure in America _ sandwiched between Roberto
Alomar and John Rocker _ to Madison Square Garden Fan Favorite in
less than a year.
</P>
<P>
   His ascension continued Sunday night at the Rose Garden. He does
not have to answer any more questions about playing on a losing
team or sit with Van Gundy on a vacant stairwell at Pauley Pavilion
and explain himself. He has done all the hard work. These days,
Latrell Sprewell no longer counts himself among his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it's a good challenge for this team,'' he said
when asked about the road trip. ``If we can finish this road trip
strong, we'll prove a lot of things to a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   He spoke as if he and the Knicks had not proved a lot. Funny,
no? Sometimes you come so far so fast, you forget where you were a
year ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
