</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-WISCONSIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WISCONSIN MADE GRADE SLOWLY, BUT SURELY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By TOM SPOUSTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. _ Dick Bennett has spent his 35-year career
coaching basketball in Wisconsin, so he always has felt a personal
stake in his players' sweat and his schools' success. As he
searched the front rows of the Pit for family members after the
Badgers' 64-60 victory over Purdue on Saturday night for a berth in
the Final Four, his emotions were especially poignant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Way to go, Dad!'' Bennett's daughter, Amy Stiever, yelled when
she caught his eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Way to go, Grandpa!'' she added for her young son, Andrew,
whom she held in her arms.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett waved as the celebration swirled around him. He cried as
he cut down the nets from the West Regional championship game. He
had cried during the pregame speech to his team. Bennett wears his
love of Wisconsin for all to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the pregame speech, he just broke down,'' said the
Badgers assistant coach, Brad Soderberg. ``Tears were running down
his face. I think it finally dawned on him that what he has been
building for 35 years was about to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   In his sixth season, Bennett has guided the Badgers (22-13) to
their first Final Four appearance since 1941, doing so with one
senior and four junior starters. None of them were voted to the
first, second or third all-Big Ten teams this season.
</P>
<P>
   Still, eighth-seeded Wisconsin jelled late in the season and
became the lowest-seeded team to reach the Final Four since No. 11
Louisiana State in 1986. It is the first eighth-seeded team to
advance this far in the National Collegiate Athletic Association
men's tournament since Villanova in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that we were worthy of respect until we finished
so strong,'' Bennett said. ``We've gotten our share. People have
been fair to us. I have no complaints.''
</P>
<P>
   The Badgers have won 10 of their last 13 games, although the
three losses were to Michigan State, their opponent in the national
semifinals next Saturday in Indianapolis. To get there, the Badgers
left four NCAA tournament opponents gasping for air, and not
because the games were played at high altitudes. Instead of defense
by intimidation, Wisconsin plays defense by frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Fresno State Coach Jerry Tarkanian said his team just died
suddenly. Arizona, seeded No. 1 in the West Regional, was
dumbfounded while scoring a season-low 23 points in the first half.
Louisiana State players talked of being stripped of their
competitive intensity. Purdue hit only 39.6 percent of its shots
and had stretches of seven minutes and six minutes without a field
goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just determination,'' said guard Mike Kelley, Wisconsin's
senior starter. ``It's all five of us being in the gaps. It just
starts off and gets going and going. We just chase you down until
you don't want to win anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Purdue, Jon Bryant stunned the Boilermakers by making
five of nine shots from 3-point range, including his first three
attempts, in the first half. He finished with 18 points, and Andy
Kowske had 14 points and 8 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Bryant, a junior guard who made 18 of 36 shots from long
range in the tournament, symbolizes the tenacious player that fits
Bennett's coaching style. While at Division II St. Cloud State in
Minnesota, Bryant hounded Bennett on the phone for a chance to play
for the Badgers, and he transferred to Wisconsin without a
guarantee of a scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``He demands the best out of everybody,'' Bryant said of
Bennett. ``He really believes if you do that, if you believe in the
system and good defense, it'll pay off.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said: ``Wisconsin is not a place where a lot of big-time
recruiters come. It's not a gold mine for talent. But if you can
find the Kelleys and the Kowskes and the Bryants, you will never be
embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett has won at every level, coaching high school teams for
11 years, at Wisconsin-Stevens Point for nine and at
Wisconsin-Green Bay for 10, before taking over the Badgers in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Although his teams were successful, it was Bennett's
disciplined, slow-paced system that caught attention. Two seasons
ago, a Sports Illustrated poll asked 115 college coaches, ``If you
could go to one clinic, whose would it be?'' Bennett tied for third
with Indiana's Bob Knight behind Duke's Mike Krzyzewski and Utah's
Rick Majerus.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of fans are addicted to highlight reels,'' Kelley said.
``It's the basketball purist who appreciates us. It's not pretty,
but Coach Bennett's system works.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
