<SLUG> BC-GLF-TPC-ROUND4-0327-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delay no help to Sutton
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ Advantage, Tiger Woods?
</P>
<P>
   Not really. You can't say that when Woods is three shots down to
Hal Sutton in the rain-delayed final round of The Players
Championship, which will resume at 9 a.m. today with seven holes to
play.
</P>
<P>
   You can't even say it because Woods, with 10 wins in his past 16
PGA Tour events, overcame a seven-shot deficit with seven holes to
play to win at Pebble Beach in January.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing is certain. A day to regroup can do nothing but
help Woods, who Sunday seemed on his way to being defeated by the
consistent Sutton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, things aren't going exactly the way I wanted, but
I'm right there and I've got a good chance of winning right now,''
Woods said. ``Now the conditions are going to be a little different
_ tomorrow, fresh start.''
</P>
<P>
   With a comment perhaps directed at Sutton's triple-bogey 6 at
the island green 17th Saturday, Woods said, ``We'll see what
happens. There's a lot of water to be played over.''
</P>
<P>
   The tournament was halted by a thunderstorm late Sunday
afternoon with 20 players yet to finish. Woods is on the front of
the 12th green, facing a putt of about 40 feet. Sutton, who won the
1983 Players Championship on a Monday finish, has an 82-yard sand
wedge awaiting to the 12th green.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I would have liked to have kept playing,'' said
Sutton, who's at 10-under par. ``But it was a dangerous (lightning)
situation. I like living better than I do finishing the golf
tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the psychological change with today's continuation, Sutton
admitted, ``I felt like we were familiar with what everything was
doing at the time _ the firmness of the greens, the speed of the
greens. We're going to have to come out and regroup and think about
other things tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it's clearly a two-man race now _ the four players on
the course tied for third are three shots behind Woods _ Sutton
labeled the TPC at Sawgrass as his true opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a Tiger Woods-Hal Sutton duel,'' Sutton said.
``You can make it out to be what you want it to be. But the fact
is, I'm playing the golf course out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
