<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8565 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-NETS-NUGGETS-NYT &LR;      03-26 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-NUGGETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NETS SQUANDER A BIG LEAD, AND PROBABLY A PLAYOFF BERTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ A Nets' season laden with
disappointment, misfortune and horrible play at the most crucial
times hit the point of near hopelessness Sunday at the Continental
Arena. With their scant playoff chances demanding a victory, the
Nets fell into a fourth-quarter haze and surrendered an 18-point
lead with less than 9 minutes to play in losing to the lowly Denver
Nuggets.
</P>
<P>
   Playing without its star player, Antonio McDyess, the Nuggets,
whose 28-42 record long ago eliminated them from Western Conference
playoff contention, displayed more heart and more desire than the
Nets. When it would have been natural for the going-nowhere Nuggets
to coast through the closing minutes and the still-alive Nets to
sprint through the finish, the Nets all but quit on themselves,
their coach and their postseason aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   Outscored by 31-11 over the final 8 minutes 6 seconds, the Nets
lost, 112-110, before 15,825 stunned fans when the former Net,
Chris Gatling, caught a rebound and put in a 5-footer all in one
motion with 6.5 seconds remaining. Terrible all season long in
their late-game execution, the Nets stayed the course on the final
play when Scott Burrell threw an inbounds pass off of Keon Clark's
leg, sending the ball rolling toward the Nets bench as the final
seconds ticked away.
</P>
<P>
   The incomprehensible loss was the eighth time the Nets (29-40)
have lost a game they led by more than 10 points, and it left them
with only the faintest possibility of qualifying for the Eastern
Conference playoffs. With 13 games remaining, they are five games
behind the Orlando Magic, which holds the eighth and final spot
with a 35-36 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a loss, as I just told the players, that there is no
defending,'' Nets Coach Don Casey said. ``It was terrible play at
critical times. They kept their heads up, and we were moping. We
had guys moping for whatever the reason. I don't really know at
this time. Maybe it's the pressure or whatever, but this was a
killer game and we did not respond to it. We got very cool with the
lead when it was time to do things and I don't have an answer for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was a microcosm of the Nets' forgettable season in
which they lost 13 of their first 15 games. They rebounded to
overcome the awful start and gave themselves a chance to make the
playoffs, and now have folded with the pressure on. Just two games
behind Orlando after upsetting Toronto on Tuesday, the Nets have
lost their last three games, all of which included inexplicable
periods of sluggishness.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday afternoon, knowing that Orlando had beaten Miami by 25
points, the Nets somehow began as if uninterested. Lethargic and
perhaps indulging in self pity after controversial officiating
contributed to Friday's 1-point overtime loss to Minnesota, the
Nets fell behind by 31-13 eight minutes into the game. Nick Van
Exel, whom Stephon Marbury held to just 2 points in a Nets victory
on March 1, shot with a vengeance, hitting 6 of 7 attempts in
scoring 14 first-quarter points.
</P>
<P>
   Van Exel would continue to outplay Marbury (16 points, 11
assists, 5 of 16 shooting) throughout and finish with 28 points and
12 assists. Raef LaFrentz did the same number on Keith Van Horn,
opening the game with 12 points and 7 rebounds in the first
quarter. He finished with 22 points and 18 rebounds as one of four
Nuggets to score 20 or more points. Gatling had 20 points and 7
rebounds, and rookie James Posey scored 21.
</P>
<P>
   McDyess, who was limited to just 14 minutes because of a
sprained left ankle, contributed just 4 points and 4 rebounds
before leaving for good in the third quarter. Casey inserted his
reserves, the vaunted ``Rottweilers,'' and they lived up to their
billing, rallying the Nets to pull within 60-56 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Newman, who socred 20 points to share team honors with
Van Horn, led the bench unit with 13 points in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   The starters picked up the momentum and, behind 11 points from
Kerry Kittles, broke it open, going ahead by 85-75 late in the
third quarter. Burrell hit two quick 3-pointers early in the fourth
and then put the Nets ahead by 99-81 with 8:36 left with a
21-footer.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the Nets began to cruise. ``We started to coast,''
Marbury said. ``We got relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nuggets caught their attention by draining three straight
3-pointers in 58 seconds to cut a 101-86 deficit to 101-95 with
5:14 to play. Casey called a timeout, but by then Denver, which
made 6 of 11 3-pointers in the fourth, was rolling. The Nets lead
disappeared quickly, with Posey putting the Nuggets up, 107-106, on
a 3-pointer with 2:10 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets regained the lead on two free throws by Marbury, but
Gatling converted a 3-point play. Burrell tied at 110-110 with a
tip-in with 6 seconds left. The Nuggets then inbounded the ball to
Gatling, who missed a shot off the glass before catching George
McCloud's tap in midair and scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gatling told us before the game that he was the mayor of East
Rutherford, or wherever we are, so I figured the mayor ought to
take the last shot,'' Denver Coach Dan Issel said.
</P>
<P>
   Gatling, an Irvington, N.J., native, was more than happy to bury
his former team's playoff hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's great,'' Gatling said. ``Anything I can do to help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
