<HEADER>
A8567 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-GLF-TPC-NYT &LR;      03-26 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TPC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUTTON OUTDUELS WOODS BEFORE RAIN GETS IN THE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ Hal Sutton's biggest problem Sunday
was not Tiger Woods. It was the weather.
</P>
<P>
   Lightning, followed by heavy rain, forced the final round of the
Players Championship to be suspended until Monday at 9 a.m.
Eastern, with Sutton holding a three-stroke lead over Woods through
11 holes. Sutton was 10 under par, Woods was 7 under, while five
players were tied at 4 under par, all stuck in a holding pattern
until play resumes.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension was a potentially bad break for Sutton, who felt
like a boxer poised to take charge of a fight, only to hear the
bell. Though Woods has plenty of time to make another dramatic
comeback, Sutton had the momentum when play was halted.
</P>
<P>
   No. 10 was a turning point: Sutton made a 30-foot putt for
birdie from the fringe of the green, then Woods missed a 6-foot
attempt for birdie. Instead of gaining a stroke at the hole, Woods
lost another stroke, leaving him three behind with seven holes to
play and with Sutton playing steady golf.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price was the only player at four under par who finished.
The others at four under were Jeff Maggert (through 17 holes),
Colin Montgomerie (14 holes), Lee Janzen (13 holes), and Tom Lehman
(12 holes.
</P>
<P>
   The horn blew at 4:45 p.m. local (Eastern) time as Sutton stood
in the middle of the 12th fairway with a perplexed look on his
face.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton could be on the verge of capturing a prestigious
tournament, the biggest first-place check in golf ($1.08 million),
and a head-to-head victory over Woods. However, instead of
celebrating tonight as he had hoped, Sutton was forced to sleep
with the lead, knowing there would be seven difficult holes left to
finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I would have liked to have kept playing, but it was
a dangerous situation, good that they called it,'' said Sutton, who
won the Players Championship in 1983 on a Monday after a rain
delay. ``Everything was going the way I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods will have catching up to do, after an abbreviated round in
which he was not at his best. Starting the day one stroke behind
Sutton, Woods pulled even with a birdie on the first hole, but that
was his only birdie of the day, and he was one over par through 11
holes. Woods made back-to-back bogeys at Nos. 3 and 4 to fall two
strokes behind.
</P>
<P>
   At the par-3 No. 3, Woods hit a poor tee shot into a bunker,
then failed to get up and down. At the par-4 No. 4, Woods missed
the green long on his second shot, then flubbed a chip shot from
the green when his ball was smothered by the deep grass. The chip
shot traveled only a few feet, landing on the fringe of the green
as the crowd groaned. Woods then missed a 20-foot chip shot for
par, forcing him to tap-in for bogey. Those mistakes, capped by his
missed putt at No. 11, left Woods needing a Monday rally.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he was far from despondent. After all, Woods has come back
on a Monday before, most spectacularly at Pebble Beach last month,
when he rallied from a seven-stroke deficit with seven holes to
play. And at the T.P.C. at Sawgrass, which presents one of golf's
most challenging finishes, including the treacherous island green
at No. 17, almost anything can happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, things aren't going exactly the way I wanted,''
said Woods, smiling. ``But I've got a pretty good chance of
winning. There is a lot of water to be played over. If there is any
kind of golf course you want to play when you are behind, it is one
of these, with a lot of water and a lot of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had an extra lucky red shirt for Monday, Woods said.
``I do, actually. Or a lot of cologne.''
</P>
<P>
   When play resumes, Sutton will have an approach shot from 82
yards at the par-4 No. 12, while Woods was already on the green in
two shots, but facing a difficult putt from 40 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton, who played par golf for the first 10 holes before making
his key birdie at No. 11, was the steadier player Sunday, and he
could have led by more if he had not missed four birdie putts from
12 feet or less on his first four holes. Sutton also made a crucial
par save at the par-4 No. 8, after hitting his second shot into a
bunker. Facing a difficult stance on a hill, squatting low over his
ball, Sutton hit a beautiful bunker shot with spin that landed
softly on the green, 10 feet past the hole. Then Sutton completed
the save by making the putt, pumping his fist as the ball
disappeared into the cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was big,'' Sutton said of his bunker shot. ``If I hadn't
gotten that up and down, that would have given him momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton's birdie putt at No. 11 was an unexpected bonus, coming
after a chip shot that rolled back toward him after failing to
clear a mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't ready for that,'' Sutton said of making his putt at
No. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Neither was Woods, who missed his 6-footer after the roar from
the crowd subsided. ``Making that putt in front of him makes that
putt a whole lot harder,'' Sutton said.
</P>
<P>
   So on Monday, Sutton hoped to finish what he started.
</P>
<P>
   ``We finished on Monday the year I won,'' Sutton said. ``I don't
know if that has anything to do with anything. But it was nice to
think about.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
