<SLUG> BC-POPE-ART-1200(2TAKES)-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE GOES TO WESTERN WALL ON LAST DAY OF HOLY LAND TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to move up 4th graf of 2nd take to 6th graf of 1st take, with
insert. Inserts middle name for Cardinal Maida. Light rewrite of
lede.)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG and ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ With 86 shuffling steps, Pope John Paul II on Sunday
approached the Western Wall, reached out a trembling hand to touch
its cool stone, and as is the custom of Jewish visitors, tucked
into a crevice a heartfelt note to God. Then he made a fluid sign
of the cross at the most sacred site in Judaism, and a hush
carpeted the plaza.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's note bore the message of reconciliation that has been
the public theme of his six-day personal pilgrimage, which
concluded peacefully Sunday as he moved from the Al-Aqsa Mosque to
the wall and then to the Church of the Holy Sepulcher. Traveling in
an armored jeeplike vehicle with heavy security, he linked with his
presence the nerve centers of the three Abrahamic faiths that
consider Jerusalem holy and reluctantly share the walled Old City
in its heart.
</P>
<P>
   But the interfaith link was a tenuous one. And it wavered even
before the pope flew off Sunday evening, visibly moved by his
journey along Jesus' footsteps, though the path traversed a Holy
Land mined with religious and political sensitivities. Having made
a mark on a place that does not impress easily, the pope left
behind the tensions _ and an open white sheet of paper that stood
out among the hundreds of folded slips wedged into the Western
Wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``God of our fathers, you chose Abraham and his descendants to
bring your name to the nations,'' said the note, in English, which
was later moved to the Holocaust museum to be preserved. ``We are
deeply saddened by the behavior of those who in the course of
history have caused these children of yours to suffer. And asking
your forgiveness, we wish to commit ourselves to genuine
brotherhood with the people of the covenant. Jerusalem, 26.3.2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joannes Paulus II.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope's message created a document for Israel. It was taken
from his prayer at a Mass this month at St. Peter's Basilica in
which the pope apologized for the historic sins of the Roman
Catholic Church. ``A 2,000-year-old account is now closed!'' said
Binyamin Ben- Eliezer, the Communications Minister.
</P>
<P>
   Hovering above the Old City, in the blue sky of a brilliant
Sunday, was a red, white, green and black Palestinian flag,
accompanied by scores of similarly colored balloons. The flag
disappeared and reappeared to flutter above the pope as his white
jeep bumped along the Via Dolorosa to the Church of the Holy
Sepulcher.
</P>
<P>
   From Jerusalem to Bethlehem to Nazareth and back, the pope, 79
and frail, has kept up a grueling schedule during the long-awaited
trip that many describe as an apex of his 21-year papacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is unsteady on his feet and he appears weak, but this has
probably been the strongest moment of his pontificate,'' Cardinal
Adam Joseph Maida of Detroit, a friend of the pope's, said Sunday
as the visit was drawing to a close.
</P>
<P>
   Many Israelis and Palestinians have been touched by the pope's
determination and balanced compassion as he progressed on his cane,
obviously with great physical difficulty, from place to place and
people to people.
</P>
<P>
   As they waited for the pope to board an El Al plane called
Jerusalem, Vatican officials declared the trip a success because
the pope acted and spoke from genuine, deep-seated convictions.
``The pope told everyone the truth without humiliating anyone,''
said Joaquin Navarro-Vals, the Vatican spokesman. ``He said what he
truly felt, and this was respected.''
</P>
<P>
   Vatican officials, who began the trip anxious about their
relationship with Israel, left feeling a stronger bond. They were
impressed by Prime Minister Ehud Barak, an official said _ by what
they considered the gracious and uplifting speech he gave at the
Holocaust memorial and by the way his government turned the other
cheek to Palestinian provocations.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the Palestinians, whose cause they support,
somewhat disappointed them by failing to take advantage of the
worldwide platform they were afforded by the pope's visit. Vatican
officials were unnerved by the outbreak of violence among
Palestinians after the pope left a refugee camp on Wednesday and by
the strident political advocacy of Islamic clerics, one of whom
wagged his finger in the pope's face Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's itinerary, with its many sensitive stops, had the
potential to sabotage a successful trip in which the pope has
remained above the fray.
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem _ its sanctity, its sovereignty and its complexity _
moved front and center, and the pope's first stop was at the
Al-Aqsa mosque, the domain of the mufti, the city's chief Islamic
cleric.
</P>
<P>
   The pope inched out of the car onto a three-step riser covered
with worn carpeting. He followed other carpets, stamping down bumps
with his cane, into a small stone building beside the Dome of the
Rock. Before he entered, Muhammad Said Al Jamal, an elderly,
bearded imam, pressed a letter into the pope's hands and preached
to him, quite heatedly, about Palestinian rights.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the meeting, the pope did not know that the mufti,
Sheik Ikrima Sabri, had given several interviews over the weekend
filled with incendiary hostility toward Israel that minimized the
enormity of the Holocaust, said Navarro-Valls.
</P>
<P>
   The pope had hoped to have a conversation with the Muslim
leaders. Instead, the mufti read a speech in Arabic, which was then
translated into English by an assistant. Pointing out the window at
the gilded Dome, the mufti instructed the pope that Jerusalem is
``eternally bonded to Islam.'' He also cataloged grievances about
the Israelis, ending with a demand that the pope ``stand by justice
in order to end the Israeli occupation of Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope responded that he considered Jerusalem ``a part of the
common patrimony'' of Christianity, Islam and Judaism _ ``the holy
city par excellence.'' He did not verbally endorse Palestinian
claims to Jerusalem, but Palestinian officials later said that the
visit itself made it clear that Jerusalem is a divided city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pope came to help us,'' said Faisal Husseini, the senior
Palestine Liberation Organization official in Jerusalem. ``We hope
that in Jerusalem, we can build two capitals in one open city.''
</P>
<P>
   As if to make the Palestinians' point about the occupation, the
Dome of the Rock compound was ringed by scores of blue-uniformed
Israeli soldiers, who clearly made the Muslims tense _ especially
those who were kept out.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after the pope left, the tension erupted, when Muslim
youths poured into the esplanade. Some shouted at the police,
``Jews, the army of Muhammad will come back.'' Others started
throwing pebbles and water, some at Husseini, accusing him of
``giving the keys of Jerusalem and Al-Aqsa to the pope.'' After
much shoving, the scuffle broke up.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, the pope had arrived at the wall, which Tzip
Zwick, 13, her braces shining in the sun, said was an affront to
the Jewish people. ``I feel that he has no right to be here,'' said
Miss Zwick, an Orthodox Jewish girl from Brooklyn, N.Y. ``This is a
special place for the Jews.'' She pointed to the women who faced
the wall with their noses pressed into prayer books and to the men
covered with fringed shawls who swayed and murmured.
</P>
<P>
   Official Israel disagreed. Rabbi Michael Melchior, an Israeli
Cabinet minister, walked the pope to the wall with a protective
hand ready to steady his gait. Earlier, the rabbi's voice had
boomed triumphantly across the plaza, calling for ``a new era in
which we commit ourselves to end the manipulation of the sanctity
of Jerusalem for political gain.'' But he also claimed Jerusalem as
the ``eternal capital'' of the Jews.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One after the other, Melchior, in Hebrew, and then the pope, in
Latin, read Psalm 122, an ode to peace in Jerusalem. Melchior said
the Jewish-Catholic reconciliation had been difficult for both
sides, ``which is why it took 52 years for this to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult for them theologically, and it's difficult for
us psychologically,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As the ceremony progressed, most of the Jewish visitors to the
wall stopped praying and watched, hemmed in by security officers.
One young man, who shouted out in Hebrew, ``Jews, Jews, my family
was killed in Europe,'' was quickly hauled away by the police. The
police detained seven Jews and three Palestinians for disrupting or
planning disruptions of the visit, Israeli radio said.
</P>
<P>
   Like everything else here, the Church of the Holy Sepulcher is
riven. Three major Christian rites and several other denominations
share it. But the strife was quieted for the day as the sects
postponed their individual services to allow the pope to celebrate
Mass in what he called ``the mother of all churches.'' It stands on
what are venerated as the sites of Jesus' crucifixion, burial and
resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   Greeted by Syrian Orthodox clergymen wearing red Fez hats,
gold-embroidered tunics and ceremonial swords, John Paul was led to
the pink slab where tradition says that Jesus was prepared for
burial. Assisted, the pope sank to his knees and kissed it, lifting
from its marble surface a face lost in reverie.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he delayed his departure from the Holy Land so that he
could return to the Holy Sepulcher to pray once more before
leaving. ``The message of the Gospel takes on flesh and blood when
you come to these places,'' Maida said. The pope is ``a mystic and
very spiritual man _ the pilgrimage has brought this out like never
before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
