<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZUBER FINALLY SEES THE LIGHT AT END OF YANKS' DEPTH CHART 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Jon Zuber turned at his locker to find
himself surrounded by reporters Sunday, and a shy smile conquered
his face before he looked down. If he had been 3 years old instead
of 30, he might have ducked behind the leg of his mother or father.
</P>
<P>
   Zuber has been hidden most of spring, buried on the Yankees'
depth chart behind Darryl Strawberry and Tim Raines when spring
training began. But Zuber, a left-handed hitting first baseman with
only 136 major league at-bats, keeps hitting _ he had three hits
and four runs batted in in a 12-5 thrashing of Minnesota here
Sunday _ and surviving rounds of roster cuts, and now he is
fighting off thoughts that he might make the opening day roster.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Yarnall, projected as the Yankees' fifth starter to start the
season, almost assuredly will not be, after another poor outing
Sunday. Short on stuff and command again, Yarnall needed 43 pitches
to get through the first inning and in three and a third innings of
work he permitted seven hits, two walks and four runs. ``He wasn't
very good,'' Yankees Manager Joe Torre said. ``He just seems
lost.''
</P>
<P>
   There may never be any significant impact from Yarnall's crisis
of confidence this spring. Ramiro Mendoza is expected to open the
season as the fifth starter, and the Yankees will not need a fifth
starter again until April 27, giving Yarnall about a month to sort
out his trouble with the Columbus Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Zuber might also be with Columbus, but he is batting .400 in 18
games and might benefit from the Yankees' struggles to find a
suitable backup catcher. They had hoped Tom Pagnozzi, formerly of
the St. Louis Cardinals, would play well enough on defense to serve
as the backup to Jorge Posada. But while Pagnozzi's hitting and
ability to throw to second base have been better than expected, he
has had more basic problems in camp, dropping pitches and flipping
the ball uncomfortably back to the pitcher after each delivery,
rather than firing it.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Turner has some big league experience and is 6 for 11
(.545) with three extra-base hits. He would not really add anything
to the Yankees' bench, however _ not power or speed _ and he is a
right-handed hitter when the Yankees are searching for a
left-handed hitter. Torre said Sunday that Pagnozzi and Turner are
running neck and neck and have both shown enough to make the team.
Without either standing out, however, the Yankees are considering
another option _ employing Jim Leyritz as the backup catcher.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz came up as a catcher and has plenty of experience, but
this would be a radical departure from the Yankees' off-season
plans: Leyritz was not even considered as a fill-in for Posada when
spring training began.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz has looked OK as a catcher this spring, which is all the
Yankees really need, with Posada likely to catch all but 25 or 30
games in the 162-game schedule. If the Yankees team Leyritz with
Andy Pettitte, a left-handed pitcher with a great pickoff move,
then Leyritz's subpar throwing arm would not be as much of a
factor.
</P>
<P>
   If Leyritz is the backup catcher, then the Yankees can use the
roster spot that would have gone to Pagnozzi or Turner and keep a
more versatile player, like the left-handed hitting Zuber. Ricky
Ledee is likely to be the every day left fielder, spelled
occasionally by the right-handed hitting Roberto Kelly or the
right-handed hitting Shane Spencer, and Spencer will be the
designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   But since the suspension of Strawberry, the Yankees really have
not had a left-handed hitter on the major league roster who might
share time as the designated hitter. That is where Zuber comes into
the picture, much to his own surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Zuber spent his first eight seasons in the Philadelphia
organization, playing parts of two seasons in the majors. He is
what is often referred to as a ``professional'' hitter _ he is
patient and puts the ball in play against all types of pitchers,
but does not hit for power. When he signed with the Yankees in
January, he admitted, he had no dreams of starting the season with
them; he hoped only that he might impress them over time and
perhaps earn a promotion during the regular season if a hole
developed.
</P>
<P>
   Zuber felt comfortable immediately once spring training began,
surprised when Bernie Williams and Derek Jeter would say hi _
``how's it going, Zubes'' _ because there had always been distinct
lines that were not crossed in the Phillies' caste system of
veterans. He was a journeyman, and journeyman did not speak with
the older players.
</P>
<P>
   But he is at ease with the Yankees. He began to chat with Don
Mattingly, the former Yankees' player who worked as a
spring-training coach this year, gleaning some advice and writing
it down on a piece of paper at home. ``Some things about hitting,''
Zuber said.
</P>
<P>
   And now he is applying his knowledge. In the first inning
Sunday, he fell behind the Twins' LaTroy Hawkins, no balls and two
strikes, fouled off a couple of pitches and ran the count to full,
before driving a ball between the outfielders in center and right;
three runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   Zuber also added a couple of singles. ``He's making a case for
himself,'' Torre said. ``He has quality at-bats, whether it's a
left-hander or a right-hander.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have other options as well. They could make a deal
to acquire another player, pick up somebody dropped by another team
in this last week of spring training. They could keep Zuber as a
left-handed complement to Spencer.
</P>
<P>
   Zuber does not want to think about it. He said that Shannon, his
wife, tries not to get too excited about the possibility of him
making the team, ``because then that would make me get excited.''
</P>
<P>
   He smiled shyly Sunday, raised his head slightly and looked at
the reporters surrounding him, hiding again. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
