<SLUG> BC-BKC-SOUTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH CAROLINA ELIMINATES TULSA AND DOUBTS FOR SHOT AT DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ There will be blue blood, after all, in the
Final Four, a regal shade of North Carolina blue. The Tar Heels
entered tournament play as a No. 8-seeded team in the middle of a
two-game losing streak with a dull 18-13 record. But now, after
tripping Tulsa, 59-55, for the South Regional crown, all is
forgiven. All is forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   This edition of Carolina basketball has won despite adversity.
It has won over the Carolina throng of fans who once saw a dreary
team suddenly, amazingly, remarkably turn into a pristine gem.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could say what I wanted to all the fans who left us and
all the media who slammed us, it would not be pretty,'' said
Carolina guard Ed Cota, a warrior who played the entire 40 minutes
before 16,731 fans in the Erwin Center and directed his team's
offense and defense, too. ``But then, to be fair, I must say even I
was kind of shocked at the way we played in our first tournament
game against Missouri. I mean, the intensity we had and the
teamwork was what had been missing all year. We built off that.''
</P>
<P>
   And the meshing continued, against Stanford and then Tennessee.
And now Tulsa. A Carolina four-game winning streak, the team's
first of the year. A season flipped inside out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry it took us so long to get going,'' Carolina Coach
Bill Guthridge said. ``But it couldn't come at a better time.''
</P>
<P>
   Terrence Newby, a Carolina senior guard, said: ``We started
getting the right people the ball at the right time against
Missouri. And then our confidence kept building from that. The
whole year Coach Guthridge said that we were learning and building
something and we'd be happy in April. We are. Teamwork. This is
what it takes to cut down the nets.''
</P>
<P>
   And Joseph Forte, the freshman Carolina guard who scored a
career-high and game-high 28 points added: ``What a relief. I
didn't want to go home.''
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina (22-13) earned its 15th Final Four appearance,
its sixth in the past 10 years and its third in the past four
seasons. Guthridge, 80-27 at Carolina, is making his second Final
Four trip in three seasons as head coach. It was redemption for
Guthridge, under fire for most of the season. Cota is making his
third in four years.
</P>
<P>
   No Carolina team had ever reached the Final Four seeded lower
than No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lately, from the outside looking in, it looks like they're
playing with greater passion,'' Tulsa Coach Bill Self said about
the Tar Heels. ``They're two good shooting nights away from winning
it all. Whoever they play, I don't ever see Carolina as being an
underdog. The point spread my say so, but these guys have been
there before and they'll rise to the occasion. They're good enough
and this tournament is crazy enough that all you have to do is put
together three great weeks and they've put together two.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tar Heels coalesced to keep Tulsa (32-5) in misery. Tulsa
entered as the quicker team and Carolina the bigger one.
</P>
<P>
   In this game, size squashed quickness.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first problems for Tulsa developed early when the
senior forward Eric Coley _ the soul of the Golden Hurricanes _
labored with early foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came out with a lot of energy, maybe too much energy,
because the early fouls were kind of silly,'' Coley said. ``I tried
to stay positive. Every time I went back into the game, it seemed
like I would get into more foul trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Coley played only 24 minutes in the game. He scored only 6
points, 6 fewer than his average. But it was on defense _ Coley is
the Western Athletic Conference's career steals leader _ where he
was missed most. Without him, Tulsa was unable to trap, pressure
and create turnovers, to speed up the game and force it into more
of a high-strung, fleet-footed affair.
</P>
<P>
   Cota and Carolina also ensured the game plodded along at a nice,
even pace, Carolina style, by milking the shot clock on offense.
For a half, Tulsa was up for the methodical game and led 31-30 at
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   But then fewer than 2 minutes into the second half, Tulsa went
from being 1 point ahead to 5 points down as Carolina began
establishing its size in rebounding and in forcing Tulsa to alter
its shots over the Tar Heels' towering post players, especially the
7-foot center Brendan Haywood (3 blocks) and 6-foot-11-inch forward
Kris Lang. Both helped Carolina to a 40-29 rebounding advantage and
helped limit Tulsa to only 1 second-chance point compared with
Carolina's 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are so big on the back line, the biggest we've seen,''
the 6-5 Coley said. ``We'd be able to get past the first line of
defense but then it was hard to go around and shoot over 6-11 and
7-foot guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Coley played 14 minutes in the second half. Without its
defensive leader, Tulsa was again unable to speed up the game by
trapping and forcing turnovers. Because Tulsa was missing so many
shots (22 of 32 in the second half), it was unable to set up the
press it prefers, a full-court one that attacks after Tulsa makes a
baskets.
</P>
<P>
   But Tulsa, like Carolina, was playing a pesky brand of
half-court defense, too. It limited North Carolina to 34.6 percent
shooting from the floor in the second half and to only 29 points.
That gave the Golden Hurricanes a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Despite trailing by 51-41 with 5 minutes 25 seconds remaining,
Tulsa eventually closed the gap to 57-55 led by 7 straight Golden
Hurricane points by the freshman guard Dante Swanson (his 15 points
led all Tulsa scorers). Coley fouled out with 18 seconds left, Cota
made one free throw and then Tulsa, trailing by 58-55, raced
upcourt. The freshman forward David Shelton (1 of 9 from the floor,
0 for 2 from 3-point range) fired a hurried 3-point shot that hit
the front rim. The ball bounced into the hands of Carolina forward
Jason Capel.
</P>
<P>
   Seven seconds and a Forte free throw later, the game was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We panicked,'' Self said of his team's last shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got some turnovers there and we thought, finally, the game
was going our way, our style,'' Tulsa center Brandon Kurtz (11
points, 9 rebounds) said.
</P>
<P>
   But Carolina imposed its will and won.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is in a class by itself,'' Cota said when asked to
compare his two other Carolina Final Four teams. ``It took us a
while to learn each other and find out what it takes to win. This
team learned it late _ but we know now.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
