<HEADLINE>
PUTIN APPEARS TO BE HEADING TO OUTRIGHT VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Acting President Vladimir V. Putin appeared headed for
an outright victory in Russia's presidential election, but not
before a surprisingly strong showing by a Communist challenger gave
the Kremlin a scare and brought charges of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   With 69 percent of the vote from Sunday's election counted early
Monday, Putin had 51.17 percent of the vote, slightly more than the
simple majority needed to avoid a runoff election next month
against Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov, who was second with
30.37 percent. Liberal economist Grigory Yavlinsky was projected to
take third place with about 7 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The final tally was not expected until later Monday, but exit
polls suggested Putin, 47, would avoid a run-off with 51.2 percent.
But what would be seen as a landslide anywhere else came as the
first sign of fallibility for Putin, who had hoped for a sweeping
victory and a clear mandate for his promise to impose order at home
and to revive Russia's image abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The somber former Soviet spy, who had never before run for
public office, has been Russia's dominant politician since taking
over in the Kremlin after Boris N. Yeltsin resigned on New Year's
eve, and was always expected to win this election. Few doubt Putin
would have prevailed over Zyuganov in a run-off. But his popularity
rating, once at 70 percent over public approval for his hard line
against Chechen rebels, has gradually slipped.
</P>
<P>
   Early results from Russia's Pacific coast and eastern Siberia
had put Putin at 45 percent, causing Zyuganov, and many other
observers, to predict a runoff vote. As Putin's rating slowly rose
throughout the evening, some commentators suggested that the
Kremlin might be doctoring the results.
</P>
<P>
   Zyuganov went further, openly accusing the government of using
the computerized tallying system to inflate Putin's support and
steal his own. Zyuganov claimed his real support was closer to 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often they use the electric system to bring people figures
that do not correspond with the real ones,'' Zyuganov told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's election committee chairman, Alexander Veshnyakov, said
he had no evidence of major falsifications. He also suggested that
Zyuganov had more supporters in the east, and that Putin's share of
the votes grew as the ballot counting moved west along Russia's 11
time zones to the major urban centers where Putin is strongest.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's own campaign staff suggested their candidate may have
been hurt by the widespread assumption that he would win, which
convinced many Russians that there was no need to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Independent analysts said the vote had shown that millions of
Russians had used the election to register their discontent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The far east is a very handicapped region economically, and
there is a strong protest vote there, and Putin represents the
Kremlin,'' said veteran political commentator Alexei Pushkov said.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, looking relaxed after a day spent at a Russian bath house
in a village outside Moscow, acknowledged the strong show of
support for Zyuganov despite his lack of funding and the daily
media coverage. He promised to pay attention to the popular
discontent indicated by the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means that our policy must be more balanced, take into
account the existing realities and aim at increasing living
standards,'' Putin said at a news conference at his campaign
headquaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means that there is a large amount of the Russian
population that is not satisfied with the way things are,'' Putin,
clad in a casual gray sweater, said at the briefing early Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's promise of restoring law and order have struck a chord
with many voters, and his straight-talking, can-do image, honed
during the Chechen campaign, have made him an instant favorite of a
country tired of the doddering Yeltsin. One analyst, Igor Bunin,
called Putin ``the anti-Yeltsin.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said a first-round victory would give Putin an added
measure of independence from the Kremlin insiders and regional
elites who have heavily influenced Russian politics in the past
years. How he will use this mandate, or whether he truly seeks
independence, is still anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has barely campaigned, and has revealed little about his
plans beyond vague promises to fight corruption, revive the economy
and restore the pride of Russia's armed forces. He insists he is a
democrat, but stresses to strengthen the role of the state and its
security forces.
</P>
<P>
   Some Russian liberals fear Putin may reverse Russia's fragile
democratic achievements and restore a measure of the broad police
controls of the Soviet era.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we buried the idea of a liberal democracy in Russia,''
Yevgenia Albats, a prominent Russian journalist, said on privately
run NTV television.
</P>
<P>
   She was addressing former Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko, who
typifies Russian political and business leaders who believe Putin
will restore confidence in the economy, making stalled reforms
finally bring results.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday, Putin warned his countrymen not to expect miracles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people start believing in a miracle that does not happen,
then despair will begin,'' Putin told reporters in his campaign
headquarters. ``People are tired, they have it hard, and they
expect a change for the better, but miracles do not happen.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 68 percent of Russia's 108 million registered voters
took part in the balloting Sunday. The turnout was average for
post-Communist Russia, but less than the high turnout Putin had
hoped for.
</P>
<P>
   Putin did welcome the 65 percent turnout in war-ravaged
Chechnya, saying the vote there was a sign that Russia's military
campaign against rebels was working.
</P>
<P>
   But a new attack by the separatists in a mountain village showed
that the rebels are not the defeated force Moscow says they are.
</P>
<P>
   Also, a car bomb exploded in the city of Makhachkala, the
capital of the Russian republic of Dagestan near Chechnya early
Monday, injuring a local government official and his driver.
Chechen rebel attacks on Dagestan last summer and unsolved, deadly
apartment bombings in Dagestan and other Russian cities including
Moscow, were among the reasons Putin has often given for sending
troops into Chechnya.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
