<HEADLINE>
FRANKEL MAKES IT FIVE IN SANTA ANA HANDICAP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ If there is a race that establishes the
country's best older female horse, it's the Santa Ana Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   One need look no further than the race's impressive list of past
winners. It's a list that includes such names as Fiji, Anoconnor,
Reloy, The Very One and Belle Marie.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Spanish Fern added her name to that roll call of winners
in the $150,000 Grade II 1-1/8 mile route on the Santa Anita turf
course. Perhaps it was her destiny. After all, trainer Robert
Frankel has now won the race five times in its 33-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some nice fillies,'' said Frankel's assistant
trainer Humberto Ascanio. ``And, that's the key to winning this
race.''
</P>
<P>
   In winning, Spanish Fern and jockey Victor Espinoza covered the
nine furlongs in a slow 1:49.30. She paid $5.60, $2.60 and $2.60.
</P>
<P>
   For Espinoza, who's been on a hot streak lately, the win was his
third of the day. He took a call in the jock's room from Frankel
who told him to lay off the pace and fire late. He did just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did the job the way Bobby (Frankel) wanted,'' Ascanio said.
``(Frankel) told him to make a late run -- he did a good job on the
rail.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay, who rode in Saturday's Dubai World Cup arrived back in
Los Angeles late Sunday and was delayed en route to Santa Anita
from the airport, officials said. Virginie paid $3 and $2.40.
</P>
<P>
   Third was Country Garden with Eddie Delahoussaye in the saddle.
She paid $3.30.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel, a member of the Thoroughbred Racing Hall of Fame, now
has saddled five winners in the Santa Ana Handicap. They are, last
year's winner, See You Soon; 1995 champion Wandesta; and 1994
champion Possibly Perfect. In 1992 he won the race with Gravieres.
</P>
<P>
   --California Thoroughbred racing lost a huge part of its heart
with the passing of Clement Hirsch on Thursday at the age of 85.
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch's friends Sunday remembered him as the man responsible
for bringing Oak Tree to Santa Anita and saving the Del Mar meet,
when it was nearly put out of business.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Del Mar's lease came up, he was the most influential one
in making sure it stayed there,'' said trainer Warren Stute. ``He
did a lot for racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of my very good friends,' Stute said. ``He was not
only intelligent, but he was also one of the most honest men I've
ever met.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a Marine during World War II and participated in the
landing at Guadalcanal,'' Chillingsworth. said. ``Not many people
know that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard that he went to a party once and took the MGM lion
with him,'' Chillingsworth said. ``He was showman. But, he was also
kind and courteous. When he lost he never bitched about it. He was
always a gentleman.
</P>
</TEXT>
