<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ASSAD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON UNABLE TO BRIDGE ISRAEL-SYRIA DIFFERENCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite having persuaded Syria's ailing president,
Hafez Assad, to make a rare trip abroad, President Clinton failed
Sunday in Geneva to restart the Israel-Syria peace talks _ the
least ambitious of his earlier goals.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Assad talked for three hours in their first
face-to-face discussions in six years, and while White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart characterized the session as ``very
useful,'' he added, ``The differences are significant and
important, and obviously more work needs to be done to bridge them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe it would be productive'' for Syrian-Israeli
talks to restart, he said. ``It is impossible to predict when those
talks might resume.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's quick stopover at the end of a grueling weeklong South
Asia trip revealed, according to analysts, the administration's
lack of groundwork in the negotiations as well as the intransigence
of both Israel and Syria on the key question of establishing a new
border.
</P>
<P>
   After more than 50 years of enmity between Israel and Syria,
Middle East experts believe that the conditions are now ripe for
the countries to reach a treaty, based on the principle of Israel
returning all or much of the Golan Heights to Syria and Syria
opening normal relations with Israel _ including the flying of an
Israeli flag above a new embassy in Damascus, only a
four-and-a-half hour car ride from Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   But after Sunday's Clinton-Assad meeting, it was clear again
that the sides can't agree on how to resume talking.
</P>
<P>
   Syria's depth of mistrust of the process was freshly telegraphed
just a day before the meeting. It came on the smallest of issues.
Syrian officials refused to agree to a joint press conference
because of the presence of Israeli journalists, a US official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can't let Israeli journalists into a press conference,
how do you expect Israel to give up lakefront'' on the Sea of
Galilee in exchange for peace, said a US official, speaking on the
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   In the hours before the Clinton-Assad meeting, Syria's refusal
to attend a press conference caused senior US officials to suddenly
play down the expectations from the meeting. ``There's no guarantee
here,'' Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright said prior to the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But clearly, US officials were disappointed at the outcome and
uncertain of what to do next. Lockhart said Clinton would meet with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on Tuesday to chart the next step.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is,'' said the US official, ``I don't think there
are any new ideas. It's really up to both sides on whether they
want to make a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak, in an interview with the Globe Sunday at the Blair
House, said Clinton and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak should
not underestimate Assad's firmness in insisting that Israel return
all the land it captured from Syria after June 4, 1967.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will not make any concessions. . . . If he makes any
concessions, there are going to be terrible problems for him. I
told Barak the same thing,'' Mubarak said.
</P>
<P>
   Israel also is insisting on security guarantees in the deal,
which could mean putting an Israeli observer at a guardpost atop
Mount Hermon, the highest point on the Golan Heights, or receiving
intelligence on Syrian troop movements from US satellites.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such difficulties, the Egyptian president said he
believed an Israel-Syria deal could be completed in two or three
months, an optimistic assessment based on talks with both leaders
in the last week.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke to Barak by telephone after the meeting, and US
Middle East envoy Dennis Ross left Geneva for Jerusalem, where he
will give Barak a fuller briefing on the Clinton-Assad talks.
</P>
<P>
   In Jerusalem, Deputy Defense Minister Ephraim Sneh told the
Associated Press the main sticking point was Syria's demand for a
prior commitment to give back the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that Syria insists upon dictating an agreement and
not obtaining an agreed-upon agreement is what made the resumption
of the talks impossible,'' Sneh said.
</P>
<P>
   In Geneva, Syrian presidential spokesman Joubran Kourieh said in
a statement that Israel was the one placing obstacles. He repeated
Syria's demand that negotiations must resume on the basis of an
Israeli commitment to withdraw from the entire Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the Syrian statement, Lockhart said, ``I would not
agree with any statement that tries to place responsibility on one
side or the other from moving forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts had called the Clinton-Assad meeting the best
chance for a peace deal between Israel and Syria for several
reasons: Israel's upcoming deadline for pulling troops out of south
Lebanon, which could greatly strain regional tensions if it were
done unilaterally; Clinton has only the rest of the year before he
leaves office; and Assad's poor health.
</P>
<P>
   The solitary fact of Assad traveling to Geneva despite his
well-documented aversion to trips abroad caused speculation that
Clinton's discussions with him and Barak since talks had broken
down in January at Shepherdstown, W.Va., had led to a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   But those predictions withered Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It demonstrated once again, that it's not necessarily the case
. . . that if they meet, there's an indication they're close,''
said Geoffrey Aronson, head of Foundation for Middle East Peace, a
Washington think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Aronson and others, though, said that progress still could be
made between Israel and Syria, and soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may not be anything but a little bump on the road here,''
he said. ``That's my sense because so much of the answers to the
issues have been given.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, said the US official, no progress in Geneva was
``dramatic. The president will keep pushing this thing. He'll go
back to doing what he was doing after Shepherdstown _ talking to
both sides. Except now, there's not as much time left.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
