<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S OFFICIAL: PEREZ IS IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ Los Angeles Dodgers manager Davey Johnson has
seen enough. Carlos Perez is in the starting rotation and Eric
Gagne is on his way to Triple-A Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, horrific in his first two starts, clinched it Sunday
against Florida with five innings of solid pitching on three days'
rest. The lefty allowed an unearned run on four hits, walked three
and struck out four.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have to say pretty much (Perez is the starter),'' Johnson
said. ``He's come back from a little shaky start and he's thrown
the ball good for me. I thought his mechanics were good, I thought
he made some good pitches, used his fastball well.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Gagne faltered terribly, it was Perez who clinched the
deal. Johnson wanted to see improvement, and in his last three
starts Perez obliged. In that span Perez has shown improved
mechanics and an ability to throw his split-finger fastball for key
outs while posting a 2.57 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   While Gagne's ERA ballooned to 15.63, Perez's has dropped to
5.68. And though Johnson is keeping quiet about when Perez will
pitch, the rotation is set for Perez to pitch the finale of the
four-game series in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's already said Kevin Brown will start the opener,
followed by Chan Ho Park. He's also said Darren Dreifort would
pitch the Friday series-opener in New York. Orel Hershiser is
slated to start the third game in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can't be anymore surprises,'' Perez said. ``What more do
I have to do? Nothing else. I'm happy with my last three starts. If
they want to see a bunch of shutouts, just wait until the season
starts. If they really want to see nine innings, eight innings,
just wait. This is spring training. I don't want to be too excited,
but I feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the situation could leave the Dodgers in a jam if
Hershiser and Perez, who pitch back-to-back, struggle to eat
innings. Hershiser averaged 5 innings per start last season while
Perez averaged 5 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said lefty Onan Masaoka will pitch in a Tripe-A game
Tuesday to stretch out his arm. Johnson said Masaoka would be the
Dodgers' situational lefty and, most likely, long relief man out of
the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield returns: Left fielder Gary Sheffield missed eight
games after gashing his left pinkie sliding into third base, and
returned to club two homers against the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could have seen more breaking balls so I could gauge
that and see where I'm at with that,'' Sheffield said. ``But I saw
two and swung the bat real well on them, so if I see a few more
I'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Outside of having Perez on the mound, the
Dodgers' lineup was what it will most likely be opening day, which
is a week from today in Montreal. It was Devon White (CF), Mark
Grudzielanek (2B), Sheffield (LF), Shawn Green (RF), Eric Karros
(1B), Todd Hundley (C), Adrian Beltre (3B) and Kevin Elster
(SS).... Right-hander Antonio Osuna remains ahead of schedule in
his recovery from elbow surgery, but don't expect him back until
there's a spot for him in the bullpen. When the time comes, Johnson
said he would use Osuna as a long relief man when he was ready to
join the Dodgers.... Right-hander Mike Fetters had to assure his
health to the Dodgers by bringing back an old tradition. He had to
run the 17th street bridge, which goes over the Indian River. ``It
was tougher than I thought,'' Fetters said. ``The wind was right in
my face, but I'll do it again if they want. I'll do anything they
want.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
