<SLUG> BC-POPE-MIDEAST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE PRAYS AT WESTERN WALL   TO CAP PILGRIMAGE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Pope John Paul II's hand trembled Sunday as he
reached out across 2,000 years of history to touch the ancient
Herodian stone of the Western Wall, the most holy site in Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   The frail, 79-year-old pontiff sank to his knees in the Church
of the Holy Sepulchre and then prayed at the site where the
Christian faith holds the resurrection of Jesus occurred.
</P>
<P>
   He ascended the hill Muslims call the ``Noble Sanctuary'' to see
the shimmering, golden Dome of the Rock, where the faithful believe
the prophet Mohammed ascended to heaven.
</P>
<P>
   It was a day of images that will endure through history as the
pope crowned his Holy Land pilgrimage with a final interfaith
journey that wove its way through the narrow, cobble-stone paths of
Jerusalem's walled Old City to visit the three clustered sites so
revered by Judaism, Christianity, and Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most indelible of these images and certainly the one
most laden with history came at the Western Wall.
</P>
<P>
   When the pope shuffled forward slowly and stood before the
massive stones _ all that remains of the Second Temple, which was
destroyed by Rome in AD 70 _ he placed a note in a crack in the
wall.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving prayerful notes in the crevices and nooks of the
yellow-gray, hand-hewn stones is a tradition for generations of
Jewish worshipers, and the pope's was a prayer for forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``God of our fathers, you chose Abraham and his descendants to
bring your Name to the Nations,'' read the typewritten message,
which was saved by Israeli authorities and will be kept for
display. ``We are deeply saddened by the behavior of those who in
the course of history have caused these children of yours to suffer
and, asking your forgiveness, we wish to commit ourselves to
genuine brotherhood with the people of the Covenant.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope's words were from an address earlier this month in Rome
in which he offered a sweeping apology for Christian sins of the
past. He had reiterated this theme at a moving ceremony Thursday at
Yad Vashem, Israel's Holocaust memorial. But this was a gesture at
the holiest site in all of Judaism. And standing there murmuring a
prayer in his white vestments, slumped over with age, against the
backdrop of the massive wall, he appeared to have deeply touched
the hearts of many Israelis and Jews worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Brodman, 40, an Orthodox rabbi from Jerusalem who came to
see the momentous occasion, said, ``This is history we saw today.
It seems that this pope is a real friend of the Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``That picture of him at our `kotel,' '' he said, using the
Hebrew word for the wall, ``is the sign of Christianity and
Jerusalem coming together again after 2,000 years.''
</P>
<P>
   John Paul became the first pope to pray at the site of the
Temple since Peter, among the first disciples whom Jesus chose to
lead the church and who is the pope's spiritual predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   The wall embodied sadness for Diaspora Jews forced out of
Jerusalem by the Roman Empire and only allowed to return once a
year to lament for all they had lost, which is why it is also known
as the ``Wailing Wall.'' The Jews' exile was viewed by the early
Christian church as a punishment for failing to accept Jesus
Christ. But in 1967 when Israel captured the Old City from Jordan,
the wall, the western retaining wall of the Temple Mount, took on
new symbolism of the triumphant reemergence of the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   ``By standing there, this symbolized the humility of the church
which for Jews had been viewed as arrogant,'' said Father Jerome
Murhpy-O'Connor, a priest of the Dominican order and one of the
world's preeminent biblical historians. ``By standing there he
transformed the relationship of Christianity toward Judaism. It is
a complete reversal of history.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope's comments were also a balm over wounding words made
the day before when the Palestinian Muslim chief cleric _ whom the
pope visited Sunday at the Dome of the Rock _ was dismissive of the
horrors of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way of the pope's pilgrimage Sunday _ and throughout
his week-long sojourn through what he called the ``history of
salvation'' _ the pope carefully navigated the minefield of
religious and political themes of the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   By the time his Israeli El Al plane had departed from Tel Aviv
for Rome Sunday evening, the pope seemed to have succeeded in
making a great plea for reconciliation and a resonant call for
peace in a land that writhes with bitterness and violence. Whether
any of his message will affect Israelis and Palestinians as they
head into the critical, final phase of the peace process remains to
be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Israelis of almost all political and religious
persuasions seemed to embrace his message of reflection on
Christian anti-Semitism that contributed to the Holocaust. And
Palestinians seemed uplifted by his message of peace and justice
and a recognition of their suffering as refugees under Israeli
occupation.
</P>
<P>
   In the Old City, the pope wound his way through the streets in a
white Chevrolet Suburban. As he passed through the Christian
Quarter, hundreds of people struggled to catch a glimpse of the
pope's motorcade.
</P>
<P>
   Asharaf Abu Gesh, 21, blessed himself as the pope passed,
saying, ``This is a man of peace. As Palestinian Christians, we are
very proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Lena Qassem, 23, a Muslim, who is a medical student, said, ``The
pope is very popular among Arabs for his stance on the side of
justice. He is always with victims, and he knows we are the victims
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing security concerns, the Israelis had virtually shut down
the entire Old City, forcing shops to close and people to stay in
their homes. The move had outraged Palestinian Christians and
Muslims who wanted to welcome the pope. The Israelis also refused
to allow Christian Palestinian political leaders to attend the
pope's mass at the Holy Sepulchre.
</P>
<P>
   Hanan Ashrawi, a Palestinian legislator and member of the
Anglican church, who said she was infuriated that Israelis had
pressured church officials not to permit her to attend the mass
because she was a political leader, said, ``They wanted to make an
impression that Jerusalem is an empty city. . . . That our churches
are only empty museums. . . . But Jerusalem is a living, throbbing
city in pain, under siege and under occupation.''
</P>
<P>
   As the pontiff was reminded at almost every turn in the warrens
of this city of stone, the most explosive issue of all was the
future status of Jerusalem and its competing claims of sovereignty.
Israel claims it as its eternal, indivisible capital. Palestinians
say East Jerusalem must be the capital of their future state.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have tried to capitalize on the pope's visit. The
Western Wall plaza was festooned with 50 Israeli flags fluttering
in the wind and strategically placed around the podium from which
the pope spoke.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians, ordered by Israel not to raise flags, were
forced to be creative. They unleashed an enormous column of baloons
of red, white, black, and green _ the colors of Palestine _ and
some with actual flags tethered to them floating all over the city
just before the pope's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   The pope had vowed to come to Jerusalem on a spiritual
pilgrimage and not a political trip, and in the end, he lived up to
that. On Sunday, he made a surprise and secretive return visit to
the Holy Sepulchre. There, far from the glare of the TV cameras and
the crowds vying to greet him, he slipped into the Crusader-era
church and climbed the steep steps that lead up to ``Golgotha,''
the rocky outcropping where it is believed Jesus was crucified.
There, amid the cool shadows and smell of frankincense he quietly
prayed.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's Cardinal Adam Maida said, ``This is the highlight.
This is the most spiritual. . . . Spiritually for Christians, the
Holy Sepulchre is where it all began because of the resurrection. .
. . The pope is a mystic and very spiritual man. He is unsteady on
his feet. He appears weak, but this has probably been the strongest
moment of his pontificate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
