<HEADER>
A8584 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-REPUBS-YOUTH-NYT &LR;      03-26 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-YOUTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH THE BABY BOOMER WILL BE HIS PARTY'S FIRST 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By the time Gov. George W. Bush became the de facto
Republican presidential nominee, there were several striking
numbers that defined his candidacy and helped explain his success.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy million: the estimate of dollars he had raised for the
primary fight. One hundred ninety: the count of members of the
House of Representatives who had endorsed him.
</P>
<P>
   But a smaller number that drew less notice could be the most
significant of all: 54. That is how old the Texas governor, whose
birthday is July 6, will be at the Republican National Convention
in August, and it will make Bush the party's youngest nominee in 40
years.
</P>
<P>
   It will also make him the first Republican nominee in more than
30 years who is almost the same age as his Democratic rival _ Vice
President Al Gore will be 53 at the Democratic National Convention
_ and the first who was born too late to have had any involvement
in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   That youthfulness and generational shift are more than
interesting trivia. They represent a changing of the guard for the
Republican Party. And they are keys to why so many party leaders
believed that Bush could credibly cast himself as a new-style
Republican who, to borrow a metaphor that was clubbed to death in
the last presidential election, is a bridge to the country's
future, not its past.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a definite underlying, subliminal theme within the
party that we needed to nominate a hip young conservative, somebody
who can directly relate to baby boomers, who understands them,''
said Greg Mueller, a Republican strategist in the Washington area.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I say hip, I don't mean music,'' Mueller added. ``I mean
politically hip to the issues of the day, someone who is looking
forward and looking to the next century.''
</P>
<P>
   Mueller and other political analysts said that Bush's repeatedly
stated desire to inject a new sensitivity and compassion into the
Republican Party _ a message crafted with the political
sensibilities of swing voters in mind _ requires an accompanying
image that defies voters' expectations for a Republican
presidential candidate in vivid, easily projected ways.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aura of youthfulness is one of those ways. It stands in
stark contrast to the personas of the party's last two nominees:
Bush's father, who was 68 in 1992, and Bob Dole, who was 73 in
1996. Both men lost to Bill Clinton, who was 45 at the Democratic
convention in 1992, and 50 at the convention in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's doings and demeanor on the campaign trail often
accentuate his energy and athleticism, sometimes deliberately,
sometimes not.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the Iowa caucuses in January, the governor ended a
campaign appearance in Council Bluffs by straying over to a band of
college students who had been loudly playing popular music,
lingering over the drummer and moving rhythmically to the beat.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, in New Hampshire, Bush's itinerary was chock-full
of physical fun and play: bowling, soccer, a ride on a snowmobile,
a trip down a snowy hillside on a sled. One of his advisers in the
state said that the Bush campaign had been consciously trying to
convey the governor's vigor and vitality.
</P>
<P>
   But that bid is a complicated endeavor. For one thing, Gore is
working the same theme with his blue jeans, his Palm Pilot and a
campaign appearance in California last year in which former members
of the Grateful Dead allowed his wife, Tipper, to take a seat at a
drum set and jam with them.
</P>
<P>
   For another, one of Bush's sustained challenges has been to
project a proper degree of presidential seriousness, which his
playfulness carries the risk of undercutting.
</P>
<P>
   Playful was not a word often associated with the party's last
nominee, Bob Dole, who was 23 years older than Clinton. While that
gap was especially large, it belonged to a decades-long pattern in
presidential politics. The last time the Republican nominee was
younger than the Democratic one was in 1968, when Richard M. Nixon,
55, beat Hubert H. Humphrey, 57.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, the Republican candidates (Nixon in 1972, Gerald
Ford in 1976, Ronald Reagan in 1980 and 1984, Bush's father in 1988
and 1992, and Dole in 1996) have been at least nine years older
than their Democratic counterparts. In six of those seven
elections, the Republican nominee was over 60. In all of them, the
Democratic nominee was under 60.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts and historians said this tradition fed into
an identity for the Republican Party that Bush would clearly like
to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Republican Party always fights the image of being
reactionary, of being backward-looking, of not being atop the most
recent trends in the country,'' said Allan J. Lichtman, chairman of
the history department at American University in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of a transition for the Republican Party,'' Lichtman
said of Bush's age, ``this is important.''
</P>
<P>
   Youth alone is by no means a clear advantage. In the span of
time that Republican nominees have been older than Democratic ones,
the Republican Party has emerged victorious more often than not.
</P>
<P>
   No Republican nominee in the last several decades has proved as
popular as Reagan, with younger voters as well as older ones. And
Reagan was 69 when he was first inaugurated, 73 when he began his
second term.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Bush's age _ and for that matter, Gore's _ has a
potential downside. Whit Ayres, a Republican pollster in Atlanta,
said that Clinton, the first baby boomer in the White House, turned
that generational status into a double-edged sword because his
behavior played into stereotypes of his generation as
self-absorbed, indulgent and reckless.
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, political analysts said, Bush's appeal to
voters as someone who is in touch with their concerns and
lifestyles is strengthened by youthful attributes, including the
fact that he still has school-age children, twin 18-year-old
daughters, living at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a connectedness factor,'' said Bill McInturff, the
Republican pollster who worked for the presidential campaign of
Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   And it clearly gives Bush an ability to try to relate to voters
of different ages without looking ridiculous or uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   As he left a bookstore in Chicago in December, Bush noticed that
a 20-year-old sales clerk had rings in her pierced tongue.
Seemingly charmed and intrigued by that detail, he stopped to chat
with her about it. There were no television cameras and only one
reporter nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you eat steaks?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't eat meat,'' she responded, and as the easy exchange
continued, Bush wore a delighted expression that was positively
boyish. It was not a look that his Republican predecessors often
managed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
