<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-EAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG FLORIDA PLAYS WITH INSPIRATION INTO THE FINAL FOUR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ Few college basketball fans figured Florida for
the Final Four, but there go the Gators _ catch them if you can.
Young, fast, tough and talented, they advanced to the penultimate
round Sunday with a thorough 77-65 victory over Oklahoma State in
the final of the East Regional of the National Collegiate Athletic
Association tournament in the Carrier Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a tough basketball team to play,'' said Mike Miller, a
sophomore forward who led the Gators with 14 points and was named
most valuable player in the region. ``We're a great basketball team
when we execute and play hard.''
</P>
<P>
   In a motivational ploy devised by Coach Billy Donovan and a team
counselor, Miller and his teammates wore on their ankles the names
of relatives or friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what you accomplish in your life, if you have no
one to share it with, it doesn't mean a thing,'' Donovan said. ``We
needed something motivationally to have them reach down inside. We
tried to have them dedicate this game to someone they love.''
</P>
<P>
   It is only the second time that Florida has advanced this far.
In 1994, the Gators lost to Duke in the semifinals. Florida will
play North Carolina on Saturday in Indianapolis. The Tar Heels
eliminated Tulsa earlier this afternoon. In the other semifinal,
Michigan State will play Wisconsin. Florida, seeded fifth in this
region, is 28-7 and beat top-seeded Duke on Friday night. Oklahoma
State, seeded third, finished 27-7.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys started four seniors and a sophomore, but it was
Florida _ with no senior starters _ that played with poise
bordering on cockiness. Cowboys Coach Eddie Sutton said that for
much of the first half ``we looked like our team was in a daze. We
missed too many easy shots. We made some foolish turnovers,
carelessness on our part.''
</P>
<P>
   Udonis Haslem and Donnell Harvey each added 10 points for
Florida. Fredrik Jonzen led Oklahoma State with 14 points. Glendon
Alexander had 13 and Joe Adkins 12. But Adkins made only 4 of 14
field-goal attempts and the team shot 42 percent from the field.
Gottlieb, the point guard, said the Gators ``run waves at you''
with their many substitutions and ``maybe your shots are out of
rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Gators opened the game with the full-court press that
has served them so well, the Cowboys had little trouble solving it,
passing and running up the court for easy baskets and a 5-point
lead. The only turnover forced by the press in the first nine
minutes came when an official called a five-second violation on
Gottlieb, the Cowboys' veteran guard who was moving back and forth
while trying to inbound the ball from the baseline. Sutton thought
his team was the victim of a fast count and got whistled for a
technical foul when he protested.
</P>
<P>
   It proved ominous as the Gators surged to a 33-18 lead. Oklahoma
State suffered from poor shooting in the interior and unforced
turnovers in the middle of the floor. The Gators were scoring in
transition and forcing a fast tempo that favored them. And the
Gators also played with a certain attitude. When Desmond Mason of
Oklahoma State crashed to the floor in pain beneath the basket
while on attack, Brent Wright of Florida casually stepped over him
as if Mason were but a puddle on the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the second half, Wright exchanged rude shoves
with Brian Montonati and goaded him into a fourth foul that sent
him to the bench. On various rebounding occasions, Harvey _
Florida's freshman forward _ swung an impressive set of elbows.
Later, he began to dunk _ including twice in an 80-second span late
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He opened up the game for us,'' Donovan said. Harvey also had
five rebounds and the Gators dominated the glass by 43-31. But they
did other things well, with skill and aggression that rattled the
Cowboys. When Gottlieb set up Andre Williams for a dunk with a
no-look pass down the lane, Williams clanged the stuff shot off the
rim. When Gottlieb looked clear for a layup on a breakaway, he was
chased down by Miller, who knocked the ball out of his hands.
Moments later, Brett Nelson of Florida turned a Cowboys turnover
into a fast-break dunk that was preceded by a behind-the-back whirl
of the ball as he elevated.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, Florida increased the lead to 17 before
Oklahoma State went on a 20-6 run run to cut the deficit to 3
points with eight minutes left. But the Cowboys never got closer
than that. In the final seconds, when almost everyone stood still
and waited for the buzzer, Kenyan Weaks, the only senior on the
Florida team, waltzed down the lane for a gratuitous dunk. Couldn't
he have saved that for the next game?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told to hold the ball,'' Weaks said. ``But I was intent
on doing something else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
