<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-NABISCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEBB RUNS AND HIDES FROM LPGA'S BEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOHN STREGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RANCHO MIRAGE, Calif. _ Karrie Webb's final-round victory lap
here Sunday included an encore at the fifth hole, where she made a
hole-in-one to provide an exclamation point to a remarkable run.
</P>
<P>
   Victory was a formality for Webb, who took an eight-stroke lead
over Dottie Pepper into the final round of the Nabisco
Championship, then won by a tournament-record 10 strokes with a
14-under 274 total.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd have had one heck of a tournament if not for Karrie
Webb,'' said Pepper, who finished second, one stroke ahead of Meg
Mallon.
</P>
<P>
   This was Webb's fourth victory this year in five LPGA starts and
her fifth victory in six starts over all in 2000. It was also her
second straight victory in a major championship (she won the du
Maurier Classic in 1999) and her 19th victory in four-plus years on
the Ladies Professional Golf Association Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a good feeling, a rewarding feeling, for all the
hard work I've put in,'' said the 25-year-old Webb, who celebrated
in the traditional way, by jumping into the water at the 18th
green, where she was joined by her caddie, Evan Minster, and the
singer Celine Dion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to win golf tournaments. I love to be in the situation
I put myself in today, and four or five other times this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The only unanswered question entering the final round was how
13-year-old Aree Wongluekiet would fare playing in the final group
in a major championship. She was undone not by the pressure, but by
her own carelessness, incurring a two-stroke penalty when she
inadvertently and unknowingly caused her ball to move with her
putter on the 14th green and failed to replace it before hitting
her next putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking at the hole, and apparently the ball moved maybe
an eighth of an inch,'' Wongluekiet said. ``I didn't see it, but TV
did. I didn't replace the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than shooting a 73 and finishing in a tie for sixth, she
shot a 75 and finished in a tie for 10th, which did nothing to
dampen anyone's enthusiasm in assessing her skill.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's an amazing talent,'' Webb said. ``On the first hole, she
ripped it off the tee straight down the middle, and I was impressed
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   It was all that prevented Webb from claiming a monopoly on
impressiveness here. Webb shot a two-under-par 70 in the final
round and earned $187,500. It was her fourth straight round under
par on the difficult Dinah Shore course at Mission Hills Country
Club.
</P>
<P>
   Pepper, the defending champion, was playing despite an aching
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payback is hell,'' said Pepper, who won by six strokes a year
ago and holed shots from the fairway twice this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Although Webb eliminated the drama with Saturday's round of
five-under 67, she delivered excitement Sunday with an ace on the
170-yard, par-3 fifth hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost didn't see it go in,'' Webb said. ``When it landed, I
saw it roll up pretty close. I bent down to pick up my tee and
heard Evan say, `Go in.' I looked up and saw it fall in the hole.
When things are going good for you, they're going good.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb's lead grew to 11 strokes through 16 holes Sunday. No one
threatened to make a move on her.
</P>
<P>
   ``After such a good start, I did wonder if I'd peaked a little
too early,'' Webb said of her season. ``But there wasn't anything I
could do about that. I played tremendously the first three days.
Today I was more excited to just get into the clubhouse and hold
the trophy. I'm extremely happy with what I've done this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Given her play, Webb was asked if she is capable of winning this
year's four major tournaments _ the Nabisco, the LPGA Championship,
the United States Women's Open and the du Maurier _ for which
Nabisco offers a $2.5 million bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess anything's possible,'' Webb said. ``But I think
they've got a pretty safe bet.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb will take a month off, returning at the Chick-fil-A Charity
Championship starting April 28. The question is, will she lose
momentum with inactivity? With six victories in 1999 and four in
2000, it would seem that Webb has taken her game to a level she can
sustain.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got it going, you've got it going,'' Pepper said.
``You have to sit back and admire her golf. She's getting it in the
hole faster than anybody else.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
