<SLUG> BC-BKC-FINALFOUR0327-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Michigan State is only No. 1 seed to survive, joined by Florida,
North Carolina and Wisconsin
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If history is an indicator, Michigan State should like
its chances Saturday when it is joined by three surprise teams at
the NCAA Final Four in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State is the only No. 1 seed to make it, along with
fifth-seeded Florida and a pair of No. 8 seeds, Wisconsin and North
Carolina, that have a combined 26 losses.
</P>
<P>
   Only six previous times since the tournament went to 64 teams in
1985 has a lone No. 1 advanced to Final Four. Four of those times,
that No. 1 won the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   But given the craziness of this tournament, just about anything
could happen at the RCA Dome. Here is an early preview of
Saturday's games.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State vs. Wisconsin: The Big Ten teams have played
three times since Feb. 12, with Michigan State winning them all _
Wisconsin's only losses in that time. Only one of those games was
decided by more than nine points.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the first time two teams from the same conference
have met in the national semifinals since Illinois and Michigan
tangled in 1989. Michigan won that game 83-81 and went on to beat
Seton Hall in overtime for the championship.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin has already beaten one No. 1 seed, eliminating Arizona
in the second round. Michigan State rallied from substantial
deficits to win its last two games over Syracuse and second-seeded
Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   Florida vs. North Carolina: Florida earned its second trip to
the Final Four since 1994 by beating Oklahoma State 77-65 Sunday in
the East Regional final in Syracuse, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators were almost eliminated in the first round but scored
at the buzzer to beat 12th-seeded Butler 69-68 in overtime. Since
then, Florida has been playing inspired basketball, including a win
over top-seeded Duke in Friday's semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   After North Carolina finished the regular season at 18-13, some
wondered if the Tar Heels would even make the tournament field. But
Sunday they knocked off Tulsa 59-55 to advance to their 15th Final
Four in school history and the third in four years. It was quite a
moment of vindication for coach Bill Guthridge; some Tar Heels fans
had been calling for him to be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
