</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-REDWINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS PLAYING AS IF THEIR SEASON HAS ALREADY ENDED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Forget the final five games of the regular season. The
New York Rangers have already quit.
</P>
<P>
   They still cling to dim playoff hopes, according to the
standing. Realistically, they have little chance after their 8-2
drubbing in Detroit, which demonstrated again why the Rangers have
dissolved into a $61 million mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, the atmosphere at Madison Square Garden could be
ugly when the Red Wings visit to complete the home-and-home series.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing positive out there,'' the Rangers' Brian
Leetch said. ``It was an embarrassment.''
</P>
<P>
   The defeat was the Rangers' fourth straight, dropping them eight
games under .500. The Rangers are 1-7-1 over the last nine games.
Since the All-Star Game break, the Rangers are 6-14-4 and seem
assured of missing the Stanley Cup playoffs for the third
consecutive season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was the longest game I've ever played in,'' Adam Graves
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who allowed the most goals since March 24, 1996 (an
8-2 Penguins romp), are 3 points behind Montreal for the final
Eastern Conference playoff berth. But the situation is dire because
three teams are ahead of the Rangers, who have the fewest number of
games remaining (5).
</P>
<P>
   Mike Richter was magnificent in the first period, stopping all
but one of Detroit's 22-shot barrage. But you got the sense that
Richter was only delaying the inevitable collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit scored 5 goals in the second period on 11 shots; the
Rangers had 5 shots on goal. Martin Lapointe, who had not scored in
15 games, finished off his first National Hockey League hat trick
with two second-period goals.
</P>
<P>
   Brendan Shanahan, Steve Yzerman, Sergei Fedorov, Tomas Holdstrom
and Nicklas Lidstrom also scored for the Red Wings, who scored six
consecutive goals to take a 7-1 lead. Leetch and Graves scored for
the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers hit no one, leaving both goalies _ Richter (who left
after two periods) and Kirk McLean _ at the mercy of the Red Wings,
who skated through and around defenders like they were standing
still.
</P>
<P>
   The team's two biggest free-agent signings _ Theo Fleury and
Valery Kamensky _ again were invisible on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Despite two power-play goals, the Rangers were unable to score
with the man-advantage at the most crucial time _ after major and
game misconduct penalties were assessed to Larry Murphy for
spearing Fleury 14 minutes 19 seconds into the game.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the major expired , the Rangers had not only not
scored, they had been outshot by the short-handed Red Wings, 5-3.
After one period, the game was tied at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   And Richter had done all he could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the intermission, we talked about helping out our
goaltender,'' said Leetch. ``And it got even worse.''
</P>
<P>
   How, the Rangers' captain was asked, does a team respond to such
a beating?
</P>
<P>
   ``Start over tomorrow,'' Leetch said.
</P>
<P>
   Wait until seems more likely route.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers entered the season thin at center, a weakness that
was again underscored Sunday. With Coach John Muckler refusing to
play Alexandre Daigle (a healthy scratch for the third straight
game), Fleury, a lifelong right wing, started the game at center
just three days after he and Muckler had agreed it was best for
Fleury to stay at a wing.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, an irate Fleury stormed out of the dressing room for
the second time in three games. When asked if he had a minute to
answer some questions, Fleury said, ``For what? I've got nothing to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleury _ who alternated at wing and center while Muckler
double-shifted Petr Nedved _ took just three shifts in the third
period. That was three more than Kamensky, who was nailed to the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``As badly as we got beat, it's the same guys that work hard,''
said Muckler. ``It's been the same guys all year long. Nothing
changes. It's the same guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Muckler said there was no need to name names. But he did single
out three he thought played well today: Mike York, Stephane Quintal
and Rich Pilon.
</P>
<P>
   These Rangers were built like a rotisserie team consisting of
high-priced veterans who looked good together on paper but had
showed little chemistry on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Even among his staunchest supports, there is little doubt that
Muckler will return next season. The question is whether team
president and general manager Neil Smith will be back. Smith has
been promoting the Rangers' bright future since before the season
even began. But no one could have imagined the present would ever
be this bleak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know whether the guys quit,'' said Richter, who did
not seem to rule out the possibility. ``I do know we have to be
better than this.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
