<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS STILL LOOKING AT THEIR OPTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ The Anaheim Angels will break camp in Arizona on
Wednesday, then play their final three games of spring training
over the weekend in Anaheim and San Diego as they set up their
pitching rotation.
</P>
<P>
   There are still decisions to be made, but it seems it could set
up like this: Ken Hill will open the season at home against the New
York Yankees next Monday. Kent Bottenfield, who arrived in camp
Sunday, will probably start the second game of the series. And Kent
Mercker is expected to start the third game.
</P>
<P>
   After that, it gets more complicated. The Angels are off
Thursday, April 6, then begin a three-game series against the Red
Sox on Friday, April 7. The starter that day could be one of three
pitchers - Jason Dickson, Brian Cooper or Scott Schoeneweis.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of variables still there,'' manager Mike
Scioscia said. ``The only way we can do it is look at our options
and let it play out. There are going to be some tough decisions,
but it's going to make our ballclub better.''
</P>
<P>
   New guy: Bottenfield spent his first day in an Angels uniform
throwing in the bullpen, running in the outfield and meeting his
new teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about the opportunity,'' he said. ``I've heard
nothing but great things from guys who play here and guys who have
played here. I've been told there's an upbeat attitude in the
clubhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield will get his first start Wednesday against the
Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Pitcher Jarrod Washburn (strained oblique muscle)
threw a simulated game Sunday and will throw another in a couple of
days.... Ramon Ortiz (sore shoulder) will throw in a minor-league
game today in Mesa, Ariz.
</P>
</TEXT>
