<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: BILLY DONOVAN'S MOTIVATION AND TRADITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ Billy Donovan was attempting to drum up
sympathy for his young Florida team. The Gators' 34-year-old coach
was making the point about the hazards of recruiting young players
and having them turn professional, leaving the cupboard bare and
all that.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan said that what concerned him about Oklahoma State was
that the Cowboys were a tight, cohesive group of seniors, deep in
experience and valuable frames of reference. His team, freshmen and
sophomores, lacked a deep emotional well.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always the danger that the team that's less talented
but has a lot of seniors can beat a young, talented team because
they've been there,'' Donovan said. ``You don't know who's going to
stay and who's going. At one point it's exciting; at another point
it's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, it was exciting.
</P>
<P>
   With just over three minutes remaining in the East Regional
final, 6-foot-8-inch Donnell Harvey _ one of Donovan's freshmen _
swooped down from what seemed the Carrier Dome roof and slammed
home a riveting, Vince Carter-like dunk. Harvey's dunk increased
Florida's lead to 70-57, extinguished what had been a last-gasp
comeback by Oklahoma State and sent out a resounding message.
Florida won, 77-65, to join an eclectic group in Indianapolis next
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators are going to the Final Four, where they will face
North Carolina on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Donovan was so concerned that his players might
not have the emotional reserve to dig deep when the going rough
that he dug deep into his own bag of motivational tricks. He told
each player to choose one person he loved, really loved, and to
dedicate the game to that person. Put that person's name on his
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to make it so that when they got tired, when they
looked down, they saw that person's name,'' Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Miller dedicated the game to his family _ two older
brothers, a younger sister and his mother, who drove him to
practice and sometimes rebounded for him. Brent Wright dedicated
the game to his 18 brothers and sisters. Harvey, the middle of
three boys, dedicated the game to his family.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan's tactic worked, or something worked. When Florida
fumbled away a 17-point lead to lead by only 3 with eight minutes
to go, the Gators kicked into gear and sped away. Two foul shots by
Teddy Dupay, two more by Miller, a 3-pointer by Miller, a layup by
Udonis Haslem and, finally, 5 consecutive points by Harvey: a dunk,
a foul shot and that riveting dunk to make it a 13-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, with fans going crazy, his teammates scrambling
to cut down the nets, an unfazed Harvey stood alone, looking as if
he were waiting to buy a ticket to a movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just taking what the defense gave me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Was he excited? ``This was a good victory,'' he said ``It's
special, but we have two more games to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone asked Harvey if he knew that freshmen were not supposed
to play the way Florida's did. He shrugged. ``Age doesn't matter on
the court,'' he said. ``All that matters is how you play.''
</P>
<P>
   In the span of 48 hours, Donovan had looked two coaching icons
in the eye and beaten them. On Friday, he defeated Mike
Krzyzewski's Duke team and last night he defeated Eddie Sutton's
Oklahoma State.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year is only the seventh year in 80 years that the
University of Florida has been to the NCAA tournament,'' Donovan
said. ``It's not a tradition-laden school, but I'm happy there.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the game, his 59-year-old father and his
87-year-old grandfather came down to the court and hugged. What a
scene: the son the coach, proud father and grandfather all locked
in an embrace. Donovan's father, Bill, played at Boston College;
his grandfather, Bill, played in the Navy in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife died last year,'' the eldest Donovan said. ``She
really loved Billy; we used to watch all of his games together.
Something like this helps to take some of the pain away.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally there was Donovan's father, the man responsible for
pushing his son to leave Wall Street and get into coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to do what every young kid out of college wanted to
do: I wanted to make a million dollars,'' Donovan remembered. ``I'd
pick up the phone, try to get some guy from Texas to invest money
with me, and I had no idea what I was doing with it anyway. That
was very short-lived for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like most athletes, I never thought my career was ever going
to come to an end. I thought I was going to play forever. I had to
sit back and look at my career. My dad always told me that while
you're young, do what you love doing. That's what's going to make
you happy. All the money in the world can't buy happiness. Do what
you love. That hit home to me.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Sunday night, everything worked: the press, the trap, the
motivation, the four generations of Donovans.
</P>
<P>
   Relax and enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Then start all over again Monday.
</P>
<P>
   That's what makes it tough; that's what makes it exciting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
