<SLUG> BC-TALK.COM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALK.COM PLANS TO ACQUIRE ACCESS ONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talk.com, a provider of long-distance telephone services,
announced Sunday it would buy Access One, a privately held local
telephone company that operates in nine Southeastern states, in a
stock deal valued around $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   Talk.com has made clear that it wants to expand into local
service. The company expects to offer local calling in New York
State in the next few months. And though Gabriel Battista,
Talk.com's chairman, said that he was not yet in discussions with
other companies, he said that Talk.com was looking closely at other
small local phone providers as possible acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers will want to deal with one company for local and
long-distance services,'' Battista said, ``and this deal is
jump-starting us in nine states'' _ Alabama, Florida, Georgia,
Kentucky, Louisiana, Mississippi, North Carolina, South Carolina
and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   By buying Access One, which had revenue of about $50 million
last year, Talk.com gets 55,000 local-service customers in
BellSouth territory, as well as local service it can offer the
300,000 long-distance customers it has in the area. Most of Access
One's customers are small businesses, while most of Talk.com's
customers are residential, so there is little overlap in customer
bases.
</P>
<P>
   And though the combined customer base is still a fraction of the
27 million telephone users in the region, Battista says the new
company will easily garner more. ``Talk.com,'' he said, ``is a
marketing machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk.com has been around for 10 years, but has had a huge growth
spurt over the last six months. In March of last year, it had one
million subscribers for its long-distance services; by December,
the figure was 1.5 million. The company, which lost $2 a share in
1998 _ in part because of skyrocketing marketing expenses, Battista
said _ earned 90 cents a share, or about $58 million, on $515
million in revenue in 1999. It has transferred much of its
marketing to the Internet, a far lower-cost way to sell.
Stockholders remain skeptical. Talk.com's shares, although they
rose above $22 in December for a few hours, traded around $17 for
most of last year. The shares closed at $14.5625 on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
