<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8608 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-DALEY-PROFILE-NYT &LR;      03-26 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DALEY-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER CALL FOR THE QUARTERBACK OF POLITICAL PERSUASION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If William M. Daley ever needs to be reminded why
President Clinton made him secretary of commerce, he need only hike
across his office. On the far wall of the great rectangle, past the
sofas, the generous hearth and the boardroom dining table, hangs a
small photograph of the Oval Office with Daley and Clinton standing
shoulder-to-shoulder inside. Inscribed across the bottom, in
Clinton's curly scrawl, is a note of thanks to Daley for heading
the Lazarus Project.
</P>
<P>
   In the Clinton era, such biblical code is reserved for sensitive
political missions. Daley headed one of Clinton's most successful:
getting the North America Free Trade Agreement through a wary
Congress in 1993. Daley, then working as a lawyer, was hired to
salvage Nafta from what was seen as probable defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought I raised it from the dead,'' Daley said one recent
afternoon, explaining how the project got its name and how he, a
bit reluctantly, got his niche. ``I enjoy the politics stuff, but
you do get pounded with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Day to day, Daley oversees Commerce duties like forecasting
weather, counting how many people live in America, promoting United
States goods abroad and collecting data on the national economy.
But despite a self-conscious effort to thrive as a wonk _ as second
son of the Chicago mayoral dynasty, he hopes to be remembered for
something other than campaign savvy _ Clinton uses him as political
offensive coordinator, especially when it is third and long.
</P>
<P>
   So, in the twilight of Clinton's presidency as in its dawn,
Daley is driving a White House legislative crusade. Along with
Steven Richetti and a team of aides in every corner of the
executive branch, Daley heads the effort to persuade Congress to
grant China permanent normal trade relations. Clinton has called it
his top remaining foreign policy goal. Daley, however he handles
this year's census, has his reputation riding on a ``yes'' vote.
</P>
<P>
   Like Nafta, it is an uphill struggle. Union pressure on
Democrats, Republican loyalties to Taiwan and bipartisan concerns
about human rights abuses have turned many lawmakers against
extending permanent trading rights to China. Daley calls the vote
too ``mushy'' to predict.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterbacking comes instinctively to Daley, who is 51. Like
his father and his brother, the past and present Chicago mayors,
politics runs in his blood. White House officials said Clinton
trusts Daley's political intuition more than that of anyone else in
the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   With brother Richard always first in line to fill the family
shoes in Chicago, Daley practiced law at the Chicago office of
Mayer, Brown &AMP; Platt and sought his fortune in national politics,
working for Walter F. Mondale and Michael S. Dukakis before joining
Clinton's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The hoped-for payoff, a cabinet post, did not materialize in the
first Clinton administration. But in early 1993 he was asked to
move into the Old Executive Office Building next to the White House
and mobilize support for Nafta. It was a paltry consolation prize _
his friend Dan Rostenkowski, then the powerful Ways and Means
chairman from Illinois, called him crazy for accepting _ but Nafta
squeaked through Congress. And after the commerce secretary, Ronald
H. Brown, died in a 1996 plane crash, Daley was offered the post.
</P>
<P>
   In an administration with many workaholics, Daley is known as an
especially sober worker bee. His wife remains in Chicago, where
their children are in school. He says it is easier that way because
he is usually at the office when not on the road. He keeps the same
long hours investment bankers do and dresses like they used to. His
close-cut blue suits and pinched shirt collars make him look prim
even by Washington's atavistic standards of attire.
</P>
<P>
   Daley would clearly prefer to enjoy the challenges and trappings
of Commerce secretary than the grind of a six-month legislative
campaign. He said he is especially proud of little-noted
achievements, like straightening out accounting practices in
Commerce's many departments. With trademark deadpan, he said he
hopes his legacy will be ``getting out of here without hiring a
lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet over a working lunch (chicken noodle soup in a plastic foam
bowl, Diet Coke from a can) in his Olympic-pool-sized office, Daley
says that shaping the China debate and cajoling members of Congress
has become his new full-time job. His strategy: Link China trade to
America's national security and the fate of China's reformers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economics of this are great,'' he says. ``But if this
fight stays on economics, we lose. It has to be about Chinese
politics, Taiwan and our position in the world. It's a big vote.
Congress is just going to have to walk the plank.''
</P>
<P>
   To manage the process, Daley moved David Lane, his chief of
staff, across the Mall to the White House. There, they set up a
``war room'' that monitors everything China and commands a
remarkable chunk of Clinton's own schedule. He makes sure nearly
every nanobyte of good news about bilateral relations _ a
first-time export of oranges, China's decision to release the names
of some political prisoners _ gets out to the press.
</P>
<P>
   But Daley spends most of his time in one-on-one meetings with
members of Congress. Some days he sees as many as six or seven
members in their offices. He is taking 30 of them on an Air Force
jet to China next month on a three-city, six-day lobbying tour that
includes meeting with leaders in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Will it work? Daley's efforts to get Congress to approve
fast-track trade negotiating powers failed recently. But, having
been through Nafta, he seems cautiously optimistic that he will
prevail on China.
</P>
<P>
   If not, he begs, only half in jest, please remember what he did
to improve bookkeeping at the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-00 2239EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000326.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8611 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-INDIAN-ARTIFACTS-ART-     03-26 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-ARTIFACTS-ART-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTIFACTS HEADING TO WASHINGTON FOR AMERICAN INDIAN MUSEUM
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUITLAND, Md. _ A century ago, the plight of the Native
Americans had reached a nadir. Their population had been decimated
by war; their culture, in its way, was no less under assault. A
single-minded man with a formidable appetite for collecting other
peoples' treasures was buying up Indian artifacts, literally by the
boxcar, in shopping sprees throughout North America and South
America.
</P>
<P>
   From ceremonial regalia to papoose carriers, from sacred
weavings to towering totems, from long rows of dugout canoes to
bow-and-arrow armories, a business tycoon named George Gustav Heye
spent more than half a century accumulating a collection that is
stunning both for its quality, touched with peerless beadwork and
gold crafting, and for its volume.
</P>
<P>
   Heye left more than 800,000 objects when he died in 1957, plus a
photo archive of 86,000 images of Indian life. And now this
treasure trove is being quietly trucked from a Bronx warehouse to
the Smithsonian Institution's new Cultural Resources Center here,
amid the awe and scrutiny of specialists from the surviving U.S.
tribes, whose population has rebounded in this country from 250,000
a century ago to nearly two million.
</P>
<P>
   A renaissance of sorts is at hand with each truckload of
cultural treasure and each visit from tribal scholars and elders,
who can pause in their gratitude at the drifting smoke of a
smudging ritual in one of the center's ceremonial side rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the truck deliveries are valued at $50 million by the
insurers who protect this weekly cultural portage with security
guards. But the Heye collection in its entirety is priceless as it
arrives to become the core of the new National Museum of the
American Indian, scheduled to open late next year on the Mall in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of time, Heye has come to be honored for his
relentless, loving foray into Indian culture _ even, lately, by the
tribal leaders who are helping to plan the museum. Their
specialists are finding the objects in pristine condition, tangible
evidence of a grand tradition. The growing excitement surrounding
the new museum is personified by its founding director, W. Richard
West Jr., a veteran Washington lawyer and Indian affairs lobbyist
who is a member of the Southern Cheyenne and Arapaho tribes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heye has gifted a nation,'' West said, 40 years after first
seeing some of the Heye collection. When he was a teen-ager making
his first visit east from Oklahoma, his father took him to a small
museum in upper Manhattan that only the most knowledgeable tourists
knew to visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was almost overwhelmed by the volume and quality of the
Cheyenne material I saw,'' West recalled. ``But I also had this
other impression of `why is all this here and all of us Cheyennes
out there either in Oklahoma or Montana?' And `who is telling
people about what this material means?'''
</P>
<P>
   The new museum, the last the Smithsonian will build on the mall
to tell the story of America, is being designed to answer those
questions in close cooperation with the tribes. ``We're just
figuring out our answers,'' said West, who is overseeing the task
of presenting, at the tourist crossroads of the nation, the story
of more than 1,000 Native American communities in the Indians'
words. The tribes encompass the hemisphere from the Arctic circle
to Tierra del Fuego, as well as a history from the struggles of the
past to those of the present.
</P>
<P>
   Mapuche Indians up from Chile were working here Thursday _ two
religious leaders and two scholars consulting on the extensive
collection of objects from their tribal past. Visitors from the
Lakota nation, one of 40 whose treasures will be featured in the
opening exhibitions next year, have been working in another corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a process of community curation,'' West said. ``The
native people themselves have something authentic and worthy to say
about the objects in our collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be through natives' eyes, minds and hearts that
visitors are introduced to this vast store of cultural patrimony.''
</P>
<P>
   After the new museum opens, the Smithsonian will continue to
operate the separate Heye Center museum, which has been open for
the past five years in the historic U.S. Custom House in lower
Manhattan. In inviting close tribal cooperation, the museum board
sought to ease long-running grievances by adopting a repatriation
policy in 1991 so human remains and sacred material could be
returned to the tribes, as well as objects illegally obtained in
the Indian wars.
</P>
<P>
   The research center in this Washington suburb is open to tribal
specialists and limited numbers of casual visitors, who will soon
be able to use computerized research rooms. The three-story
building has state-of-the-art storage. It also has curatorial
equipment to clean and itemize every object with bar codes and
digital imaging.
</P>
<P>
   The five-story mall museum will be faced clifflike with Kasota
limestone and topped with a copper dome. It will cost $110 million,
with the tribes contributing one-third of the money and the
government financing the rest.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   West said estimates are that more than 5 million people a year
will visit. He welcomes the chance to contradict all manner of
stereotypes, from the notion that all Indians are the war-bonneted
plains natives depicted in movies to the impression that native
tribes are near extinction. More than 40 million Native Americans
live in the two hemispheres, he noted; most of them are in Central
America and South America, but there are also 558 federally
recognized tribes in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Though bedeviled in recent centuries by near annihilation,
broken land treaties and enforced reservation life, those tribes
have histories that go back tens of thousands of years. West
emphasized that this time frame would provide the larger context
for the museum's exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 19th century was not a particularly pleasant chapter of
our history, and I think we have to talk about that in an honest,
informed and direct way,'' he said of the tribal wars with European
settlers. ``But museums should be safe havens for controversial
discussions. And the 19th century is hardly the sum total of the
tribes' existence here or their cultural contribution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-00 2241EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
