<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DORISMOND-REACT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICISM OF MAYOR AND POLICE GROWS AFTER FUNERAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Expands earlier story with additional grafs at end, beginning
with ``At a rally ...'') 
(lb) 
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A day after violence marred the funeral for the
victim of a police shooting, criticism of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
and the city's Police Department intensified Sunday as the mayor
vigorously defended himself and the police and denounced the
protesters for what he called an ``orchestrated attack.''
</P>
<P>
   At news conferences and in pulpits across the city, the mayor's
political foes seized on the melee as further evidence of what they
described as the mismanagement of a police department that they
said was losing the confidence of New Yorkers, especially in
minority areas, after a string of police-involved shootings of
unarmed men.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani on Sunday vehemently dismissed his critics and praised
the police for having handled the funeral crowds in ``a
professional and restrained way.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the first time the mayor also voiced sympathy for the
family of Patrick M. Dorismond, the 26-year-old black
Haitian-American whose funeral on Saturday was marred by scuffles
among mourners and police officers in which 23 officers and four
civilians were hurt and 27 people were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Detective Anthony Vasquez, the undercover narcotics officer who
fatally shot Dorismond during a confrontation outside a bar in
Manhattan on March 16, sent a letter to the family on Saturday
offering his condolences. Asked by reporters about Vasquez's
gesture, Giuliani said it was ``an appropriate expression.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I commend him for doing it,'' the mayor said after marching in
the Greek Independence Day parade in Manhattan, in front of the New
York police band. ``He did it on the basis of a father losing a
son, or a mother losing a son, and I think we all feel that. We all
feel very, very bad whenever a situation occurs in which a parent
loses a child.''
</P>
<P>
   But almost in the same breath, the mayor again cited reports
that Dorismond had assaulted his girlfriend a week before the
shooting, suggesting that his temperament might have led to his
death. The police have said Dorismond angrily rebuffed an
undercover officer's request for marijuana and was shot while
struggling with Vasquez. No weapon or drugs were found on
Dorismond.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is evidence, again evidence _ not yet decided,''
Giuliani said, ``that he engaged in an assault, that he engaged in
the activity that caused the shooting and that he had up until a
week or a week and half ago indicated a strong propensity for doing
that, including punching his girlfriend in the face'' as she held
their 3-year-old child.
</P>
<P>
   From City Hall Park to a small Baptist church in the Bronx to
the evangelical church in Brooklyn where Dorismond worshipped,
anger over the Police Department's actions at the funeral and
Giuliani's response to the shooting remained strong Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   At a rally in Flatbush, Brooklyn, the Rev. Al Sharpton joined
other speakers in calling for a federal monitor to oversee the
department, though he stopped short of blaming the police for
Saturday's confrontations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's make it clear that the Haitian community of Flatbush
marched over three miles down Flatbush Avenue, no windows were
broken and there was no violence,'' Sharpton said. ``When we were
inside the church, there were reports that police with riot gear
were coming forth, which we had asked them not to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton said the Giuliani administration had moved too quickly
to blame the demonstrators for the violence, and he challenged the
mayor and the police commissioner, Howard Safir, to ``name the
demagogues'' who they said sparked the confrontations.
</P>
<P>
   The state comptroller, H. Carl McCall, said at a news conference
Sunday, ``The mayor is incapable or unwilling to deal with this
crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   The simmering hostility between residents and the police in many
quarters led McCall, who as comptroller is the highest black
elected official in the state, to send a letter to the governor on
March 23 asking him to set up a commission to study ways to improve
relations among police officers and residents, with a focus on but
not limited to New York City.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At around the same time on Sunday, the city's public advocate,
Mark Green, reiterated his demand, first made a year ago, that
Safir resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never urged any other Giuliani appointee to resign,'' he
said. ``But Howard Safir is an exceptional case. I'm not
criticizing the cops but rather the commissioner, whose policies
have failed to accomplish what commissioners in Boston, San Diego
and other cities have _ less crime and less misconduct
simultaneously.''
</P>
<P>
   And C. Virginia Fields, the Manhattan borough president, at a
separate rally with the Black Ministers Conference of Greater New
York, demanded federal oversight of the police and urged the U.S.
attorney's office in Brooklyn, which is conducting a broad civil
rights inquiry into the department, to release its findings. An
aide to the U.S. attorney in Brooklyn, Loretta Lynch, declined to
comment Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
