<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR MONDAY, MARCH 27
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Monday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.)  
(ss) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-NY-FATHER-BARRICADE-NYT (moved Wednesday, March 22)
</P>
<P>
   An article sent on Wednesday, March 22 about John D. Fenrich, a
Long Island man who fatally shot himself after learning that the
remains of his stepson had been found, included an erroneous police
report of a family connection. Ronald Fenrich, a retired deputy
chief of Manhattan detectives who died last month, was not John
Fenrich's father or a member of his family.
</P>
<P>
   BC-PAPERS-BROADCAST-MEDIA-NYT (moved Sunday, March 19)
</P>
<P>
   Because of an editing error, an article sent on Sunday, March 19
about the relationship between CNBC and The Wall Street Journal
referred incorrectly to the audience for the Dow Jones Newswires.
Their primary audience is securities industry professionals, not
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   BC-PALM-IPO-NYT (moved Thursday, March 2)
</P>
<P>
   An article sent on Thursday, March 2 about the initial public
offering of Palm Inc. misstated the number of companies that have
licensed the company's operating system software. There are six:
Franklin Covey, Handspring, I.B.M., Qualcomm, Symbol Technologies
and TRG. Handspring is not the only one.
</P>
<P>
   BC-INTERNET-TAX-NYT (moved Monday, March 20)
</P>
<P>
   An article sent on Monday, March 20 about the commission that is
advising Congress on taxing Internet commerce misstated the title
of Ron Parrish, an executive of the Tandy Corp., part of a
retailers' group opposing a moratorium on Internet taxes. Parrish,
who called the proposal poor public policy, is vice president for
corporate development; Tandy's chief executive is Leonard H.
Roberts.
</P>
</TEXT>
