<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8749 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MOTHERS-GUNS-NYT &LR;      03-26 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTHERS-GUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 MARCH FOR GUN CONTROL STARTS WITH ONE WORRIED MOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MARIA NEWMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHORT HILLS, N.J. _ The movement of mothers for stricter handgun
laws _ a force that organizers predict will bring tens of thousands
to a Mother's Day march on Washington in May _ began with one
woman, Donna Dees-Thomases, and an image she could not get out of
her mind.
</P>
<P>
   Dees-Thomases, 42, a part-time publicist and a mother of two
daughters and three stepsons, acknowledges that she has not been
one to get involved in political issues. But on the night of Aug.
10, when she saw television news footage of children being led to
safety after a gunman's shooting rampage at a Jewish community
center in Granada Hills, Calif., she was deeply shaken. The
children's day camp, she said, looked much like the one her girls
attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was too much to bear,'' she said at her home in this
wealthy suburban community last week. ``This is what life has
become in America. You can't send your kids to nursery school
anymore and expect them to be safe.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, Dees-Thomases turned her emotions into action.
She scribbled a strategy on the back of an envelope: a plan to send
thousands of mothers to Washington to pressure legislators into
enacting tougher gun legislation. A week later, she applied to the
National Park Service to hold the Million Mom March on May 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't just be sitting around our kitchens, crying about gun
violence,'' she said. ``We have to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Originally, Dees-Thomases planned to hand over her idea to
well-connected friends in Washington. ``I'm not organized,'' she
said. ``I wrote the plan, and it was a good plan, but I wanted
others to execute it.''
</P>
<P>
   But her Washington friends all politely told her that although
it was a good idea, they doubted that it had much chance of getting
Congress' attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, it's good that they turned me down,'' she said.
``The march shouldn't be originating from Washington. It should
come from moms in New Jersey, moms in Tulsa, Okla., moms in
Portland, Ore. And that's what it became.''
</P>
<P>
   Dees-Thomases instead called a few friends in the area, some of
them homemakers, some with special job skills like hers that would
be helpful in organizing the march. All of them said they were fed
up about gun violence. By Labor Day she had a group of 100 women
who had agreed to help spread the word; some of them had been
personally touched by gun violence, and some of them were just
angry about it. They were all volunteers at first, giving of their
time, labor and money to help with a phone line and other
activities.
</P>
<P>
   At first, two grandmothers transcribed all the messages left at
the group's telephone number, but there were few calls at the
beginning. ``I used to return every call we got,'' Dees-Thomases
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the group kept putting out the word, and mothers across the
nation kept hearing about them, sharing their tales of gun use gone
awry, and little by little the news of the march spread. The group
also began to attract corporate sponsors and recently could afford
to hire a small staff in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Dees-Thomases knows a little bit about working the media: She
was an assistant press secretary for Russell B. Long, the former
senator from Louisiana; she worked for ``The CBS Evening News With
Dan Rather''; and she is the sister-in-law of Susan Thomases, a
close friend of first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The group announced its march on ``CBS This Morning.'' Members
were asked to be on television talk shows, and slowly, newspaper
reporters came calling. Rosie O'Donnell announced last week that
she would be the master of ceremonies for the march, and Mrs.
Clinton has said she will attend.
</P>
<P>
   The group has created a Web site (www.millionmommarch.com) that
is chatty and features an Apple Pie Award to those who have called
for tougher gun control laws, and a Time Out Chair for opponents of
such laws. The only one in the Time Out Chair so far is Rep. Tom
Delay, R-Texas, who once said, ``This House is a pro-gun house.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an elected official,'' Dees-Thomases said. ``He's
supposed to be out there looking out for the health and welfare of
people. Guns are a public health issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shame on him! He's just going to stay in that Time Out
Chair,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Delay said that the congressman was not
concerned about the group's uncomplimentary recognition of him, and
that it had not made him change his views. Delay is a
``conservative whose views reflect core Republican values,'' said
Jonathan Baron, communications director for Delay. ``One of those
values is the Second Amendment and the right to bear arms.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association heard about the group, and the
association's executive vice president, Wayne R. LaPierre, has
criticized its tactics. A group calling itself the Second Amendment
Sisters has announced that it will have a counterdemonstration on
Mother's Day. (Originally it was called Moms 4 Guns.)
</P>
<P>
   The attention probably helped the Million Mom March. One day in
February, its site got 15,000 hits. Two days later, after some
television appearances, there were 76,000 hits.
</P>
<P>
   Dees-Thomases emphasizes that the group does not want guns
banned. The group is not talking about rifles used in hunting, for
example. Instead, she said, it is focusing on handguns and seeking
what it calls sensible gun control. The group wants all handguns to
have childproof locks and to be registered, and all handgun owners
to be licensed.
</P>
<P>
   Dees-Thomases concedes that the group is dominated by white
suburban women, but said the members were trying to reach out to
others, including inner-city mothers. So far there are plans to
organize rallies on the same day in about 20 other cities,
including one in East Los Angeles, which is expected to be attended
largely by Hispanic women.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not let one child be forgotten,'' Dees-Thomases
said. She said that she ignored the issue of gun violence until
recent shootings in which the victims ``looked like my children.''
</P>
<P>
   Dees-Thomases said it was too early to tell how many people
would show up for the march, but she is counting on at least
10,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to roll up our sleeves and get as many moms out there
as possible,'' she said. ``And dads.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
