<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- March 26, 2000 -- ARREST-THEATER-REVIEW --
Anna Deveare Smith's theater pieces have often been compared to
Studs Terkel's books, and the melding of the writer and the
performance artist here seems a fitting act of homage, as can be
seen in ``House Arrest'', which opened Sunday night at the Joseph
Papp Public Theater in Manhattan. That all the presidency is a
stage isn't really a new idea, but it certainly has promise as the
basis for an evening of theater. Anna Deveare Smith in evokes
prominent Americans and especially presidents, warts and all, from
Jefferson to Lincoln to Bill Clinton. (Sara Krulwich/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) SERGEYEV POSAD, Russia -- March 26, 2000 --
RUSSIA-VOICES -- Two Russians who declined to give their last
names, Sergei, right, and Vladimir, left, talked politics after
voting in Sergiyev Posad, 40 miles north of Moscow, Sunday. Voters
summed up the reasons why Russian president Vladimir V. Putin was
elected Russia's next leader. ``Why do I support Putin?'' says
Vladimir, a defense worker. ``Because he is the person who, at this
given moment, has real power. Putin is our acting president, and,
in the three months since our former president resigned, he has had
control over all the leadership, all the military forces, all the
economists,'' says Vladimir. ``And look. He has already met with
Madeleine Albright, and with that, whats-his-name, Blair.'' (James
Hill/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WASHINGTON D.C. -- March 26, 2000 -- INDIAN-ARTIFACTS-2
-- A business tycoon named George Gustav Heye spent more than half
a century accumulating a collection of Native American artifacts,
who later left more than 800,000 objects when he died in 1957, plus
a photo archive of 86,000 images of Indian life. And now this
treasure trove is being quietly trucked from a Bronx warehouse to
the Smithsonian Institution's new Cultural Resources Center In
Washington D.C. Kelly McHugh, a conservator at the Smithsonian
Museum of the American Indian's Cultural Resources Center, works on
a Ute Indian baby carrier with a Q-tip in the center's conservation
area. (Susana Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON D.C. -- March 26, 2000 -- INDIAN-ARTIFACTS-1
-- A business tycoon named George Gustav Heye spent more than half
a century accumulating a collection of Native American artifacts,
who later left more than 800,000 objects when he died in 1957, plus
a photo archive of 86,000 images of Indian life. And now this
treasure trove is being quietly trucked from a Bronx warehouse to
the Smithsonian Institution's new Cultural Resources Center In
Washington D.C. Kelly McHugh, a conservator at the Smithsonian
Museum of the American Indian's Cultural Resources Center, works on
a Ute Indian baby carrier with a Q-tip in the center's conservation
area. (Susana Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) SERGEYEV POSAD, Russia -- March 26, 2000 --
RUSSIA-ELECTION-2 -- A voter in the town of Sergeyev Posad, 40
miles north of Moscow, pondered the list of candidates in the
Russian presidential elections on Sunday. Russian president
Vladimir Putin's anticlimactic triumph was huge in absolute terms,
some 20 percentage points ahead of his closest rival, the Communist
leader Gennady Zyuganov, but it also appeared likely to fall
considerably short of expectations. This further elevated doubts
about the depth of Putin's popular support. (James Hill/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) SERGEYEV POSAD, Russia -- March 26, 2000 --
SUB-RUSSIA-ELECTION-1 -- People waiting for holy water from a well
on the site of the Saint Sergius Lavra in the town of Sergeyev
Posad, 40 miles north of Moscow, on Sunday, the day of the
presidential elections in Russia. Vladimir Putin's anticlimactic
triumph was huge in absolute terms, some 20 percentage points ahead
of his closest rival, the Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov, but it
also appeared likely to fall considerably short of expectations.
This further elevated doubts about the depth of Putin's popular
support. (James Hill/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- March 26, 2000 -- DORISMOND-REACT --
Twenty-three officers were injured and 27 civilians were arrested
Saturday during the clash between mourners and officers outside
Holy Cross Church where Patrick Dorismond, a Haitian man who was
killed in a confrontation with undercover police, was eulogized.
Those arrested were arraigned Sunday and most were released on
their own recognizance. Most of the charges are expected to be
ultimately be dropped. Marie Dorismond, sings ``We Shall Overcome''
at the press conference for her son Patrick Dorimond at the
Evangelical Church in East Flatbush, Brooklyn. (Michelle V.
Agins/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- March 26, 2000 -- SPRING-AUCTIONS -- Claud
Monet's ``Le Portail (Soleil)'', expected to bring $15 million to
$20 million at Sotheby's auction house in May. The sale follows a
recent investigation that centers on allegations of price fixing
between the two major auction houses, Christie's and Sotheby's.
This season has been further marked by the appearance of a new and
rich presence that has aggressively invaded Sotheby's and
Christie's turf: Phillips, a 206-year-old auction house. Some
wonder if Phillips will be able to survive, like the other two
houses have, after the current economic boom subsides.
(Sotheby's/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- March 26, 2000 -- CINEPLEX-HITECH -- New
screens that can carry text and images are being introduced as a
way to let deaf filmgoers view subtitles that are not visible to
those in the audience who are able to hear the soundtrack. The
technology has been developed by the National Center for Accessible
Media. With the text-display system, called rear-window captioning,
subtitles are displayed, in mirror reverse, on a 7-foot-wide,
16-inch-tall light-emitting-diode screen at the rear of the
theater. People watch the film through a small smoked plexiglass
panel, which reflects the subtitles behind them while allowing them
to also see the movie screen at the front of the theater. (George
M. Gutierrez/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) JERUSALEM -- March 26, 2000 -- POPE -- Many Israelis and
Palestinians have been touched by Pope John Paul II's determination
and balanced compassion as he slowly makes his way throughout
Israel's holy land. On Sunday the pope visited the Western Wall,
and as is the custom of Jewish visitors, tucked a heartfelt note to
God into a crevice in the wall. The pope's note bore the message of
reconciliation that has been the public theme of his six-day
personal pilgrimage, which concluded peacefully Sunday as he moved
from the Al-Aqsa Mosque to the wall and then to the Church of the
Holy Sepulcher. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- March 26, 2000 -- BIZTV-WEB-MEDIA -- Large
brokerage companies like Merrill Lynch, PaineWebber and others that
provide the analysts with information are putting the the public
directly before clients, via their own Web sites. Using streaming
video technology, the financial service companies are experimenting
with daily programs that resemble half-hour newscasts but feature
the companies' own analysts. Bon Plunkett, left, a former reporter
for the Fox network, interviews Gerald D. Cohen, a Merrill Lynch
senior economist for the company's Webcast. (Ruby Washington/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) HOLLYWOOD, Calif. -- March 26, 2000 --
YAHOO-FESTIVAL-MEDIA-2 -- The Yahoo Internet Life Online Film
Festival in Hollywood drew nearly 50 companies offering some form
of online films. Distribution of digital movies on the Internet is
an explosively growing field some think is the vanguard of
entertainment for the future. One exhibitor, Mike Salmi, chairman
of the Seattle-based Atomfilms, is one of the Internet's leading
exhibitors, producers and distributors of digital movies. (Monica
Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) HOLLYWOOD, Calif. -- March 26, 2000 --
YAHOO-FESTIVAL-MEDIA-1 -- The Yahoo Internet Life Online Film
Festival in Hollywood drew nearly 50 companies offering some form
of online films. Distribution of digital movies on the Internet is
an explosively growing field some think is the vanguard of
entertainment for the future. More than 1,800 people signed up for
the online festival in Hollywood. The registration for the festival
was so overwhelming that registration had to be suspended. The
festival prompted new deals for some and ennui for others. (Monica
Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
