<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000326.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8775 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE     03-26 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: COMING BATTLES FOR REFORM
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, March 26:
</P>
<P>
   Even after Sen. John McCain's defeat in the presidential race,
the rush to embrace his themes of reform is gaining force. Vice
President Al Gore is to announce Monday that his top domestic
legislative priority should he win the election will be overhauling
the campaign finance laws. He plans to press for prompt passage of
the tough McCain-Feingold reform bill and down the road has some
imaginative ideas for moving toward public financing of
congressional campaigns and free broadcast time for candidates.
That should pose a salutary challenge to Gov. George W. Bush, who
tirelessly proclaims himself the ``reformer with results'' but has
a campaign reform proposal that is a toothless sham.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who has emerged from his own campaign finance
embarrassments with the zeal of a convert, said he intends to
commit himself so heavily to a ban on soft money as embodied in
McCain-Feingold that even the most suspicious voter will recognize
he would have no choice but to carry through. Beyond
McCain-Feingold, he said he would push for public financing through
tax-deductible contributions to a special endowment and, if that
proved insufficient, would have broadcasters provide free air time
as a condition for keeping their licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Those bold ideas make it imperative that Congress not get
seduced by phony reforms, such as the campaign fund-raising bill
sponsored by Sen. Chuck Hagel, which Sens. Trent Lott and Mitch
McConnell are touting. McCain, the leader on this issue in the
Senate, has correctly rejected the Hagel measure as a step
backward, even though its sponsor was one of the most ardent
supporters of his presidential campaign. In fact, Hagel's bill, the
focus of hearings last week, is designed to fool people into
thinking it would change the system, when in fact it would legalize
the corrupt status quo. Instead of banning unrestricted donations
to political parties known as ``soft money,'' the Hagel bill would
let them continue with an absurdly high cap.
</P>
<P>
   The Hagel bill would also raise the ceilings now in effect for
``hard money,'' or donations to candidates. In all, the measure
would legitimize big corporate and union donations, and allow
individual couples to give more than $500,000 per election cycle.
Worst of all, the bill would allow unlimited donations to state
parties for use in federal races, giving approval to the end runs
that Hillary Rodham Clinton and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani are already
doing around the fund-raising laws.
</P>
<P>
   In another battle in Congress, McCain needs support from
Democrats as well as Republicans for his opposition to President
Clinton's nomination of Bradley Smith to the Federal Election
Commission. Smith, a law professor who regards the campaign laws as
unconstitutional, was advanced as a candidate by the Republicans to
fill one of their party's slots on the commission. Some Democrats
are now arguing speciously that Republicans are entitled to any
appointee of their choice, and that his name should go through. But
a vote for Smith would be like bringing in a wrecking crew to fix a
house. His name can be blocked if supporters of reform stand firm.
</P>
<P>
   It may be clever, but Bush's embrace of the reformer's label
should be seen as cynical, as long as the governor continues to
reject the real thing. He says he would ban soft money from
corporations and unions but allow it from rich individuals. That is
a loophole inviting any special interest to drive right through
with truckloads of cash. The governor these days describes himself
as a man of conviction because he supports a tax cut for the
wealthy, knowing that most Americans oppose it. His courage would
be more impressive if it were not obvious that his tax cut was
designed to favor his rich campaign donors.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Gore is declaring himself so firmly for reform, the
pressure is on Bush to come out for real reform as well. It is not
enough for him simply to challenge Gore's credibility on the issue.
If there is no reform, corruption will follow as surely as
elections follow campaigns. New committees raising money for
congressional races in unlimited sums from secret sources are
already proliferating, as The Wall Street Journal reported last
week. Foreign money of the sort that polluted the 1996 election
could well be a factor again, and the public may not find out until
it is too late. Right now, campaign donations are effectively
determining the fate of legislation on oil prices, tobacco, health
care and other concerns. McCain is right to assume that his fight
has only now begun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-00 2339EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
