u k BC-EDIT-FLAG-NYT &LR;      03-26 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FLAG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE FABRIC OF FREEDOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, March 27:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the Senate truly respected the Constitution it is sworn to
uphold, it would not be trifling with the Bill of Rights and its
precious guarantee of freedom of speech. Yet that is exactly what
the Senate is doing as it considers the so-called flag desecration
amendment _ a mischievous addition to the Constitution that would
weaken the right of free expression by allowing federal laws
banning physical desecration of the flag. The vote on the
amendment, scheduled for later this week, is expected to be very
close.
</P>
<P>
   The vote is a sorry exercise in election-year pandering. The
flag is in no urgent need of protection. The Supreme Court issue a
controversial ruling that flag burning was constitutionally
protected free speech under the First Amendment in 1989, and there
has been no epidemic of flag burning since then.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, politicians do not like taking a stand that might
be seen as a vote against Old Glory. The House already approved the
amendment, and supporters appear only two votes shy of the
two-thirds Senate majority needed to send the measure to the states
for virtually certain ratification.
</P>
<P>
   The history of Congress' on-and-off debate over the amendment
gives reason to hope that this two-vote margin for constitutional
sanity will hold firm despite the intense lobbying campaign being
waged by the amendment's supporters. The last time the full Senate
voted on the amendment, in 1995, the pressure on lawmakers was no
less intense. But the measure came up three votes short of the
required two-thirds.
</P>
<P>
   Senatorial opponents of the amendment, led by Sen. Patrick
Leahy, Democrat of Vermont, deserve high praise for standing on
principle to try to protect the First Amendment from vandalism by
misguided patriots. Leahy and his colleagues have received
important help from Gen. Colin Powell, who expressed his opposition
to the amendment in an eloquent letter circulating to lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   People who desecrate the flag, while certainly worthy of
condemnation, ``may be destroying a piece of cloth but they do no
damage to our system of freedom,'' Powell said. ``The First
Amendment exists to insure that freedom of speech and expression
applies not just to that with which we agree or disagree, but also
that which we find outrageous. I would not amend that great shield
of democracy to hammer a few miscreants.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
