<DOCNO> NYT20000326.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8787 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-OSCARS-FASHION-LADN &LR;      03-26 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-FASHION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK TO BASICS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DEWITT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After the Grammy's display of cleavage and bare midriffs,
Oscar's crowd used a little hindsight.
</P>
<P>
   For this year's parade down the red carpet _ risky business for
the most stunning celebrities _ many stars went for Audrey
Hepburn's famous look of a long black sheath accented with a
majestic up `do and diamond chandelier earrings.
</P>
<P>
   There's something about a bare back that looks best encased in
black, and it could be the added elegance. Take Best Supporting
Actress nominee Chole Sevigny, for example. Her Yves St. Laurent
gown made her a movie star in the old-fashioned sense, exposing a
little cleavage (and claiming no glue or tape was used), a lot of
back and a perfect canvas for those glittery Asprey &AMP; Garrard
jewels.
</P>
<P>
   Also providing swell backward glances were Drew Barrymore who
wore a clingy jersey gown that dipped to the derriere to expose a
tiny angel tattoo. ``I wanted to make sure I looked nice in the
front for television, but naughty in back.'' And the angel?
``That's for my upcoming movie, `Charlie's Angels.'''
</P>
<P>
   Cate Blanchett also went for the drama of black and and a bare
back courtesy of Jean Paul Gaultier. It had an exotic golden chain
down the back that complemented her golden wrist cuffs and slave
bracelet. Cameron Diaz also chose black with a plunging neckline.
When asked about the cleavage, she laughed and said it was only
visible from the side.
</P>
<P>
   Bridging the trend between backless and a return to colorful
gowns was Charlize Theron, who exposed more than her back in a
clingy coral gown by Vera Wang.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the golden girls _ Hilary Swank in a shiny gold
gown by Randolph Duke and Nicole Kidman, whose equally bright gold
gown had flounces and flamenco flair.
</P>
<P>
   Silver still looked hot on a number of stars. Queen Latifah was
wrapped in a wrap-front design by Kara Saun. Faith Hill was
sterling in her silver Versace halter covered in large sequins
called pailettes that shimmered in the flashing lights. Mena Suvari
of ``American Beauty'' wore an Escada gown with a sheer tulle back.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy Liu was one of the fashion independents in red. It was at
least as hot as the gown worn by Catherine Zeta-Jones last year.
The one-shouldered design by Versace was sheer but beaded in a
starburst design. Any secret undergarments? ``Nothing but skin,
skin and skin under the dress,'' she confided.
</P>
<P>
   The popular color of choice was lilac. Supermodel Tyra Banks was
pure couture glamour in her Vera Wang tulle ballgown with exquisite
detailing. Ditto with Ashley Judd, in a slim silouette by Valentino
in a deeper shade of the spring color.
</P>
<P>
   Meryl Streep also used lilac accents in her artful pants
statement by Mary McFadden, the designer famous for teeny pleats
and jeweled jackets. ``American Beauty'' co-star Thora Birch also
chose the color as an accent to her two-piece ensemble by Armani
with a lilac top over an embroidered skirt accented with Asprey &AMP;
Garrard jewels.
</P>
<P>
   As with any Oscar parade there are always a few women that leave
us wondering, ``What was she thinking?
</P>
<P>
   Among them were the usually beautiful Winona Ryder who looked
matronly in a sedate ensemble that showed a modest amount of
cleavage. Her ``Girl, Interruped'' co-star Angelina Jolie went Goth
in a clingy black gown (no back or front plunge) and hopefully fake
long overly dyed black hair.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion independents who looked fresh and sweet included
Kimberly J. Brown of ``Tumbleweeds.'' She arrived in a demure
strapless gown in a tiny orange plaid by Los Angeles designer Max
Azria of BCBG. ``He sent me a whole box of stuff and I loved
this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Denzel Washington and Bill Crystal were still wearing long ties,
white shirts and tuxedos. But nominees Kevin Spacey, Jude Law,
Haley Joel Osment, Micheael Clarke Duncan, Michael Caine all wore
traditional bow ties with white cotton pique dress shirts, which
are making a comeback. Mike Myers summed it all up by saying, ``We
all called each other and decided on the look.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-26-00 2343EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000326.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
