<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8790 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-R-RUSSIA-VOICES-ART-4     03-26 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-RUSSIA-VOICES-ART-455&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACKING A TOUGH MAN IN TUMULTUOUS TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add photo note) (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Photo
is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SERGIYEV POSAD, Russia _ As a sudden blizzard added unexpected
drama to Russia's presidential elections, voters strolling through
the grounds of the Trinity Monastery of St. Sergius summed up the
reasons why Vladimir Putin would be elected Russia's next leader.
</P>
<P>
   Many said they liked him for his decisiveness. Others applauded
his discipline, his energy or his relative youth.
</P>
<P>
   But a voter named Vladimir, standing by the steps of the Trinity
Cathedral, was the most succinct, offering a reason that had a very
Russian ring to it, like the croaking of the ravens in the bare
trees, or the clanging of the monastery's bells.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do I support Putin?'' said the blond, blue-eyed defense
worker, who politely declined to give his last name. ``Because he
is the person who, at this given moment, has real power.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Putin bandwagon that has already rolled across the
political landscape in the last few months, gathering up governors,
mayors, business leaders, military officers and Orthodox priests,
pulled up Sunday at voting stations around the country, offering
the airtight logic of an anointed succession.
</P>
<P>
   The Putin phenomenon _ local shorthand for the extraordinary
eight-month political odyssey of a once undistinguished KGB agent _
has been traced to many sources: the war in Chechnya, the Russian
longing for a strong hand.
</P>
<P>
   But one factor, often overlooked, is the equally strong yearning
for stability at the top, even when it means maintaining a much
maligned status quo.
</P>
<P>
   How else to explain that the heir of a president as despised and
scorned as Boris Yeltsin in his last years could emerge with such
popularity? How else could an inexperienced politician consolidate
Russia's political elite in such a short time?
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir was ready to elaborate. ``Putin is our acting president
and, in the three months since our former president resigned, he
has had control over all the leadership, all the military forces,
all the economists,'' he said, speaking with the slow precision of
someone reporting to his boss. ``And look. He has already met with
Madeleine Albright, and with that what's-his-name, Blair.''
</P>
<P>
   He might as well have added that the Putins have already settled
into the Kremlin, and that it would be a pity to waste money in
making them move.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, as the Kremlin in the last few weeks stepped up its
campaign to propel its candidate into office on the first round of
voting, the cost of a second round _ estimated by one Putin
supporter as the cost of one month of pension checks in Moscow and
the surrounding region _ became a factor, which was mentioned by
several voters interviewed Sunday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Sergiyev Posad, 40 miles from Moscow, on the grounds of the
monastery built to honor one of Russian Orthodoxy's most revered
saints, Sergius of Radonezh, and at the site of a famous call to
arms in 1380 against the Tatars by Prince Dmitri, Putin was also
getting high marks for his appeal to Russian patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   Aleksei Yermelayev, a 47-year-old construction worker, views
Putin as the man who can best take Russia out of the chaos that he
now sees around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the country is on the edge of collapse,'' he said. ``Look
at Chechnya. Yes, the war is cruel, our soldiers are dying, theirs
too, and the civilian population is suffering. But that was a
situation that couldn't continue.''
</P>
<P>
   The strong state that Putin keeps promising means to Yermelayev
a chance for Russia to hold its own among the world's other leading
nations. ``It means not going around like some kind of beggar,
begging for loans and credits that have been suffocating our
country,'' he said. ``But it doesn't mean taking up arms. It means
Russia reshaping its own identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what Putin will do with his power, once it is reaffirmed
by popular mandate, was not clear to many voters. Those who were
backing his opponents _ most of them opting either for Grigory
Yavlinsky, the liberal democratic leader of Yabloko, or Gennady
Zyuganov, the Communist Party leader _ were still calling Putin a
dark horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can someone who has no program be elected president?''
asked Alexander Dyomin, a 47-year-old plumber _ who voted for
Yavlinsky this year, just as he did four years ago _ as he came out
of the polling station in the center of town.
</P>
<P>
   And even those who supported Putin could only guess at his
economic program, which has yet to be written, let alone made
public. ``He will continue the Yeltsin course, although he may make
some changes,'' said Igor, a Moscow factory director.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Tatyana, when asked what changes the couple _ both
Putin supporters _ expect from their candidate, responded:
``Changes for the better.''
</P>
<P>
   Gennady Shubarov, a 35-year-old chauffeur who was visiting the
monastery with his daughter, Katya, 9, said he had voted for Putin
because he was certain that Putin would do nothing to disturb the
fragile rights of Russia's small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, he will continue Yeltsin's program,'' Shubarov
said, noting that his wife was the entrepreneur of the family.
``And of course, that is a good thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
