<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-26 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8795 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-TRAILBLAZE     03-26 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-TRAILBLAZERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT CRUNCH TIME, EWING DELIVERS FOR THE KNICKS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ The high-decibel noise was raining down on the
New York Knicks in thick layers, the score was growing
uncomfortably close and all the elements of a typical collapse by
the team on the road were in place.
</P>
<P>
   This time, they weathered the chaos and kept their cool under
duress to come up with their most impressive road victory of the
season, 93-89, against the hostile backdrop of Portland's Rose
Garden. This time, Patrick Ewing delivered in the critical moments.
After the Trail Blazers cut the Knicks' 17-point third quarter lead
to 87-86 with 52.3 seconds remaining, Ewing came up with two
unshakable free throws to give his team a three-point lead. Then,
as Scottie Pippen tried to drive inside with 19.9 seconds
remaining, Ewing popped up and swiped it away.
</P>
<P>
   He raised his arms in victory. There were a couple free throws
left for Larry Johnson and Latrell Sprewell to hit in order to seal
it, but it was all theirs. And so was a piece of the Atlantic
Division lead after Miami had lost earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Just a week ago, the Knicks became frazzled in a tight finish
and lost in Indiana. With 19 points apiece from Ewing and Allan
Houston, with an unselfish game plan that helped them build their
early cushion, the Knicks had just their fourth road victory in 13
tries. They did it by shooting 48 percent from the field, and
allowing 47 to Portland. The Knicks also forced the Trail Blazers
into 15 turnovers. Although there were some shaky moments in the
end, the Knicks played the kind of road game they needed to start
their five-game West Coast swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``More so against good teams on the road, it's about mental and
physical toughness,'' said coach Jeff Van Gundy before his team
played Portland. ``You have to have the toughness to withstand a
run by the other team and to withstand a call that doesn't go your
way. You get banged. Do you fall down and stay down? Or do you get
back up? That's what winning on the road is all about, physical and
mental toughness to endure.''
</P>
<P>
   They were the vision of sharpness in the first half. Rarely have
the Knicks players been so in sync as they were while building an
impressive 56-43 halftime lead. With 18 first-half assists, they
were three shy of their season best for an entire game. With an eye
toward getting one another involved, they overwhelmed the
zombie-eyed Trail Blazers with a stream of driving layups.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks continued that pattern to open the third quarter. On
their first two scores, Sprewell drove by Steve Smith on his way to
layups under the chin of the perpetually angry Rasheed Wallace. In
the first two minutes of the third, the Knicks had a 62-45 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Knicks' strategy failed them for a couple of minutes.
They would drive but come up with nothing. When Houston lined up
from outside, he came up empty, too. During that lapse, when the
Knicks missed five straight shots, the Trail Blazers cut the
Knicks' lead to 62-51 with 6:45 left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks went back up by 66-53 after Camby came flying in for
a put-back dunk off a missed driving layup by Ewing. Then Pippen
gave the Portland fans something to cheer about. On a fastbreak by
the Knicks, Pippen got back and blocked a runner by Sprewell. Four
seconds later, he popped up to block a jumper by Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen inspired some emotion from the Trail Blazers. And it
touched Damon Stoudamire. He came up with a 3-pointer in front of
Ward with 1:05 left in the third. Then, he stripped Ward in the
backcourt, a play that led to a jumper from Brian Grant to cut the
Knicks' lead to 68-60 entering the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Trail Blazers have not been the same since they
lost to the Lakers three weeks ago, the Knicks had a lot to do with
keeping them down in the first half. Off turnovers, Chris Childs
and Ward pushed the ball up the court, looking for Sprewell to fill
the lane.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening six minutes of the game, the Knicks built an
18-10 lead with the help of seven points off the fastbreak. But
there was a slight slip in the Knicks' attention span.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of continuing to push and pound the ball inside, they
started to relax and hang out on the perimeter. Pippen started
closing down on his defense of Houston, Ewing began to miss from
the baseline and Sprewell came up short on his jumper, too. The
Trail Blazers capitalized, and took off on a 16-7 run on the
strength of Pippen's strong moves to the basket and grabbed a 26-25
lead at the end of the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But the Knicks displayed an uncanny shooting touch to open the
second quarter and hit three consecutive 3-pointers. It might have
been easy to fall in love with their jump shots at that point. But
the Knicks uncharacteristically resisted. They continued to look
for their teammates cutting to the basket, search out the best shot
with ball movement and make their shots.
</P>
<P>
   On one play late in the second quarter, Sprewell crossed the
free-throw line, fired a bullet pass to Kurt Thomas, who converted
the layup. It was like that for most of the first half. Working for
the easy shot enabled the Knicks to make 58 percent of their shots
in the first half. Although they were not exactly shutting the
Trail Blazers down by allowing them to shoot 47 percent, they did
leave by as many as 14 in the second quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
