<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-TEAMMATES GIVE AUDETTE A WARM RECEPTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The French greeting is a kiss on both cheeks, and
Donald Audette got slobbered.
</P>
<P>
   Audette said after Sunday's 4-1 Los Angeles Kings victory over
the expansion Atlanta Thrashers that his desire to leave Los
Angeles never was aimed at his former teammates.
</P>
<P>
   He met them warmly after the game and made sure former teammate
Garry Galley would pick up his children today at LAX.
</P>
<P>
   He just didn't see a future with the Kings, who sent him to
Atlanta on March 13 with defenseman Frankie Kaberle for Kelly
Buchberger and Nelson Emerson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to see the guys again,'' said Audette, who
assisted on the Thrashers' only goal. ``My concern was after this
year. Now we are talking to the Thashers about staying. It is a
good situation here.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Thrashers have the worst record in the league
(13-54-7), Audette is playing on the first line and power-play
unit. He even took a few shifts killing penalties.
</P>
<P>
   As a restricted free agent, the Kings would have had to give him
a 10 percent raise from this season's $2.2 million salary to retain
his rights. That was too steep for the Kings. But for Atlanta,
which is desperate for goal scorers, a new contract makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   Audette, who has scored 24 or more goals five times, had three
in his first four games with Atlanta. He almost poked one by Kings
goaltender Stephane Fiset late in the game and exchanged friendly
verbal jabs with his former teammate in French.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to sneak one by,'' he said. ``What really would have
been nice is if we had won.''
</P>
<P>
   Sticking around: Emerson, who broke his left index finger five
games into his Kings career, joined the club in Atlanta, where he
played before the March 13 trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, you want to win, but there were some fun things,
too,'' Emerson said. ``I must have seen 10 guys score their first
NHL goal. I got as excited as they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Emerson, expected to be back for the playoffs, has been told by
doctors to limit physical activity so the finger can knit properly.
``No skating,'' he said. ``They don't want me to fall. If that
happens, the first thing you do is stick out your arm to break the
fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Emerson will remain in Atlanta the rest of the week in an
attempt to sell his house.
</P>
<P>
   Ref hurt: Referee Kerry Fraser received seven stitches on the
left side of his head after he was struck on a deflected shot by
Atlanta's Matt Johnson. Fraser left for several minutes but did
return.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
